<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENITEZ, THE METS' SUBSTITUTE CLOSER, SAVES ANOTHER ONE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nights like the last two have to make people think
Armando Benitez is ready to assume the closer role full time with
the Mets, even after John Franco comes back from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Benitez struck out the heart of the Atlanta
Braves order to preserve a one-run victory, Vladimir Guerrero of
Montreal told Benitez that he would like to see Benitez come out of
the bullpen and do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Not every night I can do it like that,' ''
Benitez said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But he was close enough. Benitez walked the first batter he
faced in the ninth inning Monday night at Shea Stadium, then
retired three in a row to nail down his fifth save of the season
and a 2-1 Mets victory over the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been nights like last Wednesday in Miami, where
the hard-throwing Benitez surrendered a game-winning home run for
the third time this season. Consistency has been a question with
Benitez since he arrived in the major leagues in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Manager Bobby Valentine did not want to answer the
question of who would be his closer when Franco returns from his
15-day stint on the disabled list with a tendon injury to his left
middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until John comes back, I won't deal with any New York job
controversies,'' Valentine said. ``Johnny's not even bending his
finger yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Valentine said, Franco might not even be ready to come back
when he is eligible in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the job is Benitez's. Monday night, he saved the
victory for Turk Wendell (2-0), after the Mets scored the go-ahead
run when Brian McRae hit into a double play with the bases loaded
in the eighth inning. Surprisingly, Montreal Manager Felipe Alou
had his infield playing back with the score tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' pitching coach, Dave Wallace, said that Benitez has
overpowered batters because ``he has an idea of how to go after
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More so than I realized,'' Wallace added. ``He is ahead of
where I thought he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed looked sharp in seven strong innings of five-hit,
one-run ball. But because Dustin Hermanson was just as good, Reed
departed for a pinch-hitter in the bottom of the seventh with the
score tied at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's chief problem was that he could not get Terry Jones out.
He allowed a triple to Jones, the game's second batter, but left
him stranded. In the third inning, Jones blooped a run-scoring
single to left just after Manny Martinez had belted a two-out
double to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   The only other time the Expos threatened against Reed was in the
sixth, when Jones singled with one out, stole second and advanced
to third on a ground out. But Guerrero popped to second to end the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson, meanwhile, kept the Mets in check until the fifth,
limiting them to only one runner in scoring position, Reed, who
doubled to lead off the third and never got farther.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets threatened again in the sixth, when John Olerud and
Mike Piazza singled to open the inning. But Hermanson stranded them
and was sailing until he had to leave in the seventh with cramps in
his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth against Guillermo Mota, Olerud walked, Piazza
doubled, Robin Ventura was walked intentionally to load the bases
and McRae hit into what turned out to be the game-winning double
play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
