<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-AIDE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPLESS GUN FOR HIRE JOINS FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 9:15 Tuesday morning, a sleep-deprived Howard
Wolfson is to accompany a lawyer to the Federal Election Commission
in Washington as the lawyer files a piece of paper establishing the
Hillary Rodham Clinton for U.S. Senate Exploratory Committee. After
tending to the television cameras, and perhaps savoring a small
role in history, Wolfson will go to Albany, N.Y., and begin caring
for 200 reporters from around the world who are to trail Mrs.
Clinton, starting Wednesday, on a four-day campaign trip across New
York; the opening day, simultaneously, of the wildest ride of
Wolfson's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in at 6 this morning and I'll probably be here until
midnight,'' Wolfson said distractedly but not unhappily over lunch,
as his pager vibrated steadily against his hip.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, 32, is Mrs. Clinton's press secretary for her
exploratory committee, a job he has held for a political eon, 11
days.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, June 25, Harold Ickes, Mrs. Clinton's
political adviser, offered Wolfson the job of press secretary to
the first first lady to explore running for political office on her
own. By the following Monday, Wolfson was out of the Capitol Hill
offices of Rep. Nita Lowey of Westchester County, N.Y., where he
was the chief of staff, ensconced in a corner of Ickes' Washington
lobbying firm. Since then he has been, basically, on the phone. Not
sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be nuts,'' said Josh Isay, the chief of staff
to Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who is a good friend of Wolfson's.
``He's perfect for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Isay, Schumer's campaign manager for his 1998 Senate race while
Wolfson was Schumer's director of communications, meant his
assessment as a compliment. In short, Isay said, Wolfson has just
the right amount of obsessiveness, aggressiveness and capacity for
hard work required in a race that will rival a presidential
campaign. (New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is Mrs. Clinton's likely
opponent in the New York Senate race, although neither has
officially declared a candidacy.)
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson was one of those responsible for the Schumer campaign's
daily ``rapid response'' counterpunches to attacks by former Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, who was thought unbeatable at the beginning of the
race. ``If he uses a fist, you use a bat,'' Wolfson told his troops
each day, citing a line from the movie ``The Untouchables'': ``If
he uses a knife, you use a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson raced with Isay to Elaine's late one night in search of
former Police Commissioner William Bratton, hoping to find him to
get assurances that he would appear at an endorsement news
conference the next morning. (They didn't find him, but Bratton
turned up in the morning nonetheless. Wolfson was in before that,
at 5:30.)
</P>
<P>
   Such is Wolfson's stock among New York politicians that Ms.
Lowey, his former boss, called up unsolicited to say nice things
about him. ``He is overwhelmed,'' she said. ``It's a huge job. But
he's up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lowey, who announced last month she would not run for the
Senate because, she said, Mrs. Clinton's intentions were clear,
also offered the unsolicited view that Mrs. Clinton had not lured
Wolfson away. ``Several people have been saying that she stole
him,'' Ms. Lowey reported. ``That wasn't the case at all.'' After
she dropped out, Ms. Lowey said, she called Mrs. Clinton and
offered Wolfson for an interview. ``And she was very grateful,''
Ms. Lowey said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the object of the women's affections, Wolfson, was
trying to concentrate the other day over his grilled chicken
sandwich at Luna, a restaurant across from Ickes' office, but he
kept looking at his watch, worrying about his pager and trying,
apparently, to be uninteresting, lest he say something delicious
that might offend his new boss at the White House. (He spent an
hour with her before he got the job, and described her as ``very
warm'' and ``funny.'')
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson wouldn't say what the two talked about, but it is
probably safe to say that Mrs. Clinton was pleased to hear that
Wolfson grew up in an apartment in Yonkers, N.Y. His parents, who
divorced when he was a toddler, were teachers; his father taught
social studies at a junior high school in South Orange, N.J., and
his mother special education at public elementary schools in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson went to Yonkers public schools until the fifth grade,
switched to the Fieldston School in Riverdale, the Bronx; graduated
from the University of Chicago, got a master's degree in American
history at Duke University and read the Theodore White ``Making of
the President'' books throughout. He got his first job on Capitol
Hill in August 1992, with Rep. Jim Jontz of Indiana, who lost his
bid for re-election in November. ``It was not an auspicious way to
begin a career,'' Wolfson said. He was hired in 1993 by Ms. Lowey,
who lent him to Schumer last year. Wolfson's girlfriend, Terri
McCullough, is a lobbyist for the National Abortion Rights Action
League in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Wolfson said he had no knowledge of Mrs. Clinton's
house-hunting forays or vacation plans in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only vacation plans I'm aware of are my own,'' he said.
``I have none.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
