<HEADER>
A0104 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETS-AT-WORK-ART-2NDT     07-06 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-AT-WORK-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: working dog.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps no dog has received more attention in Manhattan than
Boomer, the golden retriever who belongs to Parks Commissioner
Henry J. Stern. But of late, the most publicized office dog in the
city is Lil, a bichon-wheaten terrier mix and the constant
companion of Marilyn Mode, the deputy commissioner for public
information of the New York City Police Department. It seems that
Lil's every misdeed, whether swiping a lunch or nipping a
sergeant's foot, is reported by the Newsday columnist Leonard
Levitt, who covers the police department.
</P>
<P>
   It was big news last year when an anonymous letter was sent to
the city's Health Department complaining of Lil's presence, and
Police Commissioner Howard Safir, after asking the legal department
to look into it, then declared that Lil could stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hours are rather unpredictable, and the commissioner
indulges me,'' Ms. Mode said in a recent interview. But she has
grown weary of Levitt's sardonic scrutiny of 20-pound Lil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Roosevelt said about Fala,'' she said, referring to
President Franklin Delano Roosevelt and his beloved Scottish
terrier. ``When FDR was accused of sending a gunboat back to pick
up Fala, he said he was used to the press taking shots at him and
his family, but he resented their going after Fala. Well, Lil
resents it, and so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   MBS Associates, a marketing firm in Montrose, which promotes
animal adoptions and pet products, participated in last month's
Take Your Dog to Work Day. The firm sponsored contests like ``best
dressed,'' ``most congenial,'' ``best trick'' and ``most
obedient.'' The president, Mal B. Schwartz, who has a mutt named
Dvorak, is thinking of allowing dogs every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy should be explored,'' he said. ``It adds to the
camaraderie around the office. People feel really good about it.
You know, there's more to working than getting work done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
