A0109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WCUP-COACH-NYT &LR;      07-06 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WCUP-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass.) 
THE RECEPTION OF DiCICCO IS LOUD AND CLEAR 
 (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Tony DiCicco's mother was born, her parents
were so happy to have a daughter, after three sons, that they named
her Welcome. DiCicco has been just as gladly received as coach of
the women's national soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of my motivation for women's athletics from my
mother,'' DiCicco said. ``She used to shoot baskets with me in the
driveway. She was a great swimmer. I always knew girls could play,
because I played with her.''
</P>
<P>
   At 50, with four sons of his own, he still lives in his hometown
of Wethersfield, Conn., a mile from his parents. On Saturday, he
will coach the biggest game of his life when the United States
meets China in the final of the Women's World Cup at the Rose Bowl
in Pasadena, Calif. Naturally, the welcome mat has been rolled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if my mother is coming, but I've got a ticket for
her if she does,'' DiCicco said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his parents' close friends during Tony's childhood had a
great niece who turned out to be a decent soccer player _ Mia Hamm.
Funny how the whole world can fit into a phone booth. It was Hamm
who offered DiCicco the aphorism that he has hung out on his
coaching shingle: ``Coach us like men, treat us like women.''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women are far more similar than dissimilar from a
coaching standpoint, DiCicco said. The women on the national team,
many of whom have been together for three World Cup tournaments,
want to be pushed and challenged like all elite athletes, and they
play with ravenous assertion, but they do not want a coach in their
face, yelling, singling anyone out for criticism in front of the
others, he said. They are not rushing out to buy tapes from the
Bill Parcells school of motivational speaking.
</P>
<P>
   When DiCicco joined the national team as an assistant coach in
1991, he criticized midfielder Kristine Lilly during a film session
after a loss in China. Several days later, it got back to him that
Lilly was blaming herself for the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``With guys, you can yell in their face and they don't worry
about it, but I think women take it more personally,'' said Joy
Fawcett, considered by DiCicco to be the world's top defender.
``The game is different to us. It's more about building
relationships between ourselves and the coaching staff than just a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   A former team captain and all-American at Springfield College in
Massachusetts, DiCicco played professionally for five years in the
American Soccer League and had a cup of coffee with the men's
national team in 1973. He succeeded Anson Dorrance as coach of the
women's national team in 1994 and has built a supremely fit,
attacking team that he runs with a democratic style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's not a dictator; he's open to input,'' goalkeeper Briana
Scurry said. ``And he always gives 100 percent. With Tony, you know
he leaves no stone unturned.''
</P>
<P>
   He appears to have achieved a balance that suits the needs of
his players. Before the World Cup, the players trained for six
months in Orlando, Fla., away from husbands, friends, family
members. Once every four weeks, DiCicco gave the players a week's
break, saying that ``when they disconnect with those relationships,
it unsettles them.'' He uses his captains, Carla Overbeck and Julie
Foudy, as weather vanes to let him know which way the mood of the
team is blowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very open to listening to what our bodies need,'' Foudy
said. ``He talks to the captains, and he's always asking, `What do
you need? Do you need more fitness? Jogging? A day off?'''
</P>
<P>
   He has a calm demeanor, which seems to transfer to a team that
never panics. If there is pressure for the Americans to win the
World Cup, DiCicco said, that is better than the alternative,
having no chance to win. ``It's less pressure than opportunity,''
he said. He has made his players accessible to both the public and
reporters, aware that they are pioneers as well as athletes, that
they have to sell their game as well as play it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that DiCicco hasn't made mistakes or faced contentious
moments. The players say they felt overtrained during the 1995
Women's World Cup, when the Americans settled for the bronze medal.
He says he now wishes he had made changes to a four-defensive-back
alignment and a possession-type offense earlier rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, forward Debbie Keller took the U.S. Soccer
Federation to arbitration, saying that she had not been invited to
training camp because she had filed a sexual harassment suit
against Dorrance, the former national team coach who also coached
her at the University of North Carolina. The federation stuck by
DiCicco, and Keller lost in arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts when you hear that your morals are being challenged
and basically you're being told you're professionally dishonest,''
DiCicco said, adding that retaliation was not the reason that
Keller, the team's second-leading scorer a year ago, was given only
a brief tryout before the World Cup. ``Debbie had a great season
last year, but the teams we need to beat, I think she's limited to
play against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss in the 1995 World Cup was redeemed in 1996 when the
United States won the gold medal at the Summer Olympics. But
DiCicco and his players want soccer's version of the double play,
simultaneous titles in the Olympics and the World Cup. If male and
female athletes prefer to travel different motivational roads, they
still want to reach the same destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony came into the team not really knowing a lot about the
head coaching position,'' said the forward Tiffeny Milbrett. ``He's
made some hard decisions. Sometimes hard decisions are looking at
players and situations and saying, `Do I need them? Do I cut them?'
Sometimes hard decisions are evaluating your own liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '95, we lost the enjoyment of soccer. It was almost like
burning out. It's a delicate balance. You can't do the same drills,
you can't approach the game the same way you did 10 years ago. You
have to evolve. That's what Tony did, to the better of his
coaching, to the better of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
