A0116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-SURVEY-     07-06 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-SURVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY CITES ABUSES BY MANAGED CARE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years after New York state enacted sweeping
laws to combat abuses by managed care companies, a survey of city
doctors suggests that many of those abuses not only continue but in
many cases have grown worse.
</P>
<P>
   The state laws, called the managed care bill of rights, are
similar to protections passed in a few other states, and they
resemble a national plan supported by President Clinton to try to
level the playing field between customers and insurers.
</P>
<P>
   New York's regulations detail everything from the information
insurers have to disclose to the way they have to process
hospitals' requests for medical treatments. The laws even dictate
how quickly managed care companies are supposed to return phone
calls. Penalties include fines and interest charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Green, the city's public advocate, said the survey of
257 doctors, conducted in May by his office with the help of the
New York County Medical Society, showed that many parts of the law
are being routinely ignored. This has led, he said, to countless
delays in procedures that doctors consider medically necessary. In
some cases, doctors reported that patients were even forced to wait
on operating tables during minor surgeries because it took insurers
hours to grant authorization for the procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said that over the last two years insurers had added
a range of minor procedures and tests _ like X-rays _ to those that
require preauthorization. And while nearly all routine,
nonemergency requests by doctors are approved within the law's
three-day time limit, managed care companies commonly take much
longer to approve more complicated, expensive procedures, according
to some doctors surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Brescia, the medical director of Calvary Hospital in
the Bronx, reported, for example, that insurers always take longer
than three days to approve requests for pain management treatments
for the hospital's end-stage cancer patients. ``We have families on
the phone screaming for help _ `Mom is suffering!' _ and all we can
say is, `We're doing our best to get her admitted,''' Brescia said.
</P>
<P>
   Green called the report as much an indictment of the state
Departments of Health and Insurance as of the managed care
companies, because the state agencies are responsible for enforcing
the laws. ``They have allowed themselves to become so
ineffectual,'' he said, ``as to become anti-consumer.'' He added
that compared with those in other states, New York's fines assessed
against insurers under its law were incredibly small.
</P>
<P>
   But Allison Klimerman, a spokeswoman for the Insurance
Department, said that she believed that the report, one of several
by Green critical of the Pataki administration's oversight of
health care, was politically motivated. Green has plans to run for
mayor in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Green is trying to get some headlines by taking some
cheap shots,'' she said, adding that the department had imposed
$190,000 in fines against insurers for their failure to pay
health-care providers promptly from the time that law went into
effect in 1997. Under the law, the companies are also charged 12
percent interest daily on amounts not paid quickly enough to
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a slap on the wrist by any stretch,'' Ms.
Klimerman said. ``We've seen companies start to take notice and be
concerned about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Smith, a spokeswoman for the Department of Health, said
that while the department has imposed minimal fines against
insurers starting in 1997, it does conduct undercover surveillance
of managed care companies' practices and forces them to correct
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Green's report, the refrain from those interviewed was that
managed care companies do not appear to be increasing outright
denials of medical treatments, but instead create such a confusing
and frustrating gantlet for obtaining permission that medical
providers are often discouraged from trying.
</P>
<P>
   One Manhattan gastroenterologist, who insisted that his name not
be revealed in the report, told the surveyors that problems with
approvals often led to long delays in crucial colonoscopies _ a
test used to determine cancer in the colon _ and other endoscopy
exams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
