<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-GROWTH-HNS     07-06 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GROWTH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Halfway through its last season of the 1900s, NASCAR is a little
like a farmer who just won the lottery. He knows he's on a roll and
has money to burn, but he isn't quite sure what to do with it or
how it will change his life.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup racing is America's fastest-growing sport, but
booming success also brings changes that must be addressed. Here
are three key issues NASCAR faces in the future:
</P>
<P>
   The demand for more races _ Winston Cup added a race in Miami
this year, bringing the schedule to 34 points races and two
all-star race weekends. But other speedways are being built across
the country, and each one wants a Winston Cup date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 36 weekends in '99,'' said NASCAR executive vice
president Mike Helton. ``The issue is, can we make it 37 or 38 or
39? We think there is still room. We just don't know how much
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracks are being constructed in Kansas City, Chicago and
northern Kentucky. Plans are under way for speedways in New York,
Denver, Baltimore and maybe Houston. Some drivers are apprehensive
about expanding the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a driver, I want to race every day,'' said STP Pontiac
driver John Andretti. ``If it was strictly a driving thing, I'd say
let's run four or five times a week. Of course, that's not very
realistic. The crews wouldn't be able to keep up, you'd never have
enough cars, and the costs would be astronomical.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is tracks in major markets that want two dates a
year, like Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of stretching the schedule by going somewhere a second
time, right now we are choosing to go somewhere for the first
time,'' Helton said. ``We want to tap into new markets for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's healthy for the car owners and their sponsors when we go
to new markets. We can tell them they will be able to expand their
opportunities in new market areas _ and that's a driving force when
it comes to which tracks we go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe the solution is to take one race from
smaller markets that have two dates _ like Martinsville,
Darlington, Dover and Richmond _ and give those dates to big-market
tracks that have only one annual date. But NASCAR president Bill
France Jr. says he has no plans to take dates from current track
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Bruton Smith, who owns Texas Motor Speedway and five other
tracks, thinks he has the answer: Split the series, and make two
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the cure,'' Smith said. ``If you have two leagues, then
you could run 60 events instead of the 30 or 40. We have talked
about this for three or four years now. We could fill 300,000 seats
in one day because of two races.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says his plan, which would put one league on the East
Coast and the other on the West Coast on a given weekend, would
offer drivers more chances at seat time and victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a potential sponsor, you're interested in your car
winning,'' he said. ``Your car might win eight times in your
league, but in the Winston Cup we're running today, you might not
finish in the top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   But France says track owners and promoters would never warm to
the idea of Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt driving on opposite
sides of the country. He also sees a problem with drivers not
competing in their home state or the state of their sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say there's a race in Texas, but (Corpus Christi native)
Bobby Labonte isn't racing there,'' France said. ``The first thing
that's going to happen is (team owner) Joe Gibbs is going to come
to me and say he's got to be there because Bobby's a Texan and the
corporate headquarters for Interstate Batteries (Labonte's sponsor)
is there. You couldn't dictate who goes where.''
</P>
<P>
   The spiraling costs in Winston Cup _ Many people in NASCAR are
concerned about the staggering costs of fielding a competitive
Winston Cup team. While the series is booming, the price of
sponsoring a Winston Cup team has doubled in the last five years.
It costs $8 million to $10 million a year to run a top team.
</P>
<P>
   Elite drivers command seven-figure annual salaries. Top crew
chiefs are earning $250,000 a year. DuPont will spend $12 million
this season to sponsor Gordon. Chevrolet is spending $10 million to
sponsor Earnhardt's No. 3 Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   For their big bucks, most sponsors want a driver who runs up
front. Last week at Daytona, Skoal told team owner Andy Petree it
would no longer sponsor driver Ken Schrader after this year, and
Tide officials informed Ricky Rudd they were ending a nine-year
association as his sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the first time I've ever experienced anything
like this,'' Rudd said. ``NASCAR is growing, and it's changing, and
hopefully it's all for the better. But I think, unfortunately, a
lot of the guys who paid their dues and helped create the sport are
tending to get run over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd and Schrader are veteran drivers who have had long and
successful careers, but sponsors want to win and win now. Sponsors
have to be sold on a team's potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably guilty of working way too many hours and worrying
way too much about this race team,'' Rudd said. ``I should have
been going up to the sponsors with a fancy briefcase and a nice
PowerPoint pen presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton said this year there have been more conversations than
ever with car owners about keeping a cap on expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one part of our business that makes it more complicated,
though, is operating as an independent contractor, the car owner is
in total control of his own labor costs,'' Helton said. ``NASCAR
can't do much about the labor side of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing pressure on drivers _ ``The demands on these guys is
unbelievable now,'' said Richard Petty, NASCAR's all-time
winningest driver. ``When I was accessible in the garage area, I
was accessible to 20,000 people. These guys have to be accessible
to 120,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, they can't get to the people because the press is in the
way. There's almost as much media now as there used to be fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers are expected to do a lot more than drive these days.
They must entertain sponsors, answer dozens of media requests and
test cars at tracks across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest problem for drivers today is the demand on
their time,'' Rudd said. ``In the late 1970s and early '80s, we'd
sit on the pit wall and sign autographs for two hours. It wasn't
just Richard Petty doing it; everybody did it. But back then, you
didn't have to be somewhere Monday or Tuesday. Now there are
responsibilities that come with major sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for NASCAR's popularity with fans has been its
open-door policy at the track. Fans have been able to walk in the
garage area on race mornings and talk to the drivers. But the
volume of people has increased so much that changes must be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers tell us their concerns,'' Helton said. ``We don't want
them to be known as guys who don't want to give an autograph, so
we're ready to take the hit and say, `If you do give an autograph
at certain times, we're going to penalize you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup champion Gordon says the days spent away from the
track are what burn out most drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big sport now,'' said Gordon. ``There's a lot of
money involved, a lot of sponsors with commitments for the drivers
and the crew chiefs that keep you busy. You've got to learn how to
say no. You've got to make sure you're fulfilling your commitments,
but most of all you've got to fulfill your commitment to the race
team and to what really is making this all go around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There is a price to pay for stardom, as more NASCAR drivers are
learning. There also is a price to be paid for success, which
NASCAR officials are starting to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision-making process is: What is good for the sport?''
Helton said. ``We want to make it as safe as possible, as
affordable as possible and competitive as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through its 51st season, NASCAR is at a crossroads. The
popularity of the sport is at an all-time high, but keeping it
there will depend on how NASCAR handles its success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough deal,'' Andretti said. ``You want to grow
quickly, because it's exciting to grow fast. But you want to grow
with some control, because it's easy for any business to outgrow
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
