<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     07-06 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WE watch him the very same way we watched Secretariat gallop down
the homestretch at the Belmont 31 lengths ahead of the field. With
jaws dropped in awe.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger, Tiger, burning bright.
</P>
<P>
   Two magnificent athletes, clearly a breed apart. One a powerful,
four-legged thoroughbred. The other a sleek, hungry cat.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods wins the Motorola Western Open _ his third victory
in his past four tournaments _ and regains his status as the
world's No. 1-ranked golfer. And we know what that means.
</P>
<P>
   Tigermania is back. Just in time for the British Open. Maybe
just in time for golf to nose its way back in front of the X Games
on the radar screen of our sports consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   A market study recently revealed that in 1998 the interest of
Americans in golf fell back to traditional levels. In other words,
the same consistent, solid _ and high-income demographic _ level
that it had enjoyed for roughly three decades until Tiger kicked
open the doors and let in the masses. The reason was plain and
simple. So many of those instant converts, who had just learned to
tell a birdie from a bogey, believed their man would treat every
golf course like Augusta National and every tournament like the
1997 Masters, taming it, beating it, body-slamming it into
submission to win by, oh, a dozen shots.
</P>
<P>
   That was Tiger's amazing margin of victory at the '97 Masters _
12 shots _ and it not only captured worldwide attention but also
made many of the fans, new and old to the sport, think it was
always going to be that easy.
</P>
<P>
   It probably made Tiger believe that as well. Made him think he
could step up to the first tee every Thursday and dominate through
the 72nd hole on Sunday. But in 1998, he managed only one win on
tour and no major titles. And the excitement fizzled out like the
fuse on a wet firecracker.
</P>
<P>
   While Tiger groused and fumed and tried to figure it out, the
masses who are quickly bored these days looked elsewhere for their
special-event fix. This is an audience _ and a society _ that wants
its hits to be loud and big like Star Wars and its memorable
moments able to be placed in the microwave, zapped and served on
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of instant gratification, America doesn't want to be
told that the McGwire-Sosa home-run race might happen only once in
a generation or a century, and it doesn't want to hear _ or even
think _ that the mighty Tiger can't devour every single golf
tournament like it was a slab of raw meat. There is SportsCenter to
fill with highlights every night, and there are TV spots for Nike
and all the rest to tell us that Tiger isn't just a cut above _
he's entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   With his good looks, youth, beaming smile, sinewy muscles and
immense talent, Tiger fills the bill on all counts. He has not only
the ability to play the game but the charisma to transcend the
game, taking what is still a monied sport and delivering it to
every street corner of every town in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the linear descendant of Michael Jordan in terms of
marketable sports figures, an icon for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Unflashy Tim Duncan uses solid fundamentals to be named Most
Valuable Player of the NBA Finals, and it's like watching a master
carpenter build a cabinet. Polite Pete Sampras wins his sixth
Wimbledon title, and it's, well, good tennis.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Fourth of July, Tiger takes his third win in four
times out _ the only miss when Payne Stewart's putter comes up big
at the U.S. Open _ and the air is suddenly filled with color and
cannon fire and sparkling possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the measure of a megastar is whether he can draw
attention even when there is no real competition. We used to tune
into basketball games with Jordan just to see if he could dazzle us
with some new move, even if it was in a 30-point rout of Denver.
Now we stay glued to the TV to watch Tiger, even when he can
virtually do the backstroke with a final-round 71 and still win by
a comfortable three shots.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the way he attacks those drives, roaring like a Tiger.
It's in the way he gets himself out of trouble, in the rough or in
a bunker, with one of his trick shots. It's in the way he takes us
with him on an emotional roller-coaster ride. He pumps his fist
when celebrating. He throws his clubs when aggravated. He smiles
like the boy next door. He curses like a sailor.
</P>
<P>
   But he demands our attention. Oh, there are complaints that he
gets too much of it, from the TV networks, from newspapers. Maybe
some of it is still rooted in racism. Maybe some of it comes from
knowing you can't get away, can't take your eyes off him.
</P>
<P>
   Tigermania. Hear the roar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
