<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS &LR;      07-06 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CINCINNATI _ The Astros still don't have an answer for Ron Villone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cincinnati's reborn lefthander continued his mastery of the
Astros on Monday as the first-place Reds moved one game ahead of
Houston in the National League Central with a 5-2 victory at
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Villone a few times, and that's not the same Villone
I've seen before,'' Astros interim manager Matt Galante said after
his team split a four-game series with the Reds. ``I can't explain
it. There are a lot of things in baseball that can't be
explained.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the rest of the NL must be thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Villone (4-2) picked up his third consecutive win, two of them
against the Astros. In his last three starts, Villone has held the
Astros to one hit, limited Arizona to one hit in a game that
featured 17 strikeouts by Randy Johnson, and allowed the Astros two
runs and six hits through seven innings Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He threw 100 pitches in sweltering heat that reached 154 degrees
on the artificial surface at game time. Villone had a streak of 21
scoreless innings _ second-longest in the majors this season _
snapped when Matt Mieske hit a two-run homer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros played without scheduled starting pitcher Mike
Hampton, who was scratched two hours before game time because of a
strained left wrist. The loss of Hampton was a setback for the
Astros, who have lost only twice in his last 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Holt, pitching on three days' rest, made the emergency
start and allowed five runs and 10 hits in 5 innings. Joe Slusarski
made his Astros debut, allowing one hit in 1 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm felt great. I was completely ready,'' said Holt, who
was told late Sunday he might be needed to pitch a day ahead of
schedule. ``It didn't bother me to come back one day earlier. It
was easy to get loose, especially in that heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a couple of strides. It may not look good in the box
score, but I went after hitters, and that's what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros wasted several early scoring opportunities and were
1-for-9 with runners in scoring position. They left a runner at
second in the second inning and stranded runners at second and
third in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a shot or two early and didn't get it done,'' Galante
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati wasted no time in getting it done, scoring once in
the second inning and twice in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Larkin singled with one out in the second, and Aaron Boone
singled to right-center. Mike Cameron then reached on a fielder's
choice as Larkin scored from third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds got four hits in the third inning, including RBI
singles by Greg Vaughn and Boone, who had three hits for the second
straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati went up 5-0 in the sixth when Cameron sent a 2-0
pitch from Holt over the right-field wall with Boone on base.
</P>
<P>
   Holt said he implemented some of the strategy discussed in a
film session last week with Galante and pitching coach Vern Ruhle.
But it wasn't enough to prevent him from suffering his ninth loss
in 10 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One and nine is not a good pitcher. Even though I'm a 1-9
pitcher, I'm capable of doing better,'' Holt said. ``I could easily
be a lot better than that. Some crazy things have been going on
this year. I've just got to change this luck around.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Villone has done. The Reds gave him a chance to
become a starter last month after 162 career relief appearances but
considered sending him back to the bullpen only two weeks ago after
three bad outings.
</P>
<P>
   Since suffering a first-inning knockout against Milwaukee on
June 19, Villone has been almost untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a change of scenery will help a guy out,'' Astros
first baseman Jeff Bagwell. ``We used to have a guy (in relief)
named Curt Schilling who's doing pretty good as a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Graves pitched the ninth for his 11th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are 8-3 against the Astros, and the teams don't meet
again until the final week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After losing three pitchers _ Sean Bergman, Brian Williams and
Hampton _ while splitting a four-game series with the Reds, the
Astros have to feel fortunate to come away trailing by only one
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon believes his club has left an
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (the Astros) went back home realizing, `These
guys can play with us. We're not running away with this thing,'''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
