<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDING SIREN TO END CAR CHASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until about three years ago, Liz Rice hardly ever noticed the
terrible stories in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Some kid boosts a car and the cops chase him and he runs a
couple of red lights and ``bam'' _ somebody dies.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day, that somebody was Jennifer Lynn Rice.
</P>
<P>
   She was 23 years old and engaged to be married. Early on the
morning of Sept. 8, 1996, she was heading to her parents' house to
have breakfast with them.
</P>
<P>
   They were close that way.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer had no idea that two teenage boys had stolen a car in
north Phoenix, then raced away from a Maricopa County sheriff's
deputy after he tried to pull them over.
</P>
<P>
   The boys had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Their car was doing 80 mph when it shot through a red light at
Bell Road and 40th Street, crashing into Jennifer's car.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, detectives arrived at the home of Bob and
Liz Rice, knocked on the door, and handed Liz her daughter's bloody
purse.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing since has been the same.
</P>
<P>
   Those newspaper articles Liz barely used to notice now whack her
in the gut like a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened last week. &QL; 
POLICE PULL BACK
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old and a 16-year-old jumped in a van outside a
Scottsdale deli and were spotted by police. There was a brief
chase, but then police pulled back. They do that now.
</P>
<P>
   If a helicopter is available, police use it to keep tabs on the
punks, who always drive too fast on streets filled with too many
innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   This time the van made it all the way to Osborn Road and 16th
Street in Phoenix, where it plowed into a car driven by 26-year-old
pastry chef Dion Ybarra, father of a 3-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since her daughter's death, Liz Rice has seen too
many of these stories.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was the young offenders who got her attention.
There were two boys in the car that killed Jennifer. One died of
injuries from the crash. The other was sent to a juvenile detention
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Liz went on a crusade to have underage criminals charged as
adults. They are now. The driver who killed Dion Ybarra could be
tried as an adult for murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, while I think that's a good thing, that we should try
kids as adults, I think it's even more important that we step back
a minute and look at the bigger picture,'' Liz said. ``Why do we
chase these kids at all?''
</P>
<P>
   She knows the reason.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say if we announced there would be no pursuits
whatsoever, thieves would declare open season on automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, not many people in law enforcement believe juvenile
car thieves care one way or the other. &QL; 
A FEW OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately,'' Liz said, ``we have to ask ourselves if it's
worth it. Are the risks acceptable? Once a kid steals the car,
there are only so many things that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There's escape, of course.
</P>
<P>
   There's capture.
</P>
<P>
   There's the body of Jennifer Rice.
</P>
<P>
   And of Dion Ybarra. And of whoever's next.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also the families, like mine,'' Liz said. ``Every day
we face the reality of a daughter who's not there, who's never
going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer's fiance recently moved out of state. Even after three
years, the memory of what happened to the woman he planned to marry
was just too much for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great young guy and he's trying hard, but his life
isn't what it was supposed to be,'' Liz said. ``He's having a real
hard time dealing with that. And what about the kids who commit
these crimes? They didn't start out to be killers. Most of them
probably never would have become killers.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no good options here.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, we either have a thief on the loose with a hot
car, or we have a killer in custody and a corpse.
</P>
<P>
   I know which one Liz Rice would choose. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
