<HEADER>
A0147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-INTERRA     07-06 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-INTERRACIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER:   THE FINAL SHOWDOWN ON INTERRACIAL MARRIAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The right to love and live with the person we choose is
fundamental to the concept of freedom. But laws that made it a
crime to marry, live with or have sex with someone of a different
race restricted that freedom over much of the country for more than
three centuries. Laws against interracial marriage were enforceable
in 17 states when the Supreme Court declared them invalid in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The old Confederacy did its best not to comply. Two states _
South Carolina and Alabama _ actually reached the '90s with the
invalid prohibition inscribed in their constitutions. South
Carolinians voted to expunge the bigoted language in 1998. The
Alabama legislature approved a similar referendum last month, and
its sponsor, Rep. Alvin Holmes, is struggling to get it on the
ballot as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Modern liberals typically see the Southern obsession with
interracial sex as a product of Confederate hysteria. But during
the Civil War and Reconstruction, Northern abolitionists like
Wendell Phillips, Harriet Beecher Stowe and the madcap Horace
Greeley did much to inflame Southerners about the question of
interracial intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of the Civil War, the notion that racial problems
could be solved only by merging the races had become a standard
abolitionist theme. Phillips, for example, wrote that race-mixing
was ``God's own method of crushing out the hatred of race and
civilizing and elevating the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Greeley, the founder of The New York Tribune, wielded the idea
like a weapon against the South. In a 10-point program for
``miscegenation,'' Greeley wrote: ``The solution of the Negro
problem will not be reached in this country until the public
opinion sanctions a union of the two races. ... As the Negro is
here and cannot be driven out there should be no impediment to the
absorption of one race in another. ...'' Greeley thundered that
``It is the duty of anti-slavery men everywhere to advocate the
mingling of the two races.''
</P>
<P>
   Scandalizing slave owners who had slept with the property,
Greeley sneered that ``Legitimate unions between whites and blacks
could not possibly have any worse effect than the illegitimate
unions that have been going on for more than a century in the
South.''
</P>
<P>
   The abolitionists' enthusiasm for race-mixing drew lengthy
condemnations in Congress. Rep. Samuel Cox of Ohio read Greeley and
Phillips into the record and ridiculed them for wanting to top the
Capitol dome with a brown-skinned statue of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Cox joked about this. But whites in the plantation South took it
seriously. Mixed-race children had become so numerous by 1850 that
the government began to count ``mullatoes'' as a separate category
in the census. In areas of the Cotton Belt where slaves outnumbered
masters by substantial margins, white families sometimes went
``black'' and fell completely across the color line.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that whiteness might be swept away, Southern states
passed laws or amended their constitutions to preserve ``racial
purity'' _ which was laughably futile after 300 years of
interracial sex. Alabama tried to close the door for all time with
a constitutional provision in 1901 that read: ``The legislature
shall never pass any law to authorize or legalize any marriage
between any white person and a Negro, or descendant of a Negro.''
The legislature later went further, making interracial sex a felony
punishable by two to seven years in jail
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court overturned these laws in the 1967 case of
Loving vs. Virginia, which concerned a white man and a black woman
who were arrested for the crime of being married and banished from
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day Alabama has seen nothing so blatant as that. But
Holmes contends that rural judges sometimes make it difficult for
interracial couples to marry even today. He expects the referendum
to pass, but not by a landslide, given the state's history of
intense commitment to segregation. But as in other Southern states,
Alabama elections are sometimes decided by progressive whites and
blacks voting as a bloc. This was the case in the last
gubernatorial election. When the issue of interracial marriage
comes up for a vote, Americans will know how much of Alabama is
trapped in the past and how much has arrived in the present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
