<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-FATAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREWORKS EMPLOYEE WHO SUFFERED BURNS IN PEORIA ACCIDENT DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fireworks expert, severely burned while she set up displays
for a Fourth of July celebration in Peoria, died Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators still don't know what caused the explosion that
injured four of her co-workers just hours before the annual
celebration was set to begin at the Peoria Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real mystery right now,'' said Mike Tellef, a spokesman
for the Peoria Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The accident canceled the fireworks event, which was expected to
draw more than 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Galanda, 36, of Moorpark, Calif., was burned over 95
percent of her body and died Monday morning at the burn unit at
Maricopa Medical Center. Two co-workers also were severely burned.
One was in good condition, but the other was in critical condition
late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks began exploding Sunday about 5 p.m. as a crew from
Lantis Productions Inc., a Salt Lake City fireworks company, began
unloading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fireworks may have gone off right at their feet,'' said
Larry Bettendorf, a spokesman for the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms. About 15 investigators from the federal
agency lent their expertise to Peoria officials to try to find out
what sparked the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Bettendorf said Lantis workers had dug several trenches and set
up a big steel tube to hold the fireworks once they were hooked up
to a control board.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said they heard 50 to 60 explosions as some families
set up blankets and ice chests about 400 yards from the display for
pre-fireworks picnics.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, more than 20 local and federal investigators slowly
swept through the field for unexploded fireworks. The task is slow,
Tellef said, adding that investigators won't even reach the
explosion's site until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, investigators may be able to determine if human
error or some mechanical malfunction, including static electricity,
sparked the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Lantis had 1,074 shells set to explode Sunday night, Tellef
said. About 150 to 200 pounds of them remained in a truck near the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators interviewed two Lantis workers who weren't
seriously injured and also talked to several Peoria workers who
were near the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   They have not yet been able to talk to the surviving burn
victims at Maricopa Mecical Center: Jeff Fraizer, 36, of
California, who remained in critical condition; or Joyce Gyorffy,
of Newbury Park, Calif., who is in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are trained, they are professionals, they do this
for a living,'' Tellef said. ``So, we just don't know what caused
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lantis officials were not not available for comment Monday, said
a woman who answered the phone at their Salt Lake City
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which staged last year's show in Peoria, also has
set fireworks off at Los Angeles, the Aloha Bowl and in fireworks
competitions across the country.
</P>
<P>
   On the company's Internet web site, it says Lantis uses
``trained, state-licensed pyrotechnicians and laser artists who
adhere to strict standards of safety and professionalism.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
