A0154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HONGKONG-NYT &LR;      07-06 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HONGKONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HONG KONG'S INVALUABLE COURTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years after Hong Kong was returned to China, the
independence of its courts has been breached. At the behest of Tung
Chee-hwa, the man Beijing chose to be the territory's chief
executive, the mainland's legislature last month overturned an
important immigration ruling by Hong Kong's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   China's action does not technically violate its agreement with
Britain on the special status of Hong Kong. That permits the
mainland legislature, under certain circumstances, to ``interpret''
decisions by Hong Kong courts. But by inviting China to invoke this
right, Tung has undermined confidence that the territory's judicial
independence can survive.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Hong Kong's high court broadly interpreted a
law giving children of Hong Kong residents a right to move there.
China objected that this could mean more than a million additional
immigrants over the next decade, straining Hong Kong's social
services. In striking down the court ruling last month, the
mainland legislature imposed narrower eligibility standards. How
many people would actually have immigrated under the court's
interpretation, and when, is unclear. China's estimates may be
unrealistically high. It would have been wiser for Tung to see if a
serious problem actually developed before taking such a drastic
step as inviting mainland intervention.
</P>
<P>
   China has so far meddled less crudely in Hong Kong affairs than
many critics feared. But the decisive test will be how much
judicial independence Hong Kong can preserve. Hong Kong's impartial
judiciary has been a key to its extraordinary economic success,
with average incomes some 20 times those on the mainland. To
sustain that prosperity Tung must do a better job of protecting
Hong Kong's courts from mainland interference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
