DiSARCINA FINDS HITTING STROKE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina appears to be
finding his rhythm at the plate since returning to the lineup after
missing three months with a broken left forearm suffered in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting .182 (4-22) in his first eight games, DiSarcina
went 5 for 12 during the Angels' three-game weekend series in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My swing is coming around. I'm still in survival mode,''
DiSarcina said.
</P>
<P>
   Rest for the weary: Omar Olivares' complete-game, five-hitter in
Oakland could turn out to be a huge lift to the Angels and their
fatigued bullpen in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim started right-hander Shigetoshi Hasegawa (his first
start since Sept. 27, 1997) on Monday night against Seattle in the
opener of a three-game set. Hasegawa has been the Angels middle
reliever and setup man since the '98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to stay out there, Olivares said of his 5-2
win at Oakland on Sunday. ``We needed an outing like that to give
our bullpen a rest. With Shige going, that makes it a little bigger
right there...''
</P>
<P>
   The Kid hits 10: Seattle's Ken Griffey was selected to his 10th
All-Star Game on Monday. The Mariners center fielder was named one
of three American League outfield starters along with Cleveland's
Manny Ramirez and Kenny Lofton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
