<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMAN-VP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TALK: IN SHADOW OF REPUBLICANS' DOLE, DEMOCRATS SEEK A
WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Calif., Md., N.H., N.Y., Wash.)    (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The name game always starts with Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, which is no surprise. With her high profile and decades
of political experience, Feinstein, a D-Calif., has long been
considered a credible vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But can the same be said for Rep. Nita M. Lowey, a Westchester
Democrat little known outside New York? Or Sen. Mary L. Landrieu,
D-La., with all of 2 1/2 years in national politics? Or Lt. Gov.
Kathleen Kennedy Townsend of Maryland, who plays second fiddle in a
state that is a pivotal battleground for little except soft-shell
crabs?
</P>
<P>
   All these names, plus those of many other women, dance in and
out of conversations about what Vice President Al Gore might do
when it comes time _ assuming he wins the Democratic nomination for
president _ to choose a running mate for the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the early, undoubtedly ephemeral buzz about Democratic
vice-presidential possibilities is thicker with women than at any
other time since 1984, when Geraldine Ferraro actually made the
ticket, not to mention history. Any decision by Gore is political
eons away, but the degree and range of the chatter about women is
telling, an outgrowth of both the panic among Democrats about
Gore's poll numbers with women and the absence, despite decades of
advances for women in politics, of a tidy, short list of obvious
female contenders to share the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   With few unassailable choices, many names are mentioned, and the
tree of floated notions branches out in unexpected directions. Rep.
Nancy Pelosi of California stokes interest for being attractive and
articulate, then gets nixed for a liberal voting record. Ditto for
Sen. Barbara Boxer of California, who carries the double whammy of
being an in-law of the Clintons. (Her daughter married Hillary
Rodham Clinton's brother.) For Gore, a candidate trying to get
separation, that might fairly be characterized as a tether.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray of Washington is deemed too anonymous. Sen.
Blanche Lincoln of Arkansas, first elected to the Senate in 1998,
gets points for a historic last name, but she is still unpacking
her bags.
</P>
<P>
   Into the subsequent gap of possibilities steps Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen of New Hampshire, the lone woman among the meager crop of
Democratic governors. She might give Gore a toehold _ though not
exactly a foothold _ in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Ms. Lowey, who was actually asked by an
interviewer on the Cable News Network a week and a half ago if she
was interested in the job of vice president. (Ms. Lowey ducked the
question, saying she was honored to serve in Congress.)
</P>
<P>
   ``These other names pop up almost by default,'' one dispirited
Democratic aide said. Another added: ``It's pathetic. Other than
Dianne Feinstein, we really don't have one woman who makes any
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of all the gossipy match-making for Gore boils down to the
presence, on the other side of the political aisle, of a candidate
whose name recognition arguably trumps that of all of these
Democrats: Elizabeth Dole, a Cabinet secretary in two Republican
administrations and the former president of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Dole's campaign for the presidency looks like an
increasingly long shot, she could theoretically find herself in
contention for the No. 2 spot on a Republican ticket, a prospect
that gives the shivers to Democrats, who depend on an advantage
among women to win elections.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows how decisively these voters would respond to
a female vice-presidential candidate. But some Democrats _
including, of course, the women whose names are being bandied about
_ assume it would have to make some sort of difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it were the right woman, it would generate more
support,'' Ms. Landrieu said.
</P>
<P>
   Is she that woman? Ms. Landrieu, 43, said she was flattered by
the talk and had the kind of moderate voting record _ restrained on
financial issues, tempered on social ones _ that Gore might deem
prudent. But as the mother of two young children, ages 7 and 2, she
said that a higher office would not make sense for her family right
now.
</P>
<P>
   She chalked up all the chatter to a widespread sense that it is
about time for a second act to Ms. Ferraro. ``I think the pressure
is really building,'' Ms. Landrieu said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feinstein agreed. ``I think it's kind of a natural
progression,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Leading to her?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to be coy,'' Ms. Feinstein said, ``but I've had no
indication that that's the thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party's desire to hold on to Ms. Feinstein's
Senate seat in the 2000 campaign, which Ms. Feinstein intends to
do, is a potent argument against having her run with Gore. But
there are other reasons. Her husband has had business ties to
China, a fact that would be chum to shark-toothed Republican
researchers. It would also serve as a constant reminder of Gore's
own troubled dealings in that part of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Feinstein, too, slides at least halfway off the list,
leaving space for others. Several Democratic aides swear that Donna
Shalala, the secretary of Health and Human Services, has been
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
