<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SAFECOFIELD-SPI &LR;      07-06 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SAFECO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PARK OPENS FOR BUSINESS; FOCUS SHIFTS TO BALLCLUB 
</HEADLINE>
 FIELD-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Despite the good vibes that Safeco Field's first open
house created Monday, fans, politicians and ballpark officials all
demanded that the Mariners now do their part by producing a winning
team that can make the new stadium a lasting monument to baseball
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today and the July 15 opening game is the first day of their
organizational life,'' said Ron Judd, a member of the Public
Facilities District that oversaw construction of the $517 million
ballpark. ``They need to be focusing on the health and vitality,
the excitement and the energy and the support of the fans. We've
given them the ability to provide the forum to take baseball to the
next level in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners president Chuck Armstrong, one of the main speakers at
the dedication and ribbon-cutting ceremony, acknowledged that the
team has a responsibility to field a competitive team. And that
includes trying to retain players such as Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best ownership in all of sports and they told me
to do everything we can. We are committed to trying to sign them,''
Armstrong said of Griffey and Rodriguez. ``Ken and Alex have to
want to stay here. We hope they do and we hope they spend the rest
of their careers in a Seattle uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, media reports have uncovered the fact that Mariners
owners have brought up the Griffey and Rodriguez contract
negotiations in an effort to get more public funds to cover about
$100 million in cost overruns on the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Owners have contended that they might not be able to retain
their superstars if forced to pay for the overruns. Both players
are signed through the 2000 season and could then become free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Griffey has said he's unhappy that his name
surfaced in connection with the owners' efforts to use public money
for the overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Because of comments Griffey made Sunday about the situation,
Armstrong spoke Monday with the center fielder's agent, Brian
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments were taken out of context,'' Armstrong said of
Griffey's rebuke of management. ``I think Ken knows where we stand
and how much we want him to stay here. To the best of my knowledge,
he's not being used as a bargaining chip (on the cost overruns).''
</P>
<P>
   M's owners were noticeably absent from the list of speakers, and
John Ellis, chairman and chief executive officer, was a scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he hopes the new stadium will provide the team
with the amount of revenue that makes it possible to sign both
players and compete with bigger market teams like the New York
Yankees, Baltimore Orioles and Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't build a major league ball team, you don't build a
major league ballpark if you're not going to be able to keep you
homegrown players,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ballpark was funded through a combination of public
sources, such as tax increases and lottery proceeds, as well as the
sale of naming rights by the team, the M's will be in charge of
operations and expect the new stadium to be a money maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballpark allows us to have the revenue opportunities that
just were not available in the Kingdome,'' Armstrong said. ``We
know that Major League Baseball is a closed loop system _ for every
winner, there's a loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's so many nice things in the (new) ballpark, that
fans will come here for the entertainment, the enjoyment and all
the wonderful things that we have. ... Without a new ballpark,
there really wasn't a lot of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope was evident everywhere Monday as 32,000 to 35,000 fans
streamed into the new facility to get their first glimpse of
Safeco. But most hoped the new ballpark would put the team on a
winning track once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Steve Van Luven, R-Bellevue, one of the key
politicians who helped piece the stadium legislation together,
called Safeco Field one of four wonders of the world that now exist
in Washington state along with Mount Rainier, the Space Needle and
Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a fifth wonder now,'' he said. ``We wonder how soon
Griffey, Rodriguez and (Edgar) Martinez will bring us a World
Series to Safeco Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Edo Vanni, 81, who played with the old Seattle Rainiers of the
Pacific Coast League, criticized M's ownership for the timing of
their dispute over the cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is separating the fans and you don't like
that,'' Vanni said. ``This town doesn't deserve that. In order to
have a team spirit and get on a winning ballclub, you have to get
them all together. But if they keep on going like they are now,
you're going to get them going in two different directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans also expressed their displeasure with the recent disputes
between the M's owners and the Public Facilities District.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disconcerted with what has been going on with the PFD and
the recent talk about Griffey and A-Rod,'' said Jack Blake, an M's
fan from Burien. ``I'd be outraged, absolutely outraged, if they
blow that. I'm real upset about that whole situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blake wasn't about to let the controversy spoil his first
impressions of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was awestruck,'' he said of Safeco. ``Just glancing in to
the green grass and the atmosphere, I was blown away. I started
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd noted the timing couldn't have been worse when the dispute
with the M's was made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``To bring up the cost overruns and taxpayer dollars since we've
known from Day One it's been controversial doesn't get them any
closer to their goal,'' Judd said.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong said the controversy shouldn't overshadow the
importance of getting an outdoor baseball stadium built after 20
troubled years at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, I wasn't sure if we were ever going to have this
happen,'' Armstrong said. ``But now we have the best ballpark for
the best fans for generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, too, was filled with hope, even as a few boos greeted
him when he stepped up to the microphone at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing a fan can have is apathy,'' Armstrong said.
``These fans are not apathetic. They care passionately about their
ballclub. I welcome their passion and their interest, and I just
hope we can fulfill their trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
