A0191 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-06 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFECO OPEN HOUSE GOES STRAIGHT FOR THE HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After a drive from Tacoma, Desmick Louis and his
mother, Doris, were walking away from a ticket window, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought tickets even before we went inside,'' he said.
``Then we went inside, came out and bought more tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   In the business of baseball, the Mariners' new stadium, the
Guilty Pleasure, had perfect execution Monday: It ran the play to
the heart, avoiding the head.
</P>
<P>
   The Louises were among thousands charmed and awe-struck Monday
by their first viewing of the most expensive playfield ever,
including anything built in the Old Testament or by NASA.
</P>
<P>
   The sunny open house did for the franchise what sunny open
houses are supposed to do in real estate: create impulse buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot prettier than I thought,'' said Russ Tate, a Yakima
native who was with his nephew, Darren Clark, of Grant's Pass, Ore.
They are the kind of baseball fans who haven't been reading the
intimate details of cost overruns and back-room blackmailing that
have been the principal features of the run-up to the July 15
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were in the highest row of the third-base
grandstand. When they looked down, they saw a pristine greensward
surprisingly close. Over their shoulders was a view of a
mountain-draped harbor full of ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will,'' he said, ``be back.''
</P>
<P>
   The franchise is counting on it. They are counting on this park
to be an attraction on its own, for locals as well as tourists, so
that all the baseball missteps and management misdeeds will be lost
behind the romance of old-timey grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   As fig leaves go, it's a dandy.
</P>
<P>
   But it is different from Kingdome baseball, so much so that we
offer some early public-service advisories following the first day
of real crowds that enlivened the steel and concrete.
</P>
<P>
   (DESK NOTE: BOLD-FACE LEAD-IN ITEMS)
</P>
<P>
   Daughters of darkness: On a 70-degree day, young women who came
in shorts and halters and sat in the shade nearly went hypothermic.
In dressing for the Guilty Pleasure, except for all but the warmest
day games in the outfield bleachers, two words of advice: Think
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Getcher Wappler Dopplers here: The hottest selling sidewalk
game-day items will be amateur meteorology kits. If high pressure
prevails, the wind comes from the north, so the upper right-field
grandstands are well-sheltered, comfortable and a best buy. When
low pressure brings in rain from the southwest in April and May,
hunker down in the upper grandstand between first and third bases.
Not only are those seats max-protected, the smoke from your
campfires will be high enough so as not to interfere with many
other spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Roooof! Roooof! The massive carport-on-rails is so fascinating
that watching a game here may prove to be like maintaining eye
contact in a conversation with Dolly Parton: Eventually the mind
and eye drift to questions of engineering, architecture and the
sheer overdoneness of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Itty-bitty-bladder contest winners welcome: Unlike the Kingdome,
which apparently was constructed before the invention of kidneys,
there are so many bathrooms that the only excuse anymore for
wetting oneself will be when Piniella picks up the bullpen phone.
</P>
<P>
   Trying too hard, food division: The ``Ivar dog'' is fried
whitefish in a hot-dog bun. I don't know what I was expecting when
I ordered, but that wasn't it. Coming soon to a stadium kiosk:
Black &AMP; Decker strawberry shortcake.
</P>
<P>
   There was much to be fascinated by Monday, not the least of
which is seeing how a half-billion dollars looks and feels.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Caldwell of Seattle saw more than the tactile and the
visual.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is gives the Mariners more credibility in terms
of a franchise,'' said Caldwell, another upper-grandstand denizen
and longtime Mariners fan who also has been to the new yards in
Denver and Phoenix. ``Until '95, the Mariners were never taken
seriously. Now with this, they can compare with the big boys.''
</P>
<P>
   But Caldwell, long a stadium advocate who was happy to pay the
restaurant taxes for the building, couldn't avoid a cringe when it
came to assessing the owners' recent gambit for more tax money
after promising they would filch no more: ``That seems to me to be
a real boondoggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kinner of Edmonds was more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real crime what the owners have done,'' he said as he
gazed from the main concourse. ``They led us down the garden
path.''
</P>
<P>
   But will that really affect your enjoyment of Mariners baseball,
Ron?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too old for that,'' he said, laughing. Then he grew
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, actually, it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as with any temptation for which you've overpaid, or
acquired in dubious fashion, it's a guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday was for the pleasure. As long as we're thinking
Scottish, a wool sweater and a wee dram would help make the guilt
go away with the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
