<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-06 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO FINDS GROOVE; MARINER MATES BELT SEVEN HOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's called gripping, and it's slang for
trying too hard, putting pressure on yourself, stressing out.
</P>
<P>
   All those things may have contributed to Jeff Fassero's
struggles. But the literal meaning of gripping played its part,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his last start, Fassero discovered that he'd been
gripping the ball too hard and decided to loosen his hold. He
wasn't rewarded that time, but he was Monday night. The Mariners
left-hander tossed eight shutout innings against the Anaheim
Angels, allowing three hits and striking out 10 in a 10-0 victory
at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   He was boosted by the bombs bursting in air. Before the postgame
fireworks show, the Mariners clubbed seven home runs, matching a
franchise record and setting a new standard for gopher balls by
Angels pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had failed to homer in the first four games of this road
trip. But that wasn't what pitching coach Stan Williams meant when
he offered this two-word summation of the game: ``Welcome back.''
</P>
<P>
   The innings and strikeouts were season highs for Fassero, the
hits a season low. After going the first 80 games without a
shutout, Seattle now has thrown them in back-to-back games for the
first time in three years. John Halama blanked the Texas Rangers
Sunday, and Paul Abbott completed Fassero's masterpiece with a
1-2-3 ninth. The win brought the Mariners within four games of the
American League West-leading Rangers, who lost to Oakland Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting close to where I should be,'' said Fassero, who
improved to 4-8. ``Right now, I'm just trying to carry all the good
parts into my bullpen and then into my next game. I used the last
five innings against Oakland (last Wednesday) and took them into
this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Location was the biggest thing tonight; everything was down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero walked four, but he used his walks wisely: three were to
the most dangerous hitter in the Angels' lineup, Mo Vaughn. He
threw 127 pitches, the most by a Mariner this season, and manager
Lou Piniella couldn't grant Fassero's request to pitch the ninth.
No matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we've been waiting for from Jeff,'' Piniella said.
``He really threw the ball well. The ball had life on it. He used a
good changeup late in the game, and he had a good breaking ball,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   And none of them were gripped too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``His last outing turned it around for him,'' Williams said.
``He was out there squeezing the ball, not pitching nice and
relaxed. When you're squeezing the ball with your hand, your whole
arm tenses up, your whole body tenses up. He'd been laboring trying
to throw the ball, and it took away all his movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels threatened only in the second, when a Matt Walbeck
single should have loaded the bases with one out. But Troy Glaus
overran second on the play and was thrown out, and Gary DiSarcina
fanned to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Mariners had built a 3-0 lead off spot starter
Shigetoshi Hasegawa (1-3), thanks to a solo homer from Ken Griffey
Jr. and Edgar Martinez's two-run shot in the first. For Griffey,
the home run was his 28th of the season and 378th of his career _
exactly halfway to 756, which would eclipse Hank Aaron's all-time
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I don't think about,'' Griffey said. ``I'm
just trying to help our club any way I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Martinez would have company in the home run parade.
After singling and scoring on Martinez's homer, shortstop Alex
Rodriguez went deep in the third and fifth innings, giving him 16
on the season _ and, no doubt, making a tougher decision for
All-Star manager Joe Torre, who could pick three reserve shortstops
when he chooses the team later this week. Rodriguez had his first
four-hit night of the season and improved his batting average to
.317.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was 2-for-24 before the Rangers series over the
weekend, 9-for-18 since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got to get better,'' he said. ``Tonight was a fine
game for me, but I wasn't feeling as bad as I was doing in Oakland.
I felt pretty good, and I'm beginning to feel a little better at
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Torre decides to put me on the team, I'd be more than
honored to go and represent the American League for my fourth time.
If not, I'll go home and rest my knee for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Another homer came from third baseman Russ Davis, who led off
the fourth with his 17th of the season. In the seventh, John Mabry
hit his first homer in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez added the final blow, a two-run rocket over the
center-field fence that was his 14th of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
