<HEADLINE>
ANGELS OVERPOWERED BY MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The question is who DIDN'T hit a home run for
the Seattle Mariners on Monday night at Edison Field?
</P>
<P>
   The answers are Brian Hunter, David Bell, David Segui and Dan
Wilson. Everyone else in the Mariners starting lineup had at least
one home run against the suddenly homesick Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez each homered twice. Ken
Griffey Jr., Russ Davis and John Mabry also went deep in the
Mariners' 10-0 victory over an Angels team that has been outscored
42-5 in four straight home losses.
</P>
<P>
   The seven home runs by Seattle tied a club record for the third
time. The Angels pitching staff had not allowed this many balls to
leave the yard since it surrendered eight against Oakland on June
27, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what they do,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said of
the Mariners. ``We were putting the ball over the plate too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss sends the last-place Angels (37-44) 9{ games behind
American League West-leading Texas at the halfway point of the
season. To make matters even worse, the Angels once again
surrendered offensively to a veteran pitcher who came to town with
his own mound woes.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Texas' Mike Morgan and John Burkett shut them
down here last week, Seattle lefty Jeff Fassero looked nothing like
the 3-8 pitcher with a 7.21 ERA who started Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero pitched a three-hitter (all singles) over eight innings
and he struck out a season-high 10. Paul Abbott pitched a 1-2-3
ninth inning that met with some scattered boos from some of the
36,987 fans who stuck around for another fireworks show after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the first time I've seen him dominate a game,''
Collins said of Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, whose starting rotation has been bitten by the
injury bug, gave middle reliever/setup man Shigetoshi Hasegawa the
ball against the potent Mariners. He was gone after 21/3 innings.
He gave up four runs on homers to Griffey (solo) and Martinez
(two-run) in the first inning and Rodriguez (solo) in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were expecting me to throw strikes,'' Hasegawa said. ``I
tried to do that as often as possible. Starting was exciting, maybe
too exciting. It was a good opportunity and a good decision. It
just didn't work out too well.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins was uncertain if Hasegawa would get a second start in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the roster moves, I'm not sure if he'll get that
opportunity,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Triple-A Edmonton call-up Jarrod Washburn surrendered a
fourth-inning homer to Davis and Rodriguez's fifth inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry homered off of Al Levine and Martinez hit another two-run
shot, this time in the ninth off Mike Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz was sent to Triple-A Edmonton following the game to make
room for tonight's starter, Mike Fyhrie, who will be making his
big-league starting debut.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, seemingly forgotten among elite shortstops these
days, also added two singles to complete a 4-for-5 evening in which
he also scored four runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
