<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX KEEP DEVIL RAYS AT BAY
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The top three batters in the Red Sox
lineup didn't get the ball out of the infield the entire night. The
drowning Jose Offerman struck out four times in a game for only the
third time in 1,073 big-league games.
</P>
<P>
   This, it would seem, was no way to retaliate against a Tampa Bay
Devil Ray team that last week slapped the Sox around for 23 runs in
two nights at Fenway Park. Especially with Nomar Garciaparra, the
newly elected All-Star, playing spectator for the third straight
night.
</P>
<P>
   But in the air-conditioned comfort of domed Tropicana Field,
where the temperature was roughly 30 degrees cooler than the
sizzling sidewalks outside Yawkey Way Monday night, the Sox chilled
the Devil Rays, 4-2, while simultaneously applying a little more
heat to the New York Yankees in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   With Mike Stanley providing the long ball, Troy O'Leary the
rally-starting double and the rookie bottom-feeders in the order
doing the rest, the Sox closed to within two games of the Yankees,
9-1 losers to the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Portugal, who now has one more win against Tampa Bay
(three) than he has against everybody else he has faced (two), gave
the Sox six productive innings, holding the Devil Rays to two runs
on seven hits. His pitches were dancing so much, according to Jose
Canseco, that the All-Star at one point asked the umpires to check
the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had them check the ball because I thought he might be
scuffing it,'' Canseco said. ``But there was nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox managed only two singles over the last five innings.
But by then, Stanley's 10th home run gave the Sox a 1-0 lead in the
second, and O'Leary's double, which extended his hitting streak to
13 games, started the Sox' three-run rally in the fourth, in which
Lou Merloni walked, Wilton Veras delivered an RBI single, and Trot
Nixon came through with a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   After walking Randy Winn to start the seventh, Portugal gave way
to Derek Lowe, who may not be quite ready to close, but still has a
knack for getting big outs with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe had the tying runs on base with none out in the seventh
with three veteran hitters waiting their turn _ Dave Martinez,
Canseco, and Fred McGriff. None of them put the ball in play in
fair territory. Martinez fouled to third baseman Veras, and Canseco
and McGriff went down swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco didn't call for another inspection of Lowe's sinker. The
movement on his pitches is well-known by now, even if this is just
his second full year in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those pitches he threw to Canseco and McGriff went straight
down,'' raved pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``There was no
side-to-side action at all, just straight down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Lowe gave up a one-out single to Wade Boggs, then
hit Bubba Trammell in the elbow with a 1-and-2 pitch. Once more,
Tampa Bay was ripe to tie. Instead, Lowe induced Aaron Ledesma to
roll to Veras, who turned a nifty 5-4-3 double play, ending the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   His work done for the night, Lowe made way for Tim Wakefield to
accept the handshakes that come to the closer when his team wins.
Wakefield pitched a 1-2-3 ninth for his ninth save and second in
two nights, and the Sox were winners for the third time in four
games on this 10-game trip that leads to the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe figured to get first call as closer when Tom Gordon had
elbow problems, and that's what happened the first time Gordon went
on the DL. But Lowe scuffled in that role, and when Gordon went
down (and out until mid-August at least), the Sox chucked that idea
and opted to recast Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   They put Lowe back on the timeline Kerrigan mapped out for him
back in January, when he was doing pitcher profiles on his laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the bottom of his profile, I wrote, `Should be a dominant
closer in two years,' '' Kerrigan said. ``People don't understand,
you don't get to be either a starter or a closer overnight. It
usually takes three or four years. John Wetteland scuffled. Jeff
Shaw, he was in the (John) Wasdin role for four years. These things
take time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's time will come. In the meantime, he's thriving in the
comfort zone of setup man, allowing just one earned run in his last
11 appearances, for an 0.56 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence goes a long way,'' he said. ``I think I was trying
to do too much early in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   No one did more in the first six weeks of the season than
Offerman, who as late as May 19 was batting a team-best .346. But
his average over the last 41 games is .226 (37 for 164), dropping
his overall average to .284, and he's hitless in his last 16
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The strikeouts have been coming with alarming frequency: the
four Monday night, nine in his last five games, 16 in his last 11.
Three times he was called out on strikes, usually while looking at
a pitch in the vicinity of the outside corner. Most of those
pitches, Offerman maintained, haven't been strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my zone,'' he said, ``and usually those pitches are
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman has been taking the classic approach to trying to snap
a slump, hitting the ball the opposite way. But nothing is falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a slump,'' he said, ``no matter where you hit
it, you hit it right at somebody. (Monday) was the only day I've
felt really bad at the plate. I may be trying to do too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to relax and let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how hard it would be to relax if the Sox were losing.
But they're not. ``We just find a way to win,'' Lowe said, reciting
a familiar theme. ``It's happened all year, and I don't see it
stopping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
