A0289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKAN-LEADERS-BOS &LR;      07-06 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKAN-LEADERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALKAN LEADERS' DAYS ARE NUMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ Franjo Tudjman, the father of his country, is
77, physically shrunken by cancer, politically diminished by the
corruption and economic malaise in which his nine-year rule of
Croatia has bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   Alija Izetbegovic, the father of his country, is 74 and mentally
exhausted, marking time until he can pass the stewardship of
Bosnia, which is also economically stagnant, to a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic, the stepfather of his country and its
best-known alleged war criminal, is only 57, but _ as events of
last week underscored _ he is under intense pressure from growing
numbers of his own people and the governments of the entire Western
world to give up his decade-long control of Serbia-dominated
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for fundamental changes in leadership in one of the
most volatile regions of the world _ changes that will affect the
stability of southeastern Europe and deply influence European and
American ideas of whether it is possible to bring hate-ravaged,
politically under-developed countries into the democratic world.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of the importance of Milosevic's staying or going is
everywhere: On the airwaves, in the councils of the G8, in the
scores of international aid agencies and governments which find
themselves trying, with little success, to put the Balkans back
together again after the shattering of multi-ethnic Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   There is less talk of Croatia and Bosnia, even though the
leadership succession in those countries will be crucial to the
future of the region. As the men who led the Croats and Muslims
through their wars for independence pass from the scene, there will
be power shifts and adjustments of alliances throughout the Balkans
regardless of what transpires in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   For while Serbia remains most populous and developed of the
former Yugoslav republics, both Croatia and Bosnia have better
chances to ``join'' Europe, politically and economically _ or to
destroy any hope NATO has left that it can accomplish more in the
Balkans than just keeping people from killing one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the leadership changes, we're going to have difficult
problems,'' says Jacques Paul Klein, an American diplomat and
retired Air Force major general who has filled top United Nations
posts in Croatia and Serbia. ``Until there is democracy in Zagreb
and Belgrade, Bosnia, indeed the whole region, is problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   The current leaders, Klein says, all formed their ideas about
government and administration during a period of orthodox communist
rule and tight central control, and though political parties now
champion nationalism rather than communism, ``on all three sides,
unless you're a party member you don't get a loan, you don't go to
school, you don't open a new business.''
</P>
<P>
   The next good shot at changing this system will come in Croatia,
and not simply because illness is loosening Tudjman's grip.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party, the Croatian Democratic Union, is an
impossibly broad coalition of groups ranging from far left to far
right, held together by Tudjman personally and by the nationalist
sentiments of the struggle for independence. Tudjman's death or
retirement would lead to a struggle between people whose top
priority is integration into the European milieu and those who
still dream of Croatia annexing Herzegovina, the southernmost
region of Bosnia, which has a large Croat population.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons to hope that the Europeanists will win
out.
</P>
<P>
   One is that, under sharp prodding from the US and other
countries, Tudjman's government has revealed its formerly secret
payments to Croat forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina. Disclosure that
$200 million a year was being siphoned off for this purpose when
the Croatian government is unable to pay pensions or jump-start its
own economy has angered many citizens and alienated them to the
Herzegovina cause.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Foreign Minister Mate Granic, a top-level Croatian
official since 1992 and the odds-on favorite to succeed Tudjman, is
a staunch Europeanist, who said in a recent interview that the
strategic aims of Croatia are membership in the European Union,
NATO, and the World Trade Organization _ goals which are out of
reach until Croatia moves decisively toward liberalism and away
from conflict in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   European nations ``have told the Croats repeatedly that the
basis for normal relations with us was return of the Serb refugees
(to their pre-war homes), freedom of the press, speech and
religion, and . . . forgetting about acquisition of Herzegovina,''
says Albert Rohan, secretary-general of the Austrian Foreign
Ministry, who has been deeply involved in Balkan affairs. ``But in
fact they don't want the return of the Serb refugees and have
obstructed it, efforts to have a free media and reduce corruption
also have failed,'' and territorial ambitions persist among some
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Granic works hard at selling Croatia as the most stable country
in the region, the most welcoming of returning refugees, the most
loyal and helpful to NATO. But, according to a senior cabinet
source, the foreign minister ``is looking to the future'' and is
ready to do what must be done to achieve the coveted organizational
affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is far murkier in Bosnia, where Izetbegovic appears
ready to go _ if he could only find a plausible successor. But with
the country's future relations with Serbia and Croatia unsettled,
and foreigners countries around the world running or influencing
policy at all levels, potential future leaders are laying low.
</P>
<P>
   Izetbegovic ``is tired,'' says Klein, who sees the Muslim leader
frequently. ``He feels he's done his part and that its time for a
new leader to manage privatization, and take a more managerial
approach to administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps saying they can't get local officials to make
decisions, and everything floats up to him,'' Klein says. ``No one
wants to make the wrong move. He in a sense is stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems only one crucial question about the post-Izetbegovic
Muslim leadership: Will it be secular or religious?
</P>
<P>
   At present there is no indication of broad support for a
religious state. Now, as through most of its history, Bosnia's fate
is in the hands of outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   A right-wing, annex-Herzegovina swing in Croatia, or a
continuation under a new regime of Tudjman's attitudes on refugee
returns, freedom of speech, and corruption, probably would push the
Muslims away from liberalism and secularism too. So would a
resurgence of support for Milosevic or Serb nationalism. The
Bosnians, with a flexibility born of centuries caught in the
middle, will wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tudjman two or three years ago announced that Croatia was not
part of the Balkans, it was part of central Europe,'' says Jakob
Finci, head of the Soros Foundation's efforts to build an open
society in Bosnia. ``Slovakia, the Czech Republic, Poland? That is
not so nice. When we decide we are not in the Balkans, we will
declare we are in North America.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's future is hardest of all to divine. It is hard to see
how Milosevic can stay in the face of opposition from the Serbian
Orthodox Church and growing numbers of ordinary citizens as well as
the whole of Europe and much of the rest of the world. But it also
is hard to see how he can go short of an improbable forcible
removal, when that likely would land him in The Hague to stand
trial as a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special problem,'' says Klein. ``You have here a
wounded bear with nothing to lose, because he already has lost
everything. The (war crimes) indictment means he can't leave
Yugoslavia and we can't negotiate with him. Yet we have to'' find a
way to get him off the stage ``if we are to bring Serbia and the
Serb people back into Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Charles A. Radin is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
