<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY'S SCARS FROM ITS SOVIET PAST RUN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DNEPROPETROVSK, Ukraine _ The house mothers who maintain a
24-hour vigil on every floor of the hotel offer the first clue of
how much hasn't changed here since the Communists were swept out.
</P>
<P>
   They collect and dispense room keys and hand tally long-distance
phone charges, a reminder to anyone who had been here before the
Iron Curtain was lifted of the days when the ``dejournaya'' also
helped the Communist Party keep tabs on guests' comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   There are more reminders in the rooms at the sprawling Hotel
Dnepropetrovsk, which rent for $20 a night if you're from around
here and more than $100 if you're from the West. Shower water flows
from a tube attached to the sink, and cold is typically the only
option. The toilet sometimes flushes, and it always sounds like a
passing train.
</P>
<P>
   A ride around this city, or any other in the now-independent and
democratic Ukraine, dredges up other memories. Of major highways
that are barely paved and have only two lanes, and the thrill of
trying to pass another car before the oncoming truck reaches you.
Of Ladas, Volgas, and other Russian-built cars still clogging the
roads and the air.
</P>
<P>
   When you're out at night, the dearth of street lights seems
romantic at first, offering a clear view of the stars even in major
urban centers. Then you recall what street lights are for as you
try to cross the road, and hope oncoming cars can spot you.
</P>
<P>
   Dnepropetrovsk, an industrial city of about 1.3 million, has its
own special tributes to its dysfunctional Soviet past. Rusting
cranes hover over the rusting skeleton of a hotel whose
construction was launched 30 years ago, and is unlikely to be
completed. Two ends of a bridge reach out from opposite banks of
the Dnepr River, but they never meet. The money ran out before the
span could be completed, and one segment has sunk so deep in the
riverbed it is tough to imagine that it ever will.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lots of things have changed in the decade since the
Soviet Empire collapsed, thanks in part to a seemingly endless flow
of US aid. But the changes are not always for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Prostitutes are everywhere, from hotel doorways to the lush park
that lines the riverfront. So are short skirts, shorter than
anything America saw in the '70s _ or since. And jazz has come to
town, no matter that musicians at the Jazz Cafe don't know any Duke
Ellington tunes and the cover charge is higher than most
pensioners' monthly pension.
</P>
<P>
   The life of a pensioner is different, too: thousands have taken
to peddling cigarettes and candy as rents soar and incomes shrink
in the face of inflation. When they don't have enough, they simply
don't pay the rent, one of many signs of economic distress that
opposition candidates are trying to exploit in the ongoing
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   High-priced apartment houses and restaurants have sprung up
across the country, but the economy now is so sick that half the
apartments remain unsold and the expensive eateries are half-empty.
And that's not the only worry for this nation's new breed of
entrepreneurs: They are also concerned about staying alive, which
is why armed bodyguards have become a standard feature of the
Mercedes, Audis, and other luxury cars visible across the city.
</P>
<P>
   Long lines used to be the surest sign that you were in a
Communist country, but they're tough to find today.
</P>
<P>
   You can find air conditioners and Coke, along with lots of other
consumer items that have transformed life here for those who can
afford them.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want a telephone you can get it within a matter of
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest problem that was solved,'' says Uri Laber,
the American-born president of Optima, a company here that is
involved in everything from telecommunications to real estate
development. ``In the old days it involved paying a bribe or
waiting 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Larry Tye is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
