u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEC-REBUILD-BOS &LR;      07-06 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEC-REBUILD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEC CITIZENS VOW TO REBUILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ For seven generations, the Pepa family lived
in a grand, four-story home of hand-hewn stone decorated with
antiques and artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Now their home is a heap of charred rubble. Only one wall is
left, offering a glimpse of the elegance that once stood there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs destroyed everything. They did not just burn the
home, or loot it. They bulldozed it. They were trying to destroy
more than our homes, they were trying to destroy our culture, our
confidence,'' said Mercia Pepa, 50, the matriarch of one of the
most prosperous families in Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Albanians of Pec are very hard workers,'' she said,
using the Albanian pronunciation, ``Peah,'' which had been outlawed
under Serb rule. ``We will rebuild. We will start over and we will
rebuild Pec just as beautiful as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Pec suffered by far the worst damage to homes and property at
the hands of the Serb forces who set out on a well-orchestrated and
methodical campaign to rid the province of its majority ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, 80 percent of the housing stock was destroyed. Almost
all of the major industries were burned and their essential
machinery stolen. And now returning ethnic Albanians bent on
revenge continue the destruction by destroying Serb homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   So Pec is left in ashes, and posing the greatest challenge to a
massive international effort to help Kosovo rebuild. The
undertaking will require billions of dollars and years of work.
Estimates for rebuilding Kosovo are in the $5 billion range, but
for the whole Balkans they soar to $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Postwar reconstruction will mean more than providing sufficient
money to rebuild homes and businesses. It will mean reestablishing
government on a local and national level because virtually all of
the Serbs, especally those in positions of power, have fled.
</P>
<P>
   It will mean repairing a ravaged infrastructure of roads,
bridges, power plants and water systems _ much of which is
intricately woven into neighboring Serbia. And all of this will
have to be mapped out in compliance with the US insistence that no
financial support go to a Serbia controlled by Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere does the task seem more daunting than in the northern
town of Pec. This town and its surrounding villages of 120,00
people was the heart of prosperity and culture for the Kosovar
Albanians. It is the ancient seat of the Serbian Orthodox Church's
patriarchate and a holy land to the Serbs. But now it is in rubble,
for Kosovar Albanians and Serbs alike. Destroyed along with it is
any hope that Kosovo can retain its multiethnic identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepa family owned a chain of a dozen photo development
stores known as ``Foto Pepa.'' All were set ablaze. The Fuji film
processing machines that cost millions of dollars were stolen by
the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Searching through the charred brick and collapsed stone of what
was once their home, Mercia and her daughter, Lirika, 24, found her
wedding photo album. Lirika, cried when she saw the family
portraits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all just a memory now,'' she said, in a neighborhood
where house after house and block after block was reduced to
rubble.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, one of few commercial buildings not destroyed is the
Peqko Pivo brewery, which employed 500 people. A large state-owned
bakery is also intact and will provide jobs for about 150.
</P>
<P>
   The state-owned ``Crevena Zaztava'' auto parts assembly plant,
which employed 5,000 people and was the middle class backbone of
Pec, was destroyed, and the Serbs stole its machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Pec had the largest privately owned shoe factory in Yugoslavia
which was ravaged and looted, leaving 4,000 more people out of
work.
</P>
<P>
   A brick factory, which employed about 300, was demolished. This
is the first plant that officials say they will focus on getting up
and running. They will need a lot of brick in Pec. The primary need
is housing.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Curtis of World Vision said the American, Christian-based
international aid agency, was being contracted by the European
Union countries to coordinate the home rebuilding effort. He said
the original intention was to keep the refugees in the camps until
homes could be rebuilt. But the mass return was spontaneous and
uncontrollable. Now they are left trying to help equip homes to
withstand the harsh Balkans' winter.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, there are virtually no municipal services. No
functioning fire trucks. No local police. Phone service is still
cut. Water is scarce. Streets are mounded with garbage and refuse
which lies putrefying. Flies and rodents are omnipresent. Fears are
growing of an outbreak of disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a long way from establishing order. And we will have to
do that before we can begin to rebuild,'' said Gafor Alshane, 41,
proclaimed civil administrator of Pec for a provisional government
that may or may not hold onto power.
</P>
<P>
   The new provisional government for Pec has been set up in the
Kosovo Liberation Army's makeshift headquarters in a publishing
house. The KLA's eagerness to lay claim to power, and the Kosovar
Albanian business establishment's reluctance to accept it, is
playing out on the municipal level in Pec and on the national level
in the provincial capital in Pristina. How it will be resolved
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Rinaldo Locatelli, a senior representative for the UN Mission in
Kosovo, was touring Kosovo compiling a document that will address
the primary needs of Kosovo and an analysis of the best way to
restore government to the province.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, he walked through the burned out rubble and pronounced,
``This is the hardest-hit place we've seen. All of Kosovo seems
apocalyptic at times, but Pec especially.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have anarchy here at this point,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the anarchy, the few Serbs left are suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the courtyard of the 14th century ecclesiastical compound
that is the Serbian Orthodox Church's patriarchate, Archbishop
Amfilohije Radovic was surrounded by Serb refugees, mostly elderly
women evacuated by NATO. One had a large pancake-sized black eye
from KLA fighters who she said stormed into her home. The
archbishop had just finished a burial service for a mentally ill
woman who he said had been raped and strangled by KLA soldiers in
the Serb paramilitary stronghold of Belo Polje near Pec.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Amfilohije was among the church leaders who embraced
Milosevic when he soared to power more than a decade ago. Now the
bishop is among those calling for his resignation, as the onetime
alliance between the church and Milosevic lies in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need penitence,'' Archbishop Amfilohije said, as buses
idled at the front gate to transport the last of Kosovo's
frightened Serbs to Serbia. ``The rebuilding of Kosovo will have to
begin with the rebuilding of morality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 0932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
