<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KIN-BOS &LR;      07-06 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VILLAGE, SEARCH FOR KIN TURNS GRUESOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBENIC, Yugoslavia _ The stench of the decaying bodies on the
hillside was so pungent, Vjollca Ukshinaj had to cover her face to
keep from vomiting. But she needed to know: Was one of the dead her
father, whom she has not seen for months?
</P>
<P>
   It seemed not, based on the 20-year-old Ukshinaj's squeamish
inspection of what was left of the two figures. The corpses were
fairly fresh, but animals had gnawed at the remains, leaving
returning villagers concerned that neither local people nor
forensics specialists will be able to know for sure who was killed,
and how.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all looking for our people,'' a teary Ukshinaj said.
``I don't know where my father is.''
</P>
<P>
   Elhame Haradinaj is sadly certain what happened to her own
father. Weeping, Haradinaj holds a sock and eyeglass case engraved
with her father's name, items she found dumped at the side of the
road where survivors of a mass killing here say he was
machine-gunned.
</P>
<P>
   Haradinaj said she hasn't seen her father since being forced to
leave Ljubenic for Albania. ``But the witnesses say he was
killed,'' after attempting to convince a Serb soldier that the
small village never made trouble, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 75 men in this hillside, western Kosovo village are
believed slain in what survivors describe as a massacre by Serb
paramilitaries early April 1. Three men were killed separately, and
about 70 other men perished in a 5-minute machine-gun attack on a
line of Kosovar Albanian men.
</P>
<P>
   With 36 bullet wounds, 57-year-old Gani Bushati still can't
believe he survived the attack. ``I was pretending to be dead,''
Bushati said.
</P>
<P>
   After about 40 minutes, he struggled to his feet. ``I said, who
is alive? Get up!'' Bushati recalled. Nine males walked and crawled
to a nearby forest, where they waited in fear for 12 hours. A
16-year-old boy died soon after they arrived, and the remaining
eight ultimately fled to Albania, returning only a few days ago to
search for relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The only physical evidence of the massacre is the bones of at
least two bodies, still lying in a courtyard near the massacre
site. Residents believe the rest of the bodies were burned inside
the adjoining house.
</P>
<P>
   This attack, Ukshinaj fears, killed her own father. She has
examined the clothes and shoes _ some of them with bloodstains _
near the site, but she can't identify any as her father's.
</P>
<P>
   Locals want to bury the two sets of bodies, but they are waiting
for war-crimes investigators to examine the evidence first. Until
that happens, Ljubenic villagers _ most of whom have just returned
from refuge in Albania _ can only go house to house, comforting one
another, exchanging information about relatives, and trying to
ignore the pervasive smells of decomposing bodies and burned
houses.
</P>
<P>
   The Ljubenic massacre presents just one more set of grim
questions for international war-crimes investigators, who are
determining the extent of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war may be over, but tens of thousands of people are still
unaccounted for,'' said former senator Bob Dole, chairman of the
International Committee on Missing Persons. Dole is scheduled to
travel to Kosovo today, visiting mass grave sites and meeting with
Serb and Albanian community members.
</P>
<P>
   No one from the international community has come to investigate
Ljubenic, residents say, although NATO troops put a span of plastic
tape across the house and courtyard where the bones lay.
</P>
<P>
   Even more bodies, locals say, are in the mountains, as refugees
were executed by Serb forces. Based on the number still missing,
Ljubenic residents estimate that as many as 60 from five villages
may be dead.
</P>
<P>
   Nazmi Gashi found his own father on this mountain. The man was
one of 25 dead _ 12 from one family _ discovered by a group of four
young men who made the three-hour trek up the mountain to look for
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting for UNHCR to go with us to look, but we got
tired of waiting for help,'' said Gashi, 24, referring to the UN
refugee agency. ``Now, we are going alone to put white sheets''
over the bodies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
