<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA THE GEM OF THE COPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Copa America is the world's oldest continental championship, and
it remains among the most eventful, thanks to Martin Palermo of
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Palermo missed three penalty kicks in a 3-0 loss to Colombia in
a first-round match Sunday in Luque, Paraguay, a series of errors
that could be costly not only to Argentina but to the player.
Palermo was the leading scorer in Argentina while playing for Boca
Juniors this year, but European teams have been reluctant to take a
chance on him and will be even more so now.
</P>
<P>
   Palermo, 27, banged the first penalty off the crossbar, sent the
second one over the goal, and had the third penalty saved by
goalkeeper Miguel Calero.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombians took the lead on a ninth-minute penalty by Ivan
Cordoba, who celebrated by revealing an undershirt with the No. 2
as a tribute to Andres Escobar, the central defender who was slain
in Medellin during the 1994 World Cup. That would be the only
successful penalty of five awarded in the match, as Colombia's
Hamilton Ricard had his shot blocked in the second half by German
Burgos.
</P>
<P>
   If there were not enough drama in the first two-thirds of the
game, the action soon accelerated. With the score 1-0, Argentina's
Javier Zanetti was red-carded by Paraguayan referee Ubaldo Aquino
in the 68th minute, and coach Martin Bielsa was ejected for
protesting.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two minutes after replacing Ricard, Edwin Congo scored
Colombia's second goal. Another substitute, 16-year-old Johnnier
Montano, who has been linked to Parma in Italy, added the final
goal in the 87th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian president Andres Pastrana told coach Javier Alvarez
this was an accomplishment that shows the potential of the country.
This is a revamped Colombian team, with only Jorge Bermudez among
the holdovers in a key role. Colombia's national team needs to
redefine itself, but this group has far to go to match the
accomplishments of the Carlos Valderrama years, which included a
5-0 win over Argentina _ in Buenos Aires in US '94 qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   But this tournament will likely be recalled as the coming-out
party of another Brazilian Ronaldo. Brazil has two Ronaldos on its
roster, the one who plays for Internazionale in Milan and Ronaldo
de Assis Moreira, a 19-year-old from Porto Alegre who is also going
by the name ``Ronaldinho Gaucho.'' Ronaldinho was only named to the
team after Edilson was dropped because of his showboating while
playing for Corinthians. He scored a spectacular goal in a 7-0
victory over Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barcelona and Real Madrid are bidding on him, according to
Spanish publications. Italian teams will not be far behind. But
Ronaldinho's club, Gremio, is apparently holding out for a record
price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A female future
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Women's World Cup started last month, FIFA president
Sepp Blatter reiterated his prediction that ``the future of
football is feminine.'' Pele' heard the remark and admonished
Blatter by saying: ``What future? Look around you. It's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the WWC has made a significant impact. And, yes,
women's soccer is here to stay. Actually, women's soccer has been
here for some time, though marginalized. But after the championship
game in Pasadena, what will be the future that Blatter and Pele'
have discussed?
</P>
<P>
   To determine such answers, the past must be first examined.
</P>
<P>
   Credit for the success of the US national team is mostly being
given to the Title IX ruling that legislated equal opportunities
for men and women in colleges. This, however, ignores the extensive
club programs that augment the college teams and actually provide
the basis for young girls' involvement in the sport, long before
they reach high school or college age.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we should start looking beyond Title IX, because the
future of feminine football is elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The US national team has set some high standards and will not
likely improve very much while depending on the current system of
team selection. Meanwhile, Brazilian women who couldn't tell the
difference between Title IX and the Ten Commandments could be
setting the pace within a few years. Countries such as China and
Germany, Nigeria and Russia, have a chance to surpass the US
despite enormous cultural/sexist barriers. Even small countries
such as Norway can keep up with the US because of their club
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The US does not need to radically change its development system
because a club system already exists. Simply, the clubs that supply
the players to the colleges should be recognized for their role,
encouraged, and supported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
