<HEADLINE>
IN AUSTRALIA, A LOOK INTO THE `CURSE OF BLACKBUTT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKBUTT, Australia _ The pilgrimage began on the east coast,
in Brisbane, simply because my friend, Aurelio, likes to see where
memorable things and people got started. Since she does the
driving, how could I and a frequent passenger, Ron Sampson, object?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we were curious, too. For years I had wondered if such
a seemingly quaintly-named place, Blackbutt, even existed. Roy
Emerson, a jovial country boy and great athlete, had told me he was
a Blackbutt native. That was the first time he appeared at Boston's
Longwood Cricket Club to play tennis a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Emmo, as he's known, is also known as an energetic (though
good-natured) practical joker, certainly capable of fabricating a
hometown. Anything for a laugh. One time, at a place called Mermaid
Beach on the Queensland coast he took me, for a tutorial, into some
``very gentle surf so you'll get the feel of body-surfing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so gentle. Suddenly I was lifted, pitched, and spun so
vigorously to the sandy bottom that I had to look for my trunks
when I surfaced spouting and gasping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sorry,'' he guffawed loudly, ``I guess that was what we
call a dumper. You'd better get dressed again.'' After I retrieved
the trunks, the surfing lesson continued without further incident.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago Aurelio had met Emmo at Longwood where he was doing
TV commentary at the US Pro. Luckily she drew him as her partner in
the Bob Dunbar Memorial press tourney, a giggler at best, without
any idea that he was a Hall of Famer, holder of the record that
Pete Sampras is currently chasing: 12 major singles championships
(Pete entered Wimbledon holding 11.) But playing softly, sportingly
in the hackerly company he was keeping, Emmo didn't flaunt his yet
formidable prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Later, on learning of his accomplishments, among them
spearheading Australia to eight Davis Cups, she shrieked, ``Was
that really my partner!''
</P>
<P>
   None other. ``The pride of Blackbutt,'' I said. ``If there is
such a place.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brisbane we pored over maps, and _ voila! _ found Blackbutt
to the west in Nanangoshire. We would also find out about the
``Curse of Blackbutt.' According to a lifelong resident, Kevin
Allery, the Curse has been protecting native son Emerson's record
that has stood since 1967, and will shield him from Sampras and any
other predators. Allery's name had been given us by a friend,
Queensland authority James Corvan, with, ``Just ask anybody in
town. Everybody knows Kev.''
</P>
<P>
   The route took us past the intriguing Glasshouse Mountains, a
set of three 1,000-foot volcanic plugs where a Bostonian (that's
Boston, England), the exploring mapmaker Matthew Flinders, had
camped in 1799. They're near the tidy town of Beerwah amid
pineapple and sugar cane fields.
</P>
<P>
   An up-and-down rural drive, with the curving two-lane road
mostly to ourselves and logging trucks, it took us over the
Blackall Range and through small, neat towns such as Mapleton,
Montville, and Peachester, which has a race track for
thoroughbreds, and Kilcoy.
</P>
<P>
   Kilcoy's ``dunny'' (public toilet) is imposing, an architectural
masterpiece of brick with a step-stair facade, Romanesque archway,
and slate roof. ``A prize winner on any continent,'' proclaimed
Sampson. ``Worth a stop whether you need it or not.'' We stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Forests and cattle were numerous. The most compelling town was
Eumundi, home of another tennis player, Patrick Rafter, the US Open
champ who will visit Boston next week as the main man of the
Australian Davis Cup team. Eumundi's lively Saturday market and its
county fair atmosphere is famed throughout the region. The stalls
and platforms are crowded with artists, artisans, musicians,
dealers in a wide variety of foods and goods. Aurelio bought a
handsome dish from potter Barbara McIvor. Gary Sutherland quelled
hunger with his kebabs and falafels.
</P>
<P>
   We got there late, decided to stay, and that evening blue lights
sparkled as driver Aurelio was pulled over by a cop named Belinda
Weedman for a breathalyzer test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had anything to drink, constable,'' she pleaded in
most clearly enunciated voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a random check, the kind of thing we do on a Saturday
night,'' smiled Weedman. ``Blow, please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a rookie at this, but I'll do my best,'' said Aurelio,
puffing into the tube.
</P>
<P>
   Her heavy breathing was perfect. ``Have a nice evening. You're
sober as a judge,'' pronounced Constable Weedman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not some of the Boston judges I know,'' interjected Sampson, a
lawyer by trade.
</P>
<P>
   More mileage . . . and, at last, a sign _ BLACKBUTT, Est. 1888 _
informs the pilgrims they've arrived. The sign doesn't mention the
Curse that may be stalking Pete Sampras
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that Sampras could even identify Blackbutt, a
one-saloon town of 800 souls on the outskirts of nowhere. But the
residents, depending on cattle and timber for a living, can
identify him, all right: the Yank who wants to steal their bloke's
record, Emerson's 12 major singles (six Australian, two each
French, Wimbledon, US). For 32 years that mark has stood as firmly
as the dark-trunked eucalyptus trees from which the community gets
its name and substantial sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   Although Roy Emerson, 62, is too mature now to defend himself
from the covetous Sampras, the Curse seems as strong and protective
as ever. You can feel it lurking like the deadly snakes in the
grass where the Emersonian journey began. Eventually it became a
campaign of conquest of the rectangular citadels of New York,
London, Paris, and Melbourne between 1961 and 1967, as well as
unequaled Davis Cup feats.
</P>
<P>
   This rectangle, the rude, homemade ant bed court on which the
jocular Emmo first struck a ball, lies shrouded in deep grass and
weeds. It hasn't been played on for decades, since the Emerson
family moved off the dairy farm where he developed those strong,
sharp-volleying wrists by ``milking hundreds of cows as a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Such rural courts were widespread during Australia's planetary
supremacy when country boys served as prominent cogs. The
``Rocket,'' fellow Hall of Famer and pal Rod Laver, was launched
from one, on his family's Queensland station (ranch).
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, now a teaching pro at the Palace Hotel in Gstaad,
Swizerland, remembers, ``It wasn't hard to build one. With the
tractor you just knocked down some termite or ant hills that were
plentiful, looking like traffic cones. Spread the red grit on a
fairly level space. Put up a couple of chicken wire fences and a
net. You built it and the neighbors came to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the net posts remain in his tennis field of reveries, the
tips barely showing. They seem mysterious relics of a departed king
of long ago. Visiting what amounts to an Australian shrine _ though
virtually unknown _ amid low green hills and unending
bluer-than-blue sky is like poking around a pyramid where a pharoah
left his curse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, yeah, this is the home of the Curse,'' asserts 72-year-old
Kevin Allery, a Nanangoshire councilman and Blackbuttian since
birth. He believes, ``Sampras will never overcome it even though he
has 11 titles. I knew it when another dinkum Queensland boy, Pat
Rafter, beat him at the US Open last year. And what about the
others?''
</P>
<P>
   He means principally Bjorn Borg and Laver, who stalled at 11.
``The Curse,'' he says with a smile. ``Everybody thought those
two'd roll Roy, eh?''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Laver completed his second Grand Slam in 1969 at
the US Open, his 11th major. He was No. 1, a factor for another
five years who seemed a cinch. But . . ..
</P>
<P>
   Borg, a mere 25 on winning an 11th, the French of 1981, lost his
next two major finals, Wimbledon and the US Open, to John McEnroe _
and was through. Allery points out that greats Ken Rosewall, Jimmy
Connors, and Ivan Lendl had potential to go beyond their eight
titles, and McEnroe his seven. Were they accursed?
</P>
<P>
   Allery just smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson feels Sampras ``will break the record, and good on him.
Pete's a great champion. I didn't even know I held the record until
Pete started getting close.'' In 1967 Emmo took it from Bill Tilden
by winning his 11th, the Australian. Five months later he reached
his destiny's dozen at the French. ``Nobody talked about records
then. It wasn't mentioned in the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   He disclaims any involvement with the Curse, but Emmo has
friends. Allery hints at consultation with an aboriginal witch
doctor over in Morgo to give the Curse a booster. ``We want to keep
the record in Blackbutt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep it in Australia,'' says Beverly Knight of
Melbourne, perhaps the nation's foremost dealer in aboriginal art.
Therefore, she, too, has contacted a witch doctor on Emmo's behalf
in the Northern Territory. ``It can't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Long the town champion, Allery ``rolled Emerson _ and Laver,
too. Had 'em for dinner one after the other when I won the
tournament at Kingaroy.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson confirms: ``We were kids, but, yeah, Kev beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiry white-haired Allery, who has been cowboy, cane-cutter,
lumberjack, beams at the recollection. He beat the man who beat the
illustrious Tilden's record. However, if the Curse prevails against
Sampras there will be no gloating or dancing in Coulson Street, the
town's one-block main drag. Dominating the street on a corner is
the wooden L-shaped Blackbutt Hotel in cheery tones of blue and
yellow, two-stories with balcony and the welcome barroom. ``But,''
promises Allery, ``we may raise a glass whenever Pete loses a big
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaded by jacaranda and hoop pine, Allery is standing on a plot
of crimson earth beside the onetime Emerson homestead, a yellow,
one-story frame house on 5-foot steel stilts that encouraged air to
circulate in pre-AC days. About a mile distant, long-since razed,
was Nukku Grammar School. There Emmo was ``last in my class _ but
also first, the only one'' _ and sometimes followed to school by a
pet calf in the style of Mary's little lamb.
</P>
<P>
   As Allery peers downhill at the lonely, thickly overgrown
shrine, the farm's current proprietor, Eric Wilson, says, ``I'd be
careful about walking down there, mate. Lots of (lethal) brown
snakes. I shot a 5-footer in the pantry last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Pete Sampras snakebit by the Curse of Blackbutt as he treads
in Emmo's sneaker steps, or has the Curse run out of venom?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' says the amiable Allery. Meanwhile, he suggests
we go back his home where his pleasant wife, Jane, fixes tea for
the pilgrims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
