<HEADLINE>
DO YOU WEIGH LESS AT THE EQUATOR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Because the Earth is spinning, does a person weigh less at
the equator than at the poles?
</P>
<P>
   L.E., Charlestown, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you want to lose weight without giving up the ice cream
and pizza, head for the equator. The Earth is spinning on its axis
at 1,040 miles per hour. The centrifugal force at the equator
counteracts enough of gravity's pull that a person weighing 150.8
pounds at the poles, comes in at a svelte 150 pounds on the
equator. This new weight loss program is not all due to centrifugal
force, though. The spinning of Earth tends to flatten it out a bit.
It's wider across the middle than it is top to bottom. A person
standing on the equator is 13 miles further from the center of the
Earth than a person at the poles. The further you are from the
center of a mass, the less gravitational pull it exerts on you.
Thanks to Professor Maria Zuber of MIT for the calculations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do the planets keep spinning?
</P>
<P>
   N.F., no address
</P>
<P>
   A. Scientists believe planets formed when particles of dust in
post-Big Bang space either collided, or were drawn together by
gravity, the bigger one pulling in the smaller. As each piece was
drawn in to join the growing planet, it was moving as it arrived.
That got planets spinning a little bit. But as gravity pulled those
pieces in from the distant reaches of the solar system, everything
condensed, speeding up the spin, like a spinning ice skater pulling
in her arms. Since the material in each planet was moving in
different ways, they ended up spinning at wildly different speeds.
The spin of planets is changing all the time. Sometimes it's
because the planet gets whacked by some piece of space debris big
enough alter its rotation. But mostly planetary spin is being
altered by the gravitational pull from all the other large bodies
in the solar system: the sun, the other planets, and their moons.
The Earth has slowed a lot since the time when its moon formed 4.5
billion years ago. Scientists think that back then, the Earth spun
one complete revolution on its axis every 5.5 hours, compared to
today's roughly 24 hour spin cycle. And we're still slowing down.
The day gets longer by about one second each year, according to MIT
Geophysicist Tom Herring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
