<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-ART-BOS &LR;      07-06 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY TO FITNESS IS FINDING AN ACITIVITY THAT SUITS YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one corner, the forces for fitness and health; in the other _
longstanding lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the government, doctors, health insurers, and
employers have been warning Americans that their sedentary ways are
harming their health. People struggle with this knowledge, trying
to find the will to exercise _ and stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   But lethargy seems to be winning out, despite clear evidence
that it takes only moderate activity to reduce the risks of heart
disease and other conditions and invigorate body and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   What has appeared to be a fitness boom in recent years is
deceiving. An estimated 60 percent of US adults don't do enough
exercise to improve their health and 25 percent do none whatsoever.
So it's no surprise that 1 in 3 Americans is now considered
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   Many people say they're too busy to exercise, and technology _
home computers, remote controls, cars, elevators, escalators _
increasingly act as deterrents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, when they think about exercise, think about what
they had to do in high school P.E. or the military. That's what
keeps a lot of people sedentary,'' says Steven Farrell, an exercise
physiologist at the Cooper Institute for Aerobic Research in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But surprisingly, some of the newest data suggest that so-called
``lifestyle'' activity _ walking, bowling, doing yardwork, and so
forth _ may produce similar benefits to more structured exercise,
such as aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has so much evidence supported the value of
physical activity so non-strenuous that you don't need to shower
afterward, and which can be done in bite-sized, 10-minute segments.
The important thing is to make sure it adds up to 30 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers compared structured and lifestyle activity in
experiments that were reported earlier this year in the Journal of
the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, 235 sedentary men and women were assigned either
to supervised sessions of aerobic exercise (20 to 60 minutes five
days a week) or got to choose among moderate-intensity lifestyle
activities. After two years, the volunteers in the two groups had
made comparable improvements in activity, cardiorespiratory
fitness, blood pressure, and percentage of body fat. The
improvements translated into a 15 percent reduction in mortality.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the two years, the volunteers in the lifestyle
group had more effectively incorporated physical activity into
their routines.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the Cooper Institute, said this was the
first demonstration that sedentary people can make such positive
changes without having to go to a fitness center and do strenuous
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Generally though, ``most physicians find that it's awfully hard
to change people's long-term behaviors,'' says Dr. Steven Matfis,
an internist with Harvard Vanguard Medical Associates in Quincy who
is on a campaign to get his patients to exercise more. ``If you
just tell people, `I want you to do more activity' they say, `yeah,
yeah, I'll try' but it may not go much farther than that,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   While he has had some success and can name patients who are
doing more and feeling better, he feels it's an uphill struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The key, say experts, is for people to find something they enjoy
doing, because they're more likely to become active and stay that
way.
</P>
<P>
   For Beth Kirschen, 26, finding an activity she loved made all
the difference. For years, she tried gym exercises _ the
stairstepper, exercise bike, weights _ but soon tired of each of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years ago, she tried mountain biking and became
captivated by the strenuous sport that involves riding up and down
rugged terrain for hours at a time. Now she says she's in ``pretty
great shape'' and has added calisthenics to strengthen her upper
body.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone can, or will, exercise at this level. A person
needs to ask himself or herself, ``what am I trying to
accomplish?'' says Dr. James Rippe, a Tufts University School of
Medicine cardiologist and director of the Center for Clinical and
Lifestyle Research in Shrewsbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your goal is to lose weight or improve aerobic capacity,
the means will be different from someone who wants to lower their
risk of heart disease,'' says Rippe, ``and those will be different
from that of a 70-year-old who's trying to prevent osteoporosis.''
</P>
<P>
   But either way, says Rippe, you should adopt a ``mind-set of
always looking for the nooks and crannies in your life where you
can put some physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   For Peter Davis, a 64-year-old retiree, it was walking. He had
doctors' orders to stay active following a kidney transplant and a
cardiac bypass operation. But, he said, ``I got lazy'' and slowed
down. What got him going again was acquiring a dog that he walks
several times a day. ``I have a 5-minute route, a 15-minute route,
and a 30-minute route,'' he said in an interview from his summer
place on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he goes three times a week to a Boy's Club where he
walks on the treadmill and lifts light weights. Now, he says, he's
feeling stronger and sleeping better, and _ most important _ has a
better self-image. ``I was becoming a couch potato,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police Sergeant Richard Ham is 44, but he fast-forwards in his
mind to retirement. Policemen, he says, often let themselves go
physically when they retire, and they die earlier. He's determined
to avoid that fate, and so he's enthusiastically working out at
HealthPoint, the luxurious fitness center in Waltham, Mass. owned
by CareGroup, the health corporation, and has the new Boston
Celtics training facility on its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have Popeye muscles,'' says Ham, ``I just want
to feel good and be in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes four or five times a week to the center, where he works
out on a variety of machines. He's spent extra to get the services
of a personal trainer, which he calls ``a tremendous motivational
thing'' because she keeps him focused and has taught him how to do
the exercises correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The latest U.S. Public Health recommendation is that to enjoy
better health, everyone should accumulate, on most days, 30 minutes
of moderately strenuous activity. That can be brisk walking,
playing a sport, gardening, bicycling, or any other activity that
burns about 150 calories.
</P>
<P>
   This guideline was based on research that showed a sedentary
person who moves to this level of activity can significantly reduce
his or her risk of heart disease, diabetes, colon cancer, and other
conditions. More activity, of course, is better, but the greatest
incremental gain is in going from doing nothing to doing something.
</P>
<P>
   To improve fitness, the American College of Sports Medicine
recommends more strenuous workouts. For aerobic fitness, the
guidelines say you need to do 20 minutes of exercise, three days a
week, at an intensity that speeds your heart to 55 to 90 percent of
its maximum rate. That usually means jogging, running on a
treadmill, using a stairstepper, or doing some other form of
aerobic exercise.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, fitness experts say that everyone, particularly
older people, should use weights or exercise machines twice a week
to improve strength in the major muscle groups and increase bone
mass, chalking up 8 to 10 repetitions of each exercise. And
stretching exercises for flexibility should be part of the routine.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Rosenthal, who is 81, says he's gained confidence and
strength from a weight-training program for members 80 and above
run by his health plan, Harvard Vanguard Medical Associates, at its
West Roxbury, Mass.facility.
</P>
<P>
   He and other 80- and 90-year-olds spend an hour twice a week
going through arm and leg exercises with progressively heavier
weights. They've also been given bags to carry the weights home for
a third session during the week.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after two years, Rosenthal says he's stronger, has better
balance, and needs no help getting out of a chair. ``I have less
fear of falling from being off-balance, and that's important,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, Marie Warren, 64, discovered to her dismay
that she had been gaining a pound or two a year since age 50. When
she went to the doctor after a long interval, Warren was told she
was 30 pounds overweight, was developing diabetes, had high blood
pressure, and some abnormal blood cell measurements.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse practitioner Mary Kane in the Burlington, Mass. center of
Harvard Vanguard sent Warren to a dietician and put her on a
regimen of walking 30 to 45 minutes a day, as well as strength
training.
</P>
<P>
   Rippe, the Tufts cardiologist and exercise specialist,
commented, ``She got good health care. Good for her doctors for
saying that her weight was her biggest risk _ she had probably
tripled her risk of heart disease and quintupled her risk of
diabetes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated the idea of being sick, so I really buckled down,''
says Warren. Within four months she had shed her extra weight, her
blood pressure and blood sugar readings became normal, and she
says, ``I'll never feel the way I did in my 30s, but I think I
should feel better in my old age.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
