<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING IS GO FOR EUROPEAN TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the end of fighting in Kosovo, travel to Europe by
Americans is expected to accelerate through the summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is go _ again,'' said Joseph Buhler of Switzerland,
US chairman of the 29-nation European Travel Commission. There had
been reports that travel to Europe had ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Buhler said that the Kosovo conflict caused few cancellations to
Europe; however, a larger but unknown number suspended or delayed
bookings especially to the areas near Kosovo. ``We expect that most
of these people will renew their plans with their travel agents,''
said Buhler. ``Europe is just too good a deal to pass up.'' Buhler
said the European Travel Commission continues to forecast a record
5.95 million departures by Americans to Europe this summer, or 5
percent more than last year, and that this would be followed by a
record traffic in autumn when off-peak prices go into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the areas that have been affected by travel are
destinations in the Mediterranean region and cruises there and
along the Danube. Travelers who have put off plans for these
vacations might reconsider, especially now that many tours and
cruises are on sale. Reduced prices of from $100 to $500 a person
on tours to Greece are being featured in advertisments cosponsored
by the Greek National Tourist Organization.. ``These prices are
unbeatable,'' said George Kouros, director of the Greek National
Tourist Office in New York. ``And the options will suit any
style.'' For information, call the Greek Tourist Office at
212-421-5777 or send an e-mail to GNTO(at)greektourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   Buhler notes that Europe's calendar is full of unique events,
and ``we've even arranged for an eclipse of the sun (Aug. 11), with
the path of totality crossing the heart of Europe.'' For a free
copy of events and other information, call 800-816-7530 and request
a copy of ``Planning Your Trip to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nude week
</P>
<P>
   If you like to travel light, this is the week to do it: Nude
Recreation Week continues through July 11. Some 233 clubs, resorts,
and RV campgrounds in North America are participating with open
houses, festivals, and other events. If the thought of a
clothing-optional vacation is of interest, call the American
Association for Nude Recreation for the location of events:
800-TRY-NUDE or www.aanr.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kosovo help
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers are being sought to help Kosovo refuges rebuild their
lives. Cross-Cultural Solutions, a nonprofit organization that
regularly sends volunteers overseas to work on educational, health,
and social projects, is seeking people who can volunteer three
weeks and fund their own way to immediately assist ethnic Albanian
refugees along the Macedonian border. The program is not for
everyone, the organization reports. Volunteers should be over 21,
emotionally stable, and mature and willing to face potentially
disturbing situations, temperatures up to 100 degrees, modest
living arrangements, and uncertainty as to work assignments. The
program costs $2,400, including food, lodging, and staff guidance
but does not include air fare. For information, call Cross-Cultrual
Solutions at 800-380-4777 or, on the Web, visit
www.crossculturalsolutions.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   The 30th anniversary celebration of the Apollo 11 mission will
be held July 18-20 at the US Space &AMP; Rocket Center in Huntsville,
Ala. Apollo astronauts, including moonwalker Buzz Aldrin, will
attend. For information, call 256-837-3400.
</P>
<P>
   The rich music and dance traditions of the Southern Appalachians
will come to life in downtown Asheville, N.C., when performers hit
the stage during the 72d Mountain Dance and Folk Festival, and the
smaller and more spontaneous Shindig on the Green. For information
on the Aug. 5-7 event, call 828-257-4530. The Shindig on the Green
is being held Saturday nights now through Sept. 4. For more
Asheville information, call 800-280-0005.
</P>
<P>
   Just because Boston's Harborfest ends this week doesn't mean the
fun ends in Beantown. Next weekend marks the 70th All Star Game &AMP;
Weekend, and while not everyone can get into Fenway Park, the John
Hancock FanFest at the Hynes Convention Center promises lots of
activities for all ages. Later in the summer there's the 100th
Davis Cup July 16-18 and the Ryder Cup/PGA Sept. 19-27. For all
that's happening, call the Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau and ask for the 88-page Boston Travel Planner, including a
Family Value Pass loaded with discounts: telephone 888-SEE-BOSTON
(888-733-2678).
</P>
<P>
   The annual Native American Festival and Maine Indian
Basketmakers Sale will be held Saturday, July 10, at the College of
the Atlantic in Bar Harbor. Artists from the four Maine tribes _
the Maliseet, Micmac, Passamaquoddy, and Penobscot _ will
demonstrate and sell their work. Festival events include
storytelling, traditional drumming, dancing, and singing. Native
American food will also be sold. The festival is known for the
variety and quality of the basketry shown and sold. For
information, call the Abbe Museum at 207-288-3519 or visit
www.abbemuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th annual Stoweflake Invitational Hot Air Balloon Festival
is set for Stowe, Vt., July 9-11. More than 24 balloons will be
participating. Launches will be at 6:30 p.m. Friday and Saturday,
and 6:30 a.m. Saturday and Sunday. Festivities begin at 3 p.m. each
day. Admission is $5 for adults, with a chance for a free hot-air
balloon flight. For information, call Snowflake Resort at
802-253-7355.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lyme warning
</P>
<P>
   Vacationers headed to wooded, bushy, or overgrown grassy areas
might consider the new vaccine for Lyme disease, an infection
caused by bacteria transmitted via the bite of ticks that live on
deer or white-footed mice. ``But, the new vaccine might prove
tricky for travelers who do not plan their trips far in advance,''
said Dr. Cliff Dacso with the Travel Medicine Service at Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston. ``Recommendations call for vaccine
doses to be given in three injections over the course of a year.
Booster shots may be needed over time.'' Dacso noted that no
vaccine offers perfect protection protection so he encourages
nature enthusiasts to practice standard preventive measures such as
wearing protective clothing, using tick repellent, and removing
attached ticks s quickly as possible. Caught early, Lyme disease is
highly treatable. Left untreated, in rare cases the illness can
lead to a disabling arthritis and neurological problems.
Individuals who are at high risk are those who live or play in the
Northeast or Mid-Atlantic states, particularly along the coastal
areas from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Canoe adventure
</P>
<P>
   The legends of Lewis and Clark, mountain men, pioneers, and
native Americans will come alive on canoe voyages of discovery on
Montana's Upper Missouri River. Participants travel on modern,
34-foot'long voyageur canoes, which replicate those used by early
fur traders. Thirteen four-day and three six-day safaris will be
featured. Prices begin at $850. For information, call River
Odysseys West at 800-451-6034.
</P>
</TEXT>
