<HEADER>
A0335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-PROFILE07-COX     07-06 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-PROFILE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `There is nothing left ... I feel like I have died'
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar to REFUGEE.)
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Skender Rahimi, 41, is married and has three
daughters and two sons, ages 14 to 20. He worked as a technician in
a battery factory in Gnjilane, population 50,000, in Kosovo. He had
an eight-bedroom house, two tractors and land to grow corn,
potatoes and other crops for his family. He tells his story below.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing left of our past. I lost all those memories.
I feel like I have died. Everything is burned down of our home. The
Serb army took all our possessions out of the house _ the
furniture, the washer, dryer, clothes, photos _ and torched
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grenaded our village. Some people escaped, and those who
didn't they killed them. What possessions the Serbs couldn't carry
with them, they torched.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stayed after (the attack), they would shoot you down or
slit your throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even describe the terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any normal person with a normal conscience would never expect
they'd one day be forced to leave their homes and their way of
life. That's how we felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here two months in the United States. Our first
day in this apartment, our Vietnamese neighbor gave us some food
and this (root beer) soda. I feel bad as the head of the family
that I can't provide like I've done all my life. My wife, Vahide,
is also an outstanding tailor. And my oldest daughter had just
finished studying to be a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone were to give me U.S. citizenship, I would take it
right away. I would, and then go back to live in Kosovo, and if
things went wrong again, then we could come back with no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two sisters and a mother and father in Kosovo. I do not
know if they are dead or alive. They do not know if I am dead or
alive. They are always on my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something has happened to my sisters, they could give me
the whole United States and it wouldn't be enough. It wouldn't be
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Interview by Patricia Guthrie. Translation by Miro Vran.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0336 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES07-COX     07-06 2152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scarcity of jobs among problems Kosovar refugees face
 &HT;    (EDS: WITH PHOTOS AND SIDEBARS (REFUGEE-PROFILES and
REFUGEE-HELP.)
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They arrived with nothing and everything.
</P>
<P>
   And months after fleeing their homes and homeland in tears and
terror, that is what many Kosovo refugees still have as they start
over in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in terms of possessions. Everything in terms of the
people they love.
</P>
<P>
   They want to embrace their new country. But most have seen
little of it, beyond their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Their apartments are modest, yet functional and clean. Some pass
time in bare living rooms, sitting on metal folding chairs
patiently waiting for trucks to deliver donated furniture. Many
watch show after show on donated television sets, but usually only
the children catch a recognizable English word or two.
</P>
<P>
   Often, mothers and fathers share mattresses with sons and
daughters, while grandparents, uncles, nephews or aunts sleep in a
second bedroom. Wives and daughters try to cook familiar food, but
they're often stymied by not knowing the English word for a key
ingredient. Yeast to bake bread, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Although resettlement agencies provided a few days of
orientation that included how to count American money, call 911 for
emergencies, shop in a supermarket and ride MARTA, some refugees
lack the confidence to hop a bus or walk beyond the corner
convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gladstone Apartments in southeast Atlanta, one of several
new Kosovar enclaves, refugees are surrounded by neighbors who
don't look like them and cannot converse with them. Did they make a
mistake? Should they have waited it out, like the others they see
on CNN _ the hundreds of thousands of other former tent city
refugees picking up the pieces of their shattered towns in Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, I wouldn't want to go back right now,'' says Halim
Kaleshi, 35, who lives at Gladstone across the street from his
sister. ``I don't know if my house is destroyed or if anything is
left. And there are no jobs there, so why go back?''
</P>
<P>
   A construction worker, Kaleshi knows that eventually he would
find his kind of work in Kosovo, but too many land mines and acts
of revenge make it unsafe now _ and for who knows how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosovo, we all worked for the Serbs. They controlled
everything, so it is better for us here,'' Kaleshi says through
translator Miro Vran, a Croatian who lives in nearby Sandy Springs.
``Just give us a job. We can do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   About 300 Kosovar refugees have been resettled in Georgia by six
nonprofit agencies contracted by the U.S. State Department. The
refugees are spread throughout the Atlanta area: Decatur, Stone
Mountain, Marietta, Lawrenceville; 30 still reside at Jubilee
Partners near Athens, learning skills before they move to Atlanta
in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   They will be given a time frame, courtesy of Uncle Sam, when
they can return to Kosovo to live. But their towns must first be
declared safe, says Sgt. Major Hal Glassman, an Army reservist at
Fort Dix, N.J., where the Kosovars were formally processed. ``The
United States is sponsoring them all, and it is our feeling it is
not yet safe for them to go back,'' Glassman says. ``There will be
a six-month window after the military says it's safe to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees who decide to stay are expected to repay the federal
government the cost of their one-way flight once they get
established and have a job. The loan is about $3,000 for a family
of four to travel from Macedonia. All refugees coming into the
United States (78,000 are expected this year from all countries)
must sign this transportation loan. About half eventually pay it
back, a State Department official said; those who don't are marred
by bad credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 4,042 Kosovars taken in at Fort Dix has asked to
return. ``We haven't had any requests (to turn around and go back)
since the first flight or the last flight from Macedonia,''
Glassman says. ``I think the people who stayed here have a better
understanding of what's happening because we kept them informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more refugees were also processed in Macedonia and
flown directly to New York, then flown to their host cities.
Officially, the United Nations evacuation from Kosovo is over. But
5,000 people who had signed up for U.S. refugee status are still
arriving. The final tally expected: between 12,000 and 13,000.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds still at Fort Dix are expected to be in their new
American cities, ranging from San Diego to Sarasota, Fla., to
Detroit and Dallas, by Saturday. Then Fort Dix's Albanian village
will convert back to a military quarters for the National Guard and
Army Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal Refugee Act, the Kosovars are eligible for
cash assistance, food stamps, Medicaid, Medicare and Social
Security cards. But most choose not to accept cash assistance and
instead sign up for the Early Employment program, says Peter
Herbert, regional director for the International Rescue Committee.
</P>
<P>
   With Early Employment, people attend six weeks of English
classes and learn other skills while using food stamps in the
interim. The agency assists with job placement. Typical beginning
jobs are in manufacturing, hotels, restaurants or in their former
trades such as landscaping and auto repair; refugees with
professional degrees _ teachers, lawyers, physicians, engineers _
typically can't find work in their fields, because of licensing and
language barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Resettlement agencies commit to providing basic housing and
amenities for the first month, along with intensive case management
the first 90 days, including English and how to use public
transportation. Refugees also are linked to volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   After one year, refugees can apply for permanent residency.
After five years, they can take the U.S. citizenship test. They can
retain their U.S. citizenship if they return to live in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Seven U.S. Kosovars already have their citizenship because they
were born here. After the first boy_ named Amerikan_ was born at
Fort Dix, May 6, six more birthdays occurred, Glassman says. ``This
refugee effort was different from others in that we had a lot more
young mothers and a lot more children. And seven new American
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   They sit on a sloping grassy hill under the shade of an oak
tree, lighting GNP generic cigarettes with a communal orange Bic
lighter, and ponder the haves and have nots of their new worlds.
They are brothers, cousins, a brother-in-law, an uncle, nephew,
sons, or new friends.
</P>
<P>
   All live in small two- or three-bedroom brick Gladstone
Apartments. The complex of individual units and looping roads is
often used as a starting point for refugee and immigrant families,
and Catholic Social Services. The agency is now assisting 70
Kosovars, a number expected to soon double.
</P>
<P>
   As firecrackers pop in the distance, the men repeatedly express
thanks to the United States. ``I am very grateful for NATO and
President Clinton for what they have done,'' says Sylejman Dedushi,
a 30-year-old accountant. ``I hope they will solve the problem in
Kosovo and the situation will be much better. ... Now the world
knows we are just people. We're just trying to be who we are and be
left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Alive and intact with their wives, sons and daughters, they know
they are lucky. And, just now they are realizing how fortunate they
were under Fort Dix's ``Operation Provide Refuge.''
</P>
<P>
   There, they received medical and dental checks, vaccinations,
new clothes, toys and English lessons. Plenty of Albanian
translators helped them with American newspapers, magazines and
television news. They even heard ``Voice of America'' and the BBC
in their native language. And in front of 15 computers, they surfed
for Internet Yugoslavian news.
</P>
<P>
   They spent no money, and three times a day, they filed into a
mess hall for hot, hearty meals. Twice daily, the American Red
Cross drove around, Good-Humor style, giving out snacks. Even
Muslim prayer rugs were provided. And when they were sent off to
their new cities, each adult left with $50; teenagers, $20.
</P>
<P>
   But Fort Dix may have been too good. Now, there's not so much
hospitality or help. It's not for a lack of commitment from
resettlement staffs. It's the sheer numbers of this humanitarian
effort.
</P>
<P>
   While it sparked an unprecedented in-flow of clothes,
furnishings, cash and promises of volunteerism from Atlantans in
May, that enthusiasm has waned. The men in this new Albanian
enclave say they need more help translating, someone to drive them
on errands, take their kids to a playground, answer everyday
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Why, for example, have government documents needed to work been
slow in coming? Can someone explain the refugee entitlement system
to them again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I received a check for $140 to take care of seven people in my
family, but I don't know how long it is to last. A week, a month? I
don't know,'' says Mitat Berkolli, a 50-year-old who worked as
postal carrier in the capitol, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to complain. ... We are ready to work, to do
anything, absolutely anything,'' adds Kaleshi, the construction
worker. ``But many of us have not left this complex since we got
here. We don't know what Atlanta looks like. It would be great to
get on a bus and see downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again among the Kosovo men, two names are mentioned
with great warmth _ Rebecca and Michael. Both work for Catholic
Social Services, which has a community center at Gladstone
Apartments and a staff of 30. Rebecca is Rebecca Kloss, assistant
to the agency director, and Michael is Michael Gaertner, a
volunteer who often stops by to take them shopping, help with
English, and let the teenage boys send electronic mail on his
laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Kloss listened to their concerns recently and expressed as much
frustration as her clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time, time, it takes time. But knowing they want to work is
good, and we are trying as best we can to address all their
problems'' she says. ``But honestly, the situation is too many, too
soon. We've had seven families arrive in the last two weeks. Our
caseworkers are overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovars also present a unique challenge because they are
not a ``typical'' refugee from a poor country, Kloss says. They are
European, mostly upper-middleclass professionals with families used
to such material trappings as computers, cell phones, video games,
and nice cars. They are also an ethnic population not prone to
migrate, so there are few pockets of Albanians in the United
States, and hardly any in Atlanta, Kloss says. That means there's
no established Albanian community to help newcomers, unlike
communities for Vietnamese, African and Cuban refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one Albanian translator and we just hired him. We're
looking, but we haven't found another translator,'' she says.
Although many can understand other languages within the former
Yugoslavia, it's not easy to predict how they'll interact with
Croatians, Bosnians or others who might volunteer to interpret,
Kloss explains.
</P>
<P>
   Maryellen LeDuc, a volunteer with Catholic Services who teaches
English to the dozen Berkolli children every Tuesday, introduced
them to her Victoria Estates neighborhood near Emory University
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   They watched an Independence Day parade, ate watermelon and
communicated with hands and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is once my neighbors get to know them and where they
live, they'll start interacting with them,'' LeDuc says. ``One plan
I have is to take them all to a Braves game. The kids are getting
very excited about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Andi Williams, her husband, Jeff, and two children may soon live
above a Kosovar family being resettled by World Relief.
</P>
<P>
   In Peachtree City, the Williams family has a spacious basement
apartment to use as temporary housing for the refugees. Their
effort is just one of many at Providence United Methodist Church,
which is sponsoring the family. Another member is donating use of a
new home he just purchased, so the families can initially live
there, Williams says. Donated furnishings will fill it, and
mortgage and other living expenses have been raised to cover the
families' first three months.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a handle on golf-cart driving is also part of
resettlement for Williams' guests in the city lined with 60 miles
of golf-cart paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be easier for them instead of needing a car to drive,
they can just go to the grocery store or zip through McDonald's in
a golf cart,'' Williams says. ``The one thing we don't have is a
translator, but I think they'll understand when they see a golf
cart in everyone's driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
