A0340 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLAR-RACECAR07-COX     07-06 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAR-RACECAR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Race car team slaves away for solar car
 &HT;    By Erin J. Walter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's the middle of the night, and an incessant
buzzing noise fills the dark basement of the University of Texas
Experimental Sciences Building. The maintenance workers, who fill
the void during the day, have long since gone home, leaving the
cluttered, un-air-conditioned dungeon almost unattended.
</P>
<P>
   But not quite.
</P>
<P>
   In a workshop that, with fencing for walls, can only be
described as an oversized cage, members of the Longhorn Solar Race
Car Team slave away for their master, a solar car named Solstice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an obsession,'' said Amrou Al-Sharif, team president and
recent UT mechanical engineering graduate. ``In the past year I've
only taken two classes. My senior design project was on the plan to
race this car. Sometimes we sleep in the shop.''
</P>
<P>
   The solar race car team, a club of about 30 students from
various academic disciplines, has whittled down to a few seriously
devoted engineering majors during the past three months. The
reason: Sunrayce '99, a race in June that took student-built solar
cars on a 10-day trek along the East Coast and demanded major time
commitments from student automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite many sleepless nights in the basement, the Longhorns did
not get the Solstice car completed in time for the race. But club
members traveled to West Virginia for the trials, working on the
car along way.
</P>
<P>
   That determination in the face of probable disappointment has
been typical of the team, which placed second in the 1991
California Clean Air Race and fourth in the 1996 American Tour de
Sol, Al-Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In April, we drove 24 hours to the Michigan trials just to be
there and see how we fit in,'' he said. ``They gave us the Yearn to
Learn award for the university that drove the farthest knowing they
couldn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that race season is over, Austin's resident solar-power
enthusiasts are turning their attention to local audiences. The
club plans to complete the car this summer and take it on a tour of
schools and businesses to generate interest in solar and electric
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you drive a solar car to work and park it out in the sun
for seven or eight hours, it could be charging its battery while
you work,'' said Gary Hallock, team adviser and UT engineering
professor. ``It could make a good commuting vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Solstice racer is not much smaller than a normal car, but it
sits low to the ground to reduce wind resistance. The car contains
a 15-horsepower motor, weighs about 850 pounds and has just enough
room for one driver. Seven hundred 4-by-4-inch solar cells cover
the vehicle's tubular aluminum frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car has no air conditioning, and it isn't the most
comfortable thing in the world to be driving,'' Hallock said. ``But
the machining and parts are like a work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept for that unconventional artwork was hatched two
years ago, but limited money meant the team could not buy parts and
start building the car until a few months ago. While schools near
automotive centers, such as Detroit, had little trouble finding
money, the Longhorns did everything from selling nachos at Wal-Mart
to digging into their own pockets to pay for the $120,000 car,
Al-Sharif said. Ford Motor Co. chipped in $5,000, and the
university added $2,000, but much of the money raised came from
Adopt-A-Cell donations from members' friends, family and
professors.
</P>
<P>
   The team has vowed to zoom past the checkered flag at the next
Sunrayce, in 2001, but for now is back in the basement workshop it
has called home for so many nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the classic underdog challenge,'' said Dave Conrad, the
team's corporate relations chairman and a recent UT mechanical
engineering graduate. ``We go up against schools with 10 times as
much money as us. I couldn't pass that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin J. Walter writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: ewalter(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
