<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-COST07-COX     07-06 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-COST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas legislation price tag increased
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If anyone wants to recreate the 1999 legislative
session, here are the necessary ingredients: 140 days, 181
lawmakers, a governor eyeing the White House, a freshman lieutenant
governor, hordes of lobbyists and about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. With the final bills trickling in, state lawmakers
spent about $20 million during the five-month session that began
Jan. 12 and ended May 31.
</P>
<P>
   That's nearly one dollar for each Texan, or $3,000 per bill
filed (nearly 6,000) or $12,000 per bill passed (1,638, including
some resolutions).
</P>
<P>
   While that's a big number, it's merely a drop in the state's $94
billion budget bucket _ and not enough, according to at least one
government watchdog organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need and deserve more staff and information and resources
to make their decisions,'' said Tom `Smitty' Smith, head of Public
Citizen in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A penny-wise legislative budget costs pounds later, Smith said.
That's because Texas' 150 House members and 31 senators often rely
on lobbyists and special interest groups that provide incomplete or
misleading information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the relatively short period of time that our Legislature
has to debate multibillion-dollar budgets and policies that
literally affect the rest of the nation, it's shortsighted to keep
them on such tight budget,'' Smith said. ``We ought to provide our
legislators with the tools they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a former legislative staffer, said he's seen lawmakers
and staffers rely on lobbyists for information about bills because
lawmakers have inadequate information before voting on bills.
</P>
<P>
   Texas spends a healthy amount on its Legislature, compared to
other states. For fiscal year 1997, which ended Aug. 31, 1998,
Texas ranked fifth in the nation in total dollars spent on the
Legislature, but 41st nationally for legislative spending per state
resident, according to the National Conference of State
Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million figure for the 1999 session is less than half
the money lawmakers set aside for all legislative spending from
Sept. 1, 1998, to Aug. 31, 1999. Other money goes to interim
studies, keeping the lights on and preparing for the next session.
</P>
<P>
   The amount spent on the Legislature _ an amount lawmakers decide
during debates on the overall state budget _ has steadily
increased. In fiscal year 1993 _ Sept. 1, 1992 to Aug. 31, 1993 _
Texas spent $51.25 million on the House and Senate. During the
current fiscal year, lawmakers set aside $59.11 million for the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Erickson is a senior research analyst for the national
legislatures conference. Despite increases, she said, legislative
spending remains at less than 1 percent of the overall budget in
every state, including Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that legislative branch expenditures, compared
to other government expenditures, are very small,'' Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   So how can Texans decide if they're getting enough bang for
their millions of bucks? Suzy Woodford, head of Common Cause Texas,
said it depends on who's asking the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not people will consider it money well-spent
depends on whether they got the legislation they wanted,'' she
said. ``I'd say that's conservative (spending).''
</P>
<P>
   Woodford agreed lawmakers need more resources and flexibility to
hire more staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to rely on somebody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sullivan, spokesman for the Senate's presiding officer, Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry, said the best way to assess spending is consider
how much the Legislature accomplishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature meets infrequently, spends frugally, works
effectively and then goes home to live under the laws that they
pass,'' he said. ``The Texas Legislature accomplishes more in 140
days than many states do in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bender, director of communications for the House, said
technology and hard work from representatives help keep costs down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great difference between our Legislature _
particularly the House _ and say, Congress, because so much of the
work on researching and drafting legislation is done personally by
the members rather than being completely done by staff,'' Bender
said. ``The House has made significant investments in new
technology and information systems that make the members and the
public better informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan also said legislative staffers, about 1,500 of them,
and smart lawmakers spend the money wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never have too much information, but the process works
well,'' Sullivan said. ``The citizens have been well served.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: jelizondo(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
