<HEADER>
A0343 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC07-COX     07-06 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emission woes? Find trained mechanic
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About this time last year, I was trying to find a
repair shop for my daughter's car after it had failed its emissions
test. I created a fictitious though probable situation, a NOx
failure, and called around to various shops in search of repair.
</P>
<P>
   I asked specific questions about mechanics' credentials and shop
equipment for repairing emission failures. Unfortunately, the
results of my calls confirmed my suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of auto repair shops that can competently diagnose and
repair vehicles that fail the state emissions test is indeed
shallow. However, the situation is far from hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   If your vehicle fails its emissions test, the inspector is
supposed to hand you, or direct you to, a blue-and-white pamphlet
containing information about what to do if your vehicle fails.
</P>
<P>
   I know that when your car fails the test, the last thing you
want to be bothered with is reading, but this little document
contains a bunch of great information. I know _ I helped put it
together.
</P>
<P>
   The insert headed ``If your vehicle does not pass the
inspection, don't panic'' is a valuable guide that will point you
in the right direction for getting your car fixed. It's not
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The use of technical terminology is prefaced by: ``When
selecting a repair technician/mechanic, ask a few basic questions.
Relax. You don't have to understand the questions; just make sure
the answers are yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds easy enough so far, right? Let me elaborate on some of
the items that you want a ``yes'' answer to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has your mechanic recently completed a state-certified
emission repair or factory training program, or are they
ASE-certified in A6 and A8 and L1 categories?'' Ask to see their
certifications.
</P>
<P>
   Several states provide for or require mechanics performing
emissions test failure-related repairs to complete an approved
course. Georgia's course, which is offered at four area technical
schools, is voluntary. Mechanics who pass the course are issued a
certificate from the school they attended and get blue patches for
the sleeves of their uniforms. These help consumers identify those
who have passed the state training.
</P>
<P>
   Factory training is good for new cars but is not much help with
older vehicles that fail the test. A mechanic's ASE certificates
should be displayed in a customer access area. They have a light
gray background with a blue gear in the upper corner. One with a
blue gear and a gold sticker is better.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanic's name and status will be printed in large type.
The areas of proficiency (A1 through A8) will be listed to the left
with the corresponding expiration date on the right. A6 and A8
certifications pertain to electrical systems and basic engine
performance. These are minimal skills when repairing emissions
failures.
</P>
<P>
   The L1 credential, for advanced engine performance, is a
separate certificate signifying the mechanic has passed a special
test on vehicle computer controls and emissions systems, ideal for
dealing with these types of failures.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to expiration dates of certifications. Additional
certificates issued by aftermarket companies, such as Snap-On Tools
or NAPA in the areas of fuel, electrical, ignition and gas
analysis, are also a good indication that the mechanic is keeping
abreast of current repair technologies and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC07-COX     07-06 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
