<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0345 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Complaints about TV show illustrate sex-education divide
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If you've ever wondered what state-run TV is like
in other countries, you'd have had a sense of it one night last
March on local ABC affiliate KXXV.
</P>
<P>
   That night the station essentially handed over a prime-time hour
to the state for what would appear to be a very good cause:
teen-age abstinence from sex.
</P>
<P>
   The program, ``Parents, Teens, Sex and Answers,'' was presented
as if a KXXV news production and introduced on the news set. In
effect, though, it was co-produced by the state _ by the McLennan
County Collaborative Abstinence Program _ MCCAP.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAP has a two-year budget of $657,950 to deliver an abstinence
message to the teens of McLennan County. That's from a pool of $50
million authorized by Washington in the welfare reform act of 1995,
funds administered by the Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Many will praise it as a good deed by KXXV, by a Republican
Congress and by Austin. But here's what others said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We can no longer depend on this station for newsworthy
information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dismayed by the lack of accurate and significant
content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did this program exclude some necessary information,
but (it) was extremely misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   The statements were contained in letters to ABC and KXXV
management from local viewers including some physicians. Their
general thrust: While abstinence is a commendable theme, the
program offered no balance on a controversial subject.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it didn't. The program did what the state funded MCCAP
to do, which is present one side of a public issue. Abstinence
education as funded by the '95 Congress meant abstaining from that
balance.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the program leaned heavily on the asserted
fallibility of condoms to protect against sexually transmitted
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``A condom is of little or no value in protecting patients from
the (human) papilloma infection,'' read an on-screen graphic.
</P>
<P>
   But Emory University's Contraceptive Technology, using Centers
for Disease Control data, says that used consistently and
correctly, latex or plastic condoms ``provide highly effective
protection against bacterial and viral STDs (sexually transmitted
diseases).''
</P>
<P>
   It's a point MCCAP not dare acknowledge. Advocacy against sex is
its mission, and condoms come with sex, or so we must hope in the
age of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Condoms do pose risks, and do not provide 100 percent protection
against disease. Yes, there's no such thing as ``safe sex.'' But
there is safer sex. Dismissing condoms because they don't provide
100 percent protection from STDs is like saying, ``Don't bother to
wash your hands. You'll still get germs.''
</P>
<P>
   In a ``focus group'' portrayed on the program, no one supported
teaching students about contraception in sex education class. (The
only thing we should teach about contraceptives, says the
abstinence-only line, is that they fail to protect.)
</P>
<P>
   The focus group was portrayed as a sampling of people just like
you and me. But in a broader sampling released in June by the
Sexuality Information and Education Council, nine of 10 people said
information about contraception, birth control and condoms should
be given to high schoolers in the context of abstinence-based sex
education.
</P>
<P>
   Though MCCAP's sexuality education curriculum is being used in
school districts throughout the county, its abstention from a
balanced discussion of contraception in part led to its rejection
by Waco Independent School District trustees after the WISD Health
Advisory Council opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's more than one side to the spiel Congress funded and
MCCAP promotes. The goal is worthy: abstinence. Too bad it doesn't
deem open discussion just as worthy.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
