<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0346 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-PRECAUTIONS07-COX     07-06 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PRECAUTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K stockpiling supplies available through Internet
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Barry Levinson was part of the problem. In his
view, he's now part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   The computer consultant said he helped write some of the old
codes that have hobbled the world's computers, setting up a
potential year-end crash because they can't read the digits 00 as
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Levinson isn't one of the army of computer programmers doing
remedial coding to fix the Y2K bug. Instead, he started stockpiling
emergency food supplies for his family, as a hedge against major
economic disruptions, then turned to selling emergency food to
others on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife said I was nuts,'' Levinson said. ``I told her it's
like insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Y2K analysts increasingly see a diminishing of such fears among
the public. The Rev. Jerry Falwell, for instance, recently took
down his alarming Web site on Y2K, saying he now foresees fewer
problems than he once did.
</P>
<P>
   But some people in the Austin area are still following
Levinson's and other Y2K entrepreneurs leads, despite assurances
from government and business that the computer bug is being fixed
and will not close banks and groceries, turn off electricity or
water, hogtie the police or cost people their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Electric generators, for instance, which can replace
utility-supplied electricity if they are powerful enough, have been
selling well in the Austin since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not selling them as feverishly as we were back in March,
but we still get calls every day,'' said Bill Bellinghausen, a
salesman with Austin Power Generation Systems. ``Not everyone buys.
Some have sticker shock. A nice (generator) is probably $1,200.
They go up to $25,000.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stadtmiller of Austin bought a generator for his home,
where he also stockpiles emergency food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling people for five years to get their beans and
Bibles ready,'' said Stadtmiller, who hosts a satellite radio
program called Truth Radio which focuses on possible Y2K
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Energy, the city-owned electric utility, discourages
people from hooking generators to homes ``because they impact the
system and may cause a problem,'' said utility spokesman Ed Clark,
such as starting fires or interrupting utility service to other
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the utility announced it is ready to provide
electricity on and after Jan. 1, 2000, with no anticipated
disruptions. But Levinson said some people won't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see brownouts and disruptions,'' he said. ``It's not the big
cities that are going to be the problem. It'll be the little ones,
and they'll demand power from the rest of us. We're so dependent on
technology that if the electricity was cut off for just a few
weeks, well.''
</P>
<P>
   For every official assurance that the Y2K bug won't be as
fearsome as alarmists predict, Levinson has an anecdote to turn the
conversation in the opposite direction. There's his friend in
Washington, D.C., for example, who recently packed up his family
and moved to New Zealand. Why New Zealand?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never communicated that,'' Levinson said. ``My guess is
it's a more civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinson recently sold his CSIN.com (``America's Discount Source
for Y2K Supplies``) because the business was becoming more than he
could handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Nutting, operations manager at Banna Bay Trading Company,
understands. Last spring, Nutting couldn't keep MREs in stock. The
military's Meal Ready to Eat comes in cases of 12 for around $80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers had dried the supply up and were driving up the
price,'' said Nutting. ``We're still selling quite a few, but it's
tapered off considerably.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadtmiller, who took over Levinson's CSIN.com, thinks emergency
food is a viable business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales have slowed due to the government putting out
misinformation on Y2K,'' Stadtmiller said. ``It was running half a
million dollars a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinson got out of the food business to devote time to a new
Web venture, Letsgotobelize.com, which sells condominiums and
building lots in the Central American nation of Belize to Y2K
worriers who want to leave the country until the anticipated
disruptions ease.
</P>
<P>
   Belize isn't as far away as New Zealand, and some Texans already
vacation there, so it's familiar territory and a good place to buy
a vacation home. And, being relatively untechnological, Levinson
said, Belize isn't expected to have many Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson got rid of his family's emergency food stockpile. He
doesn't need it anymore. He's got a waterfront condo in Belize
where he plans to spend New Year's with family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if everything's fine afterwards, we'll come back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: dstanley(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
