<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0348 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAGRANGE-TEXAS07-COX     07-06 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAGRANGE-TEXAS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History has been fickle in its dealings with La Grange
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA GRANGE, Texas _ If not for Sam Houston's mile-wide stubborn
streak, this could have been the capital of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Austin got the lawmakers and lobbyists while La Grange
found fame down other paths _ a fruit-topped pastry and a
whorehouse widely acclaimed as the best in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   History, you understand, has been fickle in its dealings with La
Grange.
</P>
<P>
   And yet this town halfway between Austin and Houston deeply
appreciates its past. Maybe because every visit to La Grange's
courthouse square is a 1950s tour of bakery smells, window shopping
and pharmacies that deserve an ``apothecary'' sign out front.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one block off the square is a 102-year-old railroad
depot, its ornately carved gables painted dark red and green. This
building is for sale _ the minimum bid a reasonable $35,000. But
before scraping together the earnest money, know that the depot
will not necessarily be sold to the highest bidder, but to the best
potential user.
</P>
<P>
   How else to keep history from being demolished or carried off to
grace another town?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would just would break my heart to see something happen to
it,'' said Gale Lincke, a La Grange railroad buff who intends to
bid for the depot. ``You look at it and you can picture the steam
training pulling in, the women in petticoats . . . with carriages
pulling up to carry them home.''
</P>
<P>
   This German-Czech town has lost other old buildings to nearby
communities that lacked La Grange's long history, but sought to
capitalize on the cachet of age. That won't happen this time.
</P>
<P>
   The La Grange Area Chamber of Commerce bought the depot in 1981,
fixed it up and outgrew it 10 years later. The chamber moved into
the renovated county jail _ where the hanging rope is on display
and prankster ghosts are said to prowl _ and rented the depot to a
beauty shop, a hair salon and today's tenant, a video rental shop.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to get out of the real estate business, said Margo
Johnson, the chamber's president.
</P>
<P>
   Sealed bids are due by July 28 and will be evaluated by the
chamber's board based on price, intended use, time line for repairs
(the slate roof needs a $6,000 fix-up), whether the depot would be
moved and whether the new owner will accept deed restrictions so
the building cannot be moved or torn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that the depot needs some attention,'' Johnson
said. ``It probably needs to be turned into a museum, but the
chamber doesn't have the financial wherewithal.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsure anybody would be interested in the depot, Johnson made
her first telephone call to Lincke, one half of a husband-wife
train enthusiast team who think nothing of driving for hours and
waiting late into the night, all to see a certain train whistle by.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what rail fans do. This is their high,'' said Lincke,
who runs a Hallmark card shop out of the courthouse square's oldest
structure, built in 1855. ``Rail fans are a nutty bunch of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Just nutty enough to offer to buy the depot, said Lincke, who
serves on the boards of the local school district and Lower
Colorado River Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The city has also stepped in, led by a train nut of its own _
Arnold Romberg, ``a rail buff and City Council member, in that
order,'' he said by way of introduction. Romberg envisions a museum
and public meeting space that would anchor the town's grand plans
for new sidewalks and improved pedestrian access.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just history. It's the future, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the ways of government are slow, Romberg said, and he's not
sure the City Council can meet the chamber's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be a problem. A coalition is forming between the
city and its train nuts, both of whom envision a rail museum
stocked with memorabilia sitting in attics from days when rail was
king in La Grange.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means that we can preserve this thing, I'll buy it,''
Lincke said. ``But I think it will be a group of citizens willing
to invest and work with city.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber has received three letters of intent to bid on the
depot _ from the Linckes, the city and a La Grange woman who did
not state her intentions. Interest has been high, and other
possible buyers have expressed interest in turning the depot into a
pub or artist's studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first wanted to sell it, we were concerned nobody
wanted to buy it. Now, everyone wants it,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   When the train line came through La Grange in the 1850s,
everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   A wave of settlers brought expanded business opportunities and a
building boom. La Grange became a center for trade. The train shook
up the social scene, putting folks a relatively quick ride away
from the big city. Rail's heyday ended as highways and the
automobile took precedence, and the last passenger train stopped in
La Grange sometime in the late 1940s or early 1950s. Left behind
was the depot built by the Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railroad in
1897 to replace a 12-year-old station that had burned down.
</P>
<P>
   A postcard bearing a 1910 postmark shows the train station has
changed little beyond a darker coat of paint, an air conditioner,
landscaping and a paved parking lot. Many windows contain the
original glass, and the charm of the wood-finish interior can't be
hidden by peeling paint or flashy posters advertising the latest
video release. Sliding wooden doors still open into a rough-hewn
room where cargo once was stored.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,423-square-foot depot, appraised at $34,760, sits on a
quarter acre.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other intangible factors that inflate the
station's value to a city changed by rail, Romberg said. ``We have
a nice downtown here, and this is one piece of that fabric,'' said
the rail buff.
</P>
<P>
   The Lukas family has been serving fruit-topped pastries known as
kolaches for 52 years. On good days, Lukas Bakery's intoxicating
aroma wafts across Main Street to envelope the Fayette County
Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Made fresh every day, by hand, no preservatives,'' Lucille
Lukas said with evident pride.
</P>
<P>
   A five-decade resident of La Grange, she was pleased to hear
that the old depot will be staying right where it is. ``I thought
somebody would probably buy it and move it off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Weikel's Bakery near Texas 71, Lukas Bakery is
helping redefine La Grange as a kolache capital. But for every
pastry-minded motorist stopping for sweets, there's another visitor
asking after La Grange's most famous attraction _ the Chicken
Ranch, the nearby brothel that inspired the play and movie, ``The
Best Little Whorehouse in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothel shut down in the early 1970s. Nothing is left, and
you couldn't get there anyway, Johnson said. It's all private
property.
</P>
<P>
   Such notoriety is a sore spot for residents who, given the
choice, would not have their town's name synonymous with sin.
Others are like artist Sally Maxwell, who shrugs her shoulders,
noting that any publicity is good publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixed bag,'' Johnson admits. ``But when people get
here, they see there's so much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson believes the town's population has begun to slowly swell
as casual visitors drop in and fall in love. La Grange has about
4,200 people, up about 250 this decade. So instead of rushing to
find that One Big Employer, the city's chamber of commerce is
working to help existing businesses grow one or two employees at a
time. And business and civic leaders are working to preserve
buildings, like an old train station, that connect La Grange to its
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are standing up and taking notice,'' Johnson said.
``The town was built around that depot. It has always played a
major role.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: clindell(AT)statesman.com
</P>
