<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0349 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-MIATA07-COX     07-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-MIATA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miata's 10th birthday treat
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If not for modesty, Mazda should have gone ahead and
called its 10th anniversary special edition of the MX-5 Miata a
``collector's car.'' The sapphire blue convertible with two-tone
interior is just exclusive enough _ 7,500 for sale worldwide, with
about 3,000 destined for North America _ to qualify for that
status.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost a given that it will, too, with Miata owners being
such a rabid lot that the Miata Club of America has 30,000 members
and a ``Save the Wave'' campaign urging owners to flash their
lights and trade salutes when they meet on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that most Miata owners have such fun driving
their cars that they're reluctant to turn loose of the steering
wheel and shifter. Mazda has made playing with the latter even more
fun by shortening the throw so that what was a snick-snick
operation now is a snicksnick process. There's another gear to play
with, too, and having six speeds instead of five does make for
easier touring on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessors, however, the '99 Miata _ no matter
whether it's the $19,770 standard model or the $26,875 anniversary
edition _ is best appreciated on two-lane roads. Sure, you see them
buzzing through heavy traffic in the city and on expressways, but
anyone who says they're comfortable mixing it up with
sport-utilities, vans and trucks whose tires are taller than the
48.3-inch two-seater has fallen victim to over-the-top Miata mania.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable, though. The Miata continues to offer the
sort of driving pleasure and appeal that marked its debut in 1989
and triggered what can only be called a rejuvenation of the
two-seater market, which includes pricier offerings such as BMW's
Z3, Mercedes-Benz's SLK, the Plymouth Prowler and the Panoz
roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Although refined during its decade-long run, the Miata remains a
car that forces its driver to remain in touch with the road, with
plenty of inputs. Feel the bumps, feel the turbulence, feel the
power being fed to the rear wheels and feel the sheer pleasure of
driving a car so basic and simple that the nonpower top can be
raised and lowered without ever leaving the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   The seating is a bit cramped for many because there's only 37.1
inches of headroom with the top up, and almost any driver's knees
will get jammed. Top-up driving also means stopping way short of
overhead traffic lights in order to see them, and the canvas top
does little to eliminate external noise.
</P>
<P>
   The body-color-matching top is the first other than black or tan
for the Miata. Its two-tone, blue-and-black interior is another
first. The colors of the blue synthetic-suede-and-leather seats are
matched by the three-spoke steering wheel and shift knob.
</P>
<P>
   Both the regular and special edition '99 get a seven-horsepower
boost to 140, with peak power coming at about 6,500 rpm, about
1,000 rpm more than the point at which the four-cylinder engine's
torque crests at 119 pounds-feet.
</P>
<P>
   That's sufficient power to give the 2,299-pound Miata zing,
provided the shifter _ no automatic for this version _ is
frequently and properly employed. Maneuverability is exceptional,
thanks to the Miata's short wheelbase (89.2 inches) and a slightly
stiffer suspension that keeps the '99 nearly dead level during
turns.
</P>
<P>
   The collector, uh, anniversary edition clearly isn't for
everyone who wants a two-seater because of its inflated price. But
it does stand out, as does the lesser version, in a niche market
segment catering to traditional sports car enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Mazda MX-5 Miata 10th anniversary edition
sports car
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $28,225 (base: $26,875)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 1.8-liter, four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (140
horsepower), six-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, optional power anti-lock disc
brakes ($550)
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: air conditioning, $900
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 24 mpg regular unleaded city; 29 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
