<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ It only takes nanoseconds after any new item
lands on the public agenda these days before sides are chosen up
and a new battle in the culture war is declared. Consider, of all
improbable matters, urban sprawl. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ A man who identifies himself as Reverend Matt
Hale Pontifex Maximus says his church does not advocate violence or
illegal activity. But anyone reading the sect's manual or other
documents on the Web would easily come to a conclusion that
violence is exactly what it proscribes and can assume that Benjamin
Nathaniel Smith paid close attention to it while gunning down
people. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ If you've ever wondered what
state-run TV is like in other countries, you'd have had a sense of
it one night last March on local ABC affiliate KXXV. That night the
station essentially handed over a prime-time hour to the state for
what would appear to be a very good cause: teen-age abstinence from
sex. Many will praise it as a good deed by KXXV, by a Republican
Congress and by Austin. But here's what others said: ``We can no
longer depend on this station for newsworthy information.'' ``I was
dismayed by the lack of accurate and significant content.'' ``Not
only did this program exclude some necessary information, but (it)
was extremely misleading.''(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ Will not move today.
</P>
