<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-PRECAUTIONS - AUSTIN, Texas - Barry Levinson was part of the
problem. In his view, he's now part of the solution. The computer
consultant said he helped write some of the old codes that have
hobbled the world's computers, setting up a potential year-end
crash because they can't read the digits 00 as the year 2000. But
Levinson isn't one of the army of computer programmers doing
remedial coding to fix the Y2K bug. Instead, he started stockpiling
emergency food supplies for his family, as a hedge against major
economic disruptions, then turned to selling emergency food to
others on the Internet. Y2K analysts increasingly see a diminishing
of such fears among the public. The Rev. Jerry Falwell, for
instance, recently took down his alarming Web site on Y2K, saying
he now foresees fewer problems than he once did. But is it wise to
take Y2K lightly? (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: ATTENTION: TEXAS EDITORS.
</P>
<P>
   LAGRANGE-TEXAS - LA GRANGE, Texas - If not for Sam Houston's
mile-wide stubborn streak, this could have been the capital of
Texas. Alas, Austin got the lawmakers and lobbyists while La Grange
found fame down other paths - a fruit-topped pastry and a
whorehouse widely acclaimed as the best in Texas. History, you
understand, has been fickle in its dealings with La Grange. And yet
this town halfway between Austin and Houston deeply appreciates its
past. Maybe because every visit to La Grange's courthouse square is
a 1950s tour of bakery smells, window shopping and pharmacies that
deserve an ``apothecary'' sign out front. (Lindell, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
