<SLUG> BC-FITNESS-TAEBO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAEBO: IT CAN TIE YOU UP IN KNOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDWARD M. EVELD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First came Tae-Bo. Now Tae-Bo injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Tae-Bo fitness craze, with its rhythmic kicking and
punching, added a new spark to aerobic exercise routines. For some,
though, Tae-Bo also is offering new ways to get injured.
</P>
<P>
   Some Tae-Bo exercisers, energized at first by the martial
arts-like movements, are turning up with muscle strains, painful
hips and lower backs, even injured knees and elbows.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Morgan of Lee's Summit tried an exercise videotape by
Tae-Bo pro Billy Blanks. She developed so much hip pain she needed
eight physical therapy sessions to get over the strain.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan hadn't done Tae-Bo before, but she regularly worked out
with aerobics tapes and lifted weights. Although she thought she
was performing the kicks as instructed, she figures she didn't have
the technique down just right. The pain lasted for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might still do the tape but eliminate the kicking portion,''
said Morgan, who has two young children. ``I don't have time to be
down like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hensley, a physical therapist with St. Luke's-Shawnee
Mission Health Systems, has seen several Tae-Bo injuries. People
who aren't used to the moves can suffer strains to the groin, hip
and lower back, among other places, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're kicking and you're not stabilizing your spine,
you're going to twist your pelvis,'' she said. ``It rotates and
gets locked.''
</P>
<P>
   What's good about Tae-Bo, said Jody Schnakenberg, an aerobics
instructor at Gold's Gym in Westport, is that it uses large muscle
groups while providing aerobic exercise. And it's popular with men,
who sometimes shy away from other aerobics classes. But the
potential for getting hurt is real, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can easily injure yourself because this is a little bit
more about body and posture alignment,'' Schnakenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Knees and elbows are other danger spots, she said. Exercisers
throwing hard punches and kicks, who make the mistake of fully
extending their arms and legs, can suffer joint damage.
</P>
<P>
   The American Council on Exercise in San Diego lauds
cardio-kickboxing exercises such as Tae-Bo because they can improve
strength, aerobic fitness and flexibility. The movements can
enhance reflexes and balance. But correct technique must be
learned, and even basic kickboxing classes require above-average
strength and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to do Tae-Bo, here are some ideas from local experts
and the American Council on Exercise to avoid injuries:
</P>
<P>
   - Because of the potential for muscle strains, do more
stretching and warming up than you would ordinarily do for an
aerobics class.
</P>
<P>
   - Reduce the time and intensity of your workouts until your body
adapts. Many Tae-Bo classes move too quickly for beginners _ or
even for those who do other aerobic exercise.
</P>
<P>
   - Get help learning proper form and technique before jumping
full-speed into a class.
</P>
<P>
   - Beginners should specifically avoid high kicks until they gain
flexibility and become familiar with routines.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't lock joints when kicking or throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't wear weights or hold dumbbells when throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch the infomercials, you see so much grace,''
Schnakenberg said. ``But when you teach it, you see people just
trying to find their center of gravity. You're not going to be a
pro. It takes awhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
