<SLUG> BC-TV-CHRISROCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHRIS ROCK: BIGGER &AMP; BLACKER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Chris Rock struts back and forth across the stage of the
Apollo Theater in New York, the question is not whether he'll say
something outrageous, but just how shockingly funny it will be.
</P>
<P>
   In his new special, ``Bigger &AMP; Blacker,'' debuting Saturday on
HBO, the outspoken comedian takes caustic aim at racism, police
brutality, homophobia, corporate greed and single mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, single mothers. Rock's tendency to confront social issues
without apology or compromise places him in the tradition of such
earlier satirists as Richard Pryor, Lenny Bruce and Dick Gregory.
</P>
<P>
   It also sets him apart from the prevailing trend toward
gross-out comedy, as exemplified by ``There's Something About
Mary,'' last summer's box-office smash, and ``Big Daddy,'' the
current Adam Sandler hit.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in ``Bigger &AMP; Blacker'' _ Rock's first special
since the Emmy-winning ``Bring the Pain'' in 1996 _ the comic
challenges the notion that violent movies and song lyrics were
somehow to blame for the recent tragedy at Columbine High School:
``Whatever happened to crazy? Did we eliminate crazy from the
dictionary?''
</P>
<P>
   He goes on to suggest that if Americans really wanted a safer
society, they'd focus less on gun control and more on bullet
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bullet costs $5,000,'' he concludes, ``there'll be no
more innocent bystanders.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock also questions whether Hillary Clinton, notwithstanding her
popularity among some people, can really be called a ``hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, she ain't,'' he insists. ``Aquaman's a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hour-long special, the comic is constantly in
motion, his jokes exploding like land mines in his wake, his
insights into the American mentality at once eye-opening and
side-splitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock is out there to entertain, but I have the feeling that
he's also trying to say something about a society _ that it's not
simply yucks for yucks' sake,'' said Mel Watkins, author of On the
Real Side: A History of African American Comedy (Lawrence Hill).
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he is being accepted, that he's doing as well as
he is, is very encouraging. Because it means that there is an
audience out there that wants something outside of the `Dumb and
Dumber' genre of comic entertainment. It means that something else
is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In his performance style, Rock combines the persuasive rhythms
of the African-American preacher with the street-smart cool of the
hip-hop generation, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's put the two together, and it's a very interesting
combination,'' he said. ``That's one of the things that make him so
viable. If he didn't have part of that hip-hop cadence, he wouldn't
be able to appeal to the young audience the way he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rock has a definite edge.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the ``Pain'' special, he earned instant
notoriety when he invoked a racial expletive to explain the
difference between African-Americans who behave civilly in public
and those who don't. The routine was shocking but courageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes, humor is something that certainly is going to rub
some people the wrong way, that some people are going to find
objectionable,'' said Daryl Dance, author of Honey, Hush!: An
Anthology of African American Women's Humor (W.W. Norton).
</P>
<P>
   ``But one characteristic, historically, of black humor is that
it looks at our situation as black people in this nation,'' she
said. ``And he's just as hard on the black community as he is on
the white community.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock's ability to say outrageous things without alienating his
audience has as much to do with his formidable technique as his
innate likability, said Joe Keefe, a producer with the Second City
improvisational theater in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't demand that you agree with him, necessarily,''
Keefe said. ``He just demands that you think it's funny. Whether
you like him or not doesn't really matter that much to him. And
because of that, people love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout ``Bigger &AMP; Blacker,'' the camera is constantly
recording the faces of audience members (most of them
African-American) as they register I-can't-believe-he-said-that
expressions. And not just because of Rock's frequently blue
language.
</P>
<P>
   Such reactions are not unlike those elicited in the 1950s by
such comics as Bruce, Mort Sahl and the team of Nichols &AMP; May.
</P>
<P>
   But Rock is also in the tradition of savvy, envelope-pushing
African-American artists like Pryor, Gregory, Moms Mabley and Redd
Foxx (pre-``Sanford and Son''). Indeed, in matters of race, Rock
can say some things that no white comic, in these days of political
correctness, could possibly get away with.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe noted that comedy today is in some ways more restrained
than it was in the socially conservative 1950s or the politically
volatile '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '50s and '60s, the Cold War, and civil unrest in the
United States, gave you an awful lot of opportunities for
material,'' he said. ``But today the climate's different. People
have to be so damn careful about what they say, and how they say
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The response among many comics is to play it safe, emphasizing
sex and toilet jokes to the exclusion of anything that might
genuinely engage the intellect. Hence the popularity of ``There's
Something About Mary,'' ``Booty Call,'' the Austin Powers films and
the Sandler ouevre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attraction to titillating sexual references, an
attraction to juvenilia, that I thought we'd passed,'' said
Watkins. ``But Rock stays away from it. Much like Richard Pryor, he
tends to take comedy and human beings and society more seriously,
and to deal with humor in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Rock chastises single mothers for being too lax in
bringing up their children, he does so with a barely submerged
affection. His real point is not that some of them are
irresponsible, but that we live in a society in which things can be
completely out of balance and no one notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satirists are usually people who are struggling to understand
the world themselves,'' Keefe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to figure things out, and through that, they
see the hypocrisies or the oddities of society. And that's how they
get to their comedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1102EDT &QL; 
