<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOSSILS-THEFT (San Francisco) _ The remains of dinosaurs are so
enormously prized that they attract high prices _ at potential risk
to the low-budget science of dinosaur research. Complete dinosaur
skeletons command prices in the millions, which encourages thieves.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   MORMONS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ The Mormon Church has quietly
instructed its California followers to offer financial and
political support for a ballot initiative banning gay marriages _ a
move that mirrors the church's $1.1 million effort in Alaska and
Hawaii. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SF-ELECTIONS (San Francisco) _ Along with choosing a new mayor,
San Franciscans will vote Nov. 2 on whether to outlaw some ATM
fees, rebuild the Central Freeway, and increase their access to
city records and meetings _ assuming that petition signatures
submitted to the elections office are valid. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-FAILURE (San Francisco) _ About 2 million PageNet
customers in a dozen Western states had a two-hour interruption in
services when the wireless messaging company suffered a power
failure at one of its California hubs. By The San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LUXURY-SPENDING (San Francisco) _ There's a robust market for
luxury goods and services. That market _ fueled by the powerful
combination of low unemployment, low inflation and a record- high
U.S. stock market _ is thriving nationwide, as consumers flush with
cash and confidence are demanding and getting the best. By DAVID
ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE-SURVEILLANCE (San Francisco) _ Ever find yourself
watching the clock at work? Be careful, it may be watching you. The
increasing miniaturization of video surveillance equipment is
making prying eyes at the workplace a common occurrence. By BOBBY
McGILL.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONNIE-STEVENS (West Hollywood, Calif.) _ ``Cricket'' has grown
up and become a cosmetics mogul. Who would have thought it
possible? Connie Stevens, the adorably perky blonde whose sunny
disposition and kewpie-doll looks decorated the '60s TV series
``Hawaiian Eye,'' has been selling her Forever Spring skin-care and
makeup line on Home Shopping Network for the past 10 years. By
CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEW-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ There is a reason why Janet
Evanovich's latest mystery featuring Trenton, N.J., bounty hunter
Stephanie Plum has hit the Top 10 list in fiction. The witty
dialogue and crazy plot twists make you laugh almost non-stop as
you speed through ``High Five'' (Martin's Press, $23.95. 292
pages).By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
