<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED, WHITE AND BLUE FOR A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Where I was brought up there were three things
you didn't talk about: sex, money and patriotism. In New England,
these are powerfully private matters.
</P>
<P>
   In my family, at least, flag wavers are as distrusted as those
who flaunt their wealth or sexual conquests.
</P>
<P>
   Where I live now there is only one thing you don't talk about:
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco Bay Area, in many circles anyway, you can
wave anything sexual or financial, but not the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   Except one day a year. On the Fourth of July, all of us,
liberal, conservative, old American or new American, can glory in
Old Glory. On that day, any shyness about displaying the flag
disappears.
</P>
<P>
   We go to small town parades, city parks and fireworks shows, and
we observe that all Americans are people of color, namely red,
white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   Rich folks who don't know Thomas Paine from Paine Webber wear
Ralph Lauren sweaters with American flags on the front, and I don't
even resent them. They love this country, not just the money it
gave them.
</P>
<P>
   Poor people who probably think the Concord Bridge is a overpass
on Interstate 680 wave flags, and they know exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   They love this country, despite the money they haven't made yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth of July is one day we are liberated from tired
debates about anti-flag burning amendments, or cant about American
imperialism. It's our flag, the flag of those who made this
country, freed the slaves, defeated totalitarianism and marched for
civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   We wave it for a while, and then we go to barbecues and watch
fireworks. We talk about baseball, movies, cars or the stock
market, not patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it ought to be. This is America, not Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Bay Area, not a Republican convention. Patriotism is
something to be demonstrated when needed, not proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   I got to thinking about this when I was back on Cape Cod for
vacation. My folks had a cocktail party and invited two of my
father's former scientific colleagues. The three men sipped white
wine and reminisced about the work they did together in the '50s
and '60s. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., or Rep. Tom
DeLay, R-Texas, wouldn't have been able to follow the conversation
about underwater acoustics, but Tom Clancy might have.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the days when they learned how to listen to
all the noise in the ocean. My dad and his pals were part of the
team that developed the SOSUS net of underwater listening devices
that tracked every Soviet submarine in the seas.
</P>
<P>
   To put it baldly, these three gentle Ivy League intellectuals,
including my father, who fought the loyalty oaths demanded of
professors during the McCarthy era, helped defeat the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they'd never say anything that silly, immodest and
perhaps inaccurate. What they loved was science, and at the time
they were scientists solving problems in the national interest, two
words that nowadays sound almost old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't a Clancy novel. It's not as deadly dull, for one
thing. It also isn't a fight between good guys on the right and bad
guys on the left.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union's might was neutralized by liberals as well as
the less liberal, and by mild-mannered academics as well as
military men. My father and his colleagues knew many of these
military men as colleagues and friends, and I don't think they ever
talked about patriotism. They talked about the same kinds of things
we talk about at our Fourth of July barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   What I know for sure about my father is that he is a true,
unapologetic liberal, and heaven help those who say liberals are
unpatriotic. He wouldn't say a conservative who wraps himself in
the flag is desecrating it. My dad would just say he's a blowhard.
He used that word a lot during recent impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Already I've talked too much about patriotism, at the risk of
violating family rules and Bay Area customs. But let me say a
little more.
</P>
<P>
   I like the way we take our caps off and how everyone sings along
with the National Anthem at ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   I like the way suburbanites carrying flags set up folding chairs
hours before the start of small-town Fourth of July parades.
</P>
<P>
   I like the way the contingent of Vietnam veterans always gets
the biggest hand, at least in the towns of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   I like the fact that no one has to say why.
</P>
<P>
   My father and I differed on many things during that war, and I
like the fact that we don't now.
</P>
<P>
   I like the way my dad once stood on a beach in Cape Cod, pointed
out to sea and said, ``Once there was a Soviet missile submarine
right out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He just shook his head. He didn't have to say anything else.
</P>
<P>
   We went home and fired up the barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
