<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-SURVEILLANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMILE (AND WORK): YOUR EMPLOYER MAY BE WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ever find yourself watching the clock at work?
Be careful, it may be watching you.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing miniaturization of video surveillance equipment
is making prying eyes at the workplace a more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by the American Management Association, a New
York-based trade organization with 70,000 members, found that 32.8
percent of major U.S. companies record and review employees
communications and activities while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance is used by employers as a productivity tool, to see
who is working and who is not. Others see it as a security measure,
particularly in technology-sensitive manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The minuscule size of today's high-resolution cameras are an
Orwellian dream come true, said David Simms, a private investigator
with Robert E. Morton and Associates in Danville, Calif. ``You can
put them in a fan, a smoke detector, a light switch, you can put
them in any number of places,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yuriko Crehan, vice president of marketing for Advanced
Electronics Group Inc., a Los Angeles-based manufacturer and
distributor of surveillance equipment, explained that many of the
cameras her company sells to businesses are for covert
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warehouses usually use a wall clock or smoke detector, offices
use a pencil sharpener or computer speakers or sometimes a lamp,''
Crehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Butts is the security manager at NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. Though he declined to give specific
details about the laboratory's video surveillance, he was
forthright about the use of technology for monitoring the employees
as well as potential intruders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use about every camera you can think of, covert or overt,''
Butts said. ``We are trying to head off internal threat problems
and external threat problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Fineran, a spokesman for the National Association of
Manufacturers, a 14,000-member trade organization, said employees
shouldn't fret over what he sees as an overplayed threat to their
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a great headline: `Your boss is spying on you.' If
you didn't know that, you should,'' he said from his office in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Fineran acknowledged the possibility of abuse. ``There are
mid-level managers and small business owners out there that I would
not want to work for because of what they can do, and what they do
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees may have little legal recourse to challenge the use of
surveillance equipment. There is a common law of privacy in every
state, but that is very rarely used in surveillance cases, said
Lewis Maltby, the director of employment rights for the American
Civil Liberties Union in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But not every employer likes the covert approach to
surveillance. Kevin Saucier, director of safety at Guess Jeans Inc.
in Los Angeles, prefers to use visible cameras. ``It keeps a lot of
people honest,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
