<P>
   ON THE BEACH: In ``Against the Tide: The Battle for America's
Beaches,'' Cornelia Dean, science editor for The New York Times,
writes about the reasons buildings are constructed along the beach
fall, the measures taken to prevent their falling again, the
failure of those measures and solutions for the whole soggy mess.
(Includes 3-column color photo of a home in Alabama destroyed by
Hurricane Georges and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: OSMOND: Former teen idol Donny Osmond details his
painfully emotional battles with panic attacks in his new
autobiography. (Includes 1-column B&AMP;W photo of Donny Osmond
performing and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMRADES: Few authors can match Stephen Ambrose's ability
to portray men in action. So it is surprising that Ambrose
confesses in ``Comrades'' that he seldom experienced the kind of
bonding among men that he evokes so powerfully in his books.
(Includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Peter Gay writes of the most revered name
in classical music, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. The Penguin bio gets
to the heart of the musician's genius. (Includes 1-column color sig
of columnist and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
