<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, July 7. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   MOSEN _ Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan and Sen. John Ashcroft
release their campaign finance reports for the first six months of
the year. Steve Kraske.
</P>
<P>
   CARE _ Until she reached 92, Mildred Bengston maintained her
independence. She lived alone in the same Kansas City, Kan.,
neighborhood she had called home for 40 years. And with her
daughter and grandchildren nearby, help was always at hand. But in
spring 1996, she became bedridden with assorted ailments. The
nation's home health-care system, which through Medicare has helped
many elderly patients stay out of costly hospitals and nursing
homes, stepped in to help. A nurse treated Bengston at home three
times a week. But the system is in a tailspin, rocked by financial
and regulatory restrictions. For millions of in-home patients
throughout the country, the outlook is unsettling. David Goldstein.
35.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER: Will he or won't he take the job? Pascal Forgione Jr. has
until 2 p.m. to respond to the Kansas City school board's offer of
a three-year contract. And just who is this guy any way? We have
lots of background already collected. Checking whether Forgione
will show up in Kansas City Tuesday. Photo. Phil O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   LITES: After a shaky start and a few unforeseen glitches, the
highly-touted nighttime brightening of Kansas City is starting to
show some results. About 10,000 new streetlights gleam in the city.
Nearly 7,000 more are under construction. And about 11,000 more are
in various planning stages. Graphic, possible photo. Matt Stearns.
30.
</P>
<P>
   NOEL: Little Noel, Mo., has only 1,200 people. But the town
garnered two nominations for a HUD Best Practices award. The city
got its accolades for literacy and housing programs for the
immigrants that have moved into town. Trisha L. Howard. 20. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   RACES: Speeding cars hurtle down the straightaway, but pile into
each other on the turns. Some spin out of control. Some overturn.
It's a sight that would cause gasps of anguish at Indianapolis or
Daytona. But heck, this is Pleasant Hill, and these are
radio-controlled cars. The fanatics are out there every Friday
night. Robert Carroll. 28. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SEED. For years now, a group of scientists and pilots in western
Kansas has carried out an aggressive seed-clouding program with the
goal of reducing the damage hail does to crops in the Great Plains;
they say farmers out there love the program, and the group recently
claimed it may have been responsible for heading off a potentially
damaging tornado; trouble is, experts in the field say there is
absolutely no evidence that this government-funded program has any
effect at all. John A. Dvorak. Graphic
</P>
<P>
   GRAPE. For many teen-agers who feel they suffer the woeful fate
of being from Johnson County, a sliver of salvation sits in the
middle of an Overland Park strip shopping center, flanked by a
Hy-Vee and a Tanner's. The Grape Coffee House and Bar ``is an oasis
in a sea of absurdity,'' 19-year-old Joe Sandor says. Mhari Doyle.
22. Pix.
</P>
<P>
   LOOT: Kansas is again mounting a campaign to unload unclaimed
money and property entrusted to the state's treasury; someone in
Johnson County may have $81,000 coming, but the biggest jackpot is
a cool $250,000. John L. Petterson. 25.
</P>
