<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SYMPHONY-BOS &LR;      07-06 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SYMPHONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING INTO THE FUTURE OF THE MUSIC OF OUR CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When Michael Steinberg arrived as music critic of the
Boston Globe back in 1964, he ignited firestorms of controversy.
``When,'' he asked after the premiere of Leonard Bernstein's
``Kaddish'' Symphony, ``will Lenny grow up?''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg has spent a distinguished career stirring up
controversies ever since, in posts (one wants to write ``from
pulpits'') at the Boston Symphony Orchestra, the San Francisco
Symphony, the Minnesota Orchestra, and the New York Philharmonic.
But he has also lived long enough, argued and advocated his causes
so persuasively, that many of his beliefs have become truths
universally acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Last month he was the keynote speaker at the annual meeting of
the American Symphony Orchestra League, a service organization that
brings together orchestra managements, board members, and
supporters. Steinberg's address was fervently applauded in Chicago,
and it reached a wider audience when it was printed in the Sunday
New York Times. His subject was the music of the 20th century: what
orchestras must do about it, and why; what stands in the way; what
orchestras can do, and how.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was brilliantly and entertainingly argued. Speaking
of the standard repertory, the 50 ``greatest'' pieces that are at
its core, Steinberg said, ``Too often we are on cruise control. `Oh
yes, the Brahms First, isn't that nice,' and we tick off the
familiar events much as we register a familiar series of subway
stops or cross streets or highway exits on our way to work. . . .
Onstage, too, `Oh, the Brahms First again' is not an unfamiliar
response _ probably without the `isn't that nice' attached. But
that is not what it is about. . . . That is not why Friedrich
Nietzsche said that without music life would be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg believes that one way to keep Beethoven or Brahms
fresh is to give them ``new neighbors at table''; the challenge for
orchestras is to choose those neighbors in such a way as to assure
lively conversational interaction _ and to attract rather than
repel the audience that is paying for the experience. Steinberg
spoke of programming skills, of the necessity for honesty in
marketing, and, above all, of the importance of conviction in
performance (Serge Koussevitzky, he said, ``didn't mess with focus
groups or count how many bows he had taken; in fact, if a work had
not gone down well, that could be all the more reason for bringing
it back: he believed the piece needed to be heard, and that was
enough''). He also spoke of ways of making the audience feel at
home, through intelligent program notes, occasional and carefully
prepared comment from the stage, enterprising use of new
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg's speech left little room for disagreement, but a
panel afterward viewed the same landscape from the differing
perspectives of orchestra manager (Deborah Borda), composer
(Christopher Rouse), music director (Robert Spano), and the media
(John Rockwell of The New York Times, and this writer).
</P>
<P>
   Borda commented on the progress that had been made over the
years, noting how 50 years ago network radio refused to broadcast
some of the New York Philharmonic's performances of Mahler
symphonies _ works that are now central to the repertory. She
referred the audience to the model of museums, which are enjoying a
particular flush of popularity. ``Museums are `with it' and
`happening.' We need to ask ourselves why and how that happened. I
think accessibility is part of the answer _ the flexible
scheduling, the pricing, the element of choice, the quality of the
educational materials and merchandising, the dress codes. Museums
have created an accessible and personalized experience. Opera's
rise in popularity is directly correlated to the introduction of
surtitles that make the experience more accessible. What we have to
think about is how to relate to our audiences before, during, and
after concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   Borda emphasized a need for variety in programming but also for
coherence: ``We don't want to display an undifferentiated
inventory, to be a restaurant serving sushi, nouvelle cuisine, and
pizza on the same plate.'' She too looked at technology, citing a
study that established that it took radio 38 years, and television
13, to make the impact the Internet has achieved in four. She also
emphasized the importance of spending money on improving the
product. ``Imagine the difference it would make if we invested 2
percent of our annual budget on preparing for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Spano pondered some paradoxes. ``Music is ephemeral. It passes
through time and is gone _ yet we box and market music as eternal
masterpieces. Musical history is fueled by the creative impulse,
but our orchestras function as museums. And great art has not
always had market value.'' He then talked about some of the things
the Brooklyn Philharmonic has done to attract and hold on to its
audience; the most important of them ``was to make the assumption
that our audience is extremely intelligent, and eager to make
connections between old and new, exotic and familiar. It is a
mistake to program apologetically, and marketing should always
reflect what the content actually is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell spoke not only out of his experience in journalism but
from his years as artistic director of the Lincoln Center Festival.
He spoke in particular of ticket pricing, which tends to reduce
potential audiences at the concert hall and the opera house. ``What
we found is that the highest-priced tickets for special events like
Pfitzner's opera `Palestrina' and the lowest prices substantially
sold out, but the bulk of tickets in the middle price range didn't
sell.'' He also referred to the paradigm of Pierre Boulez's ``Rug
Concerts'' at the New York Philharmonic in the early 1970s. The
period atmosphere would have to change _ back then, a sideburned
audience in bell-bottoms sat on rugs because there were no chairs _
but the informal ambience of exciting, affordable, challenging
programs could and should be re-created.
</P>
<P>
   Rouse spoke of the necessity for an ``organized plan'' for
presenting new music. ``There is a lot of accessible modern
literature that makes a good place to begin. We lived too long with
the assumption that anything `easy' must be by definition inferior;
we celebrated inaccessibility for far too long. Programs must be
pragmatic and responsive to the needs of the constituents.'' Rouse
conveyed his belief that there is plenty of new music that excites
and moves an audience on first hearing _ and that awakens and
rewards curiosity to hear more.
</P>
<P>
   This writer, in a contrarian mood, wondered about just how
personalized the blockbuster museum-show experience can be; more
than once he felt herded and hurried past the Monets before being
dumped to spend as much time as he wanted in the gift shop, where
he could buy souvenirs of an experience he really hadn't had.
</P>
<P>
   He also charged at the billowing red flag of the word
``accessibility.'' Access to the arts is a real and serious issue;
``accessibility'' of the art lies in the eyes and ears of the
concertgoer _ and in the conviction of the performers. The string
quartets by Elliott Carter are now part of the permanent
chamber-music literature because of decades of brilliant advocacy
by committed ensembles; Carter's no less masterly orchestral works
have not entered the repertory not only because they are difficult
for performers and audience, but because there have not been
conductors and orchestras to lead and play them with comparable
belief and persistence (conductors like Oliver Knussen and Spano
are beginning to do the job). ``Trust us,'' said the Juilliard
Quartet, and they rewarded our trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accessibility'' has increasingly been used as the most
important criterion for quality rather than one possible such
criterion. ``Accessibility'' has been used to mask all kinds of
lazy, opportunistic, and retrograde work that both panders to the
audience and condescends to it _ too often if the marketers are
telling us something is accessible, they mean it will make
Khachaturian sound avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ``elitism'' has become a code word for
anything challenging and therefore unmarketable and undesirable.
Everyone wants an elite baseball team, dentist, plumber, brain
surgeon, and auto mechanic. The only places where the American
public doesn't seem to want quality are in the arts _ and in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, there can be quality in evey genre of music. New
York composer-critic Gregory Sandow rose from the floor to make the
common-sense observation that Proust will always be less popular
than Hemingway, a Rossini overture more ``accessible'' than
Mahler's Ninth Symphony. That does not make either work better or
worse than the other, more or less necessary. Accessibility and
elitism are not parallel to good and bad; the qualities intersect
at different angles.)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the American Symphony Orchestra League convention any
visitor would have been struck by a dual commitment _ to quality of
every kind, and to the challenge of finding new ways of putting
quality onto the marketplace and making it competitive there. The
marketing department and the artistic direction of a symphony
orchestra, or any other cultural enterprise, may not be natural
allies, but they are also not natural enemies; they need each
other. Spano cited the most provocative paradox of all when he
said, ``A donkey with a load of holy books is still an ass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
