<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BURNT-OUT CASE OF KENNETH STARR AND THE IC LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's finally over.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law _ created 21 years ago to end the
president's abuse of power _ last week was laid to rest in order to
end the independent counsel's abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   The law's origin was honorable. It was enacted primarily in
response to the ``Saturday Night Massacre'' of 1973, when two
attorneys general resigned rather than carry out President Nixon's
demand that they fire Watergate special prosecutor Archibald Cox. A
generation later came independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
five-year, $40 million investigation that began with Whitewater but
resulted in the impeachment and acquittal of President Clinton over
a White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The public and Congress _ well aware of the difference between
high crimes and misdemeanors and a private sex scandal _ decided
that they had had enough of Starr's unlimited abuse of power and
taxpayer money. And the public proved to be a lot wiser than those
conservative Republicans who thought they could fool enough
Americans into believing that Clinton actually committed crimes so
serious as to warrant removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   What the public actually saw was Starr's office evolving into a
version of the Spanish Inquisition, a dangerous and far-reaching
political body answerable to no one, yet determined to bring down
the Clintons and destroy the lives of several close friends and
associates.
</P>
<P>
   To a lesser degree, controversy over independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh's investigation of the Reagan administration's
Iran-Contra affair also played a role in the law's demise. But
Starr is the main reason the law was allowed to lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Now control over independent counsels has been returned to the
attorney general, as it was before the enactment of the law. The
attorney general has the power to appoint or remove a special
counsel as well as define what will be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concern of some that an attorney general could abuse
those privileges, events of the last few years demonstrate that it
is far better to have such a law under his or her control than
under the unlimited authority of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every member of Congress, including House and Senate
Republicans who unsuccessfully tried to use Starr's report to
remove Clinton, wanted the law to simply expire as of Wednesday
night. Attorney General Janet Reno and Starr agreed, perhaps for
different reasons, that the law was too flawed to even try to
repair or amend. Reno, like other members of the Clinton
administration, saw the law as far too abusive to be allowed to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Starr no doubt saw that his use and abuse of the law did more
damage to his own reputation than it did to his chief target,
Clinton. Starr himself suggested that his lack of popularity was a
key reason why he decided to end the Whitewater investigation by
working out a plea bargain with Webster Hubbell, former associate
US attorney general and an Arkansas friend of the Clintons, rather
than go forward with a scheduled August trial.
</P>
<P>
   By pleading guilty to a misdemeanor involving failure to pay
income tax and failure to disclose a potential conflict of
interest, Hubbell will do a year's probation and no jail time.
Starr claimed he could prove the charges against Hubbell, but
decided not to go forward with a trial because, according to
reports, he suspected the public sentiment against him would prompt
a jury to acquit Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is more than coincidental that Starr's Whitewater
investigation ended the same week, almost to the day, that the
independent counsel law came to its end. After all, they owe a lot
to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, meanwhile, said last week that he was trying to wrap up
other investigations not related to Whitewater. He was apparently
referring to his probe into whether Hillary Rodham Clinton had a
role in the 1993 firings of the White House travel office staff,
and an aspect of the Kathleen Willey case involving a Maryland
developer and Democratic Party contributor.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr wants a chance to repair his damaged reputation, he
might consider dropping those investigations now rather than face
more professional embarrassment and more public outrage over his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Republican and Democratic presidential hopefuls might
appreciate Starr fading from the public eye and the political
landscape during the campaign. None would care to see their names,
or faces, next to his in the news.
</P>
<P>
   What they, and the electorate, want to see is the end of another
era highlighted by an unwanted but stern test of our democratic
process. The nation survived Starr and his abuse of the independent
counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   With both fading into history, the nation can look to the future
with hopes of a brighter, if not more enlightened, era.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
