<HEADLINE>
HISTORIAN PURSUES BULLRING'S ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DEATH AND MONEY IN THE AFTERNOON 
A History of the Spanish Bullfight 
By Adrian Shubert 
Oxford University Press, 270 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To its followers, bullfighting is an enthralling display of
grace and bravado, a tantalizing primal dance to the death between
man and beast. In his classic meditation on the sport, ``Death in
the Afternoon,'' Ernest Hemingway spoke of ``the emotional and
spiritual intensity and pure classic beauty that can be produced by
a man, an animal, and a piece of scarlet serge draped on a stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for centuries, bullfighting has also been lambasted as an
orgy of savagery and stupidity. Spanish intellectuals have long
decried the best-known spectacle of their homeland, which Eugenio
Noel characterized as a symbol of everything that is ``negative,
corrupted, bastardized, deteriorated.'' Some writers, belonging to
the group known as the Generation of 1898, even went so far as to
blame bullfighting _ in their estimation, evidence of a nation's
failure to modernize _ for Spain's defeat in the Spanish-American
War. More recently, a member of People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, which criticized Madonna for featuring bullfighting in her
``Take a Bow'' video, dressed as a bull and followed Pope John Paul
II during his visit to a Mexico City cathedral to protest the
pontiff's reluctance to condemn the sport.
</P>
<P>
   What, many ask, does it say about a society if it still has a
place for a sport featuring some sop in brocade capri pants playing
catch-me-if-you-can with a weakened bull, who is then stabbed to
death to the roar of a bloodthirsty crowd? In ``Death and Money in
the Afternoon,'' Adrian Shubert does not make excuses for the
barbarity of the corrida. Instead, in this absorbing history of
Spanish bullfighting, he puts aside moral judgments to explore the
sport in a historical and social context.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Shuburt writes, ``we escape from the idea that it's
a peculiarly Iberian activity and can begin to compare it to
similiar spectacles elsewhere. There are numerous comparisons
available in the many other entertainments for which large numbers
of people pay money to get in special buildings to watch the
performances of highly paid professionals, who are objects of great
popular adulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although practiced in France, Portugal, Mexico, and numerous
South American nations, bullfighting is most associated with Spain.
The earliest bullfights, however, date back thousands of years:
Gladiators fought bulls in the Roman Colosseum. Bullfighting in
Spain has existed since the 16th century, and its early advocates
were artistocrats, institutions such as hospitals, and the church.
The reason for their involvement was immediately clear: Bullfights
were moneymakers. They were often held as fund-raisers to help
victims of accidents and natural disasters. While some officials,
Shubert writes, ``felt that the bullfight was not a desirable
custom,'' its ability to draw customers and cash ``usually trumped
any qualms officials had about their nonmonetary value.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure and simple, the bullfight was a business _ and one, of
which, everyone wanted a piece, especially as it blossomed in the
19th and 20th centuries. As its popularity rose, it spawned a
cottage industy of promoters, breeders, agents, and journalists to
cover the events, whether they championed the spectacle or
condemned it. It also introduced the notion of the athlete as
celebrity, and the sport became a means for poor young men to seek
fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Much the way boxing and basketball have in this century allowed
dispossessed young American men an avenue out of poverty,
bullfighting offered upward mobility in Spain. Surprisingly, it
even provided some opportunities for women who could make enough
money to live independently, though their presence in the sport was
hardly welcomed. In the book's best chapter, Shubert acknowledges
that there were always toreras, or female bullfighters. None
achieved the stardom of their male counterparts _ sexism, and the
general feeling that the sport was inappropriate for women even to
watch, let alone participate in, prevented that. Still, some, like
the Catalan Lady Bullfighters, earned a grudging respect from
critics, one of whom wrote, ``They fight with more art than some
bullfighters from the ugly sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Shubert, who chairs the history department at York University in
Toronto, has written extensively about Spain, and his knowledge of
that nation shines. And ultimately, it doesn't matter than he
avoids taking sides in the bullfighting debate. With textbook
precision, he reveals how the corrida shaped Spain's culture, and
provided the blueprint for the modern sporting industry. He has, in
essence, contributed a valuable history on the marriage between
sport and commerce as we know it today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
