A0487 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAD-SUITS-BOS &LR;      07-06 1692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAD-SUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINT MAKERS FACE SUITS OVER LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paint manufacturers, who have withstood lawsuits more
successfully than their old lead-based product weathered wear and
tear, are facing an aggressive new legal attack that borrows its
key strategy and players from the battle against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   While recent attention has been focused on lawsuits that use the
tobacco litigation as a model for suits against gun makers, cases
against the paint industry are quietly pending or planned in Ohio,
New York City, Buffalo, Rhode Island, and elsewhere, with several
more expected in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The suits generally accuse paint and pigment manufacturers of a
long-term, concerted effort to mislead regulators and the public
about the dangers of lead paint, charges the industry denies. The
lawsuits seek millions of dollars in financial relief for victims
of lead poisoning and reimbursement to state and local governments
that have borne the costs of preventing and treating lead-related
maladies.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the highest-profile, lead-paint suits are being
pressed by the same lawyers who played leading roles in the tobacco
litigation that led to a $246 billion settlement, including the law
firm of Baltimore Orioles owner Peter Angelos and South Carolina
attorney Jack J. McConnell. Both were also involved in successful
suits against asbestos makers.
</P>
<P>
   Their involvement and approach _ soliciting individual victims
and state and local governments as clients _ have raised the hopes
of antilead activists that paint and pigment makers will be forced
to pay billions of dollars for lead abatement efforts, medical
costs, and compensation for physical and emotional damage to
victims. In other words, a tobacco-like deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lead industry has a sorry track record over the 20th
century of obscuring the scientific evidence, intimidating
researchers, and stonewalling regulation. That certainly has
striking parallels to tobacco, and these suits reflect those
parallels,'' said Don Ryan of the Washington-based Alliance to End
Childhood Lead Poisoning. The alliance, a nonprofit public interest
organization, is not a party to the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Lead industry officials and paint manufacturers say the lawsuits
are groundless because the industry did nothing more than promote
and sell a then-legal product, never withholding information nor
misleading anyone about its toxicity. For instance, lead-paint
makers cite a 1996 decision in a Baltimore case in which a judge
wrote: ``There are no facts which indicate that these defendants
conspired with each other to conceal the knowledge of the dangers
of lead paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials also note that in most cases they began
phasing out lead paint for interior use 50 years ago _ long before
it was banned in 1978 _ and any current problems should be
attributed to landlords and homeowners who fail to prevent old
paint from peeling, flaking, or otherwise disintegrating. As many
as two-thirds of the 100 million housing units in the country are
believed to contain some lead paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic problem with all of these suits is nobody has sold
interior lead paint for almost half a century,'' said Don Scott, a
lawyer for NL Industries, formerly National Lead. ``It stopped
being sold because the industry took the leading role to protect
children from the potential risks of lead paint.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead industry has gained support from the US Chamber of
Commerce, which has criticized state attorneys general for using
private trial lawyers to press claims against industries in
exchange for a portion of any judgment or settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it violates the whole process of government when you
have state attorneys general making these kind of decisions and
having no checks and balances on them,'' said Larry Kraus,
president of the chamber's Institute for Legal Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, a federal judge in Boston rejected a landmark
attempt to blame the industry for the lead poisoning of a
1-year-old Boston girl in the early 1970s. That effort failed
largely because lawyers for the girl, Monica Santiago, were unable
to say which company manufactured the lead paint she ingested, and
the judge refused to spread blame among five paint and pigment
companies named in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent legal efforts against the industry have also failed,
and the only victories for victims of lead poisoning have involved
cases brought against landlords, ranging from small-property owners
to government agencies that failed to remove lead from homes and
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   But lead poisoning victims, liability lawyers, and activists
have long hoped to hold the industry directly accountable for the
damage done to children who ingest lead paint _ most often by
eating paint chips, residue, or powder. The problem is greatest in
cities with an older housing stock, such as Boston, New York, and
Philadelphia. When added to paint, lead made it spread easily, kept
it flexible in changing temperatures, and helped to form a tight
bond with wood.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials say the number of children with
elevated lead levels has dropped in recent years as a result of the
ban on residential lead paint and the removal of lead from gasoline
and water supplies. Still, they estimate that 890,000 children have
elevated blood-lead levels nationwide. In Massachusetts, a reported
13,566 children have elevated lead levels; 269 Massachusetts
children have ingested enough lead to be deemed ``lead poisoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Elevated lead levels can cause changes in brain chemistry
resulting in behavior problems, impaired growth, and lowered
intelligence; high levels can cause comas and even death.
</P>
<P>
   One lawsuit that has drawn interest is moving through the courts
in Cleveland, where a judge this summer is expected to rule whether
to turn it into a class-action suit involving an estimated 30,000
Ohio lead victims.
</P>
<P>
   Among the initial plaintiffs is Janessa Lascko, who was 15
months old in 1990 when she, her mother, and her half-brother moved
from a California homeless shelter into a mustard-colored,
Victorian-style house in Cleveland's Ohio City neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Like most toddlers, Janessa explored the world with her hands
and her mouth, touching and tasting whatever caught her attention.
Some parts of Janessa's world were coated with sweet-tasting lead,
possibly from flaking paint, and by her second birthday her blood
had more than five times the amount of lead federal health
authorities consider cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   For Janessa, now nearly 10, the only memories of the episode are
the long needles used at the hospital where she was treated. She
has shown no signs of mental or development problems, but her
mother said she lives in fear of what the future holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know how this might affect her,'' said
Janessa's mother, Janice Lascko, who said she is a former Marine
sergeant who recently retired on a disability pension. ``I wonder
about her ability to grow up, have kids, fall in love, though not
necessarily in that order.''
</P>
<P>
   Lascko said she tried to sue her landlord, but the suit was
dismissed when she was unable to prove that Janessa's lead
poisoning resulted from paint ingested in their apartment, and not
from a house next door where large flakes of old white paint still
rain down from the clapboards. But she is intent on winning damages
from the industry, for the money and to prove a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we can't afford to live out in the suburbs
doesn't mean we're not trying to be good parents, and our children
shouldn't be exposed to the dangers of lead poisoning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another plaintiff in the suit, Selina Gainer, has two
lead-poisoned children who suffered ``significant permanent
physical, psychological, and developmental injury,'' the suit
claims.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly all previous lawsuits against the lead paint industry,
an insurmountable hurdle for plaintiffs has been the inability to
pin blame on a specific manufacturer. By contrast, victims of
tobacco-based illnesses knew what brand of cigarettes they smoked
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers in lead paint suits have responded by taking
a ``market share'' approach, claiming that manufacturers'
responsibility for damages can be apportioned based on the
percentage of the lead paint market they controlled. That approach
worked in lawsuits against makers of the drug DES, which was used
to prevent miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
   Judges repeatedly rejected market share liability in lead paint
cases until February, when a judge in Buffalo said he would apply
that standard ``in the interest of justice and fairness.'' That
ruling, which is under appeal by paint makers, bolstered the hopes
of trial lawyers nationwide and has helped to fuel the boom in lead
suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a plaintiff who is injured by a product that has
no signature on it, it would be brutally unfair for a court to say
there is no way for them to recover,'' said Michael O'Shea, a
lawyer in the Cleveland case. ``That would afford defendants
absolute immunity, no matter how egregious their actions are,
solely because their products are unidentifiable once they're
manufactured.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the defendants in the suits are paint makers including
Glidden Co., Sherwin-Williams Co., and Benjamin Moore &AMP; Co.; lead
pigment manufacturers including E. I. du Pont de Nemours &AMP; Co.; and
a trade group called the Lead Industries Association.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially, the biggest share of damages could be borne by NL
Industries, which by some accounts controlled more than 50 percent
of the market with its Dutch Boy White Lead Paint.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, around the corner from the Lasckos' former home
in Cleveland is a storefront for a business called Consumers
Wallpaper &AMP; Paint Co. A large sign above the store window
advertises Dutch Boy Paints, and an old sign heralds the
availability of ``childproof paint.'' But just as the Lasckos have
moved away, so too has the business, and through a dusty window an
ever-present sign reads, ``Closed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
