<HEADER>
A0489 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIRCUT-CHAIN-ART-ART     07-06 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRCUT-CHAIN-ART-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNIP-ITS AIMS TO CUT THE FIDGETS OUT OF HAIRCUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joanna Meiseles, daughter of a Hollywood producer and
granddaughter of the late comic Jack Benny, wants to do for
children's haircuts what McDonald's has done with Happy Meals and
Chicken McNuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Only Meiseles has thrown her show-business heritage into the
mix. With bright color schemes, original cartoon characters looming
large, and electronic game stations at every pump-up chair, her
four Snip-its are theme parks of the tonsorial arts, a string of
salons for tots where the haircut is high theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of Chuck E. Cheese,'' says customer Marianne
Pilegaard, who recently took her two young daughters in for summer
coiffures at the newest Snip-its in Boston's Chestnut Hill section.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the tooth fairy of kids' haircuts,'' Meiseles
explains. ``We want to make haircuts an adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years after opening the first Snip-its in Framingham,
Meiseles is eyeing a fifth Massachusetts site in Braintree and
possible expansion into Connecticut. If all goes according to plan,
she would build a nationwide chain and a national brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this can do well in Framingham and Chestnut Hill, it can do
well in Chicago, Florida, and Seattle,'' Meiseles says.
</P>
<P>
   She sees kids' barbershops as an untapped niche.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey S. Stein isn't so keen on kids-only barbershops. An
analyst with McDonald Investments in Cleveland, he tracks the
highly fragmented US haircutting industry with its estimated
250,000 salons, most of them mom-and-pop operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything magical about kids' haircuts,''
says Stein, who closely follows Regis Corp., a Minneapolis company
with $798 million in sales that operates such chains as Regis
Hairstylists, Supercuts, and MasterCuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't walk in (to salons) by themselves,'' Stein says.
``They come with their parents, so you might as well target the
parents, too. Catering to kids only _ I don't think you can
maximize your upside doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   From a Wall Street perspective, Stein's view may make sense. But
for a parent attempting to coax a recalcitrant or terrified moptop
into a barbershop, such arguments may not hold weight.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, customer Pilegaard took her 2-year-old
daughter, Freja, to a regular salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to leave because she was crying,'' she says. ``They
told me, `Come back another day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of coming back, Pilegaard, her 5-year-old daughter,
Sara, and Freja hopped on public transportation, making a haircut
pilgrimage from their Boston neighborhood to the Chestnut Hill
Snip-its.
</P>
<P>
   After some early tears, Freja was coiffed without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lollipop is our secret weapon,'' says Snip-its stylist
Cindy White, whose chairside manner seems to draw equally on the
technique of Sassoon and the wisdom of Dr. Spock.
</P>
<P>
   Snip-its charges $11.95 for a regular haircut. According to
Meiseles, that's about $2 more than the going rate for a kid's
haircut at a walk-in discount salon.
</P>
<P>
   For the extra two bucks, the kids get a show, as well as a
haircut, with Meiseles as the maestro of the planned hilarity.
</P>
<P>
   To keep unruly young males occupied, each barber's chair is set
up so the occupant can play several games on a nearby large TV
screen. The games were designed by Meiseles's husband, a software
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The trick was to make the games fun _ but not too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was Nintendo, the kids would never want to leave the
chair,'' she says, something that could cause gridlock and delays
in the Snip-its waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Meiseles, 34, was inspired to start Snip-its after a bad
first-haircut experience with her son Ben six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a video camera, Meiseles took Ben to the salon that
coiffed her hair. But at the first sight of a tot and his mama, the
veteran stylists all skedaddled, leaving Ben in the unskilled hands
of a rookie too new to know any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an awkward experience,'' Meiseles recalls. ``I was
the kind of customer I now complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from family and friends and investing $100,000 of her
own money, Meiseles vowed to come up with a better way, thinking
long and hard about why kids find haircuts as terrifying as a trip
to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Her conclusion: Kids are told to stay away from strangers. Kids
are told to stay away from scissors. Then they go to the barber
shop, and a stranger wielding scissors is coming straight at their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   In designing a salon that would transform a scary haircut into a
fun-filled adventure, Meiseles was part entrepreneur, part
impresario, consulting with a Florida artist who specializes in
decorating children's bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   With the artist's help, Meiseles came up with such cartoon
characters as Snips the Scissors, Curly Comb, Flyer Joe Dryer, and
Marlene and Charlene, the Clipettes.
</P>
<P>
   These characters are prominently displayed in each Snip-its.
Each has his or her own story. Each has his or her own song. The
idea is to take objects such as scissors that otherwise might scare
a kid and turn them into a lovable Disney-like icon.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Snip-its innovations involve show-biz glitz.
</P>
<P>
   The grooming stations are designed with a chair for a parent
right next to the barber's chair; that means a parent can monitor _
or videotape _ the stylist's every move.
</P>
<P>
   All those extras added up. Meiseles says it cost nearly $400,000
to open the first Snip-its in 1995. Now that the
haircut-as-entertainment format has been refined, opening costs
have been roughly halved.
</P>
<P>
   So far the formula shows promise. In its first full year of
operations, the first Snip-its had sales of $430,000. By last year,
sales at that store rose to $500,000, Meiseles says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers come from as far away as New Hampshire and
Connecticut,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Snip-its seems to be a big hit with preschoolers. But by the
time a youngster has reached third or fourth grade, a Snip-its
haircut can be sniffed at as kids' stuff for 5-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Already Ben Meiseles, now 8 1/2, has expressed some interest in
the adult emporiums where barbers are skilled in buzz cuts, flat
tops, and neck shaves.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing much prepared Meiseles for a career in kid's hair. She
grew up in Beverly Hills, where her father, Robert Blumofe, was a
movie producer. His credits include such classics as ``Some Like it
Hot'' and ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a while for Meiseles to draw on her show-biz roots as
she refined Snip-its. At one point, she nearly scrapped the idea,
telling her father she didn't think she had the business savvy to
launch her own chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an artist,'' she told her father. ``I'm not a business
woman. I'm just a girl with an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' her father roared back. ``You're a producer!''
</P>
<P>
   If Meiseles is a producer, then Snip-its is her movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
