<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``My Son the Fanatic'' A hugely winning comedy of
cultural chaos. When a tolerant Pakistani taxi driver in London is
distressed to find his grown son attaching himself to Islamic
fundamentalists, he turns for companionship to another outsider and
regular customer, Rachel Griffiths's call girl. She does wonders at
avoiding cliche. Om Puri, as the driver with no control over his
destination, is unforgettable. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!! 1/2 ``Run Lola Run'' A buoyant up-up-and-away lark that
zips all over the mixed-media map in dishing out three versions of
what happens when a sweet but dumb drug courier botches a buy and
puts in a desperate phone call to his girlfriend, who has 20
minutes to save his life. Franka Potente's Lola is adorably warm
and smart and spirited _ and fast. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Summer of Sam'' Spike Lee's long hot movie about the long hot
summer of 1977, brought to a boil by the serial killer nicknamed
Son of Sam. Although he lurks around the film's edges, it's mostly
about the way fear dissolves the bonds among lifelong pals in an
Italian-American neighborhood and causes them to turn on each
other. Flawed in its larger ambitions, it's nevertheless sizzlingly
acted and richly evocative. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Wild Wild West'' This film, based on yet another fondly
remembered TV series, keeps things pretty bland between reluctant
buddies and post-Civil War lawmen Will Smith and Kevin Kline. As
the bad guy, Kenneth Branagh (wallowing in a Southern accent) seems
to have the most fun, but this outing is stolen by its huge
steam-powered toys, gadgets, and gizmos. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
