<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOM TIMES DRIVE TASTE FOR LUXURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's a robust market for luxury goods, fueled
by the powerful combination of low unemployment, low inflation, the
bullish stock market and heady consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of the San Francisco Bay Area, where the
technology industry has helped create a boom economy that contrasts
with stark times earlier in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Blackstock, manager of the Jaguar division at British
Motors, said new models and slightly lower prices have fueled sales
at the San Francisco dealership that are almost double from last
year.
</P>
<P>
   On Nob Hill, the Ritz-Carlton Hotel's occupancy rate is running
``in the mid to high 90s,'' driven as much by pleasure as commerce.
Cheryl Oliva, the Ritz-Carlton's director of business travel, said
guests increasingly ``stay on through the weekend, and they bring
their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Dario Frederick, manager of the Travel Bug, an agency
specializing in luxury travel and customized travel to Italy, said:
``The computer industry has boosted the economy for a lot of years.
People are willing to spend, especially since the Bay Area economy
is doing so well.''
</P>
<P>
   The boom has brought millions of small investors into the stock
market, putting more money into the hands of more people. Consumers
are living large and trading up.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Wine Institute, the industry's nonprofit, San
Francisco-based trade association, sales of premium wine are
surging, even as overall wine sales nationally have plateaued.
</P>
<P>
   Wine Institute statistics show that the greatest growth in
California table wines last year _ 15 percent _ came in
super-premium wines priced at $7 to $14 per bottle. Ultra-premium
wines over $14 were close behind, with growth of 11 percent. At the
bottom of the market, sales of jug wines under $3 per bottle fell 3
percent during the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Good taste and good incomes are driving the shift, according to
industry analyst Jon Fredrikson, of Gomberg, Fredrikson &AMP;
Associates in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``American consumers are moving upscale to high-end varietal
wines, shifting their preferences away from many white and blush
jug wines,'' Fredrikson said.
</P>
<P>
   Connoisseurship embraces not only fine wines but deluxe hotels.
At San Francisco's Ritz-Carlton, where corporate travel accounts
for 60 percent of the hotel's traffic, business is increasingly
merging with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Ritz-Carlton Club is extremely popular,'' said Oliva,
adding that club-level room rates, directed at the well-heeled
traveler, are $425 a night _ $60 above starting rates elsewhere in
the 336-room Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   For the extra money, guests get private elevator keys, afternoon
cocktails and hors d'oeuvres, access to a club lounge and express
checkout. In-room features include telephones with two lines,
computer hook-ups and Italian marble bathrooms with double sinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stay on through the weekend, they bring their families,''
Oliva said. ``San Francisco is such a desirable city. People want
that special occasion here.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick said business at his travel agency has never been
better for outbound travelers headed for romantic 10- to 14-day
Italian getaways. Weddings, anniversaries and other special
occasions in Italy are very much on the itinerary for affluent
clients, he said. Without citing dollar amounts, Frederick said
this is ``a particularly strong year.''
</P>
<P>
   High style has become so attractive that Las Vegas, where
high-rollers usually go more for ring-a-ding-ding flash than muted
good taste, is flirting with elegance.
</P>
<P>
   At the Resort at Summerlin, a posh property 25 minutes from the
Strip that is set to open July 12, world-class golf and holistic
health treatments are on offer in addition to keno and poker. The
nightly fee at the Swiss Casinos-owned resort: $345 September
through May, $195 in summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going for that upper end that favors golf and spas, not
entertainment,'' said Brian McMullan, the president and chief
executive of the Resort at Summerlin. ``Our clientele is not
sensitive to price. Price is not a factor, it's service.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the resort _ opening on the edge of the private Summerlin
community, a 36-square mile development built by the Howard Hughes
Corp. _ has a staff of 1,800 to pamper guests bedding down in its
541 rooms, split between two six-story Regent International Hotels
that flank a stand-alone casino.
</P>
<P>
   McMullan said the good times have given birth to the Resort at
Summerlin, but he added: ``We think our sort of resort could work
even in bad times. We have a select market. We're only aiming at
the top 2 percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
