<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUTURE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT NEXT FOR THE PRESIDENT? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES2-BOS  
 (Fixes headline)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how loath he is to leave center stage, the national
curtain will soon start to inch closed on Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The New Yorker magazine raised the inevitable
question: After having held the most powerful office in the world
for eight years, what will an ex-president of only 54 do once he
leaves the Oval Office? Run for the US Senate from Arkansas in
2002, the magazine suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said no way. ``That story is crazy and I don't know
where they got it from,'' Clinton reportedly told his spokesman,
Joe Lockhart. (Translation: Hillary will kill me if I start my
Senate campaign before she finishes hers.)
</P>
<P>
   Queried about his plans at a recent press conference, the
president said he plans to split his time between New York, where
Hillary is readying a US Senate run, and Arkansas, where he will
build his presidential library and public policy center.
</P>
<P>
   But all that seems more than a little dull and dignified from a
man who, as president, has been anything but. This, after all, is a
politician who plays the saxophone as well as he plays the field, a
president who has loved the office so much that he has savored even
the bad days.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should be thinking more creatively. If he doesn't,
others will do so for him. They already are, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, says David Kozak, program chairman for the Center for
the Study of the Presidency, is where Bill Clinton wants to be.
Clinton associates have denied that he will take a job with Steven
Spielberg at the DreamWorks studio, but those who expect that the
Clintons will part ways when their White House years end suspect
it's the stars that will draw him, eyes wide shut, to the other
intriguing possibilities of the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we hear that he is going to move with Mrs. Clinton to
New York, but among people who study the presidency, it is
axiomatic that he is going to settle in California and become part
of the entertainment industry or Silicon Valley,'' Kozak says. Why,
he could even appear on the big screen. Now that Tom Selleck has
done a May-December cameo on ``Friends,'' why couldn't Bill take a
six-show spin on that show as the new older man in Monica's life?
And that name . . .
</P>
<P>
   Kozak sees other reasons to go to California: Saddled with
staggering legal debts, Clinton needs to make serious money before
he even thinks about settling into a more dignified retirement
role. Second, during his presidency, the celebrity-crazed president
has cultivated both industries.
</P>
<P>
   With the nation increasingly asking, what do you do with a
sunken president, that's hardly the only speculative alternative.
Herein, some other suggestions, serious and otherwise, for the
Clinton post-presidency.
</P>
<P>
   From John Adams onward, presidents have taken up the quill to
tell their story, secure their place in history, or settle old
scores. And historically, some of the very best books have come
from some of the very worst presidents. Ulysses S. Grant, Herbert
Hoover, and Richard Nixon all spring to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's previous attempts at book-writing have been dull
indeed. ``Between Hope and History,'' his 1996 attempt at pensees,
was a snooze indeed. A book on race relations seems similarly
doomed for lack of a clear message.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every president has a good story to tell. In this case,
the real story is less of the times than of the man who made them
so tumultuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will probably do a book,'' said presidential
historian Paul Boller, professor emeritus at Texas Christian
University. ``He might feel a special need to justify or explain.''
(Ah, that academic understatement.)
</P>
<P>
   But for such a book to work, Clinton would have to tell the full
truth, something that has proved a challenge in the past. But that
same penchant for periphrasis could lead to another career
opportunity. . . .
</P>
<P>
   As a keen student of politics and policy, the man who solved the
electoral college puzzle and brought the Democrats back to power
would be a natural teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very experienced in the realm of politics and policy,
and I think he would make a good natural teacher, despite his
peccadilloes,'' said author and cultural critic Camille Paglia.
</P>
<P>
   Few presidents have been as skilled a communicator as William
Jefferson Clinton. Fewer still have had the president's supple
mastery of English nuance. And no one has been as skillfully
slippery in using that ability to cover his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   From his Arkansas insistence that he had never ``broken the laws
of my country'' to cover his English pot-puffing to his recent
insistence that he hadn't been aware of any espionage at America's
nuclear labs to gloss over the fact he had been briefed on security
breaches elsewhere, Clinton is a master at shaping words to suit
his needs. Meanwhile, his ground-breaking inquiry into the many
layers of meaning that attend words like ``sex,'' ``is,'' and
``alone'' has proved as significant in the annals of dissembling as
Noam Chomsky's analysis of syntactic structures was in the
epistemology of grammar.
</P>
<P>
   One Prediction: ``GOV 401: Denying Without Lying'' would be a
popular course in any public-affairs program.
</P>
<P>
   Could Clinton go to the high court? That seems unlikely. He has
no judicial experience, and after his own impeachment follies, it's
doubtful he'd want to give the US Senate a second chance to pass on
his character and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, of course, such an appointment would depend
on Vice President Al Gore winning in 2000 and his willingness to
wage a high-stakes battle to make his old boss a controlling legal
authority. Both seem problematic.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another sort of silk-robe role both more enticing
and more in keeping with the temper of the times. Despite the
disapproving frown of middle-aged America, the young have
rediscovered the Playboy Philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, at 72, publisher Hugh Hefner is no longer the best
spokesman for the libertine lifestyle he made famous. In fact, as
the silk-pajamaed septuagenarian wanders among guests 40 years his
junior, he looks a bit like an elderly houseguest awakened by the
party who has donned his slippers and wandered downstairs to seek
the source of the din.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
