u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SHAKER-BOS &LR;      07-06 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SHAKER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 KULA SHAKER MAKES A `BIG' ALBUM FOR THE '90s  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years can be an eternity in the here-today, gone-tomorrow
world of pop music. Until the release of ``Peasants, Pigs and
Astronauts'' two weeks ago, it had been that long since Kula Shaker
had released a CD, that long since it was the hot new band of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Was the band worried? No. Was it aware of the clock ticking?
Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we made a conscious effort,'' says singer-guitarist
Crispian Mills, from London, ``even if it made things a little more
difficult for us by waiting a long time, because we had to make an
album that we really loved, and if we felt that we'd rushed it and
that we hadn't done as good as we could have at that time, that
wouldn't have really been productive. So the music was the top
priority and I was lucky that we had that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Britain is a very, very fast turnover type of place,''
continues Mills, son of actress Hayley Mills, ``because it all
happens at once. It's one (small) country and there is one (main)
radio station and that's a bit insane. But I think that you need a
certain degree of faith and confidence to (make music) in the first
place and if you haven't got that, you're not going to last anyway.
I think that for us making this album was the most important thing
that we've done so far, even more important than (the first album)
`K,' because however well the album does, it will end up being all
about making music. The most important thing is, we still love the
album six months after we've recorded it. That's rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills and his mates _ bassist Alonza Bevan, drummer Paul
Winterhart, and organist Jay Darlington _ have reason to be
cheerful: ``Peasants, Pigs and Astronauts'' is a brilliant
mind-blower of a disc, an expansive sonic sojourn through
Eastern-tinged psychedelia and lush, full-blown space rock. It's
rich and multilayered. Its vision is optimistic, though not blindly
so. In ``SOS,'' Mills sings, ``This is the age of decay and
hypocrisy / Sometimes I feel like the world isn't ready for me.''
The album is, well, a journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cliched term, about an album being a journey,'' says
Mills, with a laugh, ``but it's a lot more difficult than anyone
thinks to create an album like that. It was something that we
wanted to try and achieve. On that journey, you visit lots of
different places and have lots of different people that you meet,
there are questions that you ask, so that by the time that you get
to the end you know you're somewhere else altogether from when you
started. It was ambitious and, at the same time, it felt kind of
natural. Sometimes, we'd throw a song in the middle of it all that
kind of broke up the flow of the concept a bit. `108 Battles (Of
the Mind)' is like that. It just comes out of nowhere and somebody
comes in with `I'm losing my mind!' and then we go off again. . . .
By the end of the album, we're singing in this Indian dialect,
Braj-Bhasi, and you don't know what planet you're on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills calls the music ``soundscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   The friendly ghost of Pink Floyd hovered over this project. Kula
Shaker recorded ``P, P and A'' on Floyd guitarist Dave Gilmour's
Victorian houseboat/studio, docked in London. The album was
produced by Bob Ezrin, who did the same duty for Floyd's ``The
Wall.'' (``Sound of Drums,'' the single Kula Shaker recorded in
1997 with Rick Rubin and George Drakoulias, is also included.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like one of the first bands to make `big' albums,
`big' sounds, they started all of that,'' says Mills, of Pink
Floyd, ``with `The Piper at the Gates of Dawn' and `Dark Side of
the Moon.' Both are completely different albums, but both changed
the way people listen to music. `Piper' kind of took over where
(the Beatles') `Sgt. Pepper' left off, and `Dark Side of the Moon'
was a combination of all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Kula Shaker differs, certainly from the latter-day Pink
Floyd, is in its sense of affirmation, its embrace of uplift and
splendor. Mills doesn't want to get all Pollyanna-ish about it. ``I
mean, we write lots of different songs,'' he says, ``and this,
`Peasants, Pigs and Astronauts,' is what we ended up deciding was
the best set of songs, the right flow of ideas. We have definitely
written some depressing songs, there is no doubt about that. We
tend not to record them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although, he adds, ``there's tracks on the album like `S.O.S.'
and `I'm Still Here' that are really over the top. But I feel that
is only part of the picture. You have to balance it out with other
types of vibes.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer Ezrin, who came out of a 10-year retirement, and Kula
Shaker both enjoy sound as effect, and Mills admits the
collaboration was something of a mutual indulgence society. ``The
most important thing is that we both had fun and we tried ideas
that would make us laugh,'' says Mills. ``That guy definitely has
lost his mind. There was one point in the studio where no one would
talk to each other unless they had a megaphone.''
</P>
<P>
   The mix of Indian music and English rock comes naturally to
Mills. ``I've been listening'' to Indian music ``a long, long
time,'' says Mills. They began integrating the sounds on ``K'' and
continue doing so here with Indian flutes, tablas, and the like.
(Outside musicians actually play those instruments on the album;
Mills says the band isn't proficient rnough on them to do it. In
concert, Kula Shaker triggers samples.) ``It's a great album to do
live,'' says Mills, of ``Peasants, Pigs and Astronauts.'' ``It's
difficult, but it tests you as a musician.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
