<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING THE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assuming the weatherpeople were right, your spirits may be
flagging this Fourth of July, even if the flag is flying high. (You
may even be resting in a flagged courtyard where flag-lilies grow,
but those flags are beyond our range today). Perhaps you'll be
lucky enough to flag down an ice cream vendor, if you must be on
the move.
</P>
<P>
   But what does your flagging energy have to do with the other
variety of flag, the verb that lets you flag a page with a Post-It
or flag in a race-car driver?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, as it turns out. For centuries, that flag was only a
noun _ the one you run up the pole, or carry into battle _ not a
transitive verb. Found in English around 1500, this flag has
obscure but definitely Germanic origins, though nobody's sure which
language invented it. `Whether the word originated in Eng., Du., or
Scandinavian,'' says the Oxford English Dictionary, ``it may
plausibly be supposed to be an onomatopoeic form expressing the
notion of something flapping in the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the 19th century, and railroads, and signalmen waving
flags at trains _ and English, with its usual adaptability, made
flag into a verb. Pretty soon, you didn't even need a flag to flag
a taxi: the verb could describe any kind of summons or alert,
whether by a hand wave or an urgent e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The other, intransitive flag _ to droop, fail, lose energy _ has
a different source entirely, in Old French flac, from the Latin
root that gives us flaccid. Thus you can flag a tow truck, a boat's
sails can flag for lack of a breeze, and your attention can flag _
thanks to the flexibility of English, which declared its
independence from tyrannical rule long before 1776.
</P>
<P>
   Mantras, American style
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Noonan of Wellesley is annoyed by the way mantra has been
co-opted, as we used to say, and spread about promiscuously in the
language of commerce. ``Slogans such as `Let's put the customer
first' aren't meant to inspire a vision in the mind of the
beholder,'' he notes. He would prefer that we use mantra only for
``a meaningless word or phrase designed to empty the word of
bothersome thoughts,'' not for company mottos designed to keep
workers on message.
</P>
<P>
   Mantra has, indeed, been a buzzword of the decade. Though it
arrived back in the '60s, along with Maharishi Mahesh Yogi,
transcendental meditation, and the Summer of Love _ ``Got any
mantras?'' George Harrison is supposed to have asked on meeting the
Maharishi _ the word has achieved yogic flight only in the '90s. In
Globe stories, a decent if rough barometer of word acceptance,
mantra was used just 26 times in 1988. Four years later it topped
100 citations, and in 1998 it hit 200. As Noonan notes, that's
probably because businesses _ many now led by the Beatles
generation _ picked it up as a hip substitute for ``motto,'' and
journalists followed along.
</P>
<P>
   But are we doing violence to the word? Mantras are not, in fact,
meaningless words (at least, if you know Sanskrit); I don't know
what the Maharishi offered George, but generally mantras for
meditations are holy words or names on which one focuses the mind,
not mere nonsense meant to empty it.
</P>
<P>
   So when a business refers to its mantra, it's not necessarily
warping the meaning, says Jack Hawley, a professor of religion at
Barnard College whose specialty is Hinduism. ``Surely `the customer
is always right' is a mantra in all senses _ proper discipline for
new employees and old adepts,'' he says. We may disapprove on
cultural grounds _ the object of worship here is the almighty
dollar _ but the extension of meaning is natural.
</P>
<P>
   And our mantra's no more of a stretch than the treatment we've
given other Hindu borrowings: Our pundits are not learned scholars,
but people shouting at each other on TV; our gurus are not just
spiritual guides but garden advisers and personal trainers; and we
talk about who has good parking-space karma, bad pun intended.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I've heard no protests that these adopted words are
being soiled by Americans' casual treatment; in fact, a report in
The Ethnic NewsWatch a couple of years ago seemed to celebrate the
Hindu invasion of English, noting that US companies were calling
themselves Avatar and Shiva and a Web game connection was named
Kali. Perhaps the author felt the same smugness we do when the
French adopt terms like popcorn and weekend: Our word is the best!
</P>
<P>
   And after all these centuries, Sanskrit can probably hold its
own against American
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Language column will appear every other week through summer. Write
Jan Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
