<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-06 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONG RX FOR HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton had plenty to say last week about the crisis
at teaching hospitals that he and Congress have caused.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke about the red ink that is pouring out of hospitals,
nursing homes, and home health care providers as a result of
cutbacks that helped produce a balanced federal budget two years
ago, but have proved nearly twice as deep and service-threatening
since then.
</P>
<P>
   But he was anything but helpful, suggesting that it will take
Congress's initiative to right a wrong that is severely injuring a
sector that provides more than 10 percent of all the jobs in
Massachusetts, and is also a major player in California and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, given the context of the question he was asked, it may
take some vocal dissent from a certain Democratic candidate for the
Senate in New York named Clinton to jolt him out of his current
position in the end. In the meantime, it will certainly take hard
work by the Senate's leading health care champion, Edward Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The work is delicate, because it affects the fiscal viability of
the president's overall, commendable plan to modernize Medicare
with a useful prescription drug benefit; but it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   The background is not all that complicated. When the president
and Congress negotiated the last lap of the decade-long journey to
fiscal sanity two years ago, Medicare _ and specifically the
providers of care under the giant program _ was hit for roughly
three out of every four dollars of budget restraint in the package.
At the time, the official estimate came in at about $105 billion,
but in actual practice the hit is proving to be more like $200
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In simple English, that wasn't the deal. But in his latest
proposal, the president is asking that providers not only eat the
higher amount, but absorb even more.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Massachusetts Hospital Association, the hit on
all providers in the state from the 1997 budget deal was a
whoppping $1.7 billion. What Clinton proposed last week would add
nearly another billion to that, net, with $600 million coming out
of the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Before people start a ``who cares?'' chant, listen to some of
Jeffrey Otten's recitation of recent developments in the state. He
not only chairs the Massachusetts Hospital Associationcheck, but is
CEO at Brigham and Women's (which, with Massachusetts General,
makes up the giant Partners HealthCare System).
</P>
<P>
   What has been happening is that one out of every four hospital
beds in the state has gone out of service, including more than a
third of the beds in Boston. Roughly one of every five hospitals in
Massachusetts, moreover, has closed its doors for good.
</P>
<P>
   As Otten notes, there is every kind of pressure imaginable on
the demand side of care, and precious little action of the supply
side. Great, but expensive strides are occuring in technology and
drugs, but no one wants to pay; patients want access to the system
for all the right reasons, but it is less of a system in many
respects, facing a severe labor shortage that is genuinely alarming
in the case of nurses, and about to face the ticking time bomb of
aging baby boomers; and no prospects for increased revenue are in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Already, roughly half of the hospitals have negative operating
margins on their Medicare operations (as in losing money). The
cutbacks have had the effect of gradually eliminating many positive
margins on in-patient care, which in the past have been used to
offset large deficits in out-patient services. Simply put, Medicare
cannot be healthy _ as in there when we need it _ if its most
important providers bleed red ink to run it.
</P>
<P>
   And the president's plan would make a bad situation worse. The
1997 cutbacks will be allowed to expire on schedule in three years
for nursing homes and the burgeoning home health care providers _ a
case of squeaky wheels getting grease. But with one exception, his
proposal is to keep them on for hospitals, on top of the fact that
the '97 cutbacks have proved far more severe than envisaged by the
budget dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The only semi-serious concession in the package is a proposed
$7.5 billion fund to ``alleviate present problems'' (Clinton's
words) at Congress's discretion. And the president actually said
that concerned senators should first support him on his overall
plan and then come in and deal for the scraps to assist genuinely
hurting institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, it should be the other way around. There are plenty
of ways to finance a needed reform of Medicare that don't target
its most important institutional participant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
