<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-KUBRICK-BOS &LR;      07-06 1704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KUBRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK DVD DEMONSTRATES HIS GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most directors make movies for a living. Stanley Kubrick lived
to make movies.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker, who died unexpectedly in March, was an enigma.
The Bronx-born resident of England has been described as aloof,
obsessed, calculating, cold, cutting, compassionate, funny,
humorless, sympathetic, tough, and understanding in books ranging
from Vincent LoBrutto's ``Stanley Kubrick: A Biography'' to Norman
Kagan's ``The Cinema of Stanley Kubrick.'' He never went to film
school but began as a freelance magazine photographer for Look in
1949. He was trained not by the studios but on the streets of New
York, hanging around animator Faith Hubley's studio at 1600
Broadway. ``He was a sponge,'' Hubley told biographer LoBrutto. He
spent days in movie theaters and at the Museum of Modern Art,
looking at all sorts of movies _ good, bad, and indifferent. He
was, as Hubley said, soaking it up. He was always an independent _
independent of mind and spirit and, perhaps most of all,
independent of market forces.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, historians, and fans argue the merits of Kubrick's
movies based on conventional theories that emphasize constancy of
theme and the consistency of visual expression. The reason no one
can reach a convenient, comfortable conclusion about Kubrick and
his films is that the filmmaker's life and art cannot be measured
using conventional methods. He must be appreciated as _ and here I
will use a word that I've never used to describe a director _ a
genius.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's artistry is formed and informed by curiosity. To use a
crude, but appropriate, analogy: Most cooks, when they need to
bake, go to the store for a sack of flour, bring it home, add the
other ingredients, and toss it into the oven. When it's done, they
take it out and eat it. No big deal.
</P>
<P>
   That's also the way most directors make movies. Not Kubrick.
He'd buy the flour but ask the salesclerk where he got it. He'd go
to the distribution center where the flour was stored and ask them
the same question. He'd go to the miller who ground it and the
farmer who grew it. He'd want to know the acidity of the soil, the
quality of the fertilizer, the precise watering schedule, the
genesis of the seed, and dozens of other things involved with the
process. And that doesn't include his questions about yeast, eggs,
water, the chemical processes that convert a lump of dough into a
fluffy food, and the matter of digestion.
</P>
<P>
   That's why his bread would never look or taste like anyone
else's.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, , all of Kubrick's major movies were released on DVD.
Only ``Killer's Kiss,'' ``The Killing,'' ``Paths of Glory,''
``Spartacus,'' ``Dr. Strangelove,'' and ``2001: A Space Odyssey''
were made available in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The new technolgy gives Kubrick's imagery a crispness that's
better than anything since ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' opened in
Cinerama. But for those searching for insights into Kubrick's
methods, you won't get them here. There are not many special
features except for a BBC documentary made by Kubrick's daughter,
Viv, on the making of ``The Shining'' that's included on that
disc. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Desire for debate &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, Kubrick refused to talk much about the work because
he was afraid that his word would be taken as gospel, thus cutting
off further discussion. And if there was anything Kubrick wanted
his films to generate, it was discussion. He appreciated honest
opinions _ not particularly those of the critics, but the reaction
of fans and cinephiles. The more the interpretive envelope was
pushed, the more Kubrick liked it.
</P>
<P>
   The July release of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' the last film he made
before his death, has pushed interest in him to an all-time high,
and the DVDs bring out all the textural majesty of his work. Each
movie, in its own way, is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick was unique. His films looked different because he made
them differently. Even the early movies, such as ``The Killing,''
look like they were made yesterday because the director's vision
and execution were timeless. Never one to engage in passing
fancies, Kubrick chose themes that are classic. He made 13 films,
and he took his time. ``Eyes Wide Shut'' comes 12 years after
1987's ``Full Metal Jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons that he took so long. The facile answer
is because that's how long it takes. Jack Nicholson, in a telephone
interview, said that while they were working on ``The Shining,''
over 200 days in 1978-79, Kubrick was already discussing Arthur
Schnitzler's novel ``Traumnovelle,'' the book on which ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' is based. So the film starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman
took more than 20 years to make.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick moved from science fiction and horror and war to social
commentary and costume dramas and comedy with equal alacrity. Some
critics bemoan Kubrick's coolness, yet his best moments are
emotional, not intellectual. Kubrick defies what seems to be the
basic human need to stereotype and pigeonhole. While everyone else
seems to be looking for patterns, Kubrick, the scientist as artist,
kept looking to break them.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick gets full credit as a master of technical skill. In
``The Shining,'' he had lenses specially ground because the
available technology didn't match his way of seeing. He's lauded
for his use of sound, especially in ``Spartacus,'' where his
sophisticated sound mix set a new standard for the industry. In the
editing room, his encyclopedic memory _ sharpened by a lifetime as
a brilliant chess player _ helped him recall small details buried
under thousands of takes when he was editing ``Full Metal Jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Most directors see the filmmaking process as the fulfillment of
their preconceived notions. Whether it's Hitchcock, who
storyboarded every shot and had little to do with actors _ or the
brilliant Billy Wilder, who found his greatest pleasure in the
writing, there are few filmmakers who exhibited the spontaneous
control that Kubrick did. Although that sounds contradictory, it's
not. He motivated everyone who worked for him to work as hard as he
did and to bring their talents to the movie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seeing the unexpected &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's his underrated work with actors that put the final touches
on Kubrick's artistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always thinking,'' said Nicholson, who noted that
Kubrick worked everyone hard but ``it was worth it to get the
worked-on quality out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick cast Vince Edwards as a boy toy in ``The Killing''
because that's the way Kubrick saw him.
</P>
<P>
   He realized Peter Sellers could elevate both ``Dr. Strangelove:
Or How I Stopped Worrying and Learned to Love the Bomb'' and
``Lolita'' to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most interesting scenes (in `Lolita') were the ones with
Peter Sellers, which were total improvisations,'' recalled
``Lolita'' cinematographer Oswald Morris in the LoBrutto biography.
``They'd roughly block it out, go upstairs and leave me to light
it, then come down, for instance, with the table tennis scene.
There was nothing like that in the script, it was just off the
cuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When something went wrong, he wouldn't scream about it,'' said
Keir Dullea, star of ``2001.'' ``He'd take me to one side,
seemingly blaming himself more for the mistake than me. In reality,
of course, he was fingering my fault in an adult and sensible
way.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason he cast Nicholson in ``The Shining'' was because of
the star's complex feelings about marriage and family. He cast Ryan
O'Neal in the title role in his adaptation of William Makepeace
Thackeray's ``Barry Lyndon'' not because he thought the star of
``Love Story'' was the next Olivier. He saw O'Neal as a rather
dull, ambitious character, much like Lyndon, who could capture the
18th-century exterior qualities of the novel. When he needed a
woman emblematic of the languid aristocracy, he cast the well-bred
beauty Marisa Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   He cast the grunts in ``Full Metal Jacket'' because they were
anonymous performers, not stars. Lee Ermey, who played the
wacked-out drill instructor, was making his debut, and he treated
the other actors, his recruits, as he did the US Marines under his
care in real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate collaboration,'' said Matthew Modine, who
played Joker in ``Full Metal Jacket.'' ``Sure, Stanley makes you
work but that's why we're doing what we do. It was tough and
thrilling. He taught me how to do my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people think that Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman were cast in
``Eyes Wide Shut'' with an eye open for the box office. That may be
true. But the other eye, the artist's eye, wanted to see how a
husband and wife juggling their personal and professional lives _ a
couple whose sexual lives have always been open to speculation _
would play a husband and wife whose personal and professional lives
become intermingled and whose sex lives become entwined.
</P>
<P>
   Critics describe Kubrick's common use of multiple takes as a
kind of sadistic habit the director used to beat the actors into
submission. Again, nothing could be further from the truth.
``Stanley's always looking for something,'' said Nicholson. ``And
he invites the actor on his search. You have to prepare because it
isn't like most directors who already know what they want and just
want the actor to follow some predetermined path. Stanley invites
you on a journey. It's quite a trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson went on to say how much Kubrick respects actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not autocratic in the least,'' he said. ``He incorporates
suggestions from the actor. He's very open. You just have to be
ready to make the commitment to the work that he does. And that's
not always easy.'' Nicholson paused. ``But it's always
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's oeuvre is settled _ and that's the tragedy. After
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' we can no longer look forward to a new Kubrick
film. It's reminiscent of a story Billy Wilder tells about him and
William Wyler leaving the funeral of the legendary Ernst Lubitsch.
``No more Lubitsch,'' Wilder said sadly to Wyler. ``Worse that
that,'' replied Wyler. ``No more Lubitsch pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse than that. No more Kubrick. No more Kubrick pictures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
