<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FUTURE-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     07-06 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUTURE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the din.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But think of the youthful glamour the ex-president could bring
to the role. Why, he could even write the advice column.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's television skills, his conversational charm, and his
sense of empathy make the modern television talk show one
possibility. Where better to discuss issues like family leave,
school uniforms, or sexual misbehavior?
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Next on ``William Jefferson Clinton'': Men Who Admit to a
Grand Jury They've Had an Improper Physical Relationship with a
Young Aide After Assuring Their Wives That Those Rumors Are Simply
the Work of a Vast Right Wing Conspiracy.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks Clinton would be well-cast for that
role. ``When you run a good talk show, you are always sort of
second banana to your guests,'' said Steven Stark, author of
``Glued to the Set,'' a book about groundbreaking TV shows. ``I
think he is too egocentric for that. It would be like Geraldo,
where Geraldo is always the central attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long eyed Jimmy Carter warily, but for a man
concerned with his post-presidency, the acclaim Carter has won with
his efforts to promote peace must seem enviable indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Could a man whom two-thirds of Americans consider a moral midget
on stilts (as a critic once quipped of Rousseau) ever hold such a
place in the public mind?
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly impossible, but experts say it will take both time
and work. Still, other ex-presidents have come further, from
greater disgrace or disapproval, to redeem themselves in the public
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Richard Nixon, for crying out loud,'' said Bruce
Buchanan, professor of government at the University of Texas at
Austin. ``He came from the political dead to where he was a
recognized elder statesman when he died.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's rehabilitation took years of careful effort. But years
are one thing Clinton will have to spare. Indeed, should he live
just a few weeks beyond his 86th birthday, he would surpass Herbert
Hoover's record for living the longest _ 31 years _ after leaving
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   And if Clinton spends that time as constructively as Hoover did,
he too could see his post-presidential good works outshine his
presidential misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CAREER CHANGERS IN HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Past presidents have pursued any number of careers once they
have taken the long walk from power.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, Cincinnatus, the Roman general and statesman, seemed
the model, leaving power to return to his plow.
</P>
<P>
   Washington retired to Mount Vernon, his home in Virginia, and
though he returned briefly to command the provisional army when war
with France threatened, he was ever eager to disengage from public
life.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson repaired to Monticello to pursue the varied pleasures
of a gentleman farmer. Madison served as rector of the University
of Virginia, and never ventured outside the state for the 19 years
left to him after the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But other ex-chief executives returned to active public life.
Brushing aside concerns that it was beneath his post-presidential
dignity, John Quincy Adams ran for the US House of Representatives,
serving 17 distinguished years there, hoping all the while for a
presidential comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Boller, presidential historian and author of several books
about the presidents, cites the example of Andrew Johnson as one
that might particularly interest Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he was impeached and escaped conviction by just one
vote, he ran for the Senate and won,'' Boller says. ``It was a kind
of vindication for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Johnson weren't the only presidents to win important
post-presidential offices. William Howard Taft ended up chief
justice of the Supreme Court, a job he relished far more than that
of chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those men was as young as Clinton, who'll be 54 next
year. Teddy Roosevelt, who at 50 was younger on leaving office,
waged his Bull Moose comeback attempt, and when that failed, went
exploring in Brazil, and then tried for a battlefield command in
World War I. Even if the 22d Amendment didn't foreclose another
term for Clinton, public opinion surely would. And as for a
battlefield command? Hard to see that interesting him.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy, at 43 the youngest elected chief executive,
didn't get the chance to experience a post-presidency, but
according to Richard Reeves's splendid ``President Kennedy: Profile
of Power,'' JFK wanted to stay in public life.
</P>
<P>
   After his presidency, he'd run for the US Senate again, Kennedy
told his old friend Paul Fay, then perhaps serve as secretary of
state if brothers Bobby or Teddy followed him to the Oval Office.
Or, he said, maybe he and his old Navy buddy would just ``drift
through the Greek islands, with our wives administering to our
every wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to imagine Hillary Rodham Clinton agreeing to that. That's
assuming, of course, she hasn't abandoned the USS Clinton
altogether by then.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
