A0543 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HILLARY-BOS &LR;      07-06 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY FACES UPSTATE CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton makes her first serious dive
into the race for Senate Wednesday, heading straight to the heart
of enemy territory, the center of upstate New York, where
Republicans rule, her ratings are low and slipping lower _ yet
where, ultimately, the race may be decided.
</P>
<P>
   She will start her trip with a friend, Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
the retiring Democratic senator whose seat she hopes to win.
Standing outside his farmhouse in Oneonta, an hour's drive west of
Albany, Clinton will announce that she has formed an ``exploratory
committee,'' which these days is tantamount to throwing her hat
into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it's on to a four-day road trip, to Cooperstown, Utica,
Rome, Syracuse, and maybe a few small towns along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, polls show the first lady running neck-and-neck with
her most likely Republican opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But among the voters upstate _ that is, every place but New York
City and its suburbs of Long Island and Westchester County _
Clinton trails the mayor by 13 or 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   New York politics are like a triangle, its three points
representing New York City, the suburbs, and upstate. The first
lady is way ahead in the largely Democratic city. The mayor is way
ahead in the largely Republican suburbs. And so, most politicos
agree, the fight will be fought most fiercely upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has visited New York City many times in recent months,
to great acclaim and hearty welcome. But very rarely, and then only
briefly, has she ventured to other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   She will find this stretch of land so different from New York
City, it might as well be another state.
</P>
<P>
   When most Americans think of New York, they think of the big
city, liberals, and a melting pot of blacks, Hispanics and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate New York, on the other hand, can be typified this way:
small towns, conservatives, and white Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, because a higher percentage of upstaters actually turn
out to vote, how they vote carries greater weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstate Catholics determine the outcome of statewide elections
in New York,'' says Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant who
supports but is not working for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of her journey, the first lady's numbers upstate are
falling. At the end of May, a survey by the Quinnipiac College
Polling Institute showed her in a virtual tie with Giuliani
upstate, 44-43. However, its latest poll, taken last week, shows
Giuliani ahead in that region, 51-38.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll by Zogby International, 36 percent of upstaters have a
``very unfavorable'' view of Clinton, while 13 percent have a
``somewhat unfavorable'' view. Quinnipiac shows similar findings,
with 38 percent of upstaters having an ``unfavorable'' view of her
and 22 percent having a ``mixed'' view.
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen in the two districts she will travel through
this week, Representatives Sherwood Boehlert and James T. Walsh,
are both Republicans. Boehlert voted for two of the four articles
of impeachment against President Clinton. Walsh voted for three.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton won both of the districts in the 1996
election, just as he won every district in the state. However, both
congressmen beat their Democratic challengers by wider margins than
Clinton beat Bob Dole, his Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the numbers indicate, and analysts agree, that Mrs.
Clinton has enormous room to move upward.
</P>
<P>
   One clue lies in the results of a question asked by the
Quinnipiac Poll: ``Would you say that Hillary Rodham Clinton cares
about the needs and problems of people like you, or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, New Yorkers think she does care about them, by a
60-35 margin. Even upstate, a decisive majority, 54-40, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   However Clinton did not fare as well in another Quinnipiac
query: ``Would you say that Hillary Rodham Clinton understands the
issues and problems facing New York State, or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, by 53-39 percent, most think she does not understand
New York's problems. Upstate respondents hold this view by a
devastating 60-33.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and other Republicans have been tapping mightily into
this sentiment, taking every opportunity to slam the first lady as
a ``carpetbagger.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on these two poll-findings, Clinton's road to higher
ratings, especially upstate, seems clearly paved. First, talk
sympathetically about people's needs _ something she has always
done well. Second, do more of what she's about to do this week _
travel the state and thus convince people that she is getting to
know the place better.
</P>
<P>
   This week's trip is being officially billed as ``Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Listening Tour,'' the idea being that she wants to spend
most of the time listening to what the people need.
</P>
<P>
   One point Clinton must find reassuring is that Giuliani does not
seem to be an insurmountable opponent on this ground.
</P>
<P>
   The majority statewide, a 64-29 margin, thinks he understands
New York issues, and upstate, respondents agree 60-25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, when people living upstate are asked their opinion of
Giuliani _ favorable, unfavorable, or mixed _ a surprising 30
percent say they ``haven't heard enough about him'' to judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think so,'' says Maurice Carroll, director of the
Quinnipiac polling firm, ``but _ outside the city in Giuliani's
case, and outside her capacity as first lady in Hillary's _ both of
these candidates are still largely unknown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
