<HEADER>
A0592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONNIE-STEVENS-HNS &LR;      07-06 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNIE-STEVENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'60S `HAWAIIAN EYE' NOW FOCUSES ON SKIN CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ ``Cricket'' has grown up and become a
cosmetics mogul. Who would have thought it possible?
</P>
<P>
   Connie Stevens, the adorably perky blonde whose sunny
disposition and kewpie-doll looks decorated the '60s TV series
``Hawaiian Eye,'' has been selling her Forever Spring skin-care and
makeup line on Home Shopping Network for the past 10 years. With
her sweet, girl-next-door directness and conversational, ``we're
all girls in this together'' on-air personality, she's moved $500
million worth of product, earning between $80 million and $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   When Stevens was a bouncy young singer from Brooklyn, who came
West at 15 to earn her fortune with the trio of hometown boys who
became The Lettermen (when she abandoned them to make movies), she
was the perfect type for teen and beach party films (remember
``Palm Springs Weekend'').
</P>
<P>
   Her first film was ``Young and Dangerous'' with Mark Damon, then
``Rock-a-Bye, Baby'' got her noticed by Jerry Lewis and signed to
Warners for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of her upward trajectory, she became the third Mrs.
Eddie Fisher (post Liz). Her daughters with Fisher are Joely, whose
own acting career is smokin' now (she stars with Matthew Broderick
in ``Inspector Gadget'') and Tricia Leigh (who has been seen around
Los Angeles in satirical revues where she just completed a run as
Monica Lewinsky in ``Star Struck'').
</P>
<P>
   When she was first starting out, Stevens had the makings of a
teen-queen idol: Her distinctive voice was like treacle over
sandpaper and the word ``cute'' was invented just to describe her.
She wore spikey lashes and her lush mouth was always polished to
glossy perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a beauty mogul whose age hovers somewhere in her
mid-to-late 50s, Stevens has refused to fall prey to the Beverly
Hills surgery shuffle: a little nip, a tiny tuck, a laser peel or a
lipo suck. And heaven knows how tough that Hawaiian sun can be on
your skin (``and I spent four years in it. Who knew back then?''
she moans).
</P>
<P>
   I met Stevens at her Robertson Boulevard spa/restaurant _ called
Connie Stevens' Garden Sanctuary _ a friendly, club-like mixture of
sensual general store, where she sells her own products and an
iconoclastic mix of whatever else has struck her fancy (fake fur
and velvet lap blankets; flavored lip balms; patio and beach wear;
decorative candles); a serviceable cafe with a spa menu and a small
but luxurious spa with marble treatment rooms.
</P>
<P>
   There is a massive faux tree in the center of the room and an
equally massive, 80-inch television screen hanging on the wall,
overlooking the restaurant tables, designed for her Monday ``guy
nights.'' (When she first opened Sanctuary, she invited all of her
male pals to celebrate the memory of Jim Murray, the acerbic Los
Angeles Times sports columnist who had recently passed away. ``She
has a lot of guy friends,'' one of her publicists said.)
</P>
<P>
   She greets me with a pinkly glowing face. Wearing geranium pink
tights, sweat socks, aerobic shoes and an over-sized loden green
jacket, Stevens daubs at her smeared mascara with a tissue, trying
to catch her breath. ``I'm just out of a yoga class,'' she says by
way of explanation. Her hair is a cloud of blonded dips and swoops,
a variation on the cut she's had for years. She is not rail-thin
like some of her contemporaries, and she is eminently comfortable
with herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she says in answer to a blunt question. ``I haven't had
any work done. So you stay a little plumper than you were at 20.
... I've come to a time in my life that I'm not threatened by my
life, my body or my time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Stevens says she started her cosmetics line as a way to
help put two daughters through college, she occasionally plays
Vegas and other venues and keeps her hand in as an entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   And her Forever Spring line is geared to women like her. Not
teen-agers or supermodels, but real women who have lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my women on TV, because I'm one of them _ raising two
children, living through the empty nest syndrome, juggling work and
personal life _ don't pay attention to the 14-year-olds on the
magazine covers. Don't buy into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach to beauty is: You've got to claim your own power.
Yes, it could be by using my products, or going to yoga classes or
just reclaiming your dreams.'' (She also jokes that another of her
beauty secrets is ``younger men,'' but adds quickly, ``so is a
network of really supportive friends.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the base of Stevens' extensive line _ nearly 100 products _
is what she calls The Time Machine, a hand-held facial toner used
in conjunction with several of her products. The Beauty System that
she sells on Home Shopping Network includes the machine, plus a
cleanser that also exfoliates and a moisturizer-quencher with
natural collagen, fluffy in texture, which softens the skin.
</P>
<P>
   The price is $125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of that basic system,'' she notes, ``came all my other
products.'' Such as a ginseng facial costing $29, which, says
Stevens, sold 1.2 million jars in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Stevens has taught herself about the science
of beauty products and certainly about marketing. ``I have kept my
distribution small,'' she says. ``If you ship to another country,
for instance, you have to increase the preservatives you put in
your product. My (products') shelf-life is two years. CNN did a
profile on the company and they said we come in No. 1 in the
cosmetic industry for the amount of real ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   Skin care, makeup and a fragrance called Kali, developed for
Stevens by International Fragrance and Flavors, have helped to
finance Stevens' homes in Jackson Hole, Wyo., Las Vegas, Beverly
Hills and an apartment in New York _ ``I really don't live anywhere
any more,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She has her own Web site and throws words like ``e-commerce''
and ``demographic'' around like a seasoned retailing pro. But she
has never lost what made her a star in the first place. Her ability
to communicate with a fan base that by now, is as old as she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I realize from being on Home Shopping is that so many of
the women who buy product from me never thought they deserved to
take care of themselves, never thought they should enjoy it or that
they were even supposed to. But I am honest with them. I tell them:
`Don't try this unless you really want to.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
