r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     07-06 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COIN TOSS DETERMINED WHO DIED WITH HOLLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Who was the person who was supposed to be on the plane that
killed Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens and the Big Bopper?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.H., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: When Buddy Holly chartered a plane on Feb. 3, 1959, he was
planning to travel with band members Waylon Jennings and Tommy
Allsup. During a grueling Midwest tour called the ``Winter Dance
Party of 1959,'' Holly wanted to avoid the drive from Mason City,
Iowa, to Fargo, N.D., on a bus without a working heater.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the plane took off at 1 a.m., Jennings gave up
his seat to Richardson, and Allsup lost a coin toss _ and the final
seat _ to Valens. The four-seat Beechcraft Bonanza crashed shortly
after takeoff, killing all three passengers and Roger Peterson, an
inexperienced 21-year-old pilot who was blamed for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Valens was afraid of small planes after two collided above his
junior high school and killed two students. ``I guess he was really
miserable on that bus,'' his aunt Ernestine Reyes told Reuters news
service.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings gave up his seat because Richardson was running a
fever. Holly, disappointed that his Crickets bandmate wasn't
coming, joked that ``I hope your bus freezes,'' Jennings told VH1's
``Behind the Music.'' He replied, ```I hope your plane crashes' ...
it took me a long time to get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In February, Time had an article about farm prints created by
Buddy Ebsen. Where can I order these?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.A.S., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Six lithographs of Ebsen's ``Uncle Jed Country'' oil
paintings are being sold by Phantom Bookshop of Ventura, Calif.
Color prints sell for $100 and framed lithographs on canvas sell
for $595.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (805) 641-3844 or visit the actor's official
World Wide Web site at www.buddyebsen.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ebsen, 91, also is selling an autobiography through the
bookstore. Signed copies of ``The Other Side of Oz'' sell for $35
plus $5 shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can write to Ebsen in care of Phantom Bookshop, 451 E. Main
St., Ventura, CA 93001.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the singer Cher?
</P>
<P>
   _ W.J.B., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Cher in care of the William Morris Agency, 151 El
Camino Drive, Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Cher, 53, is currently on a 40-city concert tour of the United
States. Her single ``Believe'' has been a No. 1 hit in the United
States and 22 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   She's also appearing in the film ``Tea With Mussolini.'' For
additional information, visit her official World Wide Web site at
www.cher.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
