<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAPPY STORY DESERVES A `HIGH FIVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a reason why Janet Evanovich's latest mystery featuring
Trenton, N.J., bounty hunter Stephanie Plum has hit the Top 10 list
in fiction. The witty dialogue and crazy plot twists make you laugh
almost non-stop as you speed through ``High Five'' (Martin's Press,
$23.95. 292 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Times are tough for Stephanie. Uncle Fred has disappeared after
an argument with his garbage collectors. The only clue is a set of
pictures of a dismembered body in a garbage bag.
</P>
<P>
   The only bail jumper Stephanie can go after is a
height-disadvantaged computer programmer who carries a knife. If
she nabs him, she will only net about $70. Without enough income to
pay the rent, Stephanie decides to work for Ranger, a super bounty
hunter who always has expensive cars and plenty of money.
</P>
<P>
   Stalked by a homicidal, Bible-quoting maniac, Stephanie is also
being followed by a tough-looking bookie. Adding to her problems is
her strong attraction to her former lover, vice cop Joe Morelli,
who invites her to a Mob wedding. Now she has to find a dress.
</P>
<P>
   Evanovich is the master of snappy dialogue. Her offbeat
characters seem perfectly at home in Trenton. Her plot never lags,
just escalates as the hilarious shenanigans pull you along at
break-neck speed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___
</P>
<P>
   Need a beach book, but don't want to lug a hardback? Check out
Mary Higgins Clark Mystery Magazine (Family Circle, 100 pages.
$5.95.).
</P>
<P>
   The sixth installment includes short stories by Elmore Leonard,
Edna Buchanan, Faye Kellerman, Julie Smith and, of course, Clark.
Kate Stine looks at historical mysteries, while booksellers from
around the country pick their favorite whodunits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Hunted'' (Signet. $5.99, paperback. 312 pages.), Jerry
Kennealy once again serves up a first-rate crime thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Political terrorist Philip Bovard is buying up nuclear reactors
from the Russians and his money man is Patrick Lyman, a
well-respected San Francisco banker who has a taste for young
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen-year-old Janna Drovana, a recent arrival to San
Francisco from Russia, has just lost her mother. Her uncle sells
her to Angela, a local madam whose clients include Lyman. Told she
has a virgin for him, Lyman goes to her house, is bitten by Janna,
and leaves behind his laptop computer, the one holding all the
information on the nuclear sale.
</P>
<P>
   When Angela tells Lyman she doesn't have the laptop, Bovard
hires an Irish assassin to kill Angela and her girls and retrieve
it. But Janna escapes the carnage with the laptop and thousands of
dollars from Angela's secret stash.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide detective Maureen Connah gets the case _ the case of
the whorehouse murders. Eventually, she will figure out that a
child lived through the carnage and is wanted by some very powerful
people.
</P>
<P>
   Connah's partner, Jack Kordic, has gone to London to receive an
award and nearly dies in a bombing that kills a high-ranking
Israeli intelligence officer. The British believe the bombing was
the work of the Irish Republican Army, but Mossad agent Anatoly
Weeks thinks not and heads for San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Janna calls the police, but doesn't give her name or
location. Instead, she roams Golden Gate Park, eluding both the
police and her hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Kennealy uses San Francisco as one of his characters and gets it
right. But then he should _ he's a former policeman and private
investigator. The international intrigue works surprisingly well.
</P>
<P>
   And the characters are believable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fencing Master'' (translated by Margaret Full Costa.
Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co. $24. 256 pages), Arturo Perez-Reverte's fourth
intellectual thriller to be published in the United States, was his
debut novel in Spain. Not as complex as ``The Flanders Panel,''
``The Club Dumas'' and ``The Seville Communion,'' ``The Fencing
Master'' nevertheless is a richly woven tale of intrigue in Madrid
of 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Don Jaime is a middle-aged fencing master, a man of honor who
teaches Madrid's young elite the dying art of the sword. One day he
is approached by a beautiful young woman who wants Don Jaime to
teach her the ``unstoppable thrust.'' Don Jaime refuses, but
eventually Dona Adela de Otero proves that she is a skilled fencer
and Don Jaime becomes her teacher. Little does he know that she
will draw him into a world of political plots and cause the deaths
of friends.
</P>
<P>
   Perez-Reverte is an elegant writer whose attention to detail
makes his stories vastly different from other writers in the genre.
The reader will parry and lunge along with Don Jaime, feel a real
part of the duel. Perez-Reverte fans will relish finally getting a
look at where this truly gifted story teller began his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
