<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0612 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-06 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE MAKING CHANGE, DETERMINE LONG-TERM NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; moved 7/2 in advance for 7/4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a state employee and have the opportunity to invest in a
deferred compensation plan. I contribute the maximum allowed, $150
a week, which is divided between Fidelity Growth and Income and
Fidelity Growth Company funds. My choices were random picks with no
rationale. I often wonder if I should have two funds with similar
names, or whether I should have chosen something else.
</P>
<P>
   The other options were an income fund, a short-term investment
fund, George Putnam Fund of Boston, Calvert Social Investment,
Vanguard Wellington, AIM Charter, Vanguard Institutional Index, AIM
Weingarten, AIM Constellation, and Templeton International funds,
or a life insurance investment.
</P>
<P>
   I have never had advice or talked with anybody about these
options. I am 53 and my home will be paid off in eight years. I
would like to retire by age 65.
</P>
<P>
   B.R., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your suspicion that your two holdings are too similar is well
founded.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity Growth and Income maintains a balanced portfolio
dominated by large-cap domestic stocks and Fidelity Growth
Company's portfolio is dominated by large domestic growth-oriented
stocks, there's not enough difference between the two to provide
you with very meaningful diversification.
</P>
<P>
   But before you begin making changes, we'll have to determine
when you're likely to call on this money. Let's consider two
possible intentions. One is that you'll let this money grow until
you retire and then put it to work to supply an income stream to
augment your retirement income. The second is that you'll be able
to get along on your retirement income in the early years of
retirement, and view this building fund as your buffer against
inflation when you're in your 70s and later.
</P>
<P>
   If it's the first case, your period of investment for growth in
principal will be shorter, and therefore you should be a little
more cautious. So I'd begin now by taking a tiny step toward the
kind of portfolio you'll eventually want, which is to have a
portfolio dominated by fixed-income issues 12 years from now. But
since 12 years is still a pretty long time, I'd start with a baby
step, putting perhaps a third of your ongoing contributions into
Vanguard Wellington, a fund that divides its portfolio between
stocks and bonds, with about a third of its assets on the
fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you don't expect to use this money to
produce income at the time of retirement and anticipate waiting
some years after retirement to draw upon it, I'd swap some of the
Growth Company shares for positions in AIM Constellation, a mid-cap
growth fund, and in Templeton International, so as to give you
better balance.
</P>
<P>
   I'd look for an overall portfolio that consisted of 50 percent
in Fidelity Growth and Income, with the balance evenly divided
among Fidelity Growth Company, AIM Constellation, and Templeton
International.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 38 and contribute $6,000 a year to a 401(k) plan with no
company match. Currently I have $15,000 in the plan, with the money
invested in Fidelity's Growth and Income, Contrafund, Magellan, and
Overseas funds. In addition I have a Roth IRA of $6,000 with
Vanguard, invested in the Index 500, Health Care, and Horizon
Aggressive Growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   I will continue the 401(k) contributions and add $2,000 a year
to the Roth IRA until I retire at age 60. Are my choices diverse
enough? What changes would you make? How much will I have saved
when I retire?
</P>
<P>
   J.A., Leominster, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. To start with the last question, if we assume the ongoing
contributions and 10 percent average annual growth, the grand total
would be $768,219. But I think you'd have a better chance of
getting there if you improved your portfolio diversification.
</P>
<P>
   You don't spell out the amounts in each fund, but four of the
seven funds hold similar portfolios _ Fidelity Growth and Income,
Contrafund, Magellan and Vanguard Index 500 all hold portfolios
that represent a blend of growth and value large-cap stocks. Since
three of these are in the 401(k) account where three quarters of
the contributions are going, it seems that what is already an
overreliance on this market sector will soon become a serious
overweighting.
</P>
<P>
   I would swap Fidelity Magellan for Fidelity OTC fund, and
Vanguard Index 500 for Vanguard Small-Cap Index.
</P>
<P>
   As for your fund selections, all seem solid with one exception _
Vanguard Aggressive Growth (as the Horizon fund was renamed late
last year). This fund seems to to have not lived up to its promise;
perhaps aggressive investing just doesn't match Vanguard's style.
Morningstar Mutual Funds now classifies its portfolio as mid-cap
value, which seems an unlikely focus for aggressive growth.
Although it has returned nearly 10 percent so far this year, I'd
look back to the scant 0.55 percent total return of 1998, its
two-star rating from Morningstar, and make a switch.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's Mid-Cap Index seems a better bet. If you make the
changes I suggest, the effect is that all the holdings in the Roth
IRA will serve as minor themes to the overall portfolio, with
large-cap dominance continuing in the IRA, plus the minor themes in
mid-cap stocks (the OTC fund) and international stocks through
Fidelity Overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In suggesting these changes, I'm presuming that the holdings in
the various accounts are more or less equal. If not, I'd move
things around so the diversification works out like this: 50
percent in the large-cap funds, which are now so dominant, 20
percent in mid-cap funds, and 10 percent each in small-cap,
international, and health care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have noticed that you frequently advise people to put money
in Fidelity Select Health Care fund. I am considering putting some
money in this fund, but have three main concerns.
</P>
<P>
   First, the fund's managers are quite young and seem to have no
previous experience in the health care industry _ both were
previously in charge of totally unrelated funds. Second, the fund
seems to be heavily invested in pharmaceutical companies. Even
though they can be very profitable, wouldn't a fund invested in a
broader cross-section of the health care industry be better?
Lastly, there has been much talk about greater government
regulation of health care. Were the government to impose any price
controls, the profitability of the industry would be greatly
affected. I realize that such regulations may never come, but the
possibility cannot be ignored. What are your thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   R.M., Natick, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Taking your points in order, I'll begin with the fund manager
issue. What you're seeing in the managers' career histories is
simply a reflection of the way Fidelity is organized. The fund
family makes it a practice to move managers through diverse
investment disciplines, changing their jobs frequently and giving
them experience in a lot of different kinds of markets. Do I think
it's ideal? No _ before it closed, my choice among the health care
funds was Vanguard Specialized Health Care, where the manager has
been at the job for more than 15 years. But on the other hand,
Fidelity's track record with its musical chairs approach to fund
management has been very good, and so has the record of this fund,
despite the relatively frequent change of fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, when I look at a health care fund, what I don't want is
a portfolio touching all the industry bases. Funds that devote
significant parts of their portfolio to health care delivery
companies _ hospitals, HMOs and the like _ and to biotechnology
issues offer more risk than I am willing to assume. Fidelity Select
Health Care, like Vanguard Health Care and a few others, gives
short shrift to these industries, and to me that is a plus. Besides
for pharmaceuticals, the Fidelity funds also focuses on companies
making health care equipment, which is another end of the industry
where growth prospects appear to be very good.
</P>
<P>
   The government regulation issue is, of course, troubling. And
anybody who has been following pharmaceutical stocks for the past
couple of months knows these issues are under a lot of pressure as
politicians debate the cost of prescription drugs. I guess my
summary would be this _ the government has tried before to control
the health care industry, with very small concrete results. My
guess is that the latest efforts will end up much as previous ones
did. But, reflecting this final and considerable element of risk,
please note that when I recommend health care funds, I suggest that
they represent only a small percentage of a long-term portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
