<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-LUNCH (Undated) _ Once it was the three-martini lunch.
Now it's the no-martini lunch. It's just not the occasion for that
kind of boozing anymore. It's not a lot of other things, either.
It's not leisurely. It's not expensive. It's not heavy: No dessert
most of the time. As the business lunch has come under the
increasing pressures of time, budgets and health concerns, many
restaurants realized they had a choice: adapt with a lunch that
works for the times or deal with a lot of empty tables. They're
adapting, cleverly and often agressively. By Marian Burros. With
photos.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-CUISINE (Undated) _ There is a place, at the very
geographic center of Europe, that is home to one of the most
refined food and wine cultures anywhere. It is Friuli-Venezia
Giulia, the region on the far northeast fringe of Italy, where
Europe's three principal cultures _ Latin, Slavic, Germanic _
converge. By Fred Plotkin.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED-CHICKEN (Undated) _ The best chicken I ever tasted
wasn't the poulet de Bresse stuffed with truffles that I had in
France. It wasn't the chicken wrapped in lotus leaves and baked in
a mound of clay in Hong Kong. It wasn't even my Aunt Annette's
plump, golden gedempfted capon (although it comes close). No, the
best chicken I ever tasted came off a barbecue pit in Memphis,
where it had been smoked upright in a singularly undignified
position _ straddling an open can of beer. By Sgteven Raichlen.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPAGNE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews
``Champagne Cocktails.''
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Pasta with fresh herbs.
By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   BERRY-DESSERTS (Undated) _ Simple, light berry dessserts, during
the height of the season. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Pan-roasted duck breast with
sweet white corn. By Thomas Keller and Michael Ruhlmna.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   DILBERITO-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ Eating Well column: The
Dilberito, a concoction being marketed as a vitamin pill in a
tortilla. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Bordeaux, France) _ Looking beyond the classic
regions _ the Medoc, the Graves, St.-Emilion _ for good Bordeaux at
affordable prices. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule wine review: Chateau
Montrose, St.-Estephe, Bordeaux, 1995. About $70.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Food questions answered. By Melissa Clark.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Living Section stories by early evening
with a ``d'' category code, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star,
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
