<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-06 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SPORTS COVERAGE GOES TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For women sportswriters, the ones who know the
rules of their business, the big story out of Wimbledon last week
was a disaster. Basketball Hall of Famer Julius Erving confirmed
that he had engaged in an extramarital affair with Samantha
Stevenson, a sportswriter who had covered his team, and that their
liaison had produced a child, rising tennis star Alexandra
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   A tabloid TV show promptly ran a story on female sports
journalists and their relationships with their sources. One woman,
a television reporter, said that athletes and journalists are
co-workers and that co-workers often date each other. Imagine Dan
Rather hitting on Tipper Gore, and you'll have a rough idea of how
wrong that woman was.
</P>
<P>
   Is Samantha Stevenson's private life any of our business? Let me
repeat the PG-13 version of a legendary quote from a newspaper
editor: ``I don't care if my reporters sleep with elephants, but
they'd better not be covering the circus.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't know exactly how Stevenson went about her affair with
Dr. J, aside from his statement that he ended up paying child
support. We know that Erving was married, but journalists have no
right to ask how much Stevenson intruded on the marriage, or how
badly he betrayed his wife. More than anything, I'd like the
answers to these questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did she write anything about him or his team after they had
begun a personal relationship?
</P>
<P>
   _ Has she been careful since not to cover anything that would
involve him, even remotely, in the 19 years since their daughter
was conceived, since they forged an intimate and financial bond?
</P>
<P>
   I tried to call Stevenson for answers and couldn't reach her.
All I know now is how this looks, and it's very ugly. The
appearance of impropriety hangs all over this story, in neon. Maybe
Stevenson has an explanation. If so, I hope it's better than the
one offered by that television reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Do reporters sometimes date their sources? Yes. Some do it
unscrupulously. Some remove themselves from a story or a beat as
soon as they recognize an irresistible attraction. This happens to
all reporters, male, female, straight, gay, television and print.
</P>
<P>
   But women sportswriters face the most suspicion. It's not fair,
but it's life. We go into locker rooms, among naked men _ famous,
rich, naked men. It's only natural for people to suspect that we
have motives other than good storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   When I covered the Philadelphia Eagles, several of the men on
the beat asked me which players I found most attractive. I found
the question laughable. My stock answer was: ``I'm always madly in
love with the last guy who gave me a great quote. Then I move on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just as unethical for reporters to date the trainers,
equipment managers or the public-relations staff of teams they're
covering. The same rules apply. But if Alexandra Stevenson were the
daughter of a former NBA trainer, would I be as worried about the
fallout for the women in my business? Of course not. Dr. J's fame
is part of this story. Fairly or not, it raises the issue of
whether women sportswriters use press credentials to indulge in
groupie behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing people, whether they're athletes or elected
officials, requires establishing a rapport without straying into
intimacy. Over the years, a couple of sources have asked me: ``Can
I tell you something just as a friend?'' I replied, in effect: ``I
like you and respect you, but as long as I'm in this job, we can't
be friends. If you did something wrong in your job, a friend would
never put it in the newspaper. I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times in my career, I've been asked on dates by people
I've interviewed. One was a professional athlete, and I said that
I'd have to give up my job, so thanks, but no. The other two were
not athletes. They were far out on the periphery of what I usually
covered. I asked my editors what they thought. In both cases, they
said it would be all right to go on the date.
</P>
<P>
   With one man, it was clear that I'd never need or want to write
about him again. He published a newsletter about a local sports
team. We went out.
</P>
<P>
   It thought about the other one for a while and decided that I
was uncomfortable giving up covering even the small part of the
sports world he inhabited. We didn't go out.
</P>
<P>
   Should I have to reveal this? I wish not. But the Stevenson
story makes me feel like disclosure is necessary. I never thought
it would be. One look at me on the job _ no makeup, bad clothes,
aging gracelessly, deadline by stressful deadline _ should tell
anyone that I'm not there to flirt.
</P>
<P>
   But I've also learned that some people aren't that picky.
Several years ago, I covered a double-header in Philadelphia that
lasted until 4:40 a.m. I went down into the bowels of Veterans
Stadium during one of the night's epic rain delays. I wanted to
interview the grounds crew. A San Diego Padre, relatively anonymous
and probably long gone from the game by now, was playing catch with
a coach in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you married?'' he asked as I walked by.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a boyfriend?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I have your phone number?''
</P>
<P>
   I shook my head, laughing to myself, and told him: ``There'll be
something younger and better-looking waiting for you back at the
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   And even at 4:40 a.m., I'm sure that was true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
