<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-FAME-SUB-BOS &LR;      07-06 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-FAME-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO HAS ALWAYS BELIEVED IN `FAME' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects theatre location in fourth graf.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fame'' may live forever.
</P>
<P>
   And that would be fine with David De Silva, a.k.a. Father Fame.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the phone interview is over, it's not clear whether
the sobriquet is a paternal reference or a religious one. Because
when it comes to ``Fame: The Musical,'' De Silva's unbridled
enthusiasm takes on messianic qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's played in 16 countries and had more than 4,000
performances,'' says De Silva from his Manhattan apartment. It will
add another city to its hit list when ``Fame: The Musical'' is at
the Colonial Theatre in Boston for a two-week run. ``It's amazing .
. . and wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Fame: The Musical'' is directed and choreographed by
Lars Bethke with lyrics by Jacques Levy, music by Steve Margoshes,
and a book by Jose Fernandez, it's De Silva who's been with it
since the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   De Silva conceived the idea for a musical based on a high school
specializing in the performing arts in the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always liked the idea of magnet schools,'' he says.
``Schools that take kids out of their own neighborhoods are good
for expanding their perspectives. I also think that it gets
students together with similar interests, and through friendship
they achieve more. I thought it would be a good idea for a show.''
</P>
<P>
   It was.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most amazing aspects to the story is that it took so
long for ``Fame'' to make it to the stage. Traditionally, a musical
opens on Broadway. If it's successful, it's sold as a movie. If
that's successful, it might become a TV special.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Fame'' began as a 1980 Alan Parker movie, transmogrified
into an NBC series that ran from Jan. 7, 1982, until Aug. 4, 1983,
on the network and until 1987 in syndication. It wasn't until 1989
that the stage version emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted it onstage, and we were headed for Broadway,''
says De Silva, 60, whose enthusiastic voice makes him sound like
one of the bright, optimistic kids in his show. ``But it didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   De Silva sold the film rights to his idea about a bunch of
all-singing, all-dancing, all-races, all-classes students at New
York's performing arts high school to MGM in the late '70s. In
1980, Parker's musical (or, more accurately, film with music) hit
it big in the nation's movie theaters. The idea of fresh-faced,
talented teenagers all grasping for the elusive brass ring of fame
hit at just the right time. They wanted to live forever. They
wanted us to remember their names. It was multicultural,
multiracial, and multidimensional.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, choreographer-actress Debbie Allen led a gaggle of
newcomers into the TV version. During a visit to the set on a sound
stage at the Burbank Studios, it was clear that the teenagers who
were playing characters on the verge of stardom saw themselves as
on the verge of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really play ourselves, but we play characters who
have the same goals,'' said Lori Singer, one of the stars, at the
time. And they still do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a theme that everyone understands,'' says De Silva. ``No
matter what you're interested in, it applies that you want to
achieve something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Although De Silva was listed as a consulting producer on the TV
show, he didn't have much to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have control over the screenplay and movie or the TV
show,'' says De Silva. ``But I did one smart thing. I retained the
stage rights. I always knew we would find a home for it in the
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would take a lot longer than De Silva thought.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, following a successful tryout in Miami and a smash run
at Philadelphia's Walnut Street Theatre, it looked as if ``Fame''
was destined to play just downtown from the Fiorello LaGuardia High
School of Music and Art and Performing Arts where the musical is
set _ on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   But there were problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost ready,'' says De Silva, without going into
detail. ``But none of the people involved could agree on how to put
on those final touches. And the timing was off. I realize now that
not going to Broadway was a blessing in disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because with the way everything has turned out, I couldn't be
happier,'' says the former history teacher turned theatrical agent
turned producer.
</P>
<P>
   De Silva, borrowing a page from his never-say-die musical,
refused to surrender. In 1990, the script for ``Fame: The Musical''
was published in Music Theater International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some producers read it in Stockholm,'' he says. ``And they
decided to put it on. It ran for two years _ in Swedish. It opened
in Britain, later. In the West End of London. It was so successful
in the United Kingdom that it generated more than 60 productions in
Great Britain _ in schools, community companies, and little
theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   De Silva is rolling. Enough about not making it to Broadway.
Let's accentuate the positive. ``Fame'' has apparently made it
everywhere else. He's just returned from Denmark, where a
production just opened. He went to Buenos Aires for a Spanish
production, and he's headed to Sydney next month for the Australian
version.
</P>
<P>
   And he's getting a little tired of talking about the business
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really like about the show is that it celebrates the
American musical. It gets young people involved in participating
and going to the theater. `Grease' can have the '50s and `Rent' the
'90s, we've got the '80s,'' says De Silva, in a tone suggesting the
decades concept didn't just occur to him. ``It brings together kids
of all races and classes. Black, white, Asian, rich, poor. And it's
organic. Everything that arises in the story comes from the
characters and their situation. We didn't cast stars. We cast
really talented performers who, like the characters they play, need
a shot at show business. But it's not meant to persuade students to
go into the musical theater. It's about getting young people to
appreciate the arts. To capture the kind of inspirational feelings
I had when I started going to the theater in the '50s. It's that
kind of show. The kind of show that invites them in and invites
them back.''
</P>
<P>
   But will ``Fame'' last forever?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will last forever in the theater as a blueprint for young
people who want to achieve something in life,'' says De Silva,
unapologetically. ``It's gone beyond my wildest dreams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
