<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Relax, Flan Watchers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I love to make flan, but the caramel is time-consuming and
must be watched constantly to prevent burning. Do you have a less
daunting method?
</P>
<P>
   A. The most reliable and easiest way is in a microwave oven. In
her book ``Microwave Gourmet'' (William Morrow, 1987), Barbara
Kafka says that when the sugar and water for the caramel are
tightly covered and cooked by microwave, the resulting steaminess
prevents the sugar from crystallizing and insures even cooking.
</P>
<P>
   To make caramel for a flan, combine the sugar and water called
for in the recipe (or use } cup sugar and 3 tablespoons water) in a
4- or 6-cup glass measuring cup. Cover tightly with microwave-safe
plastic wrap, and cook on high for 4 to 5 minutes, until the syrup
turns deep amber (the longer it's cooked, the darker the caramel).
Watch carefully, checking every 10 seconds as the caramel
approaches the desired shade. Remove from oven, pierce plastic with
a knife and uncover carefully. Pour the caramel into the flan mold
as the recipe specifies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To Sift Flour, or Not &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it really necessary to sift flour when baking?
</P>
<P>
   A. Even though most flour is now sifted before packaging, it
compacts as it stands. For an accurate measure, some air needs to
be incorporated back into it. Sifting does this, but so does
stirring and fluffing the flour with a fork before measuring.
</P>
<P>
   Flour still needs sifting for delicate cakes and sponges,
however. The aeration lets the particles mix more quickly and
uniformly with the liquid ingredients without overmixing, which
toughens the batter. In such cases, use a regular sifter or pass
the flour through a coarse strainer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Safety of Dried Fruit  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it true that you should boil dried fruit or dip it in
boiling water before eating it because it picks up bacteria in the
drying?
</P>
<P>
   A. Unless you want to reconstitute the fruit, there is no need
to douse it. Christine Bruhn, director of the Center for Consumer
Research at the University of California at Davis, says dried fruit
contains no more pesticides than fresh fruit, and may even harbor
less bacteria. During drying, the moisture drops so much that most
bacteria cannot survive. The Federal Food and Drug Administration
tests both dried and fresh fruit for pesticide residue and
bacteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
