<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A DOG'S LIFE IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For doggies, San Francisco is paradise compared
to any other city in America. And measured against any other region
anywhere, Northern California is just about doggy heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The city has several doggy-friendly play, run and swim areas
where pooches of every type imaginable, from Newfoundlands to Heinz
57s, have been able to celebrate the summer weather. In the Bay
Area and beyond, there are additional parklands, open space and
forests where there are more things for doggies to sniff than in
their wildest foot-shaking, yipping dreams.
</P>
<P>
   I've never seen so many dogs as in the past week in San
Francisco, as thousands of people headed to the water to enjoy the
surprise temperature tantrum, and bring their best pals with them.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are allowed to run without a leash, but under instant
control, at Fort Funston near Ocean Beach, Baker Beach just west of
the Golden Gate Bridge, and along the Bay at Crissy Field and
Marina Green. This is where doggies can satisfy every fascination,
whether it be stick or tennis ball fixations or sniffing
obsessions. Another great off-leash dog run area in San Francisco
is at the Presidio, especially starting from the parking lot
adjacent to the Presidio Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   Racks installed by the National Park Service provide dog owners
with plastic bags for cleaning up refuse so it can be disposed of
properly.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other great destinations throughout the Bay Area
and beyond where you can take your dog. And there are a few others,
where questionable wisdom has been applied, where you cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best include the open space and trails operated by the
Marin Water District, and in the East Bay, the 55 parks in the East
Bay Regional Park District. Two of the best here are the Point
Isabel Shoreline near Berkeley and the Sunol Region Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Among the worst destinations with dogs are the state parks and
state beaches in the Bay Area, such as Big Basin Redwoods and Half
Moon Bay State Beach, where dogs are prohibited on the trails.
Among state parks, McNee Ranch at Montara is a rare exception.
Another agency on the doggy dirt list is the Midpeninsula Open
Space District, which prohibits dogs on trails at its 10 best
preserves.
</P>
<P>
   In the mountain country, dogs are welcome across 20 million
acres of national forests in California, featuring thousands of
miles of trails, no leash required. That includes high-country
wilderness, though many dogs are poorly suited for wilderness
travel, especially above tree line. In national parks, such as
Yosemite, Lassen Volcanic, Point Reyes National Seashore and
Sequoia-Kings Canyon, dogs are expressly prohibited on trails.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
