A0691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      07-06 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Chateau Montrose, St.-Estephe, Bordeaux, 1995. About $70. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   T HERE is a lingering suspicion that where one tastes a wine can
affect one's judgment of it. I have always been partial to Montrose
for its power and its elegance, rating it along with Cos
d'Estournel as the finest of the St.-Estephes. But tasting through
half a dozen or so vintages at the chateau recently with the owner,
Jean-Louis Charmolue, I must confess to having been swayed by the
beauty of the place.
</P>
<P>
   Situated on a gentle rise overlooking the Garonne, with its
almost 200 acres of impeccable vines stretching to the river's
edge, Montrose is easily one of the most beautiful and lovingly
nurtured estates in the Medoc. So when I say this is a superb wine
of great depth and richness, well worth its price, you might want
to take my words with a grain of salt. So, too, my impression that
it combines the power of a great St.-Estephe with the roundness of
a fine Margaux or even a St.-Julien. Yes, my judgment may have been
swayed, so the only thing to do is try it for yourself. Or dash
over to Bordeaux, and try it with Charmolue.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, be patient; this is still a young wine, and it
really needs another five years in the bottle, by which time, I
hope, my critique will not seem flawed after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
