A0692 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-     07-06 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT GOES TO BAT FOR HOME TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Texas _ This Cooke County town of 15,000 has always
been an agricultural center. In the days of the cattle drives, it
was the last stop before Oklahoma Territory; it became a major
supply station for local ranches after the drives dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton became king; then oil surged from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball was what got people really excited. When
Gainesville prospered, it played baseball. And it prospered a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooke County Heritage Society is showing off the town's
diamond prowess now with a special exhibit at the Morton Museum,
just off the courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, called, ``Play Ball,'' will run through mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was pretty normal for the times,'' Shana Powell
said of Gainesville's love of baseball. Powell, who is in charge of
the exhibit, said baseball was played as early at the late 1880s in
North Texas. ``It was just good entertainment and people enjoyed
going to the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Games were played against local towns, like Muenster and
Lindsay, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball exhibit is not on a grand scale. The Morton Museum
uses old photographs for the most part, scattered around in
different cases, each one representing an inning. There are balls
and bats and the occasional uniform. Each display is accompanied by
a description Powell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said her love of baseball spurred her to do the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we had a lot of the items here, particularly the
photographs,'' she said. ``And, I have a real passion for baseball.
I love the game. Since I'm the one who decides on what exhibits we
have, it was a natural decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teams played in Gainesville over the years _ the
Gainesville Cookies, Gainers, Tigers, Owls and Leopards. Most of
them were semipro teams. Often, the players got little more than $1
a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Gainers produced a Hall of Fame player. Paul ``Big Poison''
Waner began his baseball career with the semipro team. He was so
nicknamed because at 153 pounds, he outweighed his brother, Lloyd
``Little Poison,'' by 3 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Waners were teammates with the Pittsburgh Pirates and are
the only brothers in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The first game in Gainesville was played in 1889, according to
museum records. Home plate was on what is now Commerce Street, and
the local team beat one from Sherman, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   In 1896, the local paper announced, ``The Baseball Association
is making plans to entertain the Fort Worth Club here next week in
a series of games to be played in the local park.'' Funds were
solicited to pay for the Fort Worth team's visit.
</P>
<P>
   By 1911, there was a team in the Texas-Oklahoma League.
Gainesville had its first salaried team then, and it won the league
title against Denton in the last game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The game almost ended in a riot, though. The Gainesville players
were accused of inserting a ``rabbit ball'' into the game _ a ball
that is more lively than normal and one that exploded off the
rough-hewn bats.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Denton team couldn't prove its allegation, and
the victory stood. Gainesville prospered.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is open Tuesday through Friday from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
and on Saturday from noon to 5 p.m. For more information, call
(940) 668-8900.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
