<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV18-NYT     07-06 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Fishing in Normandy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Two years ago in Normandy, in a restaurant in Ducey, I saw
pictures of salmon and was told they were caught in town. What can
you tell us about salmon fishing there? _ Paul P. Eggermann,
Milltown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ducey is a town of about 2,000 in the Manche Department,
about 12 miles east of Mont St.-Michel, on the Selune River. And
yes, salmon are caught there _ and in the See River, a few miles
north.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon season runs March 13 to Aug. 31, and according to
Michel Bouteloup of the Normandy Regional Tourism Board, the best
fishing is usually in May and June. There are annual limits of 142
salmon from the Selune and 261 for the See. By the end of June,
about 100 salmon were taken from the Selune and 130 from the See,
Bouteloup said.
</P>
<P>
   The individual limit is six salmon a year, and a license is
required. A carte vacance, a temporary license good for any 15-day
period, costs about $24, at 6.3 francs to the dollar. A yearly
license costs $63. Salmon fishers must also buy a minimum of two
rings to mark each fish caught. These rings, used to carry the fish
and to help the authorities monitor the overall catch, cost about
$16 each.
</P>
<P>
   In Ducey, fishing licenses and the rings are available from
Didier Guerin at Le Gain's Bar, 56 Grande Rue; phone (33-2)
33.58.46.40. He also offers a free fishing guide. The bar is open
daily, and there are usually fishermen there whom you can hire as
guides, Guering said.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to stay or dine at the Hotel Auberge de la Selune, 2
Rue de St.-Germain, 50220 Ducey, (33-2) 33.48.53.62, the chef,
Jean-Pierre Girres, will guide you to some of his favorite fishing
spots, according to his wife, Josette. She said they can help with
purchasing a license, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Normandy Regional Tourism Board is at 14 Rue Charles
Corbeau, 27000 Evreux, (33-2) 32.33.79.00, fax (33-2) 32.31.19.04,
and has a Web site at www.normandy-tourism.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An Alaska Drive &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A friend and I will be going to Anchorage in September, and
would like to drive to Nome or Kotzbue, near the Arctic Circle. Is
this possible, and if not, how can we make the best of a week
driving in Alaska? _ Ann Boyd, Plant City, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. In the words of John Beiler of the Alaska Division of
Tourism, driving to Nome or Kotzbue is ``impossible: there is no
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he suggested a route that includes three of the state's
four highways. What he calls ``the loop'' would take you from
Anchorage to Denali National Park and Preserve and to Fairbanks on
Highway 3 (the Parks Highway), then back on Highways 2 and 4 (the
Richardson and Glenn Highways). This drive of about 800 miles,
which includes two crossings of the Alaska Range, can be made
comfortably in five days or so, Beiler said. The fall colors could
be spectacular, he said, and you will probably see wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best place to see wildlife is in Denali. This park,
which includes 20,320-foot Mount McKinley, the spectacular top of
North America, has 37 species of mammals and 130 bird species _
including moose, caribou, grizzly bears and golden eagles. The
visitor center offers nature hikes and sled dog demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   It costs $5 a person or $10 a family for a seven-day pass to
enter the park. Private cars are not allowed beyond the first 15
miles of the 91-mile road through the park, but shuttle buses from
which you can get on and off ($12.50 to $31) and narrated tour
buses with lunch, but no getting off ($34 to $64), are available.
Shuttle bus places can be reserved at (800) 622-7275, and tour bus
spots at (800) 276-7234. For general information on Denali National
Park, call (907) 683-2294 or see www.nps.gov/dena.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Tranel, the park's spokeswoman, cautioned visitors to be
prepared for a variety of weather, especially in September. Snow
that can close the park road is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The only lodging in the park is at the Denali Park Hotel, (907)
683-2215, but there are many motels or lodges just outside Denali,
some of which can book wildlife tours; call (907) 683-4636, for
information.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the city of Fairbanks, with its museums, the pioneer
theme park Alaskaland and, with luck, views of the aurora borealis,
other areas to stop overnight on the loop include Paxson and
Glenn-allen. The Tourism Division's Inquiry Section, at (907)
465-2010, can help you plan the trip. Or go on line at
www.commerce.state.ak.us/tourism/homenew.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dining in Westminster &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have heard that there are restaurants in the Palace of
Westminster. Are any open to the public? _ Kenneth Utz, Uniontown,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are several restaurants in Westminster, where the
Houses of Parliament meet. But unless you somehow win election or
an invitation from a member of Parliament, you won't be able to
dine in them.
</P>
<P>
   The area around Westminster isn't highly regarded for its
restaurants, but there are a few places worth trying. Here are
three that are so regularly used by politicians that the division
bell that signals a return for a vote rings in all of them:
</P>
<P>
   The Atrium, 4 Millbank, (44-171) 233 0032, is probably the
nearest restaurant to the Houses of Parliament, about 5 minutes
walk. It is open Monday to Friday only, serving lunch from noon to
3 and dinner from 6 to 10 p.m. The food includes traditional dishes
like fish and chips and shepherd's pie in the winter as well as
more exotic offerings, like poached halibut on saute mange-tout,
baby corn and cherry tomatoes; asparagus, prawn and salmon risotto;
or stuffed saddle of rabbit on a potato rosti and peppercorn sauce.
A meal for two with house wine and tip costs about $160, at 63
pence to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Also nearby is Shepherd's, at Marsham Court, Marsham Street,
(44-171) 834 9552. It is also open only Monday to Friday, with
lunch from 12:30 to 2:45 P.M, and dinner 6 to 11 p.m. The menu
includes the traditional steak and kidney pie and roast rib of beef
and Yorkshire pudding as well as roasted monkfish and smoked bacon
with spinach and ratatouille. A three-course meal costs about $40,
including coffee but not wine.
</P>
<P>
   Simply Nico, 48A Rochester Row, (44-171) 630 8061, is another
popular haunt of politicians. It is open noon to 2 p.m. Monday to
Friday for lunch and 7 to 11 p.m. every day but Sunday for dinner.
Although the menu changes, typical dishes are fillet of brill with
artichokes and green beans, or roast saddle of lamb with lamb
sweetbreads, capers and tomato. Three courses cost about $37, not
including beverages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
