<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTING OURSELVES ON THE BACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Did you have a good Self-Congratulation Day?
<P>
   That was the unofficial title of Monday by the bay. We had it
coming. In a little over a week, we:
</P>
<P>
   -- Hosted the X Games, which were so wildly popular that Willie
Brown is considering granting full humanhood status to
skateboarders, even though Willie's cops are still telling kids
that skateboards are illegal in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the X fans not tear down the town, they freshened
it up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   If the X Games events seem silly to sports traditionalists,
imagine what baseball (the ZZZ Games?) must look like to the
uninitiated. ``I say, Harvey, that man holding the wooden stick _
what is he searching for in his pants?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Hosted the GayBiUnameit Parade, the world's most exuberant
out-of-closet experience, and who needs a closet anyway when your
summer wardrobe fits in your handbag?
</P>
<P>
   -- Hosted and dominated the greatest women's soccer match in
history, the USA's 2-0 win over the Bullies de Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I shouldn't have used the qualifier ``women's.''
</P>
<P>
   And would it be un-P.C. to call our women the Soccer Mamas?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday the women will catch up to the men in staging
big-time sports events, and then the World Cup women's soccer will
be as tedious, self-important and flat as the recent NBA Finals.
Until then, we'll all just have to endure the kind of pure joy,
unspoiled athleticism and lack of whining that beamed out of
Stanford Stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Put on the nation's grandest fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   And lived _ most of us _ to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   I WAS OUTTA town for a few days, and the first thing I did upon
returning was check the week's obit pages. I wasn't in 'em and
neither was The Chronicle, so I came to work.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mind The Chronicle being for sale, but I hope we don't
have to put up with a bunch of Lookie Lous poking around the
building, tsk-ing at our cluttered desks and unconventional decor.
</P>
<P>
   You should have seen the place before we tidied up.
</P>
<P>
   And, hey, if I draw creative inspiration from my photo montage
of Sharon Stone's greatest movie roles, that's my business.
</P>
<P>
   In The Chronicle newsroom's snack corner, there is a posted
price list for the coffee, tea and doughnuts. Somebody added to the
list: ``KRON _ $5,000,000.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, that includes Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE 31ST consecutive year, Laura Watson reminds me, I missed
the Worm Races at Clear Lake, Calif. I don't have the name of the
winning worm, but all the other competitors, as a consolation
prize, were taken on a fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking of entering a worm next year. Or if I'm feeling
low, I might sign on as a jockey.
</P>
<P>
   A prime spot for viewing Sunday night's S.F. Bay fireworks was
McCormick &AMP; Kuleto's restaurant, which was booked solid two months
in advance. Turned away at the door were two 49ers players and one
consul general, and all were miffed.
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised to hear this. Not surprised that they were
turned away, but that there are still 49ers around. With the
DeBartolo family feud still raging, I assumed the franchise had
been disbanded or relocated to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T SPREAD this around, because we don't want to scare away
the tourists, but nobody was surfing at Stinson Beach on Sunday.
Sharks were sighted in the water (where else?) the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The sharks might have been scared off by Sunday's fireworks,
though. Stinson is where the nouveau riche now gather on the Fourth
to blow their cash and explosives stash. From sunset to well past
midnight, the Stinson sky was afire with illegal and private
fireworks, and not your puny lawn-display stuff, but the
industrial-strength God-bless-America boom-booms.
</P>
<P>
   I REGRET to report, after a quick trip to Santa Monica last
week, that NorCal still lags far behind SoCal, culturally.
</P>
<P>
   Up here, we sail through red lights, sure, but not with the
consistency and consummate arrogance of our southern neighbors, who
have come to look upon signal lights as festive, year-round
Christmas decorations.
</P>
<P>
   And cell phones? Unlike the overly timid Bay Area cell-phoner,
the Santa Monican is not afraid to put his or her body into the
conversation, gesturing grandly at curbside or poolside and having
the courtesy to speak loudly so the rest of us need not strain to
eavesdrop.
</P>
<P>
   I dined at a coffee shop where the menu listed two numbers under
each item _ the calories and the grams of fat in that dish. Made me
feel so guilty that I ordered water and ate the menu. Fiber, baby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
