<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN LEAD THE WAY FOR GOLF GREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Juli Inkster has insisted on sharing the
spotlight on her great year in golf with husband Brian and
daughters Hayley and Cori, partly because she credits them for her
resurgence at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I had kids, golf was my life,'' Inkster said in a
recent telephone interview. ``I lived and breathed golf, and every
day I couldn't wait to get back out there to get it back or hold
onto it. But when I had kids my perspective changed, and it wasn't
the most important thing to me anymore. ... I enjoy it more, and I
think that's why I'm playing so well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Payne Stewart won the U.S. Open, though, not a word was
written about his children, and that double standard is not lost on
Inkster, who completed the Grand Slam with her LPGA Championship
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little different with men having kids,'' said
Inkster, who lives in Los Altos, Calif. ``The maternal gene is I
guess the guilty gene, and I think it's different for a man. Even
though they love their kids and would do anything for their kids,
the bonding isn't there. I couldn't imagine being away from my kids
for two weeks. The men will go for four weeks and it's not a big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster points out that she's privileged to be able to afford to
take her family on the road with her, something a struggling pro
probably couldn't do. Yet she embraces the opportunity to be a role
model for girls who want to have it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the kids out there to know you can do both, you can win
a tournament and have your husband there and your children there to
share it,'' she said, expressing the hope that girls who excel at
sports won't reach the point that they think feminity requires them
to be ``a cheerleader or a Barbie girl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
