<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-PEACH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANNER YEAR FOR FROG HOLLOW PEACHES  
   
 AT THE SOURCE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders.  By Janet Fletcher 
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The chilly winter and cool spring may have had
most Northern Californians complaining, but not the peach farmers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What was bad for citrus was good for stone fruit,'' confirms
Al Courchesne, who cultivates 53 acres of certified organic peaches
and other stone fruits at his Frog Hollow Farm in Brentwood. ``I
think it's going to be a banner year for peaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Courchesne's early varieties, such as Queencrest, have been
higher in sugar and larger than normal, and his overall crop size
looks larger, too. He credits the weather _ the exceptionally cold
December and January followed by a cool, dry spring.
</P>
<P>
   Winter chill apparently hardens the tree's buds so they flower
simultaneously, which improves fruit set. A cool spring promotes
slow and steady fruit development. Early hot spells _ which we
didn't have _ hamper cell division, cause pits to harden and
generally throw the growth process off track. Rain during the
growing season _ which we haven't had _ encourages fungus, mold and
brown rot.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, says Courchesne, it was a perfect spring.
</P>
<P>
   Sought after by shoppers at Bay Area produce and farmers'
markets, Frog Hollow fruit excels in part because Courchesne picks
it ripe. Supermarket peaches are typically nine to 12 degrees brix,
he says, referring to a measure of sugar content at harvest. In
contrast, his early varieties range from 14 to 17 degrees brix; his
later peaches, from 18 to 23 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken us 24 years to select the varieties we're happy
with,'' says Courchesne, who names the Cal Red, a late-August
peach, as his favorite. He has phased out white peaches because
they don't have the acid level he seeks, but he has found 25 other
varieties that allow him to harvest high-quality fruit from mid-May
to mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Late varieties such as Cal Red and O'Henry are always superior,
he says, with denser flesh and more sugar, but early peaches
satisfy consumers who just can't wait. Mid-July should bring the
Sun Crest, the older variety that Mas Masumoto wrote about in his
acclaimed ``Epitaph for a Peach.'' ``It's the first peach of summer
that gives you that true peachy quality,'' says Courchesne, who has
several acres of them.
</P>
<P>
   At the market, look at background color, suggests the grower.
The best peaches have a red blush against a deep gold background.
Check the area around the stem, the last part to ripen. If it's
green, leave those peaches behind.
</P>
<P>
   At home, keep firm peaches on the counter so you can monitor
them as they soften. ``It's a myth that the best peach is the one
you picked yourself and ate under the tree,'' Courchesne says. ``In
my experience, the best peach is the one you pick and age for three
to four days at room temperature. It will get better and better.''
In any case, avoid refrigerating peaches, which halts their
development and mutes their flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Frog Hollow Farm fans will welcome the news that Courchesne and
his partner Rebecca Smith are nearing completion of a commercial
kitchen. Smith, a former pastry chef at Oakland's Oliveto, will
make peach marmalade and peach conserve to sell at the stores and
farmers' markets that carry the farm's fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Frog Hollow's exceptional peaches fetch a
premium _ about $3 a pound at Bay Area farmers' and retail markets
(see related list for places where the peaches are sold). But the
fruit's handling is exceptional, too. Typically, the peaches are
picked in the morning and delivered in the afternoon, often by
Courchesne himself. On Saturday mornings, dressed in overalls, the
tanned farmer is at the Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market, handing out
samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the farmers' market,'' says Courchesne. ``You spend a
year growing the fruit and you get to be in on the final sale.
You're talking to the person who bought your fruit last week and
they're back this week to tell you how much they loved it. It's the
ultimate fulfillment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
