<HEADER>
A0726 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOODNEWS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-06 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD IN THE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This regular round-up column will make
practical sense of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well
as offering offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to
put on your plate.   By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle.  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Everyone knows a good marinade can do wonders for
the flavor and texture of grilled meat. Now it appears marinating
meat might help prevent cancer, too.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Studies by the American Institute for Cancer Research, a
nonprofit organization that focuses on the link between diet and
cancer, show even a 40-minute bath in an acidic marinade stops the
formation of carcinogenic compounds called heterocyclic amines. The
compounds form when meat is cooked at high temperatures and
particularly when it is charred.
</P>
<P>
   Although scientists aren't exactly sure why marinades prevent
the carcinogens from forming, a number of clinical trials with
different marinades shows acidity is key. So if you use a marinade
for cancer-fighting purposes, make sure it contains citrus juice or
vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the cancer institute has been urging people to take
steps to reduce the possible cancer risk posed by  &LR; grilled &LR;  food.
Precooking meat in the microwave, removing fat that causes grill
flare-ups, using tongs to turn meat and being careful not to
puncture the flesh are among the organization's other
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Break an Egg
</P>
<P>
   Egg cartons might soon bear labels warning consumers about the
dangers of salmonella if a proposal by the Food and Drug
Administration becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   The new label is among a package of egg safety changes the FDA
and the U.S. Department of Agriculture announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If the label makes it through a round of public hearings later
this year, it will read, ``Eggs may contain harmful bacteria known
to cause serious illness, especially in children, the elderly, and
persons with weakened immune systems. For your protection: Keep
eggs refrigerated; cook eggs until yolks are firm; and cook foods
containing eggs thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the package of industry reforms is a new federal
directive requiring that all eggs and egg products packed for
consumers be refrigerated at 45 degrees or below at every stage of
transportation and storage. That will go into effect Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 to 1998, there has been a 44 percent decrease in the
number of illnesses caused by salmonella, according to the
Foodborne Diseases Active Surveillance Network, known as FoodNet, a
collaborative effort of several federal agencies including the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The measures announced last week may prevent up to 66,000
illnesses and 40 deaths per year, according to FoodNet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
While We're on the Subject
</P>
<P>
   An astute reader from the University of California at Berkeley
noted an error in a previous Food in the News item about eggs.
</P>
<P>
   In April, we brought you the news that a study of more than
100,000 healthy individuals showed an egg a day doesn't appear to
increase chances for heart disease or stroke. In explaining that
eggs contain nutrients that might reduce harmful serum cholesterol,
called low-density lipoproteins, the column item misidentified the
sort of cholesterol contained in eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The human body produces both beneficial and detrimental serum
cholesterol. Eggs contain dietary cholesterol, which affects the
type of serum cholesterol the body produces.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the study was that eggs contain antioxidants,
folates, B vitamins and other nutrients that might help the body
produce fewer low-density lipoproteins and could raise the level of
the more beneficial cholesterol called high-density lipoproteins.
That means that eggs might not be as bad for overall serum
cholesterol levels as previously thought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
