<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-CAKE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVOLI'S STRAWBERRY SHORTCAKE IS PERFECT  
   
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim.  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Even those of us who love strawberry shortcake
have to admit that it's not always perfect; usually there's one
element that is disappointing.
<TEXT>
<P>
   However, that's not the case with Rivoli's Buttermilk Shortcake
with Strawberries and Meyer Lemon Syrup. All the components are
right on target.
</P>
<P>
   Chef-owner Wendy Brucker has created a shortcake with a tangy
sweetness and a crumbly sconelike texture. She cooks and purees
some of the berries into a sauce, and embellishes the whipping
cream with creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, she drizzles the whole wonderful dessert with a
Meyer lemon syrup. It's perfect.
</P>
<P>
   That's only one of the exceptional dishes crafted by Brucker at
Rivoli in Berkeley, which she owns with her husband, Roscoe
Skipper. I'd put the appetizers up against anyone, especially the
signature slices of portobello _ battered, deep-fried and served
with a topping of shaved Parmesan, capers and a crock of lemon
aioli. And for a main course, you can hope the pot roast with
buttery mashed potatoes is on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   The recently-remodeled dining room has an open, casual feel. The
manicured garden out back is a lovely focal point for the
interior's green and burnt umber color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Rivoli, 1539 Solano Ave. (near Peralta), Berkeley; (510) &LR; 
 &LR; 526-2542. Open for dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Berry puree. &LR;  Even less-than-spectacular berries are delicious when
they're mixed with a sweetened cooked berry puree.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The whipping cream. &LR;  Mixing creme fraiche into the whipping
cream gives the topping extra heft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lemon syrup. &LR;  This extra garnish brings all the elements
together.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; RIVOLI'S BUTTERMILK SHORTCAKE WITH STRAWBERRIES &AMP; MEYER LEMON
SYRUP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
The Shortcakes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter, chilled and cut into 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Sugar for sprinkling top
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Filling
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sliced strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze of lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   The Cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   The Syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Meyer lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Line a baking sheet with parchment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the shortcakes:  &LR; Sift together the dry ingredients into
a bowl. Add the butter and mix with your fingers until it is broken
up and the mixture has the texture of wet sand. Add the buttermilk
and gently mix it in.
</P>
<P>
   Shape the dough into 6 shortcakes on the baking sheet. Use a
4-inch ring mold to shape the cakes, easing the dough into the ring
with the aid of a soup spoon dipped into hot water. Space the
shortcakes 4 inches apart on the baking sheet. Place the baking
sheet on another baking sheet. This keeps the bottom of the
shortcakes from burning. Sprinkle the tops of the shortcakes with
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 10 minutes. Let cool, then slice the shortcakes in
half. If made ahead, store in a covered container.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the filling:  &LR; Combine 1 cup of the strawberries, the
sugar, salt and lemon juice in a small saucepan. Cook over medium
heat for 20 minutes, stirring occasionally. Puree and strain. Let
cool to room temperature, then toss with the remaining
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the cream:  &LR; Combine the whipping cream, creme fraiche,
vanilla and sugar; beat until medium peaks form.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the syrup:  &LR; Combine the sugar, water and zest in a
small saucepan; bring to a simmer over medium heat. Cook for 5
minutes. Cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble the shortcakes:  &LR; For each serving, place the bottom
half of a shortcake on a dessert plate, cut-side-up. Top with a
generous spoonful of the strawberries, then a large dollop of
whipped cream, and finally more strawberries. Crown with the top
half of the shortcake and drizzle with a portion of lemon syrup.
Dust with powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 765 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 84 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 46 g fat (28 g saturated), 151 mg cholesterol, 338 mg sodium, 3 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
