r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSHBORE-RACE-SFCHRON     07-06 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSHBORE-RACE-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GUSHES, ONE BORES _ BUT SONG'S THE SAME
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The 2000 presidential campaign has hardly begun, and already
they're calling it the Gush-Bore race.
<P>
   The media pack seems to have anointed Republican George W. Bush
as the gush _ spontaneous and fun-loving _ while tagging Democrat
Al Gore as the bore.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor came to California last week for his first
big show, and he was treated like Latin pop sensation Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was here the previous week, his 57th
California trip, and got all the attention of a Vanilla Ice.
</P>
<P>
   But from backstage, the reality is that the two front-runners
are singing the same songs _ tuned to the ear of that mainstream,
moderate, middle-of-the-road voter who will make or break their
election bids.
</P>
<P>
   Both trekked across California with a presidential air,
proclaiming that theirs is the fresh vision for the 21st century.
From fund-raiser to fund-raiser, in polo shirts and in suits, they
staged carefully crafted photo ops while corraling the press behind
velvet ropes that allow little opportunity for substantive
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in Los Angeles, San Diego and San Francisco, stressed
bedrock issues: family, faith, continued prosperity and education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in Los Angeles, San Diego, San Francisco and a roster of
other cities, stressed family, faith, prosperity and education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the 21st century goal of prosperity must be ``to reach
out to every member of our society, to make sure no one is left
behind.'' Bush said ``the purpose of prosperity is to leave no one
out ... to leave no one behind.''
</P>
<P>
   They both rubbed elbows with the Hollywood crowd, and talked up
the Latino vote, displaying their best Spanish _ yes, Hispanics in
2000 are ``muy importantes,'' they agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked of ``revolutionary changes'' in education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was praised by Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan as a
candidate who supported ``a revolution in education.''
</P>
<P>
   And they were big on families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a coalition of common sense that focuses on the best
interest of working families,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a plan ... that helps struggling families on the
outskirts of poverty,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed on gay marriage (no) and on a ban on offshore oil
drilling (yes).
</P>
<P>
   And they were positively overflowing with hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to create a brighter, more humane, optimistic future''
for all Americans,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are waiting for new hopes, new energy, new
idealism,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this conformity, a few significant differences did
manage to emerge: Gore talked guns (``We need to be shielding the
children against gun violence ... not the gun manufacturers''),
while Bush admitted signing a law permitting Texans to carry
concealed weapons and acknowledged that lawsuits against gun
manufacturers have not fared well in his state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked about protecting a woman's right to choose; Bush
stuck to his anti-abortion roots, and said he hopes for an America
in which every unborn child will be protected by law.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of them dwelled on the tough stuff. Or spent any
time detailing policy.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 months to go before the 2000 election, the moderate
middle isn't really listening, anyway. And Gush/Bore promise many
more trips to California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
