<HEADER>
A0732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERRY-DESSERTS-NYT &LR;      07-06 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRY-DESSERTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MEAL'S END, A BERRY GOES A LONG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blueberries are in the markets, velvety red and gold raspberries
beckon jewel-like from tiny baskets, and soon big, shiny
blackberries will be available to pick in the countryside or to buy
at farm stands. What a trove!
</P>
<P>
   And you can find other berries, like the good strawberries that
are still available, and less common varieties like boysenberries,
bushberries, loganberries, currants, gooseberries and fraises des
bois. As any berry picker equipped with a sun hat and a bucket
knows, ripe berries plucked from the bush need no adornment. But
the magic of berries is that even the ones you buy in summer have
enough rich, tart-sweet satisfaction to carry the day with minimal
support.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, a berry tartar that I was served for dessert
last year at Chateaubriand, a French steakhouse in midtown. It was
a deep-scarlet cylinder of a finely chopped assortment of berries
on a plate drizzled with a thick berry coulis and dotted with a few
ovals of mascarpone. With liqueur as an ingredient, it had an
intensely winy flavor, making for as satisfying a fruit dessert as
you could want.
</P>
<P>
   I obtained the recipe and decided to save it for berry season,
which was a good thing since the restaurant is temporarily closed
for renovations. But other equally fine mixed berry desserts _
intensely flavored, refreshing and kind to those who care about
looking trim at the beach _ are ripening on menus now.
</P>
<P>
   Cooling fruit soups are studded with berries and crowned with
icy sorbet. Some examples are Erik Blauberg's mixed berry and
honeydew soup with passion-fruit sorbet and Luc Dendievel's mixed
berry soup in a red wine base. Laurent Tourondel's marinated
raspberry and green-tea infusion spiked with blood-orange juice at
Cello adapts summer's iced tea for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Blauberg also makes a terrine of black and red currants,
raspberries and wild strawberries, bound with nonfat yogurt and
gelatin and garnished with mint. Similar sophisticated updates of
the old-fashioned Jell-O mold include Mary Brannigan's mixed
berries in a Sauternes gelatin at 27 Standard, and Stephane Motir's
shimmering terrine made with muscat de Beaumes-de-Venise at the
Tonic. These desserts are beautiful, delicious, easy to prepare and
as summery as a garden party.
</P>
<P>
   BERRY TARTAR
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours, including chilling
</P>
<P>
   1{ pints raspberries
</P>
<P>
   1{ pints blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, hulled
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons raspberry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Chambord liqueur or creme de cassis
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons mascarpone
</P>
<P>
   4 small mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Rinse berries, and drain on paper towels (berries must be
dry).
</P>
<P>
   2. Place 1 cup each of raspberries and blueberries plus a few
sliced strawberries in saucepan with sugar, vinegar and liqueur.
Cook over low heat about 20 minutes, until soft. Puree in food
processor, and then force through sieve. Refrigerate until cold,
for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, finely chop remaining berries by hand, and put
them into a sieve suspended over a bowl to drain for 30 minutes.
Transfer to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   4. When sauce is cool, mix a few tablespoons of it with the
chopped berries. Form }-cup portions of berry mixture into
cylinders on each of four dessert plates, using a round mold or a
can with top and bottom removed. Drizzle remaining sauce around
tartar, and then place a couple dollops of mascarpone on each
plate. Garnish with mint, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MARINATED RASPBERRY AND GREEN-TEA INFUSION
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus marinating and cooling
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups blood-orange juice (about 10 oranges), strained
</P>
<P>
   { cup green-tea leaves
</P>
<P>
   { pint raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   1. In 3-quart saucepan, dissolve sugar in 2 tablespoons water,
and cook over high heat until sugar is very lightly caramelized.
Remove from heat, and add orange juice, standing back because it
may spatter. Reheat, and stir with wooden spoon until caramel is
dissolved. Add tea leaves, and cover. Allow to cool about 10
minutes, and then strain, reserving about 1 tablespoon of tea
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add raspberries to orange juice mixture, and refrigerate for
2 hours. Using slotted spoon, scoop raspberries into four soup
plates, pour sauce over, and garnish with a few reserved tea
leaves. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINE-BERRY SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bayard's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle medium-bodied red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 clove
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split in half
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   { lemon, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1{ pints hulled strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1{ pints raspberries
</P>
<P>
   1 pint blueberries
</P>
<P>
   { pint blackberries
</P>
<P>
   Yogurt ice cream or raspberry sorbet, optional &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine wine, cinnamon, clove, vanilla, sugar and lemon in
saucepan. Bring to boil.
</P>
<P>
   2. In bowl, combine 1 pint strawberries, 1 pint raspberries, {
pint blueberries and all the blackberries. Puree in two batches in
food processor. Add to saucepan, return to simmer, strain, cool to
room temperature, and then refrigerate for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Slice remaining strawberries, and divide among six soup
plates. Scatter in remaining berries. Pour cooled soup over, add
scoop of ice cream or sorbet, if desired, and garnish with mint.
Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BERRY TERRINE IN MUSCAT DE BEAUMES-DE-VENISE JELLY
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 hours
</P>
<P>
   1{ envelopes plain gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 half bottle (350 milliliters) muscat de Beaumes-de-Venise
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar, plus more for berries
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split in half
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pink peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1{ pints raspberries
</P>
<P>
   { pint strawberries, sliced
</P>
<P>
   { pint blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   1. Soften gelatin in { cup orange juice. Combine remaining juice
with muscat, sugar, vanilla and peppercorns in saucepan. Bring to
boil. Remove from heat, stir in gelatin to dissolve, and then
strain.
</P>
<P>
   2. Puree 1 pint raspberries, strain, and sweeten to taste.
Refrigerate until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   3. Line 6-cup oblong terrine with plastic wrap. Pour in thin
layer of muscat mixture and remaining raspberries. Refrigerate
until set, about 1 hour (or freeze about { hour). Add blueberries
and half the remaining muscat mixture, and refrigerate 1 hour. Then
add strawberries and remaining muscat mixture, and refrigerate at
least 3 hours, until firm. Unmold, and peel off wrap. Serve in
thick slices with raspberry sauce drizzled around.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
