<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMPAGNE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPES FOR AN ICY GLASS OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Recipes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say it is good to sip hot soup in the summer. Good for your
health perhaps. But what feels good is anything icy cold. If it's
bubbly, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why ``Champagne Cocktails'' (Regan Books, $12) by
Anistatia Miller, Jared Brown and Don Gatterdam, is appealing. At
New Year's, you can take the bubbly stuff straight, but this time
of year a cool cocktail seems a better approach.
</P>
<P>
   This entertaining guide begins with a brief history of Champagne
and moves swiftly to the recipes, from classics like the Bellini to
new concoctions like the imperial duo, made with Champagne and
Cognac. There are plenty of tips for the novice and trivia. For
instance, lemon peel may look pretty in a Champagne cocktail, but
it has a flattening effect on the wine.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding which drinks to try was difficult. James Beard's
Champagne punch caught my eye. What could that man have found
acceptable to mix with Champagne?
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, just about everything: Cognac, Cointreau,
orange juice, lemon juice and zest. The punch was a deep amber, the
surface covered with strands of zest and slices of cucumber. The
first few sips were citrusy and refreshing, the next few cloying.
Which could be a good thing. More than one of these would put a
quick end to a day.
</P>
<P>
   Individual cocktails were more elegant. An Americana, made with
bourbon, a dash of bitters, Champagne and a slice of peach, had
guts. The bitters held the fruit and caramel flavors in balance and
kept the drink refreshing. Pink Champagne cocktail _ a swirl of
rose Champagne, Grand Marnier, brandy, bitters and sugar _ was the
color of a rose petal and tasted a little sweeter as the sugar
dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   I tried some recipes simply because of their names. The
Colonel's Big Opu (opu is belly in Hawaiian) is a mix of lime
juice, cracked ice, gin, Cointreau and Champagne. The drink is
mostly about gin and lime, but the Champagne had a lovely
lightening effect. Nelson's Blood turned out to be a beauty, the
rim of the flute coated in grenadine and sugar so that it looked
like a ruby necklace and mirrored the port and Champagne in the
glass. Perfect after a meal.
</P>
<P>
   A Champagne julep had a few problems along the way. The recipe
calls for using a muddler to mash a sugar cube with a sprig of mint
in the flute. Most flutes are too narrow for this, and it is hard
to crush a sugar cube without some liquid to loosen the crystals.
But the drink was superb, subtly minty, subtly sweet and
deliciously bubbly. All that a Champagne cocktail should be. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE COLONEL'S BIG OPU  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Champagne Cocktails''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juice of half a lime
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Cointreau
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dry gin
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Champagne. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Squeeze lime into a tall 14-ounce glass, and half fill with
cracked ice. Add gin and Cointreau, then gradually add Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 drink.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPAGNE JULEP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Champagne Cocktails'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 sugar cube
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs peppermint
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Champagne
</P>
<P>
   1 orange slice.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a short glass, mash the sugar cube with a mint sprig.
Scrape mixture into a flute; fill with Champagne. Mix with a bar
spoon; garnish with a mint sprig and orange slice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 cocktail.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
