<HEADER>
A0740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-LUNCH-ART-2T     07-06 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-LUNCH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW BUSINESS LUNCH: FASTER, HEALTHIER, NO MARTINIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A business lunch today is positively Spartan compared
with those fabled three-martini events a quarter-century ago. The
martinis have been replaced by iced tea, mineral water, possibly a
single glass of wine. The hearty dishes that lingered until dinner,
like pot-au-feu, have become grilled chicken or a salad. The
leisurely two-hour interlude has slipped back to an hour or less,
and, for many, into carryout at the desk or sandwiches in the
conference room.
</P>
<P>
   As lunch has come under the increasing pressures of time,
budgets and health concerns, many restaurants have realized that
they must either adapt or deal with empty tables. They have chosen
to give customers what they want, like three courses in less than
30 minutes, or ready to go in a plastic container. And they are
having some success.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to fill its tables at noon, Lespinasse, one of New
York City's temples of gastronomy, recently sent a promotion to its
customers: ``In the '70s, you had lunch. In the '80s, you did
lunch. In the '90s, you skipped lunch. Perhaps it's time you
redefined lunch.'' The restaurant has done just that: three light
courses for $36 in one hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to eat fast and furiously,'' said Eberhard
Mueller, the chef and owner of Lutece. ``Years ago, you could serve
the French classics, but you can't sell them anymore. Now it's
salads, grilled fish, grilled meats, less starch, more protein and
healthier than ever and
please-make-it-fast-I-have-to-be-back-at-the-office-in-one-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for prix-fixe meals, most people eat no more than two
courses, often just an entree. Lunch has become a time to abstain,
dinner a time to splurge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an image thing,'' said Chris Cannon, a partner at Judson
Grill. ``It makes them look serious and healthy in front of
customers.'' It's a far cry from the days when a boozy haze was the
desired effect and not much work was done in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's tons of water, iced tea and cranberry spritzers and
$22,000 coffee machines that make six kinds of coffee: cappuccino,
espresso, double cappuccino, double this, double that,'' said Alan
Stillman, who owns Smith &AMP; Wollensky, Maloney &AMP; Porcelli and
Manhattan Ocean Club. But wine by the glass is selling, and to
protect that single-glass toehold, some restaurants have enlarged
and upgraded the choices.
</P>
<P>
   When Union Square Cafe opened in 1985, it offered two wines by
the glass; today there are 10. Eleven Madison Park, one of its
sister restaurants, offers 36. ``People are drinking only one glass
of wine, but they are willing to pay,'' said Charles Palmer, owner
of Aureole on the Upper East Side. His list includes a $26 glass of
1996 Chateauneuf-du-Pape.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants that want to stay in business cater to the changing
demands of their clientele, even if they don't approve. If a good
customer wants a meal boxed up to eat at the desk, even the
fanciest places will oblige. In the old days, Mueller said, when a
guest asked for sauce on the side, chefs would refuse. Today the
customer is always right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a three-course prix-fixe lunch for $38,''
Mueller said, ``but now if someone wants two courses we won't
refuse. If someone wants a bowl of soup and a salad, be my guest.
My lunch business, based on these subtle changes, is much better
than three years ago, by being in tune with what people want to eat
and their time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in steakhouses, only about a third of the lunch entrees are
steak; at dinner they account for 85 percent of the meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the appearance on the menu of healthful
dishes,'' said Cannon of Judson Grill. ``But people don't want a
spa menu, because they don't want to feel like they are going to
some spa.'' Which is exactly what the Four Seasons, considered by
many to be the power center of the midday meal, learned several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The spa menu was a great idea for a year or so,'' said Julian
Niccolini, a managing partner. ``People are interested in eating
healthy food, in very fresh, freshly prepared organic food. They
are interested in flavors. Great food doesn't have to be with
sauces.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Rocco DiSpirito, the chef at Union Pacific, simple
is better. ``People may not be able to enjoy interesting or
complicated food at lunch,'' he said, because they don't have the
time. ``We've simplified our lunch menu so you're not needing the
waiter to explain everything to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Markson, a Manhattan literary agent, appreciates efforts
at simplicity. ``When I first started, lunch was incredibly
exciting,'' Ms. Markson said. ``Now I try to make it as healthy as
I can. No drinking. Water, water, water, unless I have a foreign
guest. If I'm trying to be good, it's two appetizers and coffee.
Now I'm not looking at the breadbasket. Desserts are out, out, out,
unless you are with someone who is very thin and wants you to share
a dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and health are not the only influences on the changing
lunch business. There are hundreds of new options to fill the
gaping culinary and price differential between the Four Seasons and
the corner deli. Not the least of these is the corporate dining
room, an increasingly standard feature at large companies. Conde
Nast, which moved to its new headquarters at Broadway and 43d
Street last month, will soon be operating an elaborate Frank
Gehry-designed dining room for its staff and for in-house
entertaining. Investment bankers like Credit Suisse First Boston
are providing employees with in-house dining as well as a health
club, a hair salon and a dry cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   These amenities save companies time and money. ``It's the most
efficient utilization of time from our standpoint,'' said Luther
Terry, a managing director of Credit Suisse. The executive dining
rooms are also used to entertain clients, providing privacy that a
public restaurant cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate dining rooms were considered ostentatious once,''
said Clark Wolf, a restaurant consultant. ``No longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The booming economy has also created hundreds of new
restaurants, and, Wolf said, the number of seats exceeds the
demand. In some neighborhoods the competition among top restaurants
is particularly fierce. Over the last six months, 700 seats have
been added in the Madison Park area: Union Pacific, Patria and
Gramercy Tavern have been joined by Veritas, Tabla and 11 Madison
Park. Cena, a highly regarded restaurant in the neighborhood,
closed last week for lack of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to get people in the door,'' said
DiSpirito of Union Pacific. ``We used to average 70 to 80 for
lunch; now the average is 50. We were counting on the Credit Suisse
to be a big source of revenue, but I don't think they leave their
desks.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't need to leave their building, anyway, the same one
that houses 11 Madison Park and Tabla, Danny Meyer's two new
restaurants. He, too, was counting on the 2,000 employees of Credit
Suisse. Meyer, a shrewd businessman, decided that if if they
wouldn't come to him, he would go to them. This summer he will be
delivering $12 box lunches (sandwich, dessert and beverage) to
those people and selling to anyone who wants to pick one up.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a time when tables must be booked weeks in advance for
dinner, restaurants are finding that they need incentives to get
people in the door for lunch. The annual restaurant week promotion
when dozens of the city's top restaurants offer a prix-fixe lunch _
$19.99 this year _ is frequently extended for the entire year. At
the Gotham Bar and Grill, the $19.99 lunch accounts for about half
the lunch business, said the owner, Jerome Kretchmer, whose other
restaurants include Park Avenue Cafe, Judson Grill and Mesa Grill.
``It gets lots of people to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McLaughlin, a managing partner of Oceana and Molyvos,
called last year's $19.98 lunch at Molyvos a ``win-win situation,
with 250 people a week out of 800 or 900 buying that lunch, which
will probably be a permanent feature.''
</P>
<P>
   Other restaurants offer limited, less expensive menus at the
bar. A three-course lunch in the lounge at Le Cirque 2000 is $25.
Le Bernardin began the Timely Lunch Menu 18 months ago, and Eric
Ripert, the chef, insists that it can be served in less than 30
minutes. The $32 three-course prix fixe has increased business from
about 80 or 90 noontime customers to more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, in the throngs of rushed and hungry New Yorkers,
there are holdouts _ most often in publishing and advertising,
where people still ``do lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gottlieb, the publisher and president of Harry Abrams,
remembers the old-style lunch with fondness. ``Lunch was always a
moment of relaxation, a time to catch up,'' he said. ``It still is
for me, a moment out of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Markson, the literary agent, has been eating lunch out five
days a week for 27 years. ``Lunch is absolutely the lifeline,'' she
said. ``It's the leisure of lunch that makes the deal happen. I
don't know what I'd do without it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are still some restaurants that don't need to offer
incentives to fill up. Judson Grill, Union Square Cafe, Michael's
and the Four Seasons _ which all cater to those who  &UR; do &LR;  lunch _
are almost always booked. Regulars think of those places as their
private clubs, where they are known and feel comfortable. The Four
Seasons is the ultimate lunch club, but even it is relatively quiet
on a getaway day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only day we have a problem is on Friday,'' Niccolini said.
``People want to get out of town as quickly as possible, and in the
summer they don't want to come to work at all on Friday. People are
making so much money, many don't have to, and because of the
Internet they can work at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed: just when lunch patterns seem to have settled in,
something comes along to unsettle them. Corporate dining rooms are
one thing, but the Internet may take an even greater toll on
restaurant lunch. Who needs to dicker over poached salmon when the
deal can be done in a flash on line?
</P>
<P>
   And despite evidence to the contrary, at this very moment,
martinis are making a comeback at the Four Seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
