<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0757 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     07-06 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOAP TRIES TO LURE YOUNG VIEWERS WITH GOTHIC STORY LINE,
MULTI-ETHNIC CAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a stretch to say that NBC's cancellation of ``Another
World'' amounted to a cultural crime, as one caller described the
show's death between racked sobs the other day. She received no
sympathy here. In fact, my suggested punishment for the network
programmers who wielded the ax is to force them to actually sit
still and watch the daytime soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another World'' had its core fans, but tales of serial killers
and switched babies doomed it and its loopy plot twists after 35
years. You could say it was put out of its misery.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hardly surprising that ``Another World'' faithful have
vowed bitter hatred toward its replacement, the younger and
therefore advertiser-friendlier ``Passions,'' which got its first
airing Monday on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any consolation, ``Passions'' is the brainchild of
James E. Reilly, known to harbor Stephen King-ish instincts when it
comes to creating daytime drama (it's even set in Maine). And one
of its stars is Liza Huber, a ready-made marketing device,
considering that her mother is daytime superstar Susan Lucci.
</P>
<P>
   A reading of Reilly's descriptions of ``Passions'' leads one to
expect it to borrow from ``The X-Files,'' ``Melrose Place'' and
``Peyton Place''_ although press materials also mention as an
influence ``Dark Shadows,'' the late-'60s soap that featured
vampires, ghosts, haunted houses, werewolves and other assorted
Gothic demons. All of which might help explain this reported story
line about a lusty voodoo doll coming to life.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a town called Harmony, ``Passions'' will otherwise take
on more traditional, contemporary shadings _ the core family is
wealthy and powerful, and a number of ineffably attractive
protagonists in their 20s roam about in apartments and homes they
couldn't possibly afford. The difference might be ethnicity. Each
family is multigenerational, and there's a prominent Hispanic
family and an African-American one in the loop; what a concept,
considering the absence of minorities on the upcoming prime-time
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passions,'' with a cast numbering 23, decided to forgo name
power, although you might recognize Dalton James (he played Robert
Urich's son on the series ``Crossroads'') and Tracey Ross, the
``Star Search'' winner who had recurring roles on ``Ryan's Hope''
and ``All My Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Dallas/Fort Worth residents might recall Fort Worth native
and Texas Christian University theater grad Travis Schuldt, who has
landed a plum role as Ethan Crane, a member of the town's most
powerful family.
</P>
<P>
   Schuldt will get to smooch Lucci's daughter, who portrays Gwen
Hotchkiss, a wealthy socialite and Ethan's main squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Huber, who grew up on Long Island, N.Y., jumps to ``Passions''
after having studied at four of the city's most prestigious acting
schools. But her bio lists service on the Junior Committee to
support Little Flowers Children's Services of New York, a
child-care agency, and that she's an avid skier and golfer.
</P>
<P>
   The show's pedigree alone makes it worth a sampling. As head
writer for ``Days of Our Lives'' in the early '90s, Reilly was
credited with some of the most-discussed story lines in daytime,
including devil possession, a character being buried alive, another
barely escaping a gas chamber, even a beheading. Gross in the name
of love and lust? Perhaps. But during the 1993-94 season, ``Days''
climbed from No. 8 in the Nielsen ratings to No. 1 among 18- to
49-year-old women, the most coveted demographic for daytime
producers. It's still a ratings winner.
</P>
<P>
   Demographics are mentioned here because business decisions now
more than ever drive an industry shaking with bottom-line fear.
It's part of the reason ``Another World'' became just another
cancellation in the first place. Some soaps continue to draw a
large chunk of viewers and big money (''General Hospital'' alone
earned an estimated $1 million a week ``in profit'' for ABC) but
overall there has been an exodus of its core female viewership,
about 28 percent over the past five years. Audience (read:
advertising base) of ``Another World'' ``had become stagnant,''
says Annamarie Kostura, vice president of NBC Daytime.
</P>
<P>
   If NBC's in-house audience researchers are to be believed,
daytime's core viewers, stay-at-home mothers mostly, are heading
off to work in larger numbers each year, thereby robbing the
networks of a once loyal, somewhat captive audience. That's only
part of the problem, though.
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, the networks refuse to 'fess up to cable's power,
having us believe that the ratings penetrations of HBO, USA,
Showtime and other cable channels mean little. Those how-to shows
on channels like HGTV and the Food Network have got to be driving
network executives nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do I believe the theory that soap operas were hammered by
O.J. Simpson's 1995 murder trial, and that many fans never returned
to their daytime viewing habits at its conclusion. My theory is
that, sure, O.J. coverage forced daytime watchers to notice signs
of life elsewhere. Truth is, soaps got desperate and made mistakes.
``Another World'' was one of the daytimers to turn to outlandish
story lines, figuring that it would bring viewers back to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   If you remember, all the networks were running daytime soap
teasers in prime time _ which only added to their silliness,
particularly if you were jolted by one of these absurd emotional
exchanges while in the middle of some morally ambiguous plot line
on, say, ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism was that soaps were getting too dark and too bizarre,
which is ironic, as ``Passions'' head honcho Reilly is NBC's new
go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   Kostura says they are banking on Reilly because ``he's created
people you like and care about and get invested in. That's the
challenge of soap operas. Once you get character investment, you
start caring about what happens to these people. Then (Reilly)
takes it to another degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostura also says reports on the genre's demise are all wrong,
that Nielsen doesn't keep track of high school and college watchers
who tune in to shows like the low-rated ``Sunset Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   She agrees that viewing habits have changed, but ``there's this
wonderful invention called the VCR. People do tape shows.''
</P>
<P>
   And remember, ``Dark Shadows'' was wildly popular with
teen-agers and young adults. In this era of demographics and
bottom-line madness, count ``Passions'' and those to follow it as
the next vultures to gorge on Young Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
