<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0758 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTIFACTS-HUGENOTS-$A     07-06 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIFACTS-HUGENOTS-$ADV11 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EXHIBIT OF HOW FRENCH ARTISANS SHOWED BRITAIN HOW TO SHINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 (Attn: Britain and France)   By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When looking at good English silver from the 17th and
18th centuries, one should remember that it was meant to be seen by
the flicker of candlelight. In such light, silver shimmers with the
fluidity of water. Seen under lighting that suggests candlelight,
the 112 pieces of silver in ``The Huguenot Legacy: English Silver
1680-1760,'' an exhibition at the Cooper-Hewitt National Design
Museum in Manhattan, is like a glittering ocean with more than a
few lobsters, dolphins and water monsters surfacing in the decor of
the objects.
</P>
<P>
   This collection belongs to Alan and Simone Hartman, a New York
couple who made frequent trips during the last decade to view
silver at the best British museums and amassed fine examples from
this period when Huguenot silversmiths migrated to England from
France. The Hartmans were advised by Christopher Hartop, executive
vice president of Christie's, who organized the show and wrote the
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many silver exhibitions, this one is less concerned with
who made the objects and how valuable they are. Instead, it
documents the development of the English obsession with French
taste and how the infusion of artisans trained for the French court
made it possible for British nobility to realize their ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Sampson Shinn, an assistant curator at Cooper-Hewitt,
has divided the articles into categories that relate to everyday
use _ dining, drinking, dressing. Arranging the pieces in this
manner points up the effects on the English of that other French
revolution, the one in menus and table settings. Also, each piece
is treated as intricate sculpture and displayed in the round, the
better to appreciate the elaborate trimmings with classical
references that were not lost on the original owners.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shinn opens the show with an etching based on Juste-Aurele
Meissonier's rendering of a 1735 centerpiece with a tureen on
either side. The centerpiece and the tureens, decorated with
shells, waves and leaves, became models for silver pieces made for
the Duke of Kingston, illustrating the degree to which such fantasy
landscapes made it to the table.
</P>
<P>
   As Protestants, the Huguenots were persecuted in France under
the Roman Catholic kings. In 1685, when Louis XIV revoked the Edict
of Nantes, which had affored the Hugenots limited privileges, they
emigrated en masse, many to England. Skilled and industrious, they
posed a threat to English silversmiths, who at first thwarted the
professional advancement of their French counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, as Hartop writes, England at this time was
emerging from medieval life and the dining habits of its people
were undergoing change. The new customs required new forms: soup
tureens for soups and stews and sauceboats for rich sauces. The
styles evolved from the classic al Baroque to the curvaceous Rococo
that merged so well with Chinese influences. Large quantities of
silver also arrived from South America, particularly from Peru,
where a whole mountain of silver had been discovered. Similarly
churches and convents were deaccessioning their silver.
</P>
<P>
   To broadcast the country's new sophistication, British
ambassadors were permitted to order plate from the Royal Jewel
House to use and display in foreign embassies. For his gilt dessert
service at the Hague, the fourth Earl of Chesterfield ordered a
pair of octagonal casters, with pierced and engraved domed tops,
for sugar and spice that were designed by Paul Crespin. Silver
candlesticks Crespin also made for Chesterfield are decorated with
shells and foliage like those in Daniel Marot's print, circa 1712,
of silver designs. Marot was the Huguenot designer who brought
Baroque interiors to Hampton Court for William and Mary via the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of caffeine-laced hot drinks in the 17th
century _ tea from China, coffee from Arabia and chocolate from
Mexico _ new vessels were devised to serve them. The chocolate pot
was the most complicated, requiring a high spout and a muddler or
stirrer to keep the heavy liquid from settling. Some containers
were adorned with natural forms related to a beverage: coffee
leaves enclose the spout of a coffee pot designed by Phillips
Garden, and a depiction of women picking tea leaves adorns a set of
tea caddies in the Chinoiserie style.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere were decorations more exuberant than on dining
services. The table setting in the show, laid out with symmetrical
precision, is a veritable feast for the eyes of mythical and
realistic creatures. One pair of sauceboats by Paul de Lamerie is
cast in the shape of shells with raised spirals, an engraved coat
of arms and dolphin handles. He also designed a silver bread basket
with the head of Ceres, goddess of grain.
</P>
<P>
   Even the boudoir, where a woman would receive guests in the
morning, featured grand silver toilet services with ewers for
water, repousse basins and glove trays. Throughout the house
candlesticks illuminated such luxuries at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shinn theorizes that as candlepower gave way to more modern
means of illumination, silver was replaced by porcelain as the
material of choice for the well to do. ``Gaslight and later
electric light visually flattened out the silver, and it never
seemed as wonderful as before,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
