u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALCOHOL-DRUGS-ART-NYT     07-06 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-DRUGS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MAY BOTTLE UP PUSH TO ADD ALCOHOL TO ANTI-DRUG CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Ky.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here's a commercial certain to grab attention
during a break in ``Futurama'' or ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age Bobby shows up at the door to pick up date Jennifer and
for the first time meets Dad, who politely asks where the kids are
heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd go to party at a friend's house, have some
beers,'' answers Bobby. ``Then on the way home there's a good
chance I'll date rape your daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   The jaw-dropping spot closes with this kicker: ``Face the brutal
truth about underage drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly the message that some lawmakers and others
concerned with underage drinking and its link to drug use and
similar social problems would like to see transmitted as part of
the national anti-drug campaign. At present, the almost $1 billion,
five-year effort _ best known for its famous ``your brain on
drugs'' ad _ is silent on the subject of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about an illegal, illicit drug that affects our
young people at a rate six times greater than all the other
illegal, illicit drugs combined,'' said Karolyn Nunnallee,
president of Mothers Against Drunk Driving, which produced the
public service announcement featuring Bobby and Jennifer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the nation's drug czar and leading members of Congress are
opposed to including alcohol in the drug ads, saying it would water
down the effort to steer youngsters away from hard drugs such as
cocaine and heroin. They presently hold the upper hand in the wake
of last Thursday's Senate vote prohibiting spending any drug
campaign funds on an anti-alcohol push.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding underage drinking to the drug czar's portfolio will
only stretch his resources even further and force him to take on
another tough fight,'' said Rep. Jim Bunning, R-Ky., as the Senate
decided 58-40 against including alcohol in the anti-drug
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A key House committee faces a similar choice when lawmakers
return next week from the Fourth of July recess to wade into the
second major liquor fight to break out in Congress this year.
Members of Congress are also wrangling over Internet sales of
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the National Beer Wholesalers Association, which
has led the fight against including alcohol in the drug ads,
believe they can bottle up the idea for now. Leaders of the group
say it is not a question of underage drinking, which they oppose,
but of unfairly labeling beer, wine and spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about tying beer with heroin,'' said David Rehr, senior
vice president of the group. He called the proposal the work of
``neo-Prohibitionists'' determined to turn American culture against
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one of the ways to do that is to send messages to people
through taxpayer-paid ads that there is not a lot of difference
between crack cocaine and wine,'' Rehr said.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of the powerful Washington liquor lobby, not
wanting to appear to favor underage drinking, are content to let
the beer wholesalers be out in front on this issue. But the
industry doesn't like the idea of a joint drug/alcohol campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confuses a legal product that causes beneficial health
effects with illegal street drugs,'' said John DeLuca, president of
the Wine Institute. ``They should not be commingled and not be
confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., a chief proponent of the
alcohol ads, said their purpose is not to disparage drinking by
adults, but simply to force both parents and children to focus on
underage drinking as a ``gateway'' to other drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to have an effective drug campaign, we really need
to get at the root of the problem,'' she said. ``You can't address
the problem of illicit drug use by turning your back on one of the
major ways that young people get involved with drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Roybal-Allard said she introduced her measure after retired Gen.
Barry McCaffrey, head of the White House Office of National Drug
Control Policy, testified he didn't have the authority to add
alcohol to the drug ads. She said she was ``flabbergasted'' when
McCaffrey then opposed her giving him that power.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said in a statement that an alcohol message would be a
``serious mistake'' and could ``dilute the focus of the successful
media campaign advertising effort to change attitudes of youth and
parents toward illegal drug abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   His position is shared by the Partnership for a Drug-Free
America, the coalition of advertising agencies that participates in
the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration is not united. Surgeon General
David Satcher urged McCaffrey to reconsider, writing him on June 11
that ``no comprehensive drug control strategy for youth can be
complete without the full inclusion of underage alcohol use and
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, television stations get a string of public service
announcements on underage drinking and issues such as literacy
along with the drug ads and they are encouraged to contribute air
time for those spots. But those ads do not reach the prime-time
audiences that see the anti-drug commercials the government pays to
air.
</P>
<P>
   Roybal-Allard and MADD leaders are now concentrating on keeping
their proposal alive in the House. They intend to keep fighting
even if the Appropriations Committee rejects it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't allow groups like the National Beer Wholesalers
Association to dictate our country's alcohol policies,'' said
Nunnallee, the Fort Meade, Fla., woman who heads MADD. ``Underage
drinking should have been a big part of this campaign from the
outset.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0762 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-06 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING LIGHT HAS NEW MEANING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lady, your lights are on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms., excuse me, but I noticed that your lights were on when
you came through the drive-through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, turn your lights off. They'll drain your battery.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, kind people. Thank you so much. I know that my
headlights are on at high noon, but there seems to be nothing I can
do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, I want them off. I do want to control what's on and
what's off in my vehicle. But it's getting to the point that the
car simply doesn't need me anymore. It's got a mind of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, it's a rental car. It's a nice car with a V6 engine,
which means that I don't have to wave a white flag out of the
window and bat my eyelashes adoringly to get onto the freeway.
However, it's just a little too independent for me.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I've seen cars with the OnStar system, the vehicle
communications service that provides you with stolen-vehicle
tracking and emergency roadside service. It's very useful. I don't
have it, but I wouldn't mind if I did.
</P>
<P>
   My mother has these seat belts from the dark side that
clothesline you every time you sit in her car. They might save you,
if they don't strangle you first. And, of course, the remote entry
and seats that adjust automatically are worthwhile features.
</P>
<P>
   I'm really not against new technology at all, especially if it
makes my life easier. Nevertheless, I do not want my headlights on
all the time! I have no good reason. I just don't.
</P>
<P>
   I called the rental place to ask about this phenomenon, and they
said that I have ``daytime running lights.'' All late-model General
Motors cars have this safety feature. Some other manufacturers are
doing this as well.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, until I got this vehicle, I had not noticed
the large number of cars driving around in broad daylight with
their lights on. That makes me question the assertion that cars
with their lights on are more visible in traffic. Then again, maybe
I'm just not that observant. Hopefully, we don't have to rethink
this issue five years from now like we did with the air bags.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I thought since this car is so smart, I'd get it to do
something really useful. I put $2 in the driver's seat and told it
to go get me a loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. The car didn't move.
</P>
<P>
   The lights didn't even come on.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. I guess there are still a few things to look forward
to in the new millennium after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
