u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-06 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: SEARCHING FOR GOOD, AFFORDABLE BORDEAUX 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France _ One day in June, I was sitting at the bar of
the Hotel Mercure Pont d'Aquitaine here, having a cold Kronenbourg
with an old friend from California, Bob Thompson. We were both in
town for Vinexpo, the trade fair held in Bordeaux every two years.
He buys wine for an airline.
</P>
<P>
   We compared notes; he had been spending time in the Cotes de
Castillon region, and I was heading out the next day to Fronsac. It
said a lot, we both agreed, on the present state of affairs in
Bordeaux. People are looking beyond the classic regions _ the
Medoc, the Graves, St.-Emilion _ for good Bordeaux wine at
affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Fronsac and the adjoining appellation, Canon-Fronsac, are about
15 miles east of the city of Bordeaux. They are two of the wine
communities radiating out of Libourne, a bustling little city grown
prosperous on the success of its neighbors, the best-known of which
are St.-Emilion and Pomerol.
</P>
<P>
   Others include the so-called hyphenated St.-Emilions _ Lussac,
Montagne, Puisseguin and St.-Georges, all of which have St.-Emilion
after their names _ Lalande de Pomerol, the two Fronsacs, the Cotes
de Castillon and the Cotes de Francs.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these and a few other towns to the north are called
the East Bank, meaning the wine communes east of the Gironde River.
St.-Emilion is home to illustrious chateaus like Cheval Blanc,
Ausone and Figeac, while tiny Pomerol can boast of Petrus, Le Pin
and Trotanoy. Few of the satellite communes have properties whose
names come readily to mind. Which is why bordeaux enthusiasts
increasingly are heading east to search out bargains.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change, if some of the wines I tasted are an
indication of what's happening. The 1980s and the 1990s have been
prosperous years in the Bordeaux region, enabling winemakers in
these once-forgotten towns to buy new equipment, plant better
grapes and, most important, reduce crop yields. The result: richer,
more supple wines.
</P>
<P>
   In Fronsac, excellent wines are being made at chateaus like
Fontenil, which is owned by the enologist Michel Rolland; at La
Vieille-Cure, owned by an American group, and at La Dauphine, owned
by the firm of Jean-Pierre Moueix.
</P>
<P>
   But prices, while still well below those in the Medoc, are
rising even in these appellations. So buyers are moving farther
east, to the Cotes de Castillon and Cotes de Francs. The Cotes de
Castillon appellation covers eight communes, the most famous of
which is Castillon-la-Bataille, where, in 1453, the English lost
the Battle of Castillon, effectively ending the Hundred Years' War.
</P>
<P>
   The Cotes de Castillon is a big appellation, with almost 300
properties producing some two million cases of wine a year. There
are no dazzlers among the Castillon wines, but some, like those of
Jouanin, Pitray and La Terrasse, are worth sampling. Chateau Vieux
Champ de Mars _ literally Chateau Old Battlefield _ also
commemorates the end of English rule in Aquitaine.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Romans made wine in what is now the Cotes de
Francs, the appellation wasn't created until 1967, reflecting how
tough it is for a region to convince the authorities that it has
upgraded the quality of its wines.
</P>
<P>
   Chateaux de Francs and Marsau make good wines here, but the
best, and easily the best known, property in the Cotes de Francs is
Chateau Puygueraud, a handsome estate owned by the Thienpont
family, which also owns the famed Vieux-Chateau-Certan in Pomerol.
Puygueraud (pronounced pwee-gair-OH) produces some 15,000 cases a
year, a modest proportion of which comes to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, most of these East Bank wines were made with a
large amount of malbec grapes in the blend. As one travels east
from Bordeaux, malbec becomes more and more important until, in
Cahors, under the name auxerrois, it is the predominant variety. On
its own, malbec can produce a tough, astringent wine. In Cahors,
it's smoothed out with merlot and some cabernet sauvignon. In the
vineyards farther west, it's used less and less.
</P>
<P>
   At Puygueraud, the blend is generally 55 percent cabernet
sauvignon, 25 percent cabernet franc, 15 percent merlot and 5
percent malbec. Chateau de Francs uses no malbec. In Fronsac and
Canon-Fronsac, malbec has all but disappeared, and merlot is king.
At Chateau Canon, it makes up 95 percent of the blend; at La
Vieille-Cure, it's 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With all that merlot, no wonder these wines are growing in
popularity in the United States. As for price, rarely do any of
them reach $20, and many, particularly from the Cotes de Castillon
and the Cotes de Francs, are still under $10.
</P>
<P>
   Great bordeaux? No, but definitely very good bordeaux and often
far better values than some wines from towns whose names are more
familiar.
</P>
</TEXT>
