<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEPBURN-AFI-TEX     07-06 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPBURN-AFI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFI LIST HAS WEAKNESSES, BUT HEPBURN'S LEGENDARY STATUS IS
INDISPUTABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Film Institute has squared accounts with Katharine
Hepburn at last.
</P>
<P>
   She's the foremost ``legend'' among movie actresses, ranked just
above Bette Davis in balloting by the AFI membership. Her ``African
Queen'' co-star, Humphrey Bogart, tops the roster of legendary men.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's results were revealed in a splashy telecast last
month hosted by Shirley Temple, one of the anointed top 25. And for
Kate of the illustrious Hepburns _ Audrey (no relation) placed
third _ the recognition is rich with irony.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, the American Film Institute has annually bestowed
its Life Achievement Award upon variably fabled performers and
other creative artists, beginning with director John Ford. This
honor is such a big deal in Hollywood that the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences plays copycat, now awarding a special
Oscar for career achievement. (This year, controversially, it went
to Elia Kazan.)
</P>
<P>
   The AFI award has illuminated most of the great stars of the
movies' Golden Age. But Katharine Hepburn's name is conspicuously
absent from the roll call of past winners.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The AFI's Life Achievement Award is solemnized by a national
telecast in which the honoree is present, along with friends and
colleagues who testify for his or her stature. Because Katharine
Hepburn has refused to be a party to such proceedings, the AFI has
said, in effect, ``Then you can't have our award.''
</P>
<P>
   Greta Garbo was denied the award for the same reason. She still
wanted to be alone. The award is restricted to persons still
living, and Garbo was very much alive in years when stars of less
distinction than she and Hepburn were gushed over in the televised
ceremonies. Because of such obvious grievous omissions, the AFI
award certainly has been tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Today Katharine Hepburn is 92. She, Marlon Brando and Elizabeth
Taylor are the only AFI top 10 legends who are still living. She
is, therefore, still eligible for the institute's lifetime
recognition, and the AFI could do itself proud by finally honoring
Hepburn with a televised tribute minus her presence.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the results of the poll have sparked lively
second-guessing in Hollywood and elsewhere. There is much squawking
because great artists of the silent screen were all but ignored.
Only Charlie Chaplin and Buster Keaton among the men, and Lillian
Gish and Mary Pickford among the women, made it into the top 25 in
their gender divisions. Chaplin placed 10th, which seems low for
one of his fame, stature and unargued importance in the development
of screen art.
</P>
<P>
   But the results are understandable for logical reasons. The
purpose was not to signify the greatest actors and actresses or
even the greatest stars, but those most exemplifying the meaning of
``legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Each generation creates its own legends. Sure, many stars of the
silent era were throbbing legends in their time, especially among
the men _ Rudolph Valentino, John Gilbert, Richard Barthelmess,
Harold Lloyd, Wallace Reid. But today only film scholars are
familiar with their work, and AFI membership requires no scholarly
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Yet movies from the rhapsodized Golden Age are perennially
available on the home screen. We still watch classic and
not-so-classic movies from the '30s, '40s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Stars certainly were more magnified in the years of the refined
studio system, but the greatest stars of that period do not
translate into the premier legends. Cary Grant, James Stewart,
Spencer Tracy and Gary Cooper all had more substantial starring
careers than Humphrey Bogart; yet Bogie, who died 42 years ago, is
a bigger star today than he was during his lifetime, definitely an
icon for younger generations.
</P>
<P>
   If the AFI had played this guessing game say, 30 years ago,
Bogart might not have been first, and Garbo surely would have
placed higher than fifth woman.
</P>
<P>
   Who's the finest actor the Golden Age produced? If it isn't
Spencer Tracy, surely it is Fredric March, but no legend attaches
to him simply because he was never categorized. March didn't make
the list, nor did Irene Dunne or Norma Shearer or Jean Arthur or
Olivia de Havilland, all of whom had measures of artistic
achievement that surpassed Marilyn Monroe and Elizabeth Taylor, who
are legends indeed and expectedly high on the list.
</P>
<P>
   A sure way to become a legend is to die young. Jean Harlow died
62 years ago at age 26; Carole Lombard was 33 when killed in a
plane crash 57 years ago; and James Dean, after three starring
roles, was only 24 when he died in a car crash 44 years ago. All
were prominently ranked as legends. Montgomery Clift wasn't; but if
the auto accident that almost killed him at age 34 had done so, he
would today be a legend equal to or even surpassing Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Bette Davis was the pre-eminent female star during the long
heyday of the studios and would be a less sullied legend today if
she had simply quit on top, as Garbo and Shearer did. Instead Davis
_ Joan Crawford, too _ descended into ghoulish claptrap.
</P>
<P>
   Not Katharine Hepburn. She rolled with the punches, acted her
age, remained discriminating in choosing her spots, eventually
bagged an unprecedented four Oscars, and apparently has ended her
career with distinction uncompromised.
</P>
<P>
   Kate may or may not be the greatest actress the screen has
produced; she's a prime contender for such recognition, and for
``greatest star'' label as well. But the foremost legend? No doubt
about it.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor and arts critic for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
