<SLUG> BC-FOSSILS-THEFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURASSIC CRIME: RESEARCHERS FEAR OPEN MARKET ON DINOSAUR FOSSILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sixty-eight million years ago, Cinderella
stomped around the humid swamps and forests of Montana, her
10-foot-high shoulders knocking off tree branches as she pursued
small mammals and other four-legged snacks.
</P>
<P>
   She was a 35-foot-long Tyrannosaurus rex, the king of the
dinosaurs well known to ``Jurassic Park'' fans. In her day she was
Earth's leanest, meanest and hungriest fighting machine.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays her scant remains, and those of her fellow dinosaurs,
are so enormously prized that they attract high prices, at
potential risk to the low-budget science of dinosaur research.
Complete dinosaur skeletons command prices in the millions, a
temptation that encourages thieves.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, someone sneaked into an office at the Museum of
Paleontology at the University of California at Berkeley,
surreptitiously opened a file drawer and swiped the sole proof that
Cinderella _ as Berkeley scientists have dubbed her _ had ever
lived: a 2-foot chunk of her jawbone.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it appears, the thief sold Cinderella's jawbone and
plaster copies of it.
</P>
<P>
   The recent recovery of the fossil in Europe by the FBI renewed
scientific fear that a federal proposal to open public lands to
fossil bounty hunters could create a price war, blocking
scientists' access to quality bones.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Bureau of Land Management is studying possible impacts
of letting fossil hunters sell bones found on federal lands, as
advocated by Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. These
fossils now must be turned over to approved repositories such as
museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us in the field of paleontology have been oblivious to
this (threat) because to us, these fossils are research items, or
are used in teaching or public education,'' said David Lindberg,
director of the Berkeley museum. ``And all of a sudden, we've
realized we're sitting on a small Fort Knox.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Sotheby's auctioned off a near-complete T. rex
skeleton for $8 million. The scientific community breathed a sigh
of relief when the investors turned it over to the Field Museum in
Chicago, but fear that future fossil-robber barons may not show
such public spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists ``were repulsed by the fact that there would be
an effort to take (away) what basically belongs to the kids of the
country,'' said Louis Jacobs, past president of the Society of
Vertebrate Paleontology, who is a professor at Southern Methodist
University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to paleontology is so great that one Berkeley
paleontologist, Mark Goodwin, issued a plea to the nation's
schoolchildren _ traditional dinosaur buffs _ to mass-mail letters
to the U.S. Bureau of Land Management by a July 15 federal deadline
to protest proposed commercialization of fossil collection on
public lands.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed commercialization pits Daschle against Max Baucus,
D-Mont., who opposes it. They both represent states that are meccas
for fossil hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look to the schoolchildren of our country, who often are
introduced to science through paleontology ...'' Goodwin said.
``Their fossil heritage is at risk if public lands are opened up to
the commercial collecting and sale of their fossil heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Society of Vertebrate Paleontology launched a grass-roots
save-the-fossils campaign four years ago. The ``Save America's
Fossils for Everyone,'' or SAFE, campaign warns on its Web site
that the ``most significant threat to our vertebrate fossil
resources is the illegal collecting of specimens from federal
lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increasing pressure from commercial interests and
fossil dealers to `open up' public lands to commercial collecting
and selling of vertebrate fossils,'' says a posting on SAFE's Web
site (www.museum.state.il.us/svp/ safe/mission.htm.)
</P>
<P>
   The society is a leading U.S. organization for bone-hunters and
researchers. Like the paleontologists portrayed by Sam Neill and
Laura Dern in the 1993 film ``Jurassic Park,'' they spend long, hot
summers slowly, carefully unearthing the bones of the creatures
that dominated the planet eons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Three million years after Cinderella's heyday, and thousands of
miles away from her Montana homeland, a mountainous asteroid fell
from space and punched a massive hole in the ground in Mexico's
Yucatan Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a massive cloud filled the atmosphere that cooled
the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Although not all scientists agree, some researchers believe the
climate change wiped out the dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever iced the dinosaurs, their fossils are the sole
surviving clues to their lifestyles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
