<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-COX07-COX     07-06 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-COX07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS DROPS 1987 TAX CLAIM AGAINST COX FAMILY MEMBERS
 &HT;    330&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By WILLIAM RINGLE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Internal Revenue Service has dropped claims
that Anne Cox Chambers, Barbara Cox Anthony and Garner Anthony owe
additional income taxes for 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Chambers, of Atlanta, is chairman of Atlanta Newspapers.
Her sister, Mrs. Anthony, who lives in Honolulu, is chairman of
Dayton Newspapers. Both are members of the board of directors of
Cox Enterprises Inc. (CEI), one of the nation's largest media
companies. Garner Anthony, Mrs. Anthony's husband, is the retired
chairman of CEI.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS conclusion was ratified June 18 in decisions by U.S. Tax
Court Chief Judge Mary Ann Cohen. She acted after lawyers for the
IRS and the taxpayers stipulated that no deficiencies existed.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, the Tax Court was asked in a petition to find the
IRS wrong in claiming that Mrs. Chambers and the Anthonys each owed
$4 million, besides $2.4 million that each already had paid.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS had said that Mrs. Chambers and the Anthonys each had
received $10,407,290 that it construed as taxable distributions
from trusts known as Atlanta Trust I and Atlanta Trust II. The
trusts had been created by the sisters' father, James M. Cox, who
died in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   The trusts received the payments from CEI for the purchase of
CEI stock, and each trust distributed the proceeds among secondary
beneficiaries of a type known as ``remainder beneficiaries.'' Each
remainder beneficiary got 3.06 percent of his or her interest in
the trust.
</P>
<P>
   Each remainder beneficiary reported a capital gain from the sale
of that portion, the sisters had said. And each remainder
beneficiary ``incurred substantial income tax liability as a result
of his or her sale,'' they added.
</P>
<P>
   As for themselves, both Mrs. Chambers and Mrs. Anthony had
insisted they weren't entitled to, and didn't receive, ``directly
or indirectly'' any part of the CEI payment ``or any other economic
benefits as a result of these transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the IRS settled, Bernard J. Long, Jr., of Dow, Lohnes
&AMP; Albertson of Washington, who represented the taxpayers, said the
IRS simply realized it had been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the agency would have made erroneous demands of such
size, Long replied, ``I can't speculate on what goes through a
revenue agent's mind. But when it got to a higher level, to the
attorney who had to try it, they realized they didn't have a
case.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome appears to support that. However, neither Judge
Cohen's one-sentence decisions, nor the two-sentence stipulations
by the lawyers, spelled out the IRS's reasons for dropping the
cases. The agency rarely describes publicly why it backs off a
case.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bona fide business reasons'' for the sale, the sisters had
said in their petitions, were ``for CEI to repurchase shares of its
stock at a favorable price'' and ``for the remainder beneficiaries
to turn a valuable property right into cash for their present
use.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the stock was not traded on the open market, its fair
market value had been determined by ``independent appraisers,'' the
petitions said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
