u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     07-06 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSROOM SCANDALS MAKE LOUSY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new TV show is in the works that will reveal, more or less,
what really goes on in America's newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The show, tentatively titled ``Resume Real,'' is the brainchild,
if that is the word, of a former ``Hard Copy'' producer and will
feature a panel of ``experts'' who critique and make fun of the
media's coverage of major news stories.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Steve Langford says ``Resume Real,'' scheduled to debut
next year, will ``blow the lid'' off the so-called ``respectable''
media and prove that tabloid outlets like the National Enquirer and
``Hard Copy'' are more accurate than CNN or ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Though I would never presume to second-guess a former ``Hard
Copy'' producer, I'm wondering if viewers accustomed to daily
updates on the status of Pamela Anderson's breasts will be
sufficiently entertained by stories of what goes on behind the
scenes in a typical newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   I have been in, or perilously close to, newsrooms for 25 years
and I can't think of a single incident that would ``blow the lid''
off ``respectable'' journalism unless you count the time a swarm of
love bugs shorted out the Herald-Tribune's air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   You might (or might not) question the credibility of a paper
that would be so irresponsible as to allow thousands of
slow-moving, nonbiting flies to gum up its air-conditioning system,
flies that are not only too stupid to stay out of the paths of
speeding cars but also lack the bare rudiments of family values to
the point that they wantonly engage in midair sex instead of doing
it behind closed doors in a sales-taxed motel room as God, the
Chamber of Commerce and most respectable editorial writers would
recommend.
</P>
<P>
   But I think the reaction of most people to this story,
particularly if they had tuned to get an update on Pamela
Anderson's breasts, would be one of indifference, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   While it's possible that love bugs can be sensational in some
contexts (riding a motorcycle without dental floss, for example),
for the most part they are dull, uninteresting things that live out
their brief lives anonymously and without benefit of cosmetic
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``You've seen one, you've seen 'em all'' was coined
with love bugs in mind.
</P>
<P>
   So when a news show lures in viewers expecting a breast update
and gives them love bugs instead, you've got to think there's going
to be mass disappointment bordering on outrage.
</P>
<P>
   And it will only get worse once viewers realize that
love-bugs-in-the-air-conditioner is the top story of the week and
succeeding stories will be progressively less scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking stories with titles like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspaper Drops `Marvin' From Comics Page; Local Infants Howl
With Indifference''
</P>
<P>
   ``Managing Editor Leaves Leftover Turkey Tetrazzini in Newsroom
Refrigerator for Six Months; EPA Calls It `Another Chernobyl'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Publisher Comes Clean: `I've Been Buying My Newspaper At
Half-Price for Years!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-Sought Liberal Agenda Found Buried Under Columnist's Desk
Clutter a Hoax: `It Was Just a Take-Out Menu From The House of
Wong,' Grimes Admits. `They Look a Lot Alike, You Know.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to imply that ``legitimate'' newspapers don't make
plenty of bonehead mistakes and errors in judgment and write about
events in ways that are not suitable for wrapping dead fish let
alone advancing the cause of good journalism.
</P>
<P>
   And I wouldn't want to dissuade anyone from poking fun at this
goofy business because we definitely have a tendency to take
ourselves too seriously and dismiss anyone or anything that doesn't
adhere to our so-called ``standards.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether this will result in the kind of riveting television
that viewers will want to tune into week after week remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if ``Resume Real'' found a love bug that had had a
boob job, that would be a different story.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., a
member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
