<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILGRIMS-BOOK-REVIEW-     07-06 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILGRIMS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PARIS PILGRIMS': FLESHING OUT HEMINGWAY   WITH LITERARY
LICENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One shudders to imagine what the literary scholars will make of
``The Paris Pilgrims,'' Clancy Carlile's novel about Hemingway and
other famous American exiles in France in the 1920s. Here we learn
at last what Hemingway and Joyce did during a long evening they
spent together, and how Hemingway, the neophyte American writer,
ended up trundling home Joyce, the passed-out author of
``Ulysses,'' in a wheelbarrow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here we learn how the sexually experimental Joyce encouraged his
partner, Nora Barnacle, to take a lover, in imitation of Molly
Bloom and Blazes Boylan in ``Ulysses.'' We learn that the
prospective lover Nora chose was none other than Hemingway,
although the latter, in the throes of one of his impotent phases,
ended up turning her down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How does the creator of ``The Paris Pilgrims'' know these
titillating things? He doesn't, of course. The author of ``Children
of the Dust'' (which became a CBS mini-series) and ``Honky-Tonk
Man'' (which was made into a movie with Clint Eastwood), among
other books, Carlile has simply drawn on material from memoirs,
biographies and fiction focused on Paris in the 1920s and mixed it
with his own teeming, sometimes nasty imagination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this way we learn what Gertrude Stein thought of the
bumptious young Hemingway, and how Alice B. Toklas, Stein's
partner, was jealous of him for being so attractive to her
mistress. We are shown how drawn Hemingway was to lesbians in
general, which is apparently why Carlile has him cutting short the
hair of Hadley Richardson, his young, worshipful wife at that
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The portrait painted of Hemingway here is not pleasant.
Dominating Carlile's story, Hemingway appears a boastful liar, a
sadistic bully, a sore loser who would go to cheating lengths to
win the many contests he baited his friends into joining, an
unreliable lover given to fits of what ``Hadley's Bryn Mawr sex
education books called `insufficient tumescence,''' a moody, weepy
self-pitying drunk and a bigot and anti-Semite and hater of male
homosexuals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   True, no one else comes off as much more appealing in the
novel's huge cast of characters, which includes everyone from Ezra
Pound to Sylvia Beach to Lincoln Steffens to Picasso, Braque, Gide
and Cole Porter. Nor are these negative qualities of Hemingway's
particularly new or surprising. Yet experiencing them so vividly
makes you dislike Hemingway intensely by the novel's end, despite
Carlile's repeated assurances that Hemingway appealed to everyone
who met him in those days because of his infectious enthusiasm
about whatever happened to catch his fancy, whether it was boxing,
tennis, skiing, hiking, bullfighting, fishing, drinking or going to
war. You positively wish for the satisfying comeuppance the story
eventually slaps him with. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that we see little of his development as one of
the century's great modernists, beyond Stein's telling him to cut
back on the description in his writing (``Too much of the
newspaper's telling gets into the fiction's showing,'' she says);
or Hadley's famous loss of his manuscripts at the Gare de Lyons,
which forced him to begin over again, or his enunciation to Hadley
of what he called his ``iceberg theory'' of fiction writing, ``in
which,'' as the fictional Hadley recalls it, ``only about 10
percent of the mass of the story would be above the surface.''
Mostly Hemingway comes off as a blowhard and a creep.
</P>
<P>
   So, multiple grounds exist for objecting to ``The Paris
Pilgrims'' as a literary project. First, it invents things,
inviting ignorant or naive readers to confuse what is known with
what Carlile has made up. Second, it disparages or makes light of a
group of artists whom many regard as among the most important of
the century. Finally it overemphasizes their search for sexual
freedom to the detriment of their quest for artistic freedom. In
short, it's snotty about things that should be looked on with a
measure of awe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's fun to read about these people in the flesh, so to
speak; to see them in the framework of their everyday lives. As a
historical novel, it's really not that much different in principle
from a story made up about the Emperor Hadrian or Julius Caesar or
Queen Elizabeth I; only the relative proximity of the events to the
present day makes it seem different. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also the novel touches on a deeper if somewhat crude form of
truth. Carlile is at pains to reconcile the many actual sexual
anomalies in Hemingway's life, among them his mother's having tried
to ``pass him off as a girl'' for the first four years of his life,
as Carlile puts it, ``keeping him in dresses and long curly hair
and bonnets;'' his penchant for switching sexual roles with his
wives, and the double standard he held in his acceptance of
lesbians and his hatred of male homosexuals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Responding to some of Hemingway's more extreme behavior near the
end of ``The Paris Pilgrims,'' Robert McAlmon, his friend and
publisher, speculates that ``Hemingway might someday realize that
the qualities he found so despicable, so unacceptable and hateful
in other men, might be the very qualities he was trying to deny in
himself.'' The character McAlmon continues, ``But if Hemingway was
to escape insanity or suicide, those repressed qualities would
someday have to come out. . . .''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Carlile has imagined Hemingway's Paris years, what happened
to the rest of his life makes a brutal kind of sense. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE PARIS PILGRIMS'
</P>
<P>
   By Clancy Carlile
</P>
<P>
   460 pages. Carroll &AMP; Graf. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
