<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0818 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCULPTURE-ITALY-$ADV1     07-06 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULPTURE-ITALY-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN OF SCULPTURE AS AN UP-TO-DATE EDEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISTOIA, Italy _ Sculpture gardens bloom in many a cultured
field today. Museums consider them prestigious adjuncts, cities
invest in them as tourist attractions, philanthropists see them as
proof that art is long, life short and bronze a kind of
immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Landscape-as-sculpture gallery was not always meant primarily
for pleasure. In its most ancient form the sculpture park was a
sacred grove or holy place with statues of gods and votive
offerings. In Japan today, sculpture gardens are still included in
temples as places for meditation, and in Europe and America old
cemeteries, sometimes attached to churches, might be called
sculpture parks, with their stone Virgins and guardian angels and
marble promises of the afterlife. The mid-19th-century rural
cemetery movement in America declared that cemeteries should be
sites of restful pleasure with inviting landscapes and uplifting
monuments.
</P>
<P>
   The Romans decided that, at least in gardens, esthetics were as
important as religion. They proceeded to collect antique sculpture,
both Egyptian and Greek; Hadrian's villa might be called the
classic example. The Renaissance took up this idea again. In the
early 16th century, Pope Julius II installed a sculpture garden in
the Vatican to display newly uncovered antiquities. But wealthy
aristocrats and merchants soon began dotting the landscapes of
their villas with contemporary sculpture; even Michelangelo carved
a garden statue early on.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy today, however, the past takes precedence, and Italians
show almost no interest in gardens planted with the work of living
artists. One rare exception is the home of Giuliano Gori, an
industrialist who has created a lovely and uncommon blend of
19th-century Romantic garden and art of the last 20 years at the
Fattoria di Celle, his villa and farm near Pistoia, in Tuscany.
</P>
<P>
   Celle is a 17th-century villa with a park laid out in the 1840s
in the English style. The English Romantic garden, which spurned
the adroitly embroidered orderliness of the typical Italian garden
as much too controlled and artificial, went to great lengths to
rearrange nature so that it still looked natural. The landscape at
Celle was turned into a stage set that masqueraded, delightfully,
as itself.
</P>
<P>
   Lakes and cliffs appeared where none had been before. Paths were
laid out that seemed to meander through woods and arrive by mere
chance at the best views. Bridges disguised as grottoes spanned
spunky little waterfalls. Charming ``follies'' sprang up in
fortuitous spots _ an aviary that once housed peacocks but now
shelters nothing but trees; a neo-Gothic teahouse with ceilings
painted bright blue and studded with stars.
</P>
<P>
   Today these are way-stations on the path to modern and
post-modern works of art. The teahouse raises its spiky pinnacles
not far from a Dennis Oppenheim ``machine'' that sprawls down a
hillside looking like the exploded diagram of a demented
scientist's mind. This enormous piece follows the contours of an
existing slope and endows it with a metallic climax; originally,
Oppenheim hoped to use its armature as a setting for fireworks. Now
it only implies celebration with its cockeyed energy, being a
machine too ambitious, erratic and complicated to work, perhaps a
wry comment on the park as an artifice for restoring the joys of
nature even as the industrial revolution began to smother them.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morris' splendid and surprising maze of
green-and-white-striped marble sits calmly in a tree-ringed
clearing, presenting what appears to be the side of a small, square
building. Its stripes refer to Gothic churches of the region; its
intellectual puzzles spring from modern life.
</P>
<P>
   The maze is open to the sky and its walls just high enough to
allow a view of the trees round about but not of the next part of
the maze, leaving the gaze free to revel in the landscape but still
restricted, the body moving and yet confined. The walls and floor
both slant precariously, and the corridors are so narrow they
repeatedly seem to be reaching a dead end, only to turn a corner to
the next narrow passageway. There are no right and wrong choices to
make, for the direction is prescribed _ until it stops, a true dead
end at last.
</P>
<P>
   This maze has neither solution nor exit, only a way in. Once
having left by that same way, the visitor climbs a wooden platform
at the side of the clearing to look down into the maze and discover
that it is not a square at all but a triangle with sharp angles.
Both perception and expectation have been controlled and fooled.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano Gori was one of the first people in the world to found
a sculpture park almost exclusively on commissioned, site-specific
works; Celle is still the only such park in Italy. Gori, who is now
in his late 60s, began collecting contemporary art while quite
young, and by the end of the 1950s the collection was so vast that
he built a space to house it in Prato, a town near Florence, where
he lived and worked.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, when the family and art moved to Celle, Gori
admired art made specifically for exhibition sites at the Venice
Biennale and Documenta in Kassel, Germany. This work was
site-specific in every way: designed for a particular space, it was
almost always made of impermanent materials and therefore could be
seen in no other place and at no other time. It occurred to Gori
that his new home, with its extensive farm buildings and over 58
acres of park and farm land, would be an ideal setting for
permanent installations.
</P>
<P>
   The villa, situated high on a hill in the little town of
Santomato outside Pistoia, might be an ideal setting for dreams. It
sits in one of the loveliest spots in Tuscany, which seldom lacks
for loveliness. The land looks out over Leonardo's hometown of
Vinci and across a valley of golden fields, clusters of tile roofs
and trees that flare up silver in the wind, a vista of that
undulating, domesticated order and shimmering charm that central
and northern Italy seems to specialize in.
</P>
<P>
   Gori convened an international advisory committee and invited
artists to make work that would embrace the land or speak to the
building spaces at Celle and then stay there forever, or whatever
part of forever is allotted to works of art. No changes to the
19th-century garden were allowed; any new artwork would have to
cohabit gracefully with what was essentially an artwork of a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen artists, including Morris and Oppenheim, inaugurated the
project in 1982. Since then the collection has grown to 36 outdoor
and 24 indoor installations, including works by Magdalena
Abakanowicz, Richard Serra, and Fabrizio Corneli. There are also
hundreds of paintings and sculptures that are not site specific.
Celle is open by appointment to people specializing in contemporary
art. Arrangements must be made by written request for appointments
from April through September. All visits are guided.
</P>
<P>
   The artists have taken ingenious measures to acknowledge and
reinforce the contours of the land. Mauro Staccioli sends a thin
concrete wall racing abruptly up a hill through trees to point at
the sky like an irresistible force materializing in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sculpture calls up the history of the region as
well. In a clearing, Alice Aycock unfolds a five-part, metallic
history of science and philosophy called ``The Nets of Solomon'' in
homage to Leonardo and Galileo: symbolic representations of an
astrolabe, a philosopher's stone, neutrino ramps, the charted
movement of a hurricane and a schematic sketch of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Pepper carved from a hill an updated Greek amphitheater
that is at once stately and serene, with cast iron reliefs,
embedded in the sides of grass-covered berms, serving as backdrops
for the stage; music and dance are occasionally performed here. In
a pond below a series of waterfalls, Anne and Patrick Poirier, long
involved with classical art, scatter what look like fragments of a
huge, ancient statue of one of the giants who died fighting the
Greek gods _ a staring eye with an arrow in it, bronze thunderbolts
in rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Artists who want to change the landscape may alter the farmlands
that lie outside the park. Bukishi Inoue's ``My Sky Hole'' unrolls
in time and space as a visitor walks down a long pathway between
rough stone walls into a low tunnel illuminated by a couple of
tubular holes that let in the light of the sky. At the end, the
tunnel leads around two curves to a circular stair that comes up at
ground level in a glass box among olive trees.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Sonfist proposes a history of the region in a lovely piece
composed of concentric circles of local flora: a large central
planting that he calls ``the primordial forest;'' around that, a
circle of bare branches of endangered trees cast in greenish
bronze; next, a ring of indigenous thyme and laurel, brought to
Italy by the Greeks; and around that, a ring of galestro, the local
stone that retains the sun's warmth and will in time disintegrate
to become earth. In the summer, a circle of wheat is planted
beyond, and all of it is loosely ringed about by olive trees.
Inside and outside the park, the art does not simply sit
beautifully or advantageously in the landscape but also rearranges
and comments on the viewer's experience of place.
</P>
<P>
   More site-specific art is housed in the farm's old
administrative and storage buildings, where artists have been given
small rooms for individual installations and Luigi Mainolfi has
trapped a terra-cotta ``worm'' that rears up several stories
through the grain elevator, its pebbly, pale orange body glimpsed
in segments through small windows going up the stairs. In what was
once the granary two handsome wall drawings by Sol LeWitt flank a
large circle of stones by Richard Long. Long also cut a circle in
the grass outside, a correspondence that can be seen only in
memory, as if the artist wanted to develop a history lasting no
more than the length of a visit to Celle, rather than the century
and a half between the park's design and the art that animates it
today, the long years between antiquity and Renaissance and now.
</P>
<P>
   Celle is a trip into the present with frequent pauses for
conversation with the past. A mere 10 minutes by car from its metal
abstractions, stony conundrums and smiling vistas, the
green-and-white striped facade of the cathedral of Pisa reminds a
traveler that art and history in Italy have living faces and very
deep pockets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
