<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV13-     07-06 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO MUSLIM DAMNED IF SHE WAS OR WASN'T RAPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, July 13)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the many horror stories coming out of Kosovo this one about
an alleged rape of an Albanian woman by Serb forces was even more
dismaying than the usual.
</P>
<P>
   The young wife had been taken from her village home by Serb men
to be interrogated at the police station. She was beaten, but she
wasn't raped, she told her husband. He said he didn't believe her
and has since scorned her. ``I feel very cold toward her,'' he told
a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   This is a couple whose home was looted and who lost everything
in this crazy, awful war. In another place they might be holding
onto each other and sobbing with gratitude to be alive. But his
fear and suspicion left each of them with nothing but more misery.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of rape is so potent in their Muslim village that even
her denial taints her. The reporter pointed out that the man had
limited education and was not typical of all Albanian men. But in
the small villages, traditional attitudes toward women go as
untested as ethnic prejudice. The man believes his wife didn't dare
tell him what happened because he would have to divorce her if she
was raped. She's damned if she lied or told the truth.
</P>
<P>
   You read a story like that and you want to do something for that
poor woman. Even though American women still think twice about
reporting a rape, the injustice against this Albanian woman seems
incredibly heartless. She is punished for a crime that didn't occur
and which, even if it did, was not her crime. You may even start to
imagine, as a group of us did one night, how to save this woman.
</P>
<P>
   Could we adopt her in some way? Bring her, somehow, to
California and have her live with one of us. Help her to heal.
Teach her what we know about rape. Tell her that her husband is
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just her husband. It's his father and brother and
likely his mother and the wife's family, too. Virginity and
fidelity in women are sacrosanct in Albania. There are unbending
rules for women even in a war which breaks all rules.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights workers are equally frustrated. They say the social
stigma of rape is the biggest problem they have in trying to help
investigators prove what seems obvious now, that rape is a war
crime, premeditated and carried out systematically to destroy a
people by savaging its women. Those who have broken the silence
tell of vicious attacks, torture, repeated assaults, soldiers
gleefully singling out virgins, men forcing families to watch their
wives, mothers and daughters being raped.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you will discover a smidgen of hope. Included in the
horrible accounts will be a small observation that one man in the
group held back, one soldier cried when he saw what the others were
doing to the women because, he said, he had sisters.
</P>
<P>
   But now revenge rapes are happening. A Serb mother tells how
armed Albanian men raped her mentally ill daughter and then stabbed
her to death. The attackers made the mother watch. This way they
could kill the mother too.
</P>
<P>
   What do we do with these stories? What will happen to these
women? Who will comfort them? Do they matter against the immediate
need to rebuild towns, put roads and bridges back together, find
food?
</P>
<P>
   We can send them courage and caring in our prayers. But what
else?
</P>
<P>
   Is there a place to send money to take away a woman's shame,
educate her husband, make a community see that shunning an injured
woman makes them as merciless as their enemy?
</P>
<P>
   Do we get to butt in? Where is the petition that says that we,
the undersigned, protest the further punishing of war victims by
their loved ones?
</P>
<P>
   How is it that a bullet wound or a missing limb suffered in
battle is a badge of honor but rape is a reproach? What would
happen if soldiers limped home and wives and mothers looked with
contempt at their shattered bodies and said they felt cold toward
them?
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
