<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIANISTS-SCORES-2TAKE     07-06 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANISTS-SCORES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANISTS IN HIGH-WIRE ACTS: PRESSURE TO PLAY FROM MEMORY, BUT
WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you want to know utter fear? Just ask a pianist what it is
like to have a memory lapse.
</P>
<P>
   There you are, onstage, on the spot, in the middle of piece you
have practiced for months or even played for years. All seems to be
going well. Then something happens to distract you momentarily.
Maybe your new concert shoes feel slippery on the brass pedals. Or
you can't shake the annoyance you feel for bungling a tricky
lefthand passage that you can play perfectly well.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly you are a phrase or so ahead of where you think you are
in the piece. Your fingers feel like little automatons with minds
of their own. You tell yourself: ``Think, think!'' You lean in
closer, stare into the keys, but see only the black hole in your
head that is sucking up the notes. You stumble, you try to skip
forward or backward, but it's no use. Total meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Most experienced concert pianists learn to get out of such jams
before catastrophe strikes, sometimes so deftly that the audience
doesn't even notice. Still, there have been some great pianists,
like William Masselos and Leonard Shure, who never achieved their
full potential on the concert stage because they found memorization
onerous yet could not buck the protocol dictating that piano
recitals be played from memory. For students who have difficulty
with memorization, the pressure can be paralyzing.
</P>
<P>
   So why does the protocol continue? It is enforced by
convention-bound teachers, a public enthralled with the
high-wire-act aspect of concerts, and critics who falsely assume
that a piece not memorized is a piece not thoroughly learned. And
it is time to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many musicians, especially pianists, have no trouble
with memorization and clearly find it freeing, and many honorable
teachers believe that the valuable discipline of memorizing can be
learned. But even musicians who find memorization intimidating feel
compelled to follow the protocol, which can seem terribly
arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   All solo piano recitals are expected to be performed from
memory, though exceptions are made for contemporary works. Chamber
music is never to be played from memory (presumably because
ensemble musicians need their individual parts to know where they
fit into the whole, though if the musicians have not figured this
out during rehearsals, then the piece is not ready). An
instrumentalist in a recital with a pianist is encouraged to play
from memory but can get away with playing from the music because a
duo is technically considered chamber music. But an instrumentalist
who plays a concerto with an orchestra is expected to shun the
comfort of a score to enhance the David-and-Goliath drama of the
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   None of these confusing rules take into account the essential
point: there are different kinds of talents. Some musicians have an
instinctive ability to communicate; others have a gift for total
recall. These are not mutually exclusive talents. But shouldn't
musicians who struggle with memory be encouraged to do whatever
enables them to be their best?
</P>
<P>
   The protocol is deeply entrenched, as was clear in June when the
Van Cliburn Foundation sponsored its first International
Competition for Outstanding Amateur Pianists. Sevan Melikyan, a
spokesman, said recently that the decision to allow contestants to
play from scores, a seemingly reasonable concession to amateurs,
provoked intense internal debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the same piece was performed at the same level by two
pianists, one not using the music,'' Melikyan explained, ``wouldn't
the jury naturally give preference to the one playing from memory?
The issue was discussed but never completely resolved.'' In the
high-profile professional Cliburn Competition the contestants are
required to play from memory, Melikyan added, ``in accord with the
practice in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this practice flies in the face of history. Until
well into the 19th century, music was either written out or
improvised. Written-out music was always played from scores;
improvised music, obviously, was not. To Mozart and Beethoven, the
idea that anyone would even think of playing one of their piano
works from memory would have been preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Clara Schumann was apparently the first pianist to do so
prominently. In 1837, at 18, she performed Beethoven's
``Appassionata'' in Berlin ``by heart,'' as affronted critics put
it. For this she was labeled ``insufferable.'' Bettina von Arnim,
who had been Beethoven's close friend, commented, ``With what
pretension she seats herself as the piano and plays without the
notes!''
</P>
<P>
   Then the charismatic Franz Liszt came along and changed the
public's perception. During a 10-week period in 1841-42, Liszt gave
21 solo recitals in Berlin, performing more than 80 different
works, 50 of them from memory. What was deemed uppity when done by
a woman was now found stunning and superhuman.
</P>
<P>
   The mystique took hold, and pianists since have tried to sustain
it. Not quite all. Some brave souls bucked convention, including
the distinguished Dame Myra Hess and Sviatoslav Richter, who played
mostly from music during the last 20 or so years of his life with
no diminution of his genius.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Peter Serkin has been challenging the protocol
with encouraging success. No one can say that Serkin has a problem
with memorization. On a concert tour in the early 1970's he played
Messiaen's monumental solo work ``Vingt Regards sur l'Enfant
Jesus,'' two-plus hours of staggeringly difficult music, from
memory. Today he still often memorizes complex contemporary pieces
as well as the formidable sonatas and concertos of the standard
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   But when he chooses to, he will play a work from the score, and
his choices can be surprising: a Bach partita, a Chopin nocturne.
As a prelude to a concert during the recent Stravinsky Festival of
the San Francisco Symphony, Serkin offered three solo works
(Stravinsky's Serenade, Sonata and ``Piano-Rag Music''), then
played the composer's Capriccio for Piano and Orchestra during the
main concert. For each work he played with a page turner at his
side. His performances were insightful and brilliant, and no review
I read even mentioned his use of the scores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just enjoyable to have the entire score to the Stravinsky
Capriccio to follow as I play it,'' he said recently. ``I try to
de-emphasize the whole performance aspect of a musical
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Memory is a strange thing,'' he added. ``It can happen by
itself; it does not have to be the result of an arduous process of
study. But many people do it to make a big point, or out of some
kind of vanity. It's become orthodoxy, which is unhealthy and
restrictive.''
</P>
<P>
   The pianist Gilbert Kalish has long played everything, including
solo repertory, from scores. Early into his career he was drawn
heavily into chamber music and contemporary music, which, by
custom, is always performed this way. So he got into the habit with
solo repertory as well. He feels that he would not be able to learn
and perform the range and amount of music, especially new music,
that he plays each season if he had not given up trying to
memorize.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kalish strongly encouraged those students who
memorize music comfortably to do so. Playing from scores is clearly
more cumbersome. But in an interview with me some years ago, Kalish
spoke eloquently about the unnecessary pressure young musicians
endure in forcing themselves to memorize:
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we practice for? The idea of practicing over and over
to nail a passage with such security that there's no possibility of
its escaping from you just doesn't make sense. Many students
practice so much like this that they just switch on the machine
when they play. They are not more absorbed in the music; they are
more removed from it. It's a frighteningly negative and lonely
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s Kalish was able to turn his conviction into policy
at the State University of New York at Stony Brook, where he is a
professor. He persuaded the piano faculty to allow students to play
in their recitals using the scores for any works they chose to.
</P>
<P>
   At most other conservatories and colleges, playing from memory
in recitals is either a specific requirement, as it is at the
Eastman School of Music in Rochester (though exceptions are made
for ``avant-garde'' works), or an unspoken necessity. Sometimes the
rules are amusingly specific. At Juilliard, for example, violinists
must play all recital pieces from memory except for contemporary
works composed after 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the protocol was challenged from the opposite
direction when the Jacques Thibaud String Trio, three young
musicians who met at the Berlin School of Art, gave an impressive
concert at the Frick Collection in New York, playing demanding
trios of Beethoven, Dohnanyi and Schoenberg from memory. There is
some precedent for chamber groups' playing from memory: the famous
Kolish String Quartet, which gave premieres of works by Schoenberg
and Bartok, played all standard repertory from memory. The Thibaud
String Trio did not appear to be showing off. The performances were
spontaneous and commanding.
</P>
<P>
   That said, if these enthusiastic young musicians become known
for playing from memory, will they feel trapped into always doing
so? In any case, their decision to forswear scores still helps to
undermine the existing protocols. Force is the issue: pianists are
compelled to play from memory, and chamber music ensembles are
compelled not to.
</P>
<P>
   Singers in recital have a double challenge when it comes to
memory: notes plus words. Still, most singers wisely try to sing
from memory. A song recital is, in effect, a dramatic recitation,
and it is hard for an audience to get involved in a drama when a
singer's eyes are buried in a score. That said, as a critic I would
be reluctant to fault a singer simply for using music if the
performance seemed otherwise communicative.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Kalish's question is paramount: What do musicians
practice for? Think of all the pianists, especially students, who
resist playing something challenging out of fear of memorizing it.
Think of how much time a young pianist must devote to memorizing an
easily playable slow movement of a Mozart sonata. With those hours
that same pianist could be rehearsing chamber music, working with a
composer on a new piece, playing through the piano-vocal score of a
Mozart opera or engaging in any number of enriching activities that
would inform the pianist's performance of the sonata, which was
never intended to be played from memory in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   A pianist alone onstage, taking on the Bach ``Goldberg''
Variations or the Copland Piano Fantasy. It's an alluring mystique.
But maybe it's a mystique we can finally afford to lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
