<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0834 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-NY-BALLET-$ADV1     07-06 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-NY-BALLET-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY BALLET'S 50TH YEAR DRAWS TO A CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 11)  
 (HLW)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since it ain't over till it's over, it may be
premature to declare the New York City Ballet's 50th anniversary
year at an end. The celebration continues through July 24 at the
company's summer home, the Saratoga Performing Arts Center in
upstate New York. Nonetheless, the sum went beyond the parts in the
recent City Ballet season at the New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   New contexts were provided, fresh connections among familiar
works were made, artistic lineage received its due and creativity
busted out not all over, but in the right places. Taking the long
view since a mammoth alumni party inaugurated the festivities in
November, one can easily say that the highlights were reserved for
the spring season.
</P>
<P>
   The novelties included the company's first full-length ``Swan
Lake,'' a blockbuster staging by Peter Martins, whose formal style
was guaranteed to stir debate, and the premieres, all
crowd-pleasers: Christopher Wheeldon's ``Scenes de Ballet,''
Martins' ``Them Twos',' to Wynton Marsalis' commissioned score, and
``Duke!'' an Ellington tribute choreographed by Robert La Fosse,
Garth Fagan and Susan Stroman.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it was how the repertory (100 ballets, including
revivals, since the fall) was redistributed in theme segments that
said something about where the company is and was. As artistic
director, Martins had a stroke of genius when he offered a
comparative showcase of four very different ballets to Charles
Ives' music in connection with a stunning revival of George
Balanchine's 1954 ``Ivesiana.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a mini-American Music Festival, following up on the
winter season's tributes to composers from one country or as
tributes to single composers. The second semester, so to speak,
placed the emphasis on Tchaikovsky and Stravinsky, the two
composers closest to Balanchine. It was no surprise that most of
the works in these two mini-festivals were Balanchine's. It was
also clear how directly Balanchine pushed his disciples to use
these composers.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine's ``Scherzo a la Russe'' still looked like a trifle
in a revival, but it distilled the approach that Martins has
followed in his own Stravinsky ballets: choreography as a parallel
dimension that reflects and expands upon the composer's structure
and rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Robbins saw dance as being about relationships.
This was true even in the revival of ``Andantino,'' from the
company's 1981 Tchaikovsky festival, a modest duet that did not
need to look so modest.
</P>
<P>
   The other duet that was revived after a long absence, Lew
Christensen's ``Four Norwegian Moods,'' was so superbly danced by
Janie Taylor and Benjamin Millepied that it deserves special
mention. Christensen was the star of the American Ballet, the first
Balanchine-Lincoln Kirstein troupe founded in 1934. ``Four
Norwegian Moods'' is named after the orchestral score Stravinsky
wrote in 1942 in tribute to Nazi-occupied Norway. Christensen
originally created the duet in 1976 for the San Francisco Ballet,
where he was the artistic director. When it was transferred to City
Ballet's 1982 Stravinsky Festival, it was made little impression.
</P>
<P>
   It is still a minor exercise in neo-classicism, but Ms. Taylor
and Millepied give its young-love aura a freshness that goes beyond
charm. Stravinsky's martial beginning evokes the Nazi invasion of
Norway; the stage is bare at this point until the dancers enter,
their skips and leaps subsiding into a gentle passage with Ms.
Taylor rolling her head on her partner's extended arm. Each dancer
has a solo that uses conventional steps, and Ms. Taylor flexes her
feet. The joyful image of two young people holding hands in a jete
is dispelled by their exit in opposite directions, a parting that
evokes the uncertainty of the music's wartime pretext.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor's brand of innocence has a sharp edge and the energy
that both dancers channeled into their purity gave ``Four Norwegian
Moods'' a Balanchinian backbone that made it look better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Tchaikovsky and Stravinsky aside, the American Music segment
(three weeks) emphasized the shift toward more American composers
that has occurred under Martins' leadership since Balanchine died
in 1983. It was also clear how often Robbins and Balanchine used
American music.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine familiarized the American public with Ives and Louis
Moreau Gottschalk (``Tarantella''). But as three of his most
ingenious ballets showed again, the esoteric was balanced by his
pull toward a popular culture that he transformed into high art.
Thanks to Hershy Kay's brilliant arrangement of cowpoke tunes in
``Western Symphony'' and of Sousa marches in ``Stars and Stripes,''
folk images were absorbed into the academic idiom of Balanchine's
neo-classical style. The same process could be seen in ``Who
Cares?'' with Balanchine turning to Gershwin's Broadway songs.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who had used Gershwin's symphonic pieces, was
represented by major American composers in their jazz-tinctured
mood (Leonard Bernstein and Morton Gould) as well as Philip Glass
and Ives. Martins' choices have been very different. He has
concentrated new work from leading composers like John Adams,
Charles Wuorinen and Marsalis, whose music for ``Them Twos,'' not
strictly a jazz score, is his first publicly performed orchestral
piece.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, Martins chose Ives, an experimental composer, for
his first and astringent ballet ``Calcium Light Night.'' Ten years
later, Feld used some of the same short pieces and the mysterious
``Unanswered Question'' for the Ives ballet he created as a guest
choreographer for the company's 1988 American Music Festival.
Revived with Damian Woetzel dynamically recreating his role as an
everyman seeking a muse who exits head first into a trap door (the
incomparable Maria Kowroski), the circus imagery came back with new
pungency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ives, Songs'' which Robbins also created in 1988 takes Ives'
irony toward an American past that was shattered by World War I and
translates it into high theatrical art. There is a whiff of Charles
Prendergast's paintings in the images that the current cast dances
out so strongly. La Fosse stunningly reinvents the cameo role of
the man who recalls the memories on stage. Stoop-shouldered and
dazed, he is, emotionally, at the bottom of the scale to which the
music descends metaphorically.
</P>
<P>
   The way toward these ballets was pointed in ``Ivesiana.''
Balanchine did not need to invite a modern-dance choreographer into
a ballet company. In 1954 he saw fit to have dancers go barefoot or
walk on their knees if the music called him in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully rehearsed, the ballet redefined the dissonance and
hazy texture of four Ives pieces as chilling enigmas. Everything in
the revival was haunting: James Fayette's inexorable pursuit of a
``blind'' Kathleen Tracey, Ms. Taylor as an ambiguous siren-ideal
virtually out of Tom Gold's desperate reach, Ms. Kowroski and
Charles Askegard in a no-strings urban encounter and, finally, the
corps plowing forward on seemingly amputated limbs.
</P>
<P>
   This was Ms. Kowroski's season. Tall, bold, idiosyncratic and
the epitome of where classical dancing should go in the
21st-century, she contributed the emotional dimension that Martins'
``Swan Lake'' did not have with every cast. Taking a cue from
Balanchine, who had rechoreographed a full version for the Zurich
Ballet in the 1970s, he stressed the formal over the lyrical. For
the best standard ``Lake,'' one might prefer the Boston Ballet
production, derived from a Kirov version. The Martins' staging,
with all the set pieces intact or slightly changed, is nonetheless
excellent as a gloss on the original. It clears the mind and gets
to essentials, just as Per Kirkeby's sets do the same by using
color and abstract design.
</P>
<P>
   For fun there was Wheeldon's ``Scenes de Ballet, a highly
imaginative mirror dance for students and the three-part ``Duke!''
Here, La Fosse incorporated a tap duet into a stylized swing
number, Ms. Stroman put some flappers on toe so that Ms. Kowroski,
as the outsider in a tutu, could join in and Fagan treated
Ellington as something more than a show-business composer; his
segment had mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them Twos'' may tell us little new about various stages of
love, but the way in which Martins choreographs his way through
five duets is what matters. From the first off-center shapes for
Ms. Taylor and Sebastien Marcovici to an image of loss, as Darci
Kistler fades away from Jock Soto, invention fills the eye.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Swan Lake,'' Martins turned to Kirkeby, a Danish painter
with an international reputation, just he has turned to leading
contemporary composers. This is the level of distinctive
collaboration that Balanchine and Kirstein promulgated and that is
found in no other company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
