<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAMA-BOOK-SHOP-2TAKE     07-06 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAMA-BOOK-SHOP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMA BOOK SHOP: STAGE-STRUCK KEEP PROGRESS THE WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is how Rozanne Seelen describes her marriage:
``The wife says to the husband: `I want a vanilla ice cream cone.
Not chocolate, not strawberry, vanilla. The husband goes out and
brings back a tuna fish sandwich. And she says, `Thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   While that's certainly a fair description of how marriage can
work, in Mrs. Seelen's case it's a dynamic that encompasses even
more. She and her husband, Arthur, own the Drama Book Shop _ at 723
Seventh Ave., at 48th Street _ the oldest performing arts bookstore
in the country. And along with the Howard Johnson's on Broadway at
46th Street, it is one of the few remnants of the old Times Square.
The store is celebrating its 75th anniversary. (Before going crazy
trying to find it, be advised: It's in an office building, on the
second floor.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides being married to each other, the Seelens are married to
the publishing business; they are part of the dwindling species of
independent booksellers in the country. They are also married to
the theater; they and their staff of 24 spend hours each day with
actors, helping them choose monologues for their auditions, often
without making a sale. So they both have ample opportunity to
request vanilla and end up with tuna fish.
</P>
<P>
   With 40,000 titles, including volumes on Czech, Russian,
Scandinavian and Spanish theater, the Drama Book Shop remains the
city's most comprehensive collection of performing arts books,
stocking up to 15 translations of ``The Cherry Orchard'' alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto,'' Seelen says, ``is, `If we don't have something
here, we want to know why.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Seelens (he is 75, she gives clues she's 65) spend at least
10 hours a day at the store. The shelves of their office are
crammed with books and items like shaving cream, vitamins and
Miracle-Gro. The only vacation they have taken in the last 10 years
was one three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to change that,'' the store's general manager,
Domenic Silipo, 31, said fondly. The couple regard him as a godsend
who helps shepherd the business through the advent of technology,
and through more basic considerations like security. An unfortunate
side effect of trying to sell books to starving artists is that
sometimes they're starving enough to take them without paying.
</P>
<P>
   But that kind of harsh realism is best left to others; the
Seelens are not good at at it. They are from a gentler time, when
the promise of New York City and the Rialto had a romance and
majesty that did not include the Disney Store.
</P>
<P>
   Seelen is a former actor with a dry sense of humor who bears a
striking resemblance to Walter Matthau. Mrs. Seelen is a former
dancer who speaks in a fluttery voice and always seems to be
encouraging people onward, including the staff, most of whom are
struggling actors, directors or filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all on their way somewhere,'' she says, her eyes
getting misty. ``It's nice to have people pursuing careers be with
the customers who are in the same boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Seelen nods. ``It's not a job job we have here. There's some
emotion to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple engenders much loyalty from people in the theater.
When the store suffered a fire in 1979, Mrs. Seelen says, its
collection of signed first editions was ruined. ``The playwright
Robert Anderson came in,'' she recalled, ``and I showed him the
black, wet pile. He came back the next day with a signed first
edition of `I Never Sang For My Father.'''
</P>
<P>
   Seelen sighs. ``It brings tears to my eyes when I talk about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Seelen nods. ``He's a great gentleman of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was what Seelen had also aspired to be. Born in Flatbush,
Brooklyn, and raised in the Bronx, he graduated from De Witt
Clinton High School and CCNY, which, he says, ``we called Catholic
College Now Yiddish.'' He worked as a chemical engineer at the
Battell Memorial Institute in Columbus, Ohio, where he acted in
plays on the side. He moved back to New York to act full time,
working off Broadway, in summer stock and on radio. His one
Broadway show was John Hersey's adaptation of ``The Wall,'' but he
spent a lot of time performing in children's theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about children's theater,'' he says, ``is it's like
hitting your head against the wall. It feels so good when you
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It was through Kay Rockefeller, a children's theater producer,
that Seelen met Marjorie Seligman, who founded the Drama Book Shop
in 1923. ``Kay called and asked if I wanted to buy a share of the
bookshop, and I said yes,'' he says. ``It was one of those
life-changing decision made in 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1958. Did he regret giving up his acting career?
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs. ``A friend of mine once went up to Moss Hart in
Sardi's,'' he says, ``and asked, `What's the secret to success?'
Moss Hart said, `Don't get tired.' I think with the theater I got
tired. It was always back to square one. I was always struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It would be another 11 years before the Seelens met.
</P>
<P>
   Rozanne Ritch was born and raised in San Antonio and says she
graduated from high school at 15. Given to drama early, she recalls
standing at the top of the staircase in her house declaring, ``I'm
going to New York and never coming back.'' She certainly tried. She
attended Vassar College for a year, but her parents decided she was
too young and brought her back. She graduated from the University
of Texas at Austin, then moved to New York to pursue a career as a
ballet dancer. During an audition for the Washington Ballet she
fell and was injured severely enough to end her career.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Texas she recovered enough physically to dance in summer
stock. She returned to New York, earned a master's degree in
theater at Columbia University and worked as a play reader for
Joseph Papp. She was assisting a professor at Barnard College in
1969 when she had another fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here then to work for six months,'' she says. ``I
always say I fell into this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Seelen hired her, and though they ``kept company for a while,''
as Mrs. Seelen says, they did not marry until 1980. The store,
which was originally on West 47th Street, then on 52d Street,
where, Seelen says, it ``moved from brownstone to brownstone,'' has
been in its present location since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The Seelens remain adamant about keeping the Drama Book Shop a
place where individual service is prized. Like most independent
booksellers, they have little use for the chains. They refer to
Barnes &AMP; Noble as Barnes &AMP; Ignoble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to incorporate the technology of the book business now
while keeping personal relationships,'' Mrs. Seelen says. ``But
it's terribly hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Seelen shakes his head. ``We could be out of business in 20
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Silipo's view is less dark. ``There's not a lot of competition
in what we specialize in,'' he says. ``And we're making the growing
film community in New York knowledgeable about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Seelen says the shop will ``probably go along'' with
joining a Web site for independent booksellers, though she adds:
``If a young actor needs a scene or a monologue, that can't be done
over the Web. They come in and ask, `What is a monologue that might
be appropriate for me?' They stay for hours, reading book after
book.''
</P>
<P>
   They do?
</P>
<P>
   Seelen sighs. ``The sale is not as important as the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Seelen smiles gently. ``Arthur's real name was
Seelenfreund, which means `friend of the soul,''' she says. Does
that mean she tends to forgive him his tuna fish? She laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' she says. ``I don't remember what I ordered.
That's the whole point. We've been through so much together. We're
bookends. Absolute bookends.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the office the store is emptying. ``The Drama Book Shop
is closing in less than 15 minutes,'' a clerk announces in sonorous
tones. ``Please bring your purchases to the front.'' The customers
break into applause. ``That was marvelous,'' one calls. The clerk
bows.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Seelen looks tenderly at the remaining group, mostly
handsome young men who seem to be actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when they're being difficult,'' she says, ``I tell the
staff: `Always be nice to them. Let them be stars.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
