TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Defibrillators Installed at Chicago Airports &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has installed portable heart defibrillators at Midway
and O'Hare Airports. Monique Bond of the City of Chicago Department
of Aviation said that 33 of the devices have been put into corridor
walls at O'Hare and 7 at Midway. The battery-powered devices,
Hewlett-Packard Heartstream Forerunners, are no more than a minute
apart at walking speed, she said, and can be removed and used
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand airport workers in Chicago have been trained in the
use of the defibrillators, and 50,000 airline employees are also
estimated to be familiar with them since the majority of United
States airlines are buying them. But the machines come with
relatively simple instructions, and a recorded voice tells the
operator what to do.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Port Authority is installing defibrillators at its
airports and training its staff in their use. At the end of June,
it reported saving the life of a passenger in Terminal 2 at Kennedy
International Airport with the nearest defibrillator, which was
borrowed from a Delta airplane waiting at the gate. Airport
security officers at Anchorage and the Dallas-Fort Worth airport
police have defibrillators on hand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Learning About the Earliest Alaskans &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's indigenous culture is the focus of the new Alaska
Native Heritage Center in Anchorage. Through arts and crafts
demonstrations, dance performances and interactive displays,
visitors can learn about the people who have inhabited Alaska for
thousands of years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center is on 26 acres of wooded land about 10 minutes
northeast of downtown Anchorage. A 26,000-square-foot main building
accommodates exhibition and demonstration areas, a 100-seat
theater, a multimedia cultural resource center and a gift shop
selling native arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductions of traditional villages represent five indigenous
cultural groups. In these villages, connected by a series of
handicapped-accessible trails, demonstrators show ancient
techniques for constructing buildings, making kayaks, hunting and
fishing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska Native Heritage Center, at the corner of Muldoon Road
and Glenn Highway, is open daily. Admission is $20, $15 for
children under 12. Information: (800) 315-6608 or
www.alaskanative.net.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Portland Museum Show Gathers Space Artifacts  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine Space!,'' a collection of space artifacts, is on view
through Sept. 6 at the Oregon Museum of Science and Industry in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Displays include a jumpsuit worn during the Apollo 16 mission to
the moon, a Russian spacesuit and a number of moon rocks. There is
also a 17-foot model of the Space Shuttle Columbia, a full-scale
model of the Mercury capsule flown by John Glenn in 1961 and
samples of the food eaten in space by astronauts. Interactive
exhibits allow visitors to take a spin on a Tri-Axis Astronaut
Trainer Ride and to design, build and test model rovers, rockets
and space stations.
</P>
<P>
   A film, ``Destiny in Space,'' focusing on recent developments in
space exploration and narrated by Leonard Nimoy, is showing in the
museum's Omnimax theater, which has a five-story domed screen.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Museum of Science and Industry, 1945 Southeast Water
Avenue, is open daily. Admission is $6.50, $4.50 for ages 63 and up
and 4 to 13. Omnimax admission is $6.50 and $4.50. Packages for the
galleries, the film, a tour of the decommissioned submarine
Blueback, an astronomy show and a laser-light show are $15 and
$11.50. Information: (503) 797-4000 or at www.omsi.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Seeing British Columbia by Rail, Bus and Ferry  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BC Ferries, which serves the British Columbia coast, is joining
with railroad, bus and hotel companies to offer self-guided tours
of British Columbia. Many packages include an Inside Passage
voyage, a 15-hour daylight trip between Port Hardy, on the northern
tip of Vancouver Island, and Prince Rupert, on the north coast of
the British Columbia mainland.
</P>
<P>
   In partnership with BC Rail, (800) 339-8752, the five-night
Totem Circle Rail and Cruise package is being offered through Sept.
28. It includes two train trips (Vancouver to Prince George and
Prince George to Prince Rupert), an Inside Passage cruise, bus or
ferry connections from Port Hardy to Victoria to Vancouver, and
accommodations in Prince George, Prince Rupert, Port Hardy and
Victoria. Prices start at about $585 a person, double occupancy, at
$1.47 Canadian to the United States dollar.
</P>
<P>
   A package organized with Gray Line buses, (800) 667-0882, from
Vancouver includes voyages through the Gulf Islands to and from
Victoria, a bus tour through Vancouver Island to Port Hardy, and an
overnight cruise in a private cabin to and from Prince Rupert. The
four-night package, with accommodations for two nights in Port
Hardy and one night in Victoria, starts at about $400 a person,
double occupancy; it is also available through Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   More information about BC Ferries is available at (250) 386-3431
or at www.bcferries.com. For reservations, contact BC Rail or Gray
Line.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Classic Toronto Haunt Stands Smartly Again &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Torontonians liked what the Windsor Arms said about them. A
reserved, rather clubby hotel with British airs when it opened in
1927, it evolved _ as did Toronto _ into something surprisingly
smart while staying itself.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, it was where Katharine Hepburn, Richard Burton and
Elizabeth Taylor stayed when they came to town. Its restaurants
redefined eating out in Toronto. Afternoon tea (before it was
fashionable) in the Windsor Arms' shabby-chic ambiance of leaded
windows and oak furniture was an institution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closed since 1991 and owned by a developer, George Friedmann,
since 1995, the Windsor Arms was demolished, then reborn. The hotel
that reopened in mid-May is still on a tranquil side street off
Bloor Street's luxury shops. Visitors enter through the familiar
stone Tudor Revival archway and the original doors, which are just
about the only remaining pieces of the original building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behind the brown-brick facade that replicates the original, the
four-story 28-room hotel (a condominium rises above it) has
essentially has been rethought as ``a restaurant with rooms,'' said
Christopher Ashby, the sales director. Actully three restaurants:
the Tea Room, an echo of the homey original, mutates into a
champagne-and-caviar lounge in the evening; Club 22, a bar, has a
dance floor and an already-redolent cigar room; and the Courtyard
Cafe has been given a new cream-colored classical look punctuated
by gigantic Doric columns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's 21 suites and 7 rooms have a cool, spare style
inspired by French furniture of the 1920s, with amenities that
include whirlpool tubs in every bathroom. Guests also have use of
an indoor pool, a sauna, a spa and a fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Rates range from $256 to $1,024 (at $1.47 Canadian to the
dollar); at the top end, even the limestone-floored bathroom has a
fireplace. The Windsor Arms is at 18 St. Thomas Street, Toronto,
Ontario M5S 3E7; (877) 999-2767, fax (416) 921-9121.
</P>
</TEXT>
