<HEADLINE>
THE CARIBBEAN WONDERS: WHERE ARE THE TOURISTS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a slow winter and spring, tourism officials in the
Caribbean were hoping for better things for the rest of 1999. The
NATO bombing in the Balkans heightened those expectations, on the
assumption that many travelers would shun that part of the world
and head for the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   But Caribbean tourism continues to lag. With the number of
tourists to some islands down about 20 percent, hotel occupancy
levels are well below those of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advance bookings for the Caribbean look reasonably good,''
said Michael Youngman, the executive director of the Caribbean
Tourism Organization in New York City, but many tourism officials
are somewhat puzzled by the no-shows, especially in view of a
strong United States economy and predictions by the Travel Industry
Association of America of another record summer travel season.
</P>
<P>
   Some tourism officials in the United States blame rising crime
in the region, a series of recent strikes, destruction from
Hurricane Georges last fall and increasing competition from resorts
in the United States, Mexico and Cuba. Cuba, for example, recently
began selling packages combining a vacation on its beaches with a
flight to Guatemala to visit Mayan sites and colonial cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean hotel industry has long blamed the cruise industry
for exacerbating the islands' woes, contending that by bringing
visitors who stay only a few hours in port, the cruise ships have
discouraged longer visits. And during the Caribbean Hotel
Association meeting in Nassau, the Bahamas, last month, Ed Malone,
the association president, returned to the attack, decrying what he
called the islands' aid to the cruise industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing but admiration for an industry that has
succeeded in getting its ships built with subsidies from foreign
governments,'' he said, ``sail under flags of convenience and
recruit staff from the cheapest, non-unionized labor pools in the
world, and then sail the Caribbean in a cruise operator's tax-free
heaven. While our governments help keep foreign ship lines afloat,
we are sinking on our own shores.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, cruise officials have countered that many cruise
passengers later return to the Caribbean on land-based vacations,
but this time they mostly ignored the criticism _ perhaps because
they have troubles of their own. Cruise fares to the region have
been relatively flat this year, averaging less than $100 a day per
person including port charges but not air fare. Airlines to the
region also cite a slump in passengers and fares.
</P>
<P>
   Financial woes of cruise lines and airlines have long-term
implications for tourists. A Carnival Cruise Lines spokesman at the
hotel-association conference said that while cruise passengers to
the Caribbean have doubled in the last decade, the region's share
of the overall cruise business has fallen from about 67 percent in
1989 to slightly more than 50 percent, and so the line will reduce
or not add capacity in the region.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for American Airlines, the dominant carrier in the
Caribbean, said that in part because of lower fares from
competitors, its Caribbean profits fell in the first quarter of
this year from the comparable period in 1998 and would likely
decline further in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those lower fares are still higher, on average, than
fares to Cancun, Mexico, or to Europe. In fact, the week of the
hotel conference, British Airways and American offered a free round
trip to London with each round-trip economy ticket purchased before
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, tourism to Barbados fell 2.5 percent the first
quarter of this year, after growing 9.3 percent during the same
period last year. Dominican Republic tourism has been battered by
lingering effects of Hurricane Georges and a drop in European
tourists. And Bermuda, although not in the Caribbean except for
purposes of keeping tourism statistics, has also been struggling
with sub-par hotel occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   To reverse that, Bermuda is advertising extensively in the
United States and Canada. But it got off to a shaky start when a
supposed tongue-in-cheek newspaper advertisement suggesting that
four days in Bermuda are better than in the Hamptons drew the wrath
of Long Island tourism officials. They retaliated with an
advertisement saying: ``With 1,400 square miles, Long Island's
attractions are endless. With 20 square miles, Bermuda's
attractions soon end.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some islands appear to have more visitors than last year.
Hotel occupancy in Puerto Rico increased 4 percent over the first
four months of 1999, compared with the same period in 1998. The
Bahamas also seem to be doing better than expected, in large part
because of the expansion of the 2,000-room Atlantis Resort and
Casino on Paradise Island.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons suggested for the Caribbean's slump is that
familiarity has bred boredom. And after protests over a gasoline
tax led to three days of riots, looting and violence in Jamaica in
April, cruise ships and airlines canceled scheduled visits and
flights to the island; Jamaican hotels subsequently reported
wholesale cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean officials acknowledge that some fear remains after a
recent series of violent crimes throughout the Caribbean. Although
few of the crimes involved tourists (most were drug related), it is
hard to dispel the perception of danger, especially when tourists
have many other options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
