<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
XXXXXday, XXX. xx, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While temperatures soared toward 100 degrees or more at 2 p.m.
Tuesday from New York City to interior central New England,
readings at Boston receded to 74 degrees as cool winds blew off the
Atlantic. Readings rebounded a bit later in the afternoon in
Boston, but the city was spared extreme heat. Wednesday,
temperature trends at Boston will again be somewhat opposite to
other major cities in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The record heat that stifled most of the Northeast Seaboard
Sunday and Monday will ebb a bit Wednesday in the wake of a weak
cool front. But winds from the west-northwest, which will import
noticeably less humid air, will warm on descent from the
Appalachians, boosting temperatures into the upper 80's to low
90's. Though these readings will qualify as a easing of the heat in
most places, they will constitute a return to hot weather in
Boston. Winds along the New England Coast will average 12 to 25 mph
with higher gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Widely separated thunderstorms will erupt from the southern
Rockies to the Great Basin as moist air invading from the tropics
rises in response to the uneven heating of mountain peaks. Heavy
rain is possible in some areas, particularly in south Arizona,
where the most humid air will reside.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms, some with heavy rain and a
few spawning severe weather, will erupt from the Middle Atlantic to
the Southeast and central Gulf States in response to a stalling
front, disturbances from the tropical Atlantic and the instability
from hot, humid air near the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Monsoon
</P>
<P>
   A few weathercasters refer to the ``monsoon season'' in the
Southwest states, but they employ redundancy. The word ``monsoon''
is derived from an Arabic word meaning ``a season,'' so such an
utterance translates into ``a season season.'' Semantics aside, the
summer monsoon begins around the end of June or the beginning of
July when prevailing winds shift and blow from the humid tropics.
Such a seasonal wind shift can be too subtle to detect in the
Southwest, so the operative definition of the start of the summer
monsoon in Phoenix is three consecutive days with moderate to high
humidity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
