<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-IDAHO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTING ON IDAHO'S WHITE WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 11)  
(jt) 
 By TOM REDBURN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Screams rise above the roar of white water just ahead. But as
the big rubber raft plunges out of sight below, I'm not worried. My
14-year-old daughter, Emily, is in the boat with three other girls
and an expert guide. They aren't yelling out of fear. They are
screaming as loud as they can for the sheer fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   After two days on the Middle Fork of the Salmon River in central
Idaho, I know this is not going to be any ``River Wild'' ordeal. We
are at the heart of the nation's longest free-flowing river system,
but it's August; the raging waters of early June, when the snow is
melting, are long gone. Our group of adventurers has already had
plenty of thrills and a couple of spills, but any macho pretensions
are far from my mind.
</P>
<P>
   This is a family trip, one my wife, Lisa, and I dreamed about
for years. Jeremy, our 18-year-old son, has just graduated from
high school. Emily will be starting high school in the fall. We're
celebrating by rafting more than 100 miles down the main artery of
the biggest wilderness area in the lower 48 states. Six days on the
river, five nights of camping, an escape from the clutter of our
lives back home.
</P>
<P>
   But we aren't exactly roughing it. Our trip was organized by one
of the 26 outfitters licensed to run the Middle Fork. Our flotilla
consists of 24 guests and 6 guides, 1 for each raft. We picked
Rocky Mountain River Tours mostly because of its reputation for
terrific food and friendly guides. We have not been disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the most luxurious of the outfitters (in contrast to a
few other groups, we are expected to set up our own tents, help
load and unload the rafts, wash our own dishes). And sure, we sleep
on the ground _ in tents or under the stars _ but on thick pads
that are more comfortable than most pull-out sofas. Sumptuous meals
are prepared by the guides, who double as chefs. Wine flows freely
at dinner. Each day, we have our choice of paddling in a six-person
raft or simply going along for the ride on one of the three big oar
boats that carry all the gear and two to four passengers. Later on,
there will be chances to run the rapids in one-person inflatable
kayaks.
</P>
<P>
   This vacation began with a three-hour drive from Boise to
Stanley, a tiny crossroads town on the northern edge of the
Sawtooth Mountains. Joining us on this Western adventure was Lisa's
74-year-old mother, Mary Lou. Although she has traveled all over
the world, she still had a little trepidation about the risks. I
reassured her everything would be fine, but the truth was I didn't
know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   The Sawtooth Mountains were stunning and looked exactly like
what their name suggests. That first evening, we gathered, under
threatening skies, in the parking lot outside our motel with the
rest of our group. We eavesdropped on quiet conversations, looking
over strangers we were to live with for almost a week.
</P>
<P>
   There were several different groups: families with younger
children; some retired couples; a recently married twosome in their
mid-20s; a woman with her teen-age nephew. We introduced ourselves
_ first names only. A few of the participants were clearly veterans
of similar trips; most of us were newcomers to anything more than a
day of white water paddling. One of the adults had never slept
outdoors before.
</P>
<P>
   As we tried on our matching bright yellow, orange or green
waterproof overalls and rain jackets for size, we all looked
faintly ridiculous, like giant plastic neon-colored fishing worms.
There was an underlying current of excitement, but also some basic
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go to the bathroom?'' asked one. The waterproof
bags designed to hold all our personal gear looked awfully small.
``Can we really fit all our stuff in those little rubber bags?''
Mary Lou asks: ``How will we get back in the raft if we fall out?''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a car drove by. The driver yelled: ``You're all
going to die!'' We laughed uneasily.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Mills, a native Idahoan with an aw-shucks manner who owns
Rocky Mountain River Tours with his wife, Sheila, tried to be
reassuring. ``We've never lost anybody yet,'' he says. ``But
there's always a first time.'' Easy for him to joke. He was not
going on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   On the bus ride to the put-in the next morning, we became better
acquainted with some of our companions. But where were the guides?
When we finally reached the end of the gravel road at Boundary
Creek, we saw a host of rafts for several groups, some still on
trailers, most of them already laid out on the river below. Pete,
the leader of the trip, sported a shaved head and a goatee. He gave
a short lecture about respect for the wilderness and how we would
take out everything we took in, including our human waste. ``I want
you to feel guilty about leaving a footprint,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven groups are permitted to enter the Middle Fork each
day. Four are private groups, average size about 10 people,
allocated by lottery; three slots go to commercial outfitters,
which can take up to 24 guests each. As many as 10,000 people run
the river every summer, but we would see only fleeting glimpses of
others the entire week. Assigned campsites were far enough apart to
preserve the illusion of solitude.
</P>
<P>
   The sky was still a little threatening, but the rain gear was to
protect us from the spray of cold river water. We put on life
preservers and helmets. Our guides had spent the morning loading
the three big oar rafts with just about everything we'd need for
the next six days. I chose a paddle boat with Lisa and four other
guests. Allison, the sole female guide, was in charge. The first
day was a run of just seven miles, but because the water was
relatively low, the rapids were tricky, she said. We would have to
negotiate the rocks; not simply ride over them on big waves. We
wouldn't have much time to rehearse.
</P>
<P>
   Allison read the cues of the river carefully, as if enjoying a
dance with an old friend. Our jerky nervousness quickly evaporated,
replaced by the exhilaration of leaning and pulling our paddles
hard against the force of the water as Allison yelled: ``All
forward, all forward. Really pull now.''
</P>
<P>
   We surged forward. ``OK, forward right, back on the left,''
commanding my side to back paddle hard enough to turn us to the
left around a rock. ``Back on the left,'' she says. ``Lean into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great work!'' we hear as we slide down the tongue of smooth
water between boulders. Our raft bounced off another rock and we
spun around gently into the waiting pool.
</P>
<P>
   The days quickly fell into an active routine.
</P>
<P>
   I was usually up shortly after sunrise. The smell of
fresh-brewed coffee wafted through the campground at 7. Breakfast,
around 8, was hot and filling, prepared in Dutch ovens over a wood
fire contained in a metal pan laden with charcoal. One morning it
was a goat cheese and egg strata, with coffee cake for the less
adventurous eaters. I indulged in both. Another morning it was
blueberry oatmeal pancakes. Fresh fruit and cold cereal were always
available.
</P>
<P>
   There was time for fly-fishing (catch-and-release only),
exploring the area around the campsite, or just chatting in the
circle of folding chairs. We packed our tents, sleeping bags and
personal gear, took a last look around. We were usually on the
river by 10, at first paddling leisurely with the current, then
enjoying flurries of activity as we maneuvered through the moderate
Class II and Class III rapids.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, it was hot. We stopped for lunch, which included
sandwiches, fruit, a salad, cookies. Time for fishing, a brief nap
or, for those willing to brave the chilly water, swimming. Back on
the river by 2 or so. Maybe switching to an oar boat. The
afternoons consisted of a longer run through the twisting funnel of
forest that sloped down to the water's edge. Some days we stopped
to examine Indian pictographs on the rock walls. Another time we
hiked up for 30 minutes to enjoy a misty waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
