<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-IDAHO-$ADV11-2     07-06 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-IDAHO-$ADV11-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: misty waterfall.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And there are always more rapids, a few particularly
challenging. In the paddle boats, we got wet often but dried off
quickly in the sun. There were eagles, otters, glimpses of a few
mountain goats on the cliffs above.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 5 p.m. or so we had usually found our campsite for
the night. Everyone got in the ``bag line'' to hand the gear, like
a bucket brigade, from person to person so that it moved quickly
from boats to campground. I usually took a dip to cool off.
Appetizers were served before dinner, which was an amazing feast
considering how far we were from anything resembling a store. One
night margaritas were prepared in a 10-gallon cooler, followed by
fresh salad with edible flowers. The main course: a chicken and
tortilla casserole. Dessert was freshly baked (those Dutch ovens
again) chocolate cake. Night fell just before 10.
</P>
<P>
   We're not completely cut off. On the second day, we stopped at a
sand bar below an airstrip, where Dave Mills had flown in with more
fresh food and the inflatable kayaks. There were no roads near the
river, but signs of human enterprise remained from the time before
this area was set aside as a 2.3-million-acre preserve, known as
the Frank Church-River of No Return Wilderness. We passed a stretch
of a dozen or so vacation homes reachable by private plane. A few
ranches, also accessible by landing strip or horseback, dotted the
landscape. We saw some leftover cabins and rusting equipment from
miners who never struck it rich here.
</P>
<P>
   This has always been rugged, remote territory. When Lewis and
Clark reached this point, it seemed so forbidding they had to
detour 150 miles north. The Indians called the Salmon the River of
No Return. The truth is, though, that traveling by river is by far
the easiest way to experience this still largely untouched
wilderness. There are dangers _ serious injuries or deaths for
rafters are extremely rare _ generally confined to the three or
four weeks of torrential flow in the early season.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached Haystack Rapids, the guides pointed out the
place where an experienced river runner drowned several years
earlier, his body trapped under a churning backwash for weeks while
dozens of groups unknowingly floated right over him. On our trip, a
few paddlers were tossed out but they were quickly recovered. The
worst that happens are a couple of mildly twisted ankles and
scraped knees.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we were so well taken care of that Jeremy, who had been
on several more arduous backpacking and canoeing trips, remarked
dismissively during a campfire discussion: ``This isn't really a
wilderness trip.''
</P>
<P>
   But I was glad we could enjoy it so readily. The Forest Service
is considering a proposal to severely restrict access to the Middle
Fork during the high season from mid-June to mid-August. The
outfitters are up in arms, seeing their livelihood at stake. It's
clear that it does a remarkable job keeping the river and
surrounding area as pristine as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Until the final night, the weather had been just about perfect.
But during our steak dinner, a whirlwind swept up the canyon,
spilling food, scattering sparks from the campfire and tossing
around any tent not weighted down. As the rain poured down briefly,
we all scrambled for shelter. ``Now  &UR; this &LR;  is wilderness,'' Jeremy
exclaimed happily.
</P>
<P>
   The last day was bittersweet. We were deep in Impassable Canyon
now. The rapids were bigger, the ride more rollicking. Once through
the last major white water, we all relaxed, leaned back, and
congratulated ourselves on ``surviving'' our few days away from
civilization. I took a swig from the water bottle. For a moment no
one spoke and I looked around. The sky was blue. The sun was hot.
The river was cold. Nothing else mattered.
</P>
<P>
   But all too soon, we reached the confluence of the Middle Fork
and the Main Salmon. The take-out loomed ahead on the right. The
Salmon River flowed for another 60 miles before the next exit. I
wished we could have just kept on going.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; White-water outfitters, seasons and costs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the outfitters that offer trips on the Middle Fork of
the Salmon, generally considered the premier high mountain
white-water river in the United States, are small family-owned
companies that concentrate on the area. Others are larger outfits
that operate white-water trips throughout the West. They all supply
just about everything that you will need, including tents, sleeping
bags, rain gear, meals and bus transportation to the river and back
to your car.
</P>
<P>
   Trip dates are available at least a year ahead but some
schedules could change as early as the summer of 2000 if the Forest
Service approves a more restrictive wilderness permit system. The
season generally runs from early June to late September.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rocky Mountain River Tours,  &LR; owned by Dave and Sheila Mills,
has been running the Middle Fork exclusively since 1978. It offers
four- to six-day trips, depending on the season. Costs for 1999
vary from $970 a person for a four-day high water adventure to
$1,685 for six days in the peak season during July and the first
week of August. Call (208) 756-4808 during the rafting season;
(208) 345-2400 at other times. On the Internet: www.rafttrips.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hughes River Expeditions &LR;  offers trips on the Salmon River
Canyon and a few smaller rivers in Idaho. Its prices for a five- or
six-day Middle Fork trip range from $1,100 to $1,480 a person. Call
(800) 262-1882 or visit www.hughesriver.com.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bigger, more wide-ranging outfitters are  &UR; Echo: The
Wilderness Company,  &LR; which also runs trips in Oregon and
California;  &UR; Western River Expeditions &LR; , which runs the Grand
Canyon as well, and  &UR; O.A.R.S. &LR; , which covers much of the West.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Echo, call (800) 652-3246 or visit www.echotrips.com.
Western River can be reached at (800) 453-7450 and at
www.westernriver.com. O.A.R.S. can be reached at (800) 346-6277 and
at www.oars.com. The prices are similar to those of local
outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   A complete list of outfitters is available from the  &UR; Idaho
Outfitters and Guides Association, &LR;  (800) 494-3246 or www.ioga.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; When to Go &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In late May and early June, experienced white-water rafters can
run the Middle Fork at its wildest on the full rush of the snow
melt. Trips are shorter and more dangerous, and the weather is
unpredictable. Starting in late June and generally running through
mid-August, sunny weather is common and the river becomes far more
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Families generally take six-day trips from mid-July through
mid-August. In drier years, the water flow diminishes enough by
early to mid-August that guests may have to fly into an airstrip
farther downriver from the normal put-in, cutting a day off the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Trout fishing improves dramatically by late August.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
