<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-GREEN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Green's links to his father never forgotten
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Some athletes invest in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Green, a 33-year-old receiver who signed with the Miami
Dolphins after being released by Denver in February, chose to put
his money in other commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda grass and sand.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, after attempts to buy existing courses fell
through, Green and nine other investors began building a golf
course on 180 acres in Shelby, N.C., the small town about 35 miles
south of Charlotte that he calls home during the NFL off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the 6,911-yard, par-72 course, with an 8,000-square-foot
clubhouse, opened.
</P>
<P>
   Most call it Deer Brook Golf Club. Green calls it a dream come
true _ one that produces a thrill right up there with winning
back-to-back Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   You see, for Green the golf-is-life philosophy isn't just
something from the back of a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   For him, golf is much more than a game. It's a way to figure out
who you can trust on the football field, a way to teach discipline
and ethics and, perhaps most of all, a way to spend a few more
hours with a father who died 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If Green were to tell his life story, it would begin with the
words he used shortly after he finished a recent practice, slipped
on a John Elway Golf Tournament shirt and headed to a course with
some new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to live my life like my father did,'' he said. ``He
never drank alcohol. He never did drugs. He raised nine kids. The
only thing he did his whole life was work and play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf is often thought of as a game for people who are rich and
white.
</P>
<P>
   Green's father was neither.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Green Sr. worked as a janitor at a movie theater in
Athens, Ga. He made $85 a week. He took the bus to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked every day,'' Green said. ``Holidays, Christmas,
every day. And in all those years, he missed three days.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a second job. He caddied. After caddying, he would
play. He tried to get his first six children interested. He tried
to get his wife to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried,'' Corene Green, Willie's mother, said. ``But when I
got pregnant with little Willie, I stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she knew that her seventh child, the baby boy of the
family, would be the one who took to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Little Willie spent most weekends with Big Willie. He would walk
or drive to work with him. He would go to the golf course and ride
in a cart. He would learn about golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he taught me about the game, he taught me the rules and
the etiquette,'' Green said. ``I remember those days like they were
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   He still plays by those rules. No cutting corners. Just ask his
new teammates. Several weeks ago he and cornerback Terrell Buckley
were competing against receivers coach Robert Ford and offensive
coordinator Kippy Brown. They were up by two holes on the 15th when
Buckley, preparing to hit a shot off the fringe of the green,
stomped on some of the grass behind the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-stroke penalty,'' Buckley said. ``He's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Green learned that from his dad, a man who could have found it
easy to revolt against the rules that were in place at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of courses my father couldn't play back then
because of the color of his skin,'' Green said. ``From what I saw _
the way people talked to him when he went to play golf at some
places _ that gave me the inspiration. I said to myself, `When I
get old enough I want to own my own golf course so my father will
be able to play there.'''
</P>
<P>
   So when Deer Brook opened, it was a dream fulfilled. With a
bittersweet twist.
</P>
<P>
   His father died in 1986. He was 66 years old. He had lived a
full life. The day before his death, on a fall Saturday afternoon
in Athens, he had sat in the stands at Sanford Stadium and watched
his son, then a freshman at the University of Mississippi, play in
a football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seemed like it was my father's proudest moment,'' Green
said. ``I was the first one in my family to go to college and he
was so proud. I thank God for allowing him to stay alive to see
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he wishes his father could have seen all that he's
accomplished on the field _ 10 NFL seasons and two Super Bowl
titles _ you get the sense Green wishes he could have done other
things with him.
</P>
<P>
   He could have taken him to Augusta to watch the Masters. He
could have told him about playing a round with Greg Norman, about
shaking hands with Tiger Woods, about getting his handicap down to
8, about teaching another generation, a grandson named Willie,
about the rules of golf.
</P>
<P>
   He could have taken him to places where he once was forbidden
and, Green insists, now would be welcomed without prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed,'' Green says. ``I told my mom that if my
dad were still alive today, he and I would have hit every golf
course in this world. Not just in the United States. Any golf
course he wanted to play in the world, we would have played.''
</P>
<P>
   And somehow you get the feeling their favorite might have been
one in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   One with an owner named Green.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
