<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
 
McCAIN, ALWAYS THE MAVERICK, RUNS AGAINST THE WAYS OF WASHINGTON  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sometime this month, John McCain, the senior
senator from Arizona, plans to do just the kind of thing that
drives fellow Republicans crazy.
</P>
<P>
   At a moment when others in the Senate have dropped their guard,
he will try to force his campaign finance bill to the floor for the
debate his party's leaders do not want. Whenever he strikes, he is
sure to get publicity, as the maverick once again tilting at the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   And that in turn will amplify the theme of his long-shot
presidential bid as he uses his perch in the Senate to fight
against the ways of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who is satisfied with the status quo should vote for
someone else,'' McCain told a recent noontime crowd of 200 people
packed into the town hall of Bedford, N.H. ``But anyone who
believes that America is greater than the sum of its special
interests should stand with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a larger-than-life banner of a handsome young man in
uniform stirred in the breeze. It is what John McCain, the Navy
aviator, looked like before he was shot down over Vietnam in 1967
and held as a prisoner of war for five and a half years. The
black-and-white picture is a gripping reminder of his personal
story, a history that his campaign is using to press the point that
he is not a run-of-the mill politician.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, in the sweltering hall, the real man seemed smaller, at
62 more battered, and not quite comfortable in this role as
presidential contender. He read his speech fast without the polish
of President Clinton or the catch-in-the-throat laugh of Elizabeth
Dole. He forgot to pause for applause lines.
</P>
<P>
   But in an odd way, his delivery almost gave him more
authenticity to an audience, sprinkled with men in veterans caps,
that seemed to be yearning for an antidote to the political
slickness of the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes across as a fine person,'' said Donald Rogers, a
maintenance supervisor and registered independent. ``You know what
I mean? Not a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem difficult for a 17-year denizen of Congress, a
senator who is a fixture on the Sunday television circuit, to seek
the presidency as a Washington outsider, particularly when the
leading Republican candidate is based in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is what McCain is trying to do, playing off Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's close embrace by the Republican establishment and
the governor's extraordinary $36.3 million war chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been an outsider in the Senate,'' McCain said in
an interview, fidgeting in a wing chair in his office, which was
humming with staff at 9 in the morning. As if to prove McCain's
point, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader from Mississippi,
quickly took a potshot at him after his New Hampshire speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think, when you're out there raising money right and
left, and then you're talking about how you need to reform the
system, it rings a little hollow,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain responded that his campaign ``adheres to the letter and
the spirit'' of the bill he has sponsored. The legislation would
ban the unlimited and unregulated donations to the political
parties known as soft money, but would not affect how presidential
candidates raise money.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has raised $6.1 million for his presidential race, coming
in a very distant second to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's record is complex _ raising at once the question of
whether he is too moderate for the conservatives he would need to
win the Republican nomination and too conservative for the
moderates and independents he would need in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways he is well in sync with his party. As chairman of
the Senate Commerce Committee, he just shepherded through the
chamber a measure on lawsuits addressing the year 2000 computer
problem, which was important to Republicans as a way of luring the
high-tech industry into the party fold and illustrating the
Democrats' ties to trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He voted to convict President Clinton on two impeachment counts.
He is a social conservative who voted against the procedure its
opponents call partial birth abortion. In fact, in 1998, he voted
with his party 81 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   But on a number of high-profile issues, he has alienated many
powerful Republican constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly takes to the Senate floor to expose the pork-barrel
provisions inserted in various spending bills. He has opposed
subsidies for ethanol, a corn-based fuel that is the
special-interest elixir of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's failed attempt last year to pass an anti-tobacco bill
drew criticism from both the tobacco lobby and from anti-tax
Republican purists. His effort this spring to grant Clinton the
ability to use ground troops in Kosovo was tabled by both parties.
And his campaign finance bill puts him at odds with both the
Republican leadership and conservative constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``A consensus has developed that Mr. Bush is the most electable
contender,'' said Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster. ``And John
McCain is seen as the candidate who will ultimately run into
problems by the key constituencies he's antagonized.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain has taken all his maverick stands and sewn them into
a campaign banner of reform that his advisers insist will appeal to
conservatives angry at a Republican Congress that cannot seem to
bring about change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to reform government,'' McCain said. ``We need
to reform politics. We need to reform the military, the education
system. We need to reform the tax code which would lead to greater
freedom for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   And in very personal terms last week he called his effort to
limit money in politics the most important plank of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who I serve believe that the means by which I came
to office corrupt me,'' he said in his New Hampshire speech. ``And
that shames me. Their contempt is a stain upon my honor and I
cannot live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, McCain supported another veteran, Bob Dole,
accompanying him often along the campaign trail. In some ways the
two campaigns are similar. Dole, too, stressed his war story, to
show that he was a man of character. But the theme also emphasized
his age. His war was World War II. McCain's was Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   And now, despite the long odds, McCain considers it his moment.
``I just feel I'm at a time in my life when I'm most qualified,''
he said. ``And by the way, I will not be at this point again.''
</P>
<P>
   He traces his reformers' zeal back to his abiding interest in
the military and his anger at wasteful military spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some if it had to do with when I'm really sometimes genuinely
offended, when we spend billions of dollars in pork barrel spending
in the appropriations bill as we have 11,000 enlisted families on
food stamps,'' he said. ``that really genuinely offends me.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians put themselves forward as agents of change. But
McCain's advisers hope their candidate will be viewed differently
because of the compelling story of his endurance as a prisoner of
war in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   McCain still wryly tries to downplay his valor, saying, ``It
doesn't take a hero to get shot down'' or instructing a reporter
not to watch the campaign video of his life and career. (``I'm a
bit embarrassed by that tape,'' he says.)
</P>
<P>
   But his campaign is relentlessly marketing his life story. The
video tape, titled ``America's Devoted Son,'' has been mailed all
over New Hampshire and is sometimes shown before he is introduced
at campaign events.
</P>
<P>
   It tells of the day in 1967 that his bomber was struck by a
missile over Vietnam. Of the broken legs and arm he suffered when
he ejected and plunged into a lake. The bayonet wounds and broken
shoulder he suffered at the hands of an angry Vietnamese mob who
fished him out.
</P>
<P>
   It speaks of the pilot's refusal to accept early release,
offered to him for propaganda purposes when his captors realized
his father was the commander of U.S. forces in the Pacific. And of
the beatings and two years of solitary confinement that marked his
five and a half years as a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   The video winds through subsequent pictures of McCain in
Congress, at the side of Ronald Reagan and Barry Goldwater, before
it gets to its finale, drawing an implicit comparison with Clinton.
``At a time when some leaders let us down,'' intones the narrator,
``John McCain's a man we can believe. And believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparison is not without risks. McCain acknowledges a life
``full of imperfections and flaws.'' His first marriage fell apart
after his admitted womanizing. He was named in the Keating Five
scandal, as one of the senators who met with regulators on behalf
of Charles H. Keating Jr., a savings and loan operator. He was the
least involved and in the end received only a mild rebuke from the
Senate Ethics Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But strategists believe his war story will make up for any
shortcoming. And by September, McCain will be promoting his book
``Faith of My Fathers,'' a family history tracing three generations
of the McCain family _ his father and grandfather were both
admirals.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain's strategy is unorthodox. His campaign has decided that
it can afford no more than a token effort in Iowa, the first caucus
state, where the ethanol subsidies he denounces as corporate
welfare are popular.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he is relying on the fact that voters in New Hampshire,
the first primary state, sometimes take a cranky pride in being
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also investing time and resources in South Carolina,
which is emerging as crucial because its primary quickly follows
New Hampshire's.
</P>
<P>
   In both states, he is making a special appeal to veterans. And
in New Hampshire, where independents can vote in either party
primary, the campaign has begun organizing an ``independents for
McCain'' movement.
</P>
<P>
   While some say that the compressed primary schedule makes it
impossible for an underdog to take advantage of a come-from-behind
win in an early primary, McCain argues just the opposite. He says
that if a front-runner stumbles badly he will not have time to
recover as the race moves quickly on to bigger states.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If McCain is a student of campaign strategy, it is also clear
that he has been thinking about how he would conduct his
presidency. At Harvard's Kennedy Center to accept an award recently
for his efforts to change the campaign finance system, he wandered
the Kennedy library, watching old clips of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you,'' he said, quickly adding, ``This is
really premature. But if I were president of the United States, I'd
go back to what Jack Kennedy did.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would hold a news conference every week to defuse the
strained relationship with the press. ``You can't go back to the
days where FDR used to invite everybody into the Oval Office for a
chat. But you certainly could go back to the Kennedy thing, once a
week and say, `What's on your mind, guys? No major announcement,
what's on your mind?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He talked a little more about watching Kennedy's speeches. ``I'd
forgotten how good he was at inspiring people to be involved in
causes greater than your self-interest'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, perhaps concerned at being too rhapsodic over a Democrat,
he quickly added, ``By the way, I want to emphasize it doesn't mean
I share his political philosophy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
