<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-Y2K07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web site reports on BellSouth readiness
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth has re-published a Web site dedicated to
informing customers about the Y2K readiness of its vast offerings
of telephone service and products.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the site is to let customers continually keep
tabs on BellSouth's progress in making its computer systems able to
read dates after the first of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at BellSouth are doing everything we can to make sure our
telephone network and computer systems will be ready for the Year
2000,'' said Rick Harder, vice president with overall
responsibilities for the corporate Year 2000 project. ``This Web
site provides our customers with an easy-to-use method of keeping
up-to-date with our Year 2000 program.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's Y2K site will let customers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Check whether the central switch serving their area is Y2K
compliant. The check is done through software embedded in the site.
Customers type their area code and the first three digits of their
telephone number into the software.
</P>
<P>
   _ Search a continually updated database on the Y2K readiness of
BellSouth services and products. Among the things listed are local
telephone service, wireless service and television service.
</P>
<P>
   _ Download more in-depth information about BellSouth's Y2K
compliance efforts. Among the things customers can download are the
company's compliance statement, customer letter about compliance
and a list of frequently asked questions about Y2K and their
answers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Read the company's latest press releases about Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   In general, BellSouth has said it is on track to be fully Y2K
ready by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made tremendous strides in our Year 2000 readiness
efforts,'' said Harder. ``We want to be able share this information
with our customers so that they understand the progress we are
making. We expect to update our Web site at least monthly.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is a $23 billion Baby Bell that serves the Southeast.
Based in Atlanta, the company also provides wireless telephone
service, Internet access and wireless digital television service.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find BellSouth's Y2K customer site at
www.bellsouth.com/year2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
