<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-06 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON CREATES FUND-RAISING PANEL FOR N.Y. SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of a four-day ``listening tour'' of
upstate New York, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton took the
initial step Tuesday toward an unusual campaign to join the U.S.
Senate, which barely five months ago weighed ousting her husband
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Watched by a horde of news photographers, Mrs. Clinton's
advisers submitted a single page formally notifying the Federal
Election Commission that she has created a committee to fund her
exploration of a Senate campaign from the Empire State.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the committee allows her to raise and spend money for
political travel, polling and ads. Among the committee's first
expenses will be the upstate tour on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say the 51-year-old first lady will reach a formal
decision later this year on whether to seek the seat of retiring
New York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a maverick Democrat who has
represented the state of 18.2 million since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have yet to settle on a candidate for the open
Senate seat. The Senate is currently controlled by Republicans, 55
to 45.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, an independent-minded
Republican at odds with New York's Republican Gov. George Pataki
and former GOP Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, has also formed a Senate
exploratory committee and raised almost $3 million. Giuliani called
Mrs. Clinton's move ``a good thing,'' adding: ``Who could have
anything against exploring? Or listening.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also got in a jab at her carpet-bagger status and touted
his own familiarity with the heavily Republican areas of upstate
New York that she will visit this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very significant knowledge of the whole state,'' he
said. ``Every time I've gone up there I've gotten the feeling
people like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., a four-term member of Congress and
Pataki ally, vows to announce his own Senate bid later this year,
and another Long Island Republican, Rep. Peter T. King, is said to
be interested in running. That raises the prospect of a punishing
year-long GOP rivalry that could harm the victor's campaign against
Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The latest public opinion surveys offered conflicting outcomes
to a hypothetical Clinton-Giuliani race 16 months before Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby International Poll of 705 likely voters completed June
28 showed Giuliani defeating Mrs. Clinton 50 percent to 40 percent
in a survey with a margin of error of plus or minus 3.8 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac College Poll of 1,131 registered voters, also
completed June 28, showed a virtual dead heat with Mrs. Clinton
beating Giuliani 46 percent to 44 percent. The margin of error was
plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a campaign spokesman for Mrs. Clinton, said she
will travel across the state in coming weeks to meet with New
Yorkers in small groups and listen to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Her bid to connect with grass-roots voters in her first
independent campaign of her 24-year marriage to Bill Clinton
recalls a strategy she adopted in 1983 when she led a
county-by-county listening tour across Arkansas to build public
support for education reforms. The measures were later enacted by
her husband, the governor of Arkansas, and the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
   During her tour this week Mrs. Clinton plans to highlight her
latest political concerns with six ``Listening to New Yorkers''
forums. As she planned the venture, the president will not take
part. He left Monday on a four-day cross-country tour of poor
communities left behind by America's booming prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's popularity soared as she stood by her husband
throughout the year-long impeachment struggle that arose from his
sexual dalliance with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and
subsequent allegations of an attempted cover-up. On Feb. 12 the
GOP-led Senate acquitted him of two House-passed impeachment
charges.
</P>
<P>
   GOP strategist Frank Luntz, who is urging Giuliani to seek the
Senate seat, says Mrs. Clinton's loyalty to her husband has
bolstered her political appeal so strongly that it would be a
mistake for a Republican opponent to raise the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Republicans think that they will recapture the Senate seat
in New York by attacking Bill Clinton, they are mistaken _ it will
backfire,'' Luntz warned.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Mrs. Clinton will stop first at Moynihan's farm in
Oneonta, N.Y. Then she will make talk-show style appearances at the
State University of New York there, a health-care facility in
Cooperstown, a senior citizens' home in Utica, a technology park in
Rome, N.Y., and a union-related event at a four-wheel-drive vehicle
parts plant in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Appearing before the National Education Association convention
in Orlando, Fla. on Monday, Mrs. Clinton took an indirect swipe at
Giuliani, who supports a voluntary school voucher system that would
let parents use taxpayer funds to send their children to private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who say that vouchers are the way to improve
our local schools,'' Mrs. Clinton told the NEA, a powerful
teachers' union that has long supported Democratic candidates. ``I
say they are dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans have raised questions about her use
of taxpayer-provided Air Force executive jets and about her
commitment to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson led a day-long trip in
New York state by executive jet last week to underscore GOP claims
that Mrs. Clinton had used $220,000 in taxpayer funds to stage 12
trips to New York since January.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's allies are using a site on the World Wide Web to
challenge Mrs. Clinton, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Born in Illinois and carried to power in Arkansas, with no
connection of any kind to New York, Hillary has set her sights on
the New York Senate seat and maybe _ probably _ set her sights even
higher,'' Giuliani supporters proclaim. ``The U.S. Senate is a
place for proven leaders, not a proving ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's campaign Web site, www.hillary2000.org, was set
to debut Wednesday morning to coincide with the start of her New
York swing. The site will feature Mrs. Clinton's columns and
speeches as well as information on how to volunteer or contribute
to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
