<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-TOUR07-COX     07-06 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-TOUR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former ProLaunch gets $10 million, new board members
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last year Roger Barnette was just another struggling
Atlanta entrepreneur trying to get his Web site, ProLaunch, off the
ground. Today, he'll announce that his company is the recipient of
a $10 million infusion of venture capital with a strong local
technology pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   ProLaunch asked users to check off areas of interest and if they
selected ProLaunch as their Web start page, they got a new Web page
geared to their specific interests each time they logged on. It's a
neat idea, and for people who want to surf the Web but don't really
have the time, this seemed like an ideal solution.
</P>
<P>
   In June the company came up with a more marketable name, eTour
(www.etour.com), but still directs registered users to Web sites
matched to their interests. Media Metrix, the New York and
Atlanta-based Web measurement firm that has a category for almost
everyone, ranks eTour No. 1 in the category of ``Web stickiness.''
That category also includes high rollers Hot Mail, The Drudge
Report and BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web stickiness'' means that Barnette has developed a site
people like to visit on a fairly regular basis. Once you've
accomplished that, advertising dollars and venture capital funding
usually aren't far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Today, almost one year later to the day, the company has a new
name, a new focus and plans to announce the completion of a $10
million round of funding along with some impressive new board
members. At 29, Barnett is poised to be Atlanta's next big Web
player and possible heir apparent in an impressive line of local
success stories that include MindSpring, iXL and WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, WebMD's Jeff Arnold and iXL's Bert Ellis are part of
the Atlanta all-private investing group. Rounding out the group is
Taylor Glover, senior vice president of the Atlanta branch of
Merrill Lynch Pierce Fenner &AMP; Smith. Arnold and Glover will become
directors on eTour's board. Jeff Levy of Media Metrix also serves
on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Barnette says he and Arnold were brought together by a mutual
friend _ a way of combining companies that is a hallmark of Silicon
Valley's so-called ``parking lot deals'' such as the one that
united search engine Excite with the high-speed AtHome network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had breakfast a couple of times,'' Barnette says, ``and
Jeff was impressed with the business model and how much we've done
with so little resources. I was glad to get the best of all
possible worlds with local money and great connections. It's a
great combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette says the name change to eTour is part of a new branding
strategy that he hopes to develop. ``ProLaunch didn't really tell
you anything about the company,'' he says. ``eTour tells you more,
it gives you a tour of the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's immediate focus will be on making eTour a
household name. Barnette says he wants to use the $10 million to
establish the brand and improve his product offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been underneath the radar screen,'' he says, ``but to
have these incredible resources that we can leverage is what we
really want to do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
