<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-06 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL CONGRESS FAST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the House narrowly rejected a call for days of
prayer and fasting last month, conservatives who hide behind God in
order to duck serious legislative decisions suffered a defeat at
the hands of moderates who are alarmed about mixing religion and
public policy.
</P>
<P>
   This was good news, countering the political shock of recent
House approval of a Bible-thumping measure permitting states to
allow posting the Ten Commandments in classrooms and other
state-run facilities. That act was supposedly passed to ``return
God to the schools,'' in the pretentious words of House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the prayer resolution may not be dead after all. It fell
only two votes short of the two-thirds majority required under the
speeded-up process used by its sponsor, Rep. Helen Chenoweth,
R-Idaho, to push it through without normal committee hearings.
Eleven ambivalent cowards voted ``present'' and eight members
didn't vote.
</P>
<P>
   That means a clear majority of 275 members, most of them
Republicans, favored trashing the Constitution with a religious
stunt that would do nothing to achieve the stated goal of the
resolution: stopping school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Chenoweth, a militant opponent of gun control, insists that she
will try again, one way or another. Keeping the congressional focus
on our presumed spiritual shortcomings in the wake of the Littleton
school shootings is a transparent way to distract us from the
urgent need to pass what Chenoweth calls ``restrictive laws'' that
might inconvenience gun lovers.
</P>
<P>
   The House resolution would have instructed ``leaders'' in
national, state, and local governments as well as in business and
the clergy to call on Americans to observe an unspecified day or
days of ``solemn prayer, fasting and humiliation before God.'' It
described prayer as everyone's ``necessary duty'' and declared it
to be ``incumbent on all public bodies, as well as private persons,
to revere and rely on God Almighty...''
</P>
<P>
   Chenoweth predicted that after refusing food for a day and
praying, ``perhaps then love and compassion will replace hate and
indifference.'' She actually uttered this moralizing claptrap on
the floor of a mean-spirited Congress so polarized that members
barely speak to each other or bother to conceal their intense
partisan loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad she is not seeking re-election next year. If the measure
passes and the predicted miracle does occur on Capitol Hill, it
would be the wonder of the world and worth hanging around to
observe. On the other hand, there is likely to be a wait. A very
long wait.
</P>
<P>
   Every member who objected to the resolution first endorsed his
or her own faith in God, acceptance of religious guidance and
belief in the power of prayer. They may have meant it, but no sane
politician is going to risk offending church-going constituents by
sounding irreverent.
</P>
<P>
   But most Democrats shared the skepticism expressed by Rep.
Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., that Congress shouldn't seek ``the role of
religious director of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional constitutional separation of church and state
kept getting in the way. That separation is not always easy to
define but it is fundamental to our democratic principles and to
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents felt the resolution was too zealous in describing
prayer as a ``necessary duty.'' Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas,
observed, ``Prayer should not be a government-imposed duty... What
right under our Constitution does this Congress have to tell any
citizen that it is his duty to pray? The answer is we have no right
to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., agreed. He argued it is not the
role of Congress to ``initiate, mandate, or manipulate personal
religious expression.'' He also pointed out that the resolution
called for verbal penitence but did not ask for any individual or
organizational good deeds to translate inspired thoughts into
legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ted Strickland, D-Ohio, also protested the failure to back
up prayers with a call for renewed efforts to help others. ``Talk
is cheap, and often in this chamber, rhetoric is empty,'' he said.
``Faith by itself, if it has no works, is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas, noted that several Republicans
backing the resolution had stressed that the words ``in God We
Trust'' are engraved overhead on the House chamber wall. She called
attention to additional carvings with the words ``justice and
tolerance,'' meaning we should understand our constitutional
underpinnings and respect our diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D., added, ``The way for us to urge
prayer and humility before God is by our example as individuals,''
he said, ``not by our political rhetoric as members of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Pomeroy quoted Matthew 6, verses 4-6: ``When you pray, go into
your room and shut the door and pray to your father who is in
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   But presidential candidate Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, spoke for
the prevailing GOP majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``A prayer,'' he said, ``is consistent with our Founders, our
Constitution and it is unbelievable that we are even having this
debate today.'' Period. End of subject.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no common ground there.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
