<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-LESS-ART-BOS &LR;      07-06 1944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-LESS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING LESS WITH ALL THE STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Rocky Mountain News and all needing; originally
moved 6/24 in 2 takes)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo was sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; More professionals _ many of them parents _ are cutting back
to part time, but at what cost? &QL; 
(at)6 Seated in a booth at J. P. Licks, Katy Abel is trying hard to
ignore the fact that her 4-year-old son has a death grip on her
neck. Six months ago, faced with a hectic workload that kept her
from spending enough time at home, Abel left her part-time job as
features reporter for Channel 7.
</P>
<P>
   But as Abel tries to keep cool with Rubin heading for a meltdown
in the Boston ice cream parlor, she has no regrets. Abel, 40, has
discovered what a growing number of parents are realizing: Working
part time is no panacea for people struggling to juggle the demands
of career and family.
</P>
<P>
   For many, working part time actually increases the stress of
balancing job and family demands, and also exacts a toll on career
aspirations. Even those who have successfully adjusted to a reduced
schedule often pay a price for the privilege _ in one way or
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks that working less is the ideal solution to all
the stress in today's world, but it may in fact cause you more
distress,'' says Rosalind Barnett, a senior scientist in the
women's studies program at Brandeis University who has studied the
issue. ``You have to give up a lot in career advancement, in pay,
in benefits, and a lot of people don't realize that going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett is not talking about people who work part time in
low-paying jobs and would gladly give up free afternoons for
permanent full-time jobs. While the percentage of these
second-class part-time jobs has not substantially increased since
the 1960s, according to Bureau of Labor Statistics, neither has the
number of better-paying part-time positions for professionals such
as Abel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a lot of choice out there,'' Abel says. ``You can
work part time at a full-time pace, resulting in such stress and
anxiety that your children suffer, which did happen to me to some
extent. Or you can work full time and try to carve out a more
leisurely pace that allows you to be less burnt-out with your
children. I'm not sure either option is ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lip service paid to the need for more
family-friendly work arrangements, habits long ingrained in
corporate life make it hard for most professionals to work reduced
hours, even though surveys show that the vast majority wants to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that those who succeed at this kind of part-time
arrangement, usually professional women, do so against substantial
odds. Here are some of their stories, beginning with Abel's tale in
TV land.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Katy Abel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even before she had children, Katy Abel was the type of reporter
who had no burning ambition to top the 6 o'clock news. Bright,
hard-working, and blessed with the kind of sculpted looks and big
blue eyes that are ready-made for television, Abel came to Channel
7 (WHDH-TV) from WBCN-FM (104.1) as a freelance producer 10 years
ago, to work on children's programming. In 1991, she was promoted
to education reporter, and three years later began covering
parenting issues. Channel 7 offered Abel a three-year full-time
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, Abel and her husband, a benefits consultant, who
works with unions, were raising two young sons _ and Abel didn't
want to work more. ``I said no. I liked things the way they were,''
Abel recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Although working reduced hours was unusual in the frenetic world
of television news, she made the arrangement work by filing stories
in advance, coming in after her children's bedtime to edit them,
and choosing to remain a relatively low-paid talent in a field
where the big money goes to those with contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people I worked with were very accommodating. They
were willing to roll with the punches of my family life,'' Abel
says. ``There were times when I would get a call at 1:30 p.m. from
my son's school: `Sam is in the nurse's office with a fever. Can
you come get him?' ''
</P>
<P>
   If Abel's husband couldn't get away from his work, it was up to
her to tell the producers of the 5:30 news that her story had just
evaporated. ``They would either rearrange the show or they would
look at me desperately and say, `Is there anything you can do
quickly?' ''
</P>
<P>
   And Abel would try to pull a rabbit out of a hat, as it were.
``The parenting issues I covered were often seen as the Fluff of
the sandwich. There were the murders, the accidents . . . and then
what Katy is going to do today.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times, Abel admits, when she felt as if she were
``throwing garbage on the air because I didn't have time to do
great work.'' But that was the trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last fall, things changed. An incoming news director,
recognizing the value of stories aimed at viewers struggling to
balance child-rearing and dual careers, pressed Abel to do more on
her beat, on a tighter schedule. ``At first blush, I was very
excited about this,'' she says. ``But the demands on my time
increased and got to the point where I no longer had control over
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Abel says she was coming home at night ``very tired and stressed
out,'' and her children reacted predictably: They grew ever more
needy of her attention.
</P>
<P>
   One night, when her younger son pulled her down on the floor to
do a puzzle, Abel burst into tears. ``Rubin asked, `Are you mad at
me?' That's when I realized enough was enough,'' recalls Abel,
blinking away tears.
</P>
<P>
   She asked Channel 7 for more money so she could hire a baby
sitter to pick up the children and provide after-school care so
that neither parent would need to leave work early. And when
management declined, Abel left a secure on-air job for the
uncertainty of freelance work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all happened within a week of my 40th birthday,'' Abel says
ruefully. ``But I don't want this to be Katy Abel bashing Channel
7; it just wasn't a good fit for me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Since December, Abel says she has been enjoying extra time with
her children and has kept busy working on a book proposal and
shooting a story for ``CBS This Morning,'' which will air at the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   But, as is common with parents who make similar choices, she
also has to worry about the financial cost of her decision. The
family lives in an unpretentious two-bedroom apartment in Boston
overlooking a parking lot, and her two sons, 8 and 4, share a room
with bunk beds.
</P>
<P>
   Her freelance status means that she and her husband have to
defer their dream of buying a house with a yard. ``Putting things
on hold is hard,'' she says, gently removing Rubin's arms from
around her neck. ``But I'm happier and we're happier as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lise Johnson
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is a beautiful June morning, and Dr. Lise Johnson has the day
off, as she does every Thursday, to spend time with her three young
children. But Johnson, 37, a pediatrician in a group practice at
Newton-Wellesley Hospital, doesn't look particularly grateful.
Kjartan, 5, is drawing pictures on the kitchen table, Abraham,
almost 3, is running around without pants, and Lilly, the
1-year-old, is crying in Johnson's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crisis central,'' says Johnson wearily. ``We have two
sick kids, one with strep throat and another with an ear infection.
I was just about to take this one's temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson works 3 1/2 days a week and has a supportive husband.
She says she is pleased with the balance she struck between career
and family demands. But she remains acutely aware of the
trade-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Educated at Harvard Medical School and trained at Massachusetts
General Hospital, she could have had a flourishing career in
academic medicine. But she chose to work reduced hours after she
had her first child, five years ago. And like many doctors who try
to lead a balanced life, she dropped right off the academic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss teaching, but I don't think about it anymore,'' says
Johnson, as Lilly nestles in her lap drinking from her juice cup.
``I kind of have this attitude _ there's a time for everything, and
right now I want to spend time with my children while they're
young.''
</P>
<P>
   What bothers Johnson more than a lost opportunity to groom the
next generation of medical students is the high-wire act she
performs as a part-time doctor, between meeting the needs of her
patients and reserving time for her children, her husband, and
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a certain amount of guilt in not always being the
person who sees my patients,'' Johnson says. ``If there is an
acutely ill child I'm seeing one day, it's difficult to know you're
not going to be there the next day to follow up on him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the days when she is home, there are the inevitable phone
calls about work. ``My office tries not to bother me, but there are
times when I feel compelled to check on a patient,'' Johnson says.
``I had a kid who was having severe headaches'' and needed an MRI
to look for a possible brain tumor, and ``I wasn't going to be
there that day. I felt it was important to track down the results
of the MRI and communicate them to the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I had to make at least four or five calls (the MRI proved
negative), and I was needing to do that in the middle of being at
home with a toddler and an infant. At times like that you feel
really torn and resentful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Johnson is luckier than most, in that her colleagues
and her patients understand and support her arrangement. ``I find
that my patients really value my role as mother, and they want me
to be able to have that role,'' says Johnson, as Lilly finally
falls asleep in her lap. ``To be a mother as a primary care
pediatrician is actually thought of as an asset.''
</P>
<P>
   (at)5John Day
</P>
<P>
   (at)7 The same, unfortunately, is not true of most other
professions, or even most other medical disciplines, according to
studies by Barnett and others. While a smattering of companies,
particularly high-tech ones, accommodate employees who work part
time, a 1997 survey of 2,000 professionals found that supervisors
and colleagues do not typically take part-time employees as
seriously as full-time ones.
</P>
<P>
   And that is true for professionals who work less than their
peers but more than what many people would think of as part time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think you're a dilettante,'' says Dr. John Day, a
pulmonary critical care specialist who job-shares with his wife,
also a pulmonary specialist, in a private practice in Worcester.
Together they work 80 hours a week. ``Of course that's not
something people will ever tell you to your face.''
</P>
<P>
   But Day has seen the incredulous looks on other physicians'
faces when he tells them that he is leaving early to pick up his
children (he has three, ages 14, 12, and 5) and that his wife will
be seeing the patient for a consult. Their practice has felt the
pinch of not getting referrals from physicians who can't get used
to the idea that the same specialist won't be seeing their patient
every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have dreams of being penniless and standing naked in the
street,'' says Day, half-jokingly. ``But on the other hand, I know
my children very well. I have not missed a single ballet
performance of my daughter's and I have not missed more than one or
two of my son's soccer games.''
</P>
<P>
   Day adds, ``You don't get a lot of `attaboys' doing this. But
that's OK. It's the way I want to lead my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
