A0906 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TALIBAN-SANCTIONS-HNS     07-06 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALIBAN-SANCTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON IMPOSES SANCTIONS ON AFGHANISTAN'S TALIBAN FOR SUPPORTING
BIN LADEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN C. HENRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has imposed economic sanctions
against the Taliban, Afghanistan's Islamic fundamentalist rulers,
for allegedly supporting Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile accused
of being the mastermind of the 1998 bombing of two U.S. embassies
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The move to block Taliban assets in the United States and to
halt trade with Afghanistan is designed to ``deepen the
international isolation of the Taliban'' and end its protection of
bin Laden, the president said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions were announced amid reports of direct Taliban
support for bin Laden and Saudi Arabian efforts to disrupt a
network of Saudi and Persian Gulf businessmen who have funneled an
estimated $50 million to bin Laden and his associates.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, who has been exiled by the Saudi government and
renounced by his family, is accused of plotting the Aug. 7, 1998,
bombings of U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. More than 200
people _ including 12 Americans _ died in the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who nurture terrorism must understand that we will not
stand by while those whom they protect target Americans,'' Clinton
said, noting that the sanctions will not block aid for health and
education programs or for projects related to the clearing of
anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Hakim Mujahid, a senior member of the Taliban faction,
dismissed claims that leaders of the religious militia were
allowing part of Afghanistan to be used as a terrorist base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any clear evidence provided to us that Osama bin
Laden is using Afghanistan's soil against any other country, we
will do action upon that,'' Mujahid told reporters as he arrived in
Washington from New York for a meeting at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials acknowledge that the sanctions will have little
economic impact on Afghanistan, 85 percent of which the Taliban
controls. In 1998, trade between the two countries totaled $24
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the concrete impact, this sends an unambiguous
message of the commitment of the United States to take action
against those who shelter international terrorists like bin
Laden,'' said James Foley, spokesman for the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sanctions will ensure that U.S. trade with
Taliban-controlled areas dries up until the Taliban takes steps to
halt bin Laden's activities,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's move against the Taliban was formally outlined
in an executive order issued on Monday, a day after published
reports that bin Laden in October paid Taliban authorities for a
farm near Jalalabad, a mountain city near the Afghanistan-Pakistan
border.
</P>
<P>
   An Afghan journalist reported to the London Observer that he
recently got past bin Laden's security network and found that he
has converted the farm, a former Soviet collective, into a key base
of operations. The farm is a short distance from another bin Laden
facility, a former military base used by the mujahedeen during
their resistance to Russian occupation in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Citing numerous sources, including military and intelligence
operatives, the Observer reported that the Taliban has deployed
fighters to help protect bin Laden in the wake of three
assassination attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the Taliban regime has claimed no knowledge of
bin Laden's whereabouts. U.S. officials _ who put bin Laden on the
FBI's ``10 Most Wanted'' list one month ago and offered a $5
million reward for his capture _ remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without getting into the specifics of our intelligence
capabilities, we believe the Taliban has at least acquiesced with
the presence of Osama bin Laden and his associates in Afghanistan
and has not taken action to expel him or, preferably, to turn him
over to U.S. authorities,'' said Mike Hammer, spokesman for the
White House National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, the State Department ordered six embassies in
Africa to close, saying that ``suspicious individuals'' had the
facilities under surveillance. Five of the embassies have reopened,
but the mission in Madagascar remains closed.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has been implicated in several other attacks. Clinton
administration officials say he played a role in the 1993 bombing
of New York's World Trade Center and the 1996 attack on a U.S.
military installation in Saudi Arabia. Swiss police claim bin Laden
financed the massacre at Luxor, Egypt, which killed 58 tourists in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, bin Laden and his network continue to plan new
attacks against Americans, without regard for the innocence of
their intended victims or for those non-Americans who might get in
the way of his attack,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing unnamed sources, the Associated Press reported Tuesday
that bin Laden's campaign against the United States was being
fueled by Saudi and Persian Gulf businessmen before Saudi
authorities uncovered the donations and stopped the transfers.
</P>
<P>
   The money, mostly from devoted Muslims, may have totaled $50
million, the AP reported. The donations began shortly after the
United States put a $5 million price on bin Laden's head early this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, the son of an oil tycoon, reportedly is suffering
from cash-flow problems in the wake of an international effort by
the Clinton administration to freeze his assets abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
