<HEADER>
A0914 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-REMAKES-1000(2T     07-06 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-REMAKES-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BATCH OF SUMMER FILMS HAS A SURPLUS OF REMAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer, scanning the movie listings is like thumbing
through an issue of TV Guide. Or rather, like an evening of Nick at
Nite without the shiny, happy irony. And that depressing funk of
dressing up the same old thing in new costumes is slowly settling
in.
</P>
<P>
   The feature film ``Wild Wild West,'' with the tantalizing
exception of making a black man _ Will Smith _ an empowered figure
in post-Civil War America, plays just like an episode of the old TV
show, but with a lot more money. ``Inspector Gadget,'' set to open
in a few weeks, looks halfhearted, as if once mired in making the
film, those responsible realized it wasn't a very good idea after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the point of a remake is to bring back the old
audience while finding a new one, probably those who've only heard
their parents reminisce fondly about the original. Let's conjure a
worst-of-all-possible-worlds scenario: a film version of ``The Many
Loves of Dobie Gillis,'' with Ryan Phillippe as Dobie and Vince
Vaughn as Maynard G. Krebs, directed by original ``Dobie'' cast
member Warren Beatty. (Be afraid, as the ad campaign for one remake
went, be very afraid. There actually is a ``My Three Sons'' feature
film coming, and it stars Oscar winner Michael Douglas.)
</P>
<P>
   And it's true that the summer is generally the time that the
market is flooded with tried-and-true remake stuff. What better
time to pick up the lucrative 12-to-19-year-old market prowling the
malls in lieu of school, as well as their parents, who are now the
formerly-most-highly-sought-after movie audience, the baby boomers?
</P>
<P>
   Remakes of TV shows, comic books or cocktail napkins are a way
to combine these two revenue streams. When it works, as it did with
``Batman'' a few summers back and is now with ``Phantom Menace''
(basically a ``Star Wars'' remake), the profit margin is doubled.
</P>
<P>
   This season works for this kind of film partly because it has
become the period when moviegoing peaks. And summer's also looked
upon as a time when expectations are lowered, or rather, when the
studios hope that expectations are lowered and do their best to
make sure that those lower expectations are met.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, when there's a time way too many movies based on old
TV shows are on the screen _ like ``Car 54, Where Are You?,'' ``The
Brady Bunch,'' ``The Flintstones,'' ``George of the Jungle'' _
there's a stale air of decomposition that can't be hidden, no
matter the number of trailers attempting to generate that new movie
smell.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: last summer's ``The Avengers.'' But because we
can only assume that the cast and director are erasing that movie
from each copy of their resumes by hand, there's no point in
holding that against them. Besides, that TV show-into-movies branch
of movie making _ the Lunchbox School of Film _ never really goes
away, as evidenced by ``Lost in Space'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the remakes sweepstakes also included ``Godzilla''
and ``The Mask of Zorro,'' maybe the first time one studio _
Columbia _ was shoving two such pictures at the same time. But this
year, the genre has returned in a big way, heralded by the movie
version of ``The Mod Squad'' this spring, a movie whose sole
purpose was apparently to restore luster to Levi's sagging hipness
by giving it a fashion show. And appropriately, that was the only
front on which it was a success.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion front is not rational enough for a movie based on
``The Wild, Wild West'' that stars Will Smith, Kevin Kline and,
most ridiculously yet successfully, Kenneth Branagh as Dr.
Loveless. For those who fear that the big-screen adventures of
James West and Artemus Gordon are entirely too close to a
Merchant/Ivory art film, there are also features based on the
animated heroes ``Inspector Gadget'' and ``Dudley Do-Right,'' the
latter being, of course, the latest realization of Brendan Fraser's
ambition to star in a film derived from every square-jawed lunkhead
cartoon character created by Jay Ward.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to constituting a career, as they apparently are
doing for Fraser, remakes can also be used to save a career. Eddie
Murphy used a pair of them _ ``The Nutty Professor,'' which
included a triumphal return performance, the best in his career,
and ``Dr. Doolittle'' _ to reclaim his star status.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, remakes aren't retooled the way ``Professor'' and
``Doolittle'' were retrofitted for Murphy. Rather, they're employed
as a way to avoid working up a plot and as a method to grab onto an
audience's attention through sheer name recognition, like with
``Mission: Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Such movies are about nothing, except marketing. ``The
Untouchables'' was a rare situation in which only a title and a
real-life catalyst, Eliot Ness, were used. Screenwriter David Mamet
used those elements as a taking-off point to deal with the biblical
theme of Good and Evil in the new world of 1920s Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, to paraphrase what Clint Eastwood said in ``In
the Line of Fire'' a few summers ago, that's not gonna happen this
year. These audience-ready titles are merely being used to pacify
an audience into laying out money at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   In the paint-by-numbers remakes, in which not a single move is
made to scare off a potential audience, a certain kind of actor is
required; it's a test of movie-star charisma. Fraser's good humor,
for instance, serves him well in these cartoonish movies. Smith,
too, has the boundless I'm-down-for-whatever cheerfulness that
makes him impervious to the special-effects nonsense going on
around him.
</P>
<P>
   And Antonio Banderas was finally launched as a movie star in one
of those brain-free zones, ``Zorro,'' because he finally got a
chance to show he could make fun of himself. (It made him sexy for
the first time, because he was so unself-conscious.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's sad to see poor Matthew Broderick, who
looks slightly embarrassed in them. In ``Godzilla,'' he seemed to
be trying to sneak out of the frame. He's playing Inspector Gadget,
and his sneaky, calm performances are out of place in these
big-budget noisefests. Watching him, you're not even sure Broderick
would admit to having heard of the originals in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best kind of actor for the retread movie is a
literal puppet or cartoon figure, which is why ``Muppets From
Space'' makes sense. As does ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP;
Uncut.'' And in a rare show of courage for a movie using popularity
gleaned from another venue to get it to theaters, ``South Park'' is
teeing off on the very idea of safeness _ ``Uncut'' attacks the
concept of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Remakes aren't about bravery, though; the closest thing to it is
when filmmakers choose a title or concept that's not particularly
well-known in the first place. That's a special sub-basement in the
remake genre, the movie based on a cult comic almost no one but the
creators have heard of. (Past versions of this include ``Howard the
Duck,'' ``Men in Black, Blade'' and ``Teenage Mutant Ninja
Turtles,'' which started as a self-published parody of the X-Men.)
</P>
<P>
   That category's representative this summer is ``Mystery Men,''
scheduled for late July, which revolves around the secondary
characters in a cult comic. The Mystery Men are a collection of
costumed geeks and losers from Bob Burden's ``Flaming Carrot
Comics.'' Even the Carrot, a pouting paranoiac whose mask is, yep,
a big, flaming carrot, used to ridicule them. ``Mystery Men'' is
promising because, like with ``Men in Black,'' there's nothing at
stake in terms of betraying people's concepts of the character. The
cast _ which includes Ben Stiller, Janeane Garofalo, Paul Reubens,
Hank Azaria and Kel Mitchell _ is said to have rewritten their
characters, deepening their neuroses, and ``Men's'' first-time
director was smart to enough to stay out of their way.
</P>
<P>
   Not that TV shows, cartoons and comic books are the only source
materials for attempts at finding sure-fire summer fare this year.
There are also a few remakes of old movies in store. ``The
Haunting,'' due out July 23, is a loud, big-budget rejiggering of a
small, subtle minor classic, based on the Shirley Jackson novel
``The Haunting of Hill House,'' which used the tension of being
trapped in a small, terrifying space to its advantage. It could be
presumptuous to assume that the new version will be brash and
deafening. But considering that the update is directed by Jan de
Bont _ the man responsible for ``Speed'' and ``Twister'' _ it's a
bet I'm willing to make.
</P>
<P>
   Most bewildering is Pierce Brosnan starring in the remake of
``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' due out in August. Placing the
plasticene Brosnan in ``Crown,'' in which Steve McQueen showed off
his low-key all-American cool, is like putting Whoopi Goldberg in a
``Godfather'' remake. It's definitely a rethinking. Just not one
I'm sure I want to see. But if a summer remake could give Banderas
a career in American movies, then anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7032. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
