<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-PROFANITY07-CO     07-06 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-PROFANITY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public profanity a national curse
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From ballparks to movie theaters, in cars and in
class, in sickness and in health, we curse. And lately we've been
swearing up a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Cussing made the newspapers at least three times in June: On the
same day last week that a mother's letter in ``Dear Abby''
complained about men swearing in front of her child, the
profanity-filled movie ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut''
opened. And before that a Michigan jury convicted Timothy Boomer of
violating a century-old state law against cursing in front of women
and children. Boomer, who cut loose after falling out of his canoe,
could be jailed for 90 days and ordered to pay a $100 fine.
</P>
<P>
   What the, er, heck is going on?
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, we're getting cruder.
</P>
<P>
   People have always cursed _ witness the 1897 law that Boomer
fell afoul of. What's changed is where we're doing it and how
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't live in this country without knowing how to swear.
It's like the horn in your car. It's built into us,'' says Dr.
Timothy Jay, author of ``Cursing in America'' (John Benjamins,
$14.95).
</P>
<P>
   Jay, a psychologist who has spent his career studying America's
predilection for profanity, attributes the increase in cursing to
more relaxed social rules and greater exposure to offensive
language in music, television and movies. Young children might pick
up some swear words at home, he says, but by the time they reach
school age, it's their peers who expand their off-color vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing are technology, societal mobility and dense
populations, says Dr. Stephen Steinberg, executive director of the
Penn National Commission on Society, Culture and Community at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that breeds a lot of frustration and anonymity,''
Steinberg says.
</P>
<P>
   As well as some of the most cutting-edge comedy around.
</P>
<P>
   Raw language has gotten laughs since long before Lenny Bruce
stood trial for obscenity. Comedians like Richard Pryor, Eddie
Murphy and Chris Rock have kept up that tradition by upping the
ante. On TV, in-your-face animated series like ``The Simpsons'' and
``Ren &AMP; Stimpy'' paved the way for the more intense off-color humor
of shows like ``South Park'' and ``Family Guy.'' And when ``South
Park'' made the leap to the big screen, the profanity count jumped
to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Its plot revolves around elementary schoolchildren sneaking into
an R-rated film, then trying out their new vocabulary on shocked
adults. The movie uses profanities to spearhead a satire about
freedom of speech and parental responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent screening, the heartiest laughter erupted during a
song with fewer than five nouns or verbs that would be printable in
this newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' says Mike Kretz, 39. ``It's a little over the
top, but it didn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking societal taboos to get laughs is a long-standing comedy
tradition _ think Archie Bunker's rants in ``All in the Family.''
Depending on your point of view, the ``South Park'' movie could
fall into that category _ or be a 90-minute excuse to pack in as
many four-letter words as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ```South Park' makes a joke of how crude and violent it is, the
same way `Beavis &AMP; Butt-head' does. They take speech to the next
level, to parody,'' says Dr. Joe Austin, an assistant professor of
popular culture at Bowling Green State University.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, who studies teen culture, says the way some words are
repeated in the movie is typical of how teens adapt language, add
new meanings to it and use certain terms repeatedly, with varying
meanings. A 12-letter word that most adults would find offensive
might just mean ``hello, people'' to teens, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Children and women are swearing more in public than they have in
the past, says Jay, who has conducted field studies to survey
language use. A poll of 2,000 teens bears that out: Cursing is in,
said 52 percent of those surveyed by Teenage Research Unlimited in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Chinik, a teacher at Druid Hills High School in DeKalb
County, would agree.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent screening of ``South Park,'' she said the cursing
done by the child characters in the film was fairly typical of what
she hears from high school students. She lets them know it's not
appropriate in the classroom _ but she knows it's hard for them to
avoid hearing such language almost anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were kids, we knew we weren't supposed to curse in
front of teachers,'' says Chinik, 28. ``Nowadays they let language
they use with friends run over in other areas of their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that she didn't think the R-rated movie was
funny, albeit crude.
</P>
<P>
   Her companion, 28-year-old Brian Hinsen, hears a lot of
four-letter words as a bartender. But when he first watched the TV
show ``South Park,'' he was so shocked he choked on the sandwich he
was eating.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says: ``I'm much more concerned about violence than I
am about sex and language.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
