<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-REVIE     07-06 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DARK THEME DANCES IN WITH PILOBOLUS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pilobolus Dance Theater proved as ingenious as ever
when it opened its season on Monday night at the Joyce Theater. In
the past the company has often used its acrobatic choreography in a
playful, whimsical or bizarre manner. But Pilobolus has also been
drawn to darkly dramatic subject matter, and this evening of four
works, one of them a premiere, emphasized themes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many pieces by Pilobolus are joint ventures devised by several
choreographers, and their program notes often generously credit the
members of the original casts for their collaborative assistance.
Typically, the program for ``A Selection,'' the premiere, listed
its dancers as collaborators. But the work was essentially created
by three choreographers, Robby Barnett, Michael Tracy and Jonathan
Wolken; the children's book author Arthur Yorinks, and the
writer-artist Maurice Sendak, who also designed the set and
costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sendak is celebrated for his grotesque children's
fantasies, ``A Selection'' was not child's play. The backdrop
depicted a quaint town, presumably somewhere in Central Europe. But
it was shrouded in smoke, and the characters were dressed in
clothes that could have come from the 1930s or early '40s.
</P>
<P>
   One soon suspected that this was a dance inspired by the
Holocaust, an impression strengthened by the recorded
accompaniment: emotionally intense music by Hans Krasa and Pavel
Haas, two composers interned at Theresienstadt before being shipped
to Auschwitz and death, and by Mahler, who would probably have met
the same fate if he had been alive at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Selection'' began with the sound of a train. Then five
people (Rebecca Anderson, Josie Coyoc, Matt Kent, Gaspard Louis and
Benjamin Pring) rushed onto a station platform, only to find it was
too late to catch the departing train. Their appearance suggested
they were members of an itinerant theatrical company led by Kent,
and possibly also members of a family. Another person (Otis Cook)
came onto that platform: a mysterious stranger in a black cloak.
When he removed it, he revealed that he was wearing a baggy outfit.
It could have been only a baggy outfit, but it looked a bit like a
uniform: an escaped prisoner's uniform, perhaps, or a prison
guard's uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, whose character remained enigmatic, darted busily about,
then collapsed, only to be restored to life by Kent. Far from being
grateful, he appeared to harass the actors, and he literally
stripped Kent bare. Then he did a bit of goose-stepping, but left
it unclear whether this was in earnest or in mockery.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after removing most of his own clothes, he moved
sometimes like a diabolically capering imp and sometimes as if he
were suffering. The members of the theatrical troupe separated,
some (or perhaps all) presumably going to their doom.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Selection'' was admirably ambitious and held the attention
with its unrelieved eeriness. Yet it was ultimately more mystifying
than horrifying.
</P>
<P>
   The characterizations, in particular that of Cook, remained
vague. One was never sure what people's motivations were. Perhaps
the work's creators sought to make ``A Selection'' rich in
ambiguity. Instead, it occasionally seemed dramatically confused.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, Tracy and Wolken also choreographed ``Apoplexy,'' to a
percussive score by Paul Sullivan that made the dancers constantly
fall down, rise up and fall again, as if attacked by bursts of
sonic bullets. The opening images were visually stronger than the
concluding ones. Yet the piece as a whole was startling.
</P>
<P>
   That could also be said of Alison Chase's ``Solo,'' to guitar
music composed and played by David Mills. This commentary on
confinement found Ms. Coyoc trapped behind what looked like a paper
wall. After trying to tear it with her hands, she summoned the
strength to burst through it with her entire body.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chase's ``Orangotango'' brought a bit of humor to the
evening as Kent put on an ape's mask, only to feel embarrassed to
have done so.
</P>
<P>
   He attempted to hide his face behind a pulled-down sombrero when
he encountered Ms. Anderson. But she discovered what he really
looked like and decided she quite enjoyed dancing with this big ape
to tangos by Astor Piazzolla.
</P>
<P>
   The company's season continues through July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
