<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0920 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-BOS &LR;      07-06 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK TAKES OVER WITH PLEDGE TO END STRIFE WITH ARABS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Ehud Barak took office as prime minister Tuesday,
promising that he was committed to making peace with Israel's Arab
neighbors and intent on ending religious and social strife at home.
</P>
<P>
   In a marked change from the often fiery speeches heard during
the three-year tenure of Benjamin Netanyahu, the new leader used
words of reconciliation and respect as he laid out his vision for
solving Israel's most pressing problems. To all sides, that vision
seems clear: surrendering Israeli-held land for peace, both in the
West Bank and in the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   But even before Barak took the oath of office, members of his
own coalition government criticized him, raising questions as to
how long his unwieldy alliance of religious, secular, nationalist
and leftist parties could hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this day will be recorded in the annals of history as a
turning point in the direction of reconciliation, unity and
peace,'' Barak said in a speech in parliament before presenting his
coalition government for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's speech was as wide-ranging as the problems Israel faces.
From renewing long-stalled negotiations with Syria to signing a
final peace accord with the Palestinians, Barak insisted he was
ready to end decades of hatred and bloodshed between the Jewish
state and the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call all the Arab leaders to stretch their hands to our
outstretched hand and bring a peace of the brave,'' said Barak,
using the very phrase often invoked by Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our historical duty to strengthen the state of Israel by
putting an end to the Arab-Israeli conflict,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while he called on Syrian President Hafez Assad to put aside
memories of war and work for peace, he had a softer, more personal
message for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The general-turned-statesman, who once dressed in a woman's wig
and clothing to infiltrate Lebanon and help assassinate a
Palestinian guerrilla leader, said he would work ``hand in hand''
with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know not only the suffering of my nation, but also the
suffering of the Palestinian nation,'' said the 57-year-old former
military chief of staff, the country's most decorated soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's coalition government collapsed last year largely on
the issue of the Wye peace accord, which Netanyahu signed
reluctantly and then suspended after making the first of three
agreed-upon withdrawals from occupied West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my will and aspiration to work hand-in-hand with the
elected Palestinian leadership and Yasser Arafat in the spirit of
partnership and honor,'' said Barak, who entered politics during
the tenure of Yitzhak Rabin, assassinated in 1995 by a religious
Jew opposed to the peace accords with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also assured the citizens of Israel, who gave him a
resounding 56 percent of the vote in the May elections, that he
would treat domestic problems with same fervor with which he would
pursue peace.
</P>
<P>
   Under Netanyahu's Likud-led government, social strife increased,
especially between secular and ultra-Orthodox Jews who fought over
state money, the issue of drafting ultra-religious Jewish men and
the the nature of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's campaign stressed his desire to be the prime minister of
everybody and his speech touched on the need to boost employment
opportunities, make education a priority and ensure equality among
the country's 6 million citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is a better or worse person but there are those who are
weak and we have to help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even before 120-seat parliament had approved Barak's
75-member coalition government, Palestinian officials and Israeli
commentators were already warning of possible gaps between words
and deeds.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Barak's broad coalition government of seven
parties could prove too broad. There are two ultra-Orthodox parties
who in the past have clashed with former Soviet dissident Natan
Sharansky's party over how to treat Russian immigrants of
questionable Jewish heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Another coalition partner, the National Religious Party, gets
its support from those Jewish settlers that the Meretz party would
like to see uprooted from the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   And just under half the members of the coalition served in
Netanyahu's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements do reflect Barak's policies and approach, but
it's going to be difficult for him given the nature of Israeli
politics,'' said political analyst Gerald Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's newly appointed health minister, ultra-Orthodox Shas
party member Shlomo Benizri, immediately announced the government
was unlikely to last more than three years because of the
composition of the coalition. The government's elected period is
four years.
</P>
<P>
   A member of Sharansky's Yisrael B'Aliyah party went one step
further. He voted against the coalition government when it was
presented to the parliament, saying he opposed a coalition with
ultra-Orthodox parties.
</P>
<P>
   One Arab member of parliament, already in the opposition, went
to the podium to point out that Barak said he wanted to be the
prime minister of everyone but he did not ask any of the three Arab
parties to join the coalition. Arabs makes up nearly 20 percent of
Israel's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I foresee serious crises on diplomatic issues and on issues of
religion and state,'' Labor party member David Libai, who led
coalition negotiations for Barak, told the Ha'aretz daily
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as befits their status as the group that lost the most
hope during Netanyahu's term in office, Palestinians reacted with a
great deal of caution to Barak's sweeping statements on the
importance of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words are not bad _ now I think it's necessary to start
implementation,'' said Hassan Asfour, a Palestinian negotiator who
helped draw up the Oslo peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Barak will learn from the fate of Netanyahu and realize
it is better to be a man who makes history than a man who is
history, like Netanyahu,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
