<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOCKHART-STAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOCKHART'S OFF-BROADWAY TURN IS FAR CRY FROM HER SHORT-SKIRTED TV
PERSONA
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by STAGE-OTHER ACTORS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first of three one-acts that make up ``bash,''
currently running off-Broadway, Calista Flockhart's character tries
to remember a classical Greek word she once learned: ``adakia.'' It
doesn't have a literal translation but has something to do with the
fact that humans aren't able to set our off-balance world straight
``on account we're mortal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the word is only mentioned in the opening play, it's
the underlying theme throughout filmmaker Neil LaBute's ``bash,''
(subtitled ``latter-day plays'' because of the author's Mormon
influence in his upbringing). And it seems even more appropriate
when uttered by Flockhart, who, thanks to ``Ally McBeal,'' has
become a celebrity whom people either adore or loathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mortal,'' indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The production also stars Paul Rudd (''Clueless,'' ``The Object
of My Affection'') and Ron Eldard (whose credits list his extensive
stage work and his one season on ``ER,'' but not the widely
lampooned series ``Men Behaving Badly''), but what's going to keep
this show selling tickets is Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   People are curious to see if she can de-''Ally'' herself.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting notice for her short skirts on David E. Kelley's
hit courtroom dramedy, she was an award-winning stage actress
(Broadway's ``The Three Sisters,'' ``The Glass Menagerie'') who
eventually made her way into film (''Telling Lies in America, The
Birdcage'').
</P>
<P>
   But then came ``Ally,'' the dancing baby and the Al Green
daydreams. Subsequently, Flockhart seemed to always carry around
this alter-ego. Even in interviews, such as on ``The Late Show With
David Letterman,'' she pulled and twisted her stringy hair and
protruded her pouty lips. As Helena in the recent ``William
Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' the billing might as
well have read ``Ally McBeal,'' what with the way she stomped about
as if she were having an argument with ``Ally's'' Billy.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities are a huge draw on Broadway, although it's usually
movie stars (see recent entries Nicole Kidman, Kevin Spacey).
Television stars have had less success. George Wendt did well with
``Art,'' but Helen Hunt received less-than-glowing reviews for
``Twelfth Night'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Kelley likes to pull his actors from the
stage. In addition to Flockhart, ``Ally's'' Greg Germann was a New
York stage regular, as was ``The Practice's'' Lisa Gay Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times interview, LaBute said that he chose
Flockhart because ``she comes in with a great deal of good will. A
lot of people put a certain kind of trust in her. I want to see how
that works when you lead them into a place they may not want to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   The play ``bash'' is what one might expect from LaBute, a
playwright whose first two films, ``In the Company of Men'' and
``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' showcased his knack for creating
unapologetically cruel characters.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Medea Redux,'' Flockhart offers a solid performance in
recounting, underneath an interrogation lamp and into a police
recorder, how she fell in love with a teacher at age 13. He
eventually lost interest and disappeared. When she finds him years
later, she shows him how she feels by murdering their son.
</P>
<P>
   With a Midwestern accent, Flockhart successfully transforms into
this character and never once channels the spirit of Ally.
</P>
<P>
   The meatiest portion of the play, in terms of script and
performance, is ``Iphegenia in Orem,'' in which Eldard plays a
businessman who finds that he might be fired and has to explain how
his newborn died. This section is most LaBute, as this nasty deed
is a result of a practical joking co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   The final segment, ``A Gaggle of Saints,'' stars Flockhart and
Rudd as a lovey couple on a magical night out that turns sour.
Rudd's character, an all-American type, sees two men making out in
Central Park, and he and his buddies eventually bash one of them.
As he retells the story, it's very reminiscent of the sauna scene
with Jason Patric and Aaron Eckhart in ``Your Friends and
Neighbors'' in which Patric's character remembers the time he and
some jock friends raped an effeminate boy in high school.
</P>
<P>
   As the girlfriend, Flockhart again gives a fine performance even
though the role is not nearly as juicy as in ``Medea Redux.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``bash'' proves that you can take the Ally out of the
Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``bash''
</P>
<P>
   Through July 24: Performances are 8 p.m. Mondays through
Saturdays with 2:30 matinees Wednesdays and Saturdays at the
Douglas Fairbanks Theater, 432 W. 42 St. (between Ninth and 10th
avenues), New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $45
</P>
<P>
   Information: Telecharge at (212) 239-6200.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
