<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLINER-ENSEMBLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARTURO UI' MARKS FINALE FOR BERLIN THEATRICAL COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Martin Wuttke got a bellyful of Adolf Hitler, as
did most young people growing up in West Germany in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``In school, we heard these stories about Hitler every day,''
says the slightly built, soft-spoken actor. ``So, we knew
everything about the Nazi time, we knew everything about the
Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partly why the first time Wuttke read Bertolt Brecht's
play ``The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui'' _ a thinly disguised
parable about the making of a fascist _ he found it ``too simple.''
As a boy, Wuttke also got a bellyful of Brecht's other plays, which
he found to be ``mostly boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Which gives you an idea of the circuitous route Wuttke has
traveled to star in the renowned Berliner Ensemble's production of
``Arturo Ui.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded half a century ago by Brecht and his wife, Helene
Weigel, the legendary Berlin theater company is making its U.S.
debut in Berkeley and Los Angeles this summer, prior to disbanding
and reconstituting itself under new artistic director Claus
Peymann. The company will retain its historic name when it reopens
in Berlin in December, but will switch its focus toward more
contemporary work.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a run of just four performances tonight at UCLA's Freud
Playhouse, ``Arturo Ui'' will be performed in German, with
projected English supertitles.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Chicago in the 1920s, the play uses the allegory of Al
Capone's mobster rule to demonstrate the thuggish mentality and
criminal deportment of National Socialism. Wuttke, the Berliner
Ensemble's artistic director from 1995 to 1996 and now a guest
artist, has won praise throughout Europe and in Latin America for
his performance as the brutish title character.
</P>
<P>
   Wuttke says he began to change his mind about Brecht when he
read the author's early plays such as ``Drums in the Night'' (1922)
and ``In the Cities' Jungle'' (1923). In contrast to later, more
broadly humanistic epics like ``Mother Courage'' and ``The Life of
Galileo,'' these early works embodied a more ``anarchic'' spirit.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Arturo Ui,'' Wuttke says, ``of course, it's not a play
about the whole Nazi time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a play about the phenomenon (of) how a little man
like Arturo Ui becomes a powerful person in a capitalistic world,
supported by the industry, supported by the bourgeoisie. And by
doing the work on `Arturo Ui,' it became more and more fascinating,
first of all because it's very well-written; it's a wonderful,
German writer, very direct. It's very clever. And so it's become
more and more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Los Angeles is an ironic venue for Brecht's old
company. After fleeing the Nazis near the start of World War II,
Brecht (1898-1956) came to the United States and lived in Santa
Monica from 1941 to 1947. The socialist playwright quickly grew to
loathe U.S. culture. During his L.A. sojourn, he wrote screenplay
treatments with caustic titles like ``Boy Meets Girl, So What.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally considered the single greatest influence on Western
drama in the century's second half, Brecht had only one produced
Hollywood screenplay, ``Hangmen Also Die'' for director Fritz Lang.
Although Brecht's contributions were largely excised from the final
product, the House Un-American Activities Committee, then busy
sniffing out Hollywood Communists, called Brecht in to testify in
1947.
</P>
<P>
   The next day Brecht flew to Switzerland. Two years later, after
settling in the new East German state, he founded the company that
would further his legacy, both as playwright and as developer of
theatrical techniques designed to expose the artifices of theater
and acting.
</P>
<P>
   Brecht wrote ``Arturo Ui'' while in exile in Finland in 1941, en
route to the United States, hoping to score a Broadway hit.
Instead, the play wasn't produced until two years after the
author's death, in Stuttgart, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Berliner Ensemble's production, originally helmed by former
artistic director and playwright Heiner Muller (``Hamletmachine''),
who died in 1995, was praised by German critics as some of the best
work ever from a company whose artistic fortunes have wavered
throughout its history.
</P>
<P>
   Located in the former East Berlin during the Cold War period of
Communist rule, the company had become ``a museum,'' dedicated to
preserving a sanctified image of Brecht and his plays, says Stephan
Suschke, the company's current co-director. &UR;  &LR; Wuttke's own
resignation as artistic director, in 1996, was prompted by his
mounting frustration in dealing with Brecht's daughter, Barbara
Brecht-Schall, who controls the rights to her father's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Brecht's heirs) want to see the plays made as Brecht
made the plays,'' Wuttke says. ``And I think it would be very, very
important to take the Brecht plays as material, and to show that
these plays are not only classics, (but) that this is contemporary
theater.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
