<HEADLINE>
STARS' SUMMER JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies FLOCKHARD-STAGE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television stars need something to keep them busy during the
doldrums of summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek's'' Michelle Williams just ended a run in
off-Broadway's ``Killer Joe,'' and ``The Practice's'' Lisa Gay
Hamilton was playing the title role in ``Angelique,'' about a slave
in 18th-century Canada who burns down her owners' homes, until she
pulled out to take a role in a television movie. (The play is a bit
of a jumble, but there are some nice visual metaphors, and Hamilton
was superb.) Her understudy has taken the role. ``Angelique'' runs
through July 11 at the MCC Theater in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Other TV stars tearing up the stage this summer include:
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Knight: ``3rd Rock From the Sun's'' human cop has joined
the cast of Broadway's hit show ``Art,'' along with Buck Henry and
George Segal. Since its premiere, the play has featured several TV
stars, including George Wendt. Through Aug. 15 at the Royale
Theater in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wolf: The ``Party of Five'' pretty boy took over for
Christian Slater in Warren Leight's Tony-winning ``Side Man.'' Wolf
stars through July 17 at New York's Golden Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   David Schwimmer: The ``Friend'' who became interesting again
this season stars in ``Glimmer Brothers,'' written by Warren
Leight, at Massachusetts' Williamtown Theatre Festival, July 14-25.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Danza: He's had more than his share of sitcoms, but
probably did his best work to date guest-starring in ``The
Practice'' this season. He has also been getting warm reviews for
his role in Broadway's ``The Iceman Cometh'' at the Brooks Atkinson
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brochtrup: Who? He plays John, the clerk on ``NYPD Blue.
This summer, he takes on David Marshall Grant's hit off-Broadway
gay play ``Snakebit'' at the Century Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Polly Draper: She's a stage vet, but is best known for playing
Ellen in the yuppie drama ``thirtysomething.'' She recently
replaced Natasha Richardson in Patrick Marber's sex drama
``Closer'' at the Music Box Theatre in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Lowry
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
