<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-GREENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GERMANY, OLDER GREENS BEING CHALLENGED BY `YOUNG TURKS'  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ It isn't easy being a Green, especially one
accused of being over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the challenge facing many older members of the German
Green Party. In the 1960s and '70s, they were rebels and
nonconformists. They protested against nuclear weapons, were
arrested and rarely wore ties.
</P>
<P>
   But nine months after the Greens became partners for the first
time in a governing coalition, with the Social Democrats, younger
pragmatists in the party are heaping scorn on their elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough with stories from 1968!'' declared a manifesto signed
by 40 of the self-described ``youth of the second generation.''
``We cannot and will not idly watch the moralizing know-it-alls in
our party from the founding generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent Greens have gone further, demanding the
resignation of a top leader, Juergen Trittin, who is also
environment minister. Trittin, 55, leads the party's left wing and
has unsuccessfully campaigned for much steeper gasoline taxes and a
rapid closing of nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   He is in many respects the opposite of the Greens' other top
leader, Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, a popular pragmatist who
passionately supported NATO in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Like the children of many aging baby boomers, the younger Greens
are accusing left-wing traditionalists like Trittin of being
self-righteous, out of touch, and ineffective. In many respects,
the ``second generation'' is rebelling at the Greens' own
anti-establishment roots. Its members favor pragmatism, look down
on protest politics, and sometimes sound as pro-business as Young
Republicans in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough with the rituals of an alternative movement,'' they
said in the manifesto. ``Yes, you waged an energetic if
unsuccessful campaign against big money. Yes, you treated
businesses' share of the wealth as an evil. That was wrong then,
and it is wrong today.''
</P>
<P>
   The party has been notoriously chaotic for years, in part
because its open structure is difficult to control and in part
because it has always attracted a motley array of freethinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Though its roots were in the environmental and pacifist
movements, it has attracted many young business professionals who
favor free markets and less regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But the divisions are becoming harder to reconcile. The party
came perilously close to collapse at a meeting in May, when
old-line pacifists loudly accused Fischer of being a warmonger, and
one member hit him on the ear with a balloon filled with red paint.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tide has turned, with party pragmatists and freer-market
advocates arguing that the party needs to overhaul its style and
its ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not an opposition party any more, and we have to accept
that,'' said Cem Ozdemir, a Parliament member from
Baden-Wuerttemberg.
</P>
<P>
   Ozdemir, 33, who signed the manifesto, said that the Greens were
in danger of losing young voters. Thanks to its unorthodox image _
harking back to the days when Fischer took his first oath of office
in tennis shoes or to campaign posters that featured green condoms
with smiley faces _ the Greens have usually captured most of the
votes from first-time voters.
</P>
<P>
   But youth support has slipped considerably. In state elections
in February in Hesse, the right-of-center Christian Democrats
received the most first-time votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greens have to get rid of the image that they are against
everything that is fun,'' Ozdemir said, alluding to support for
high gasoline taxes and speed limits on the Autobahn.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the rebels are from the younger generation. Fischer is
51, but has long embodied a pragmatism and an appreciation for
stimulating business.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, one of Trittin's most vehement critics is Oswald
Metzger, the party's top expert on budget policy, who is 54.
Metzger shocked party members late last month by demanding
Trittin's resignation. ``Trittin is for many people a typical
left-wing Green,'' he said in an interview, adding that the Greens
would immediately gain 1 or 2 percentage points in the next
election if Trittin departed.
</P>
<P>
   Like the younger Greens, Metzger preaches passionately about the
need for lower taxes and less intrusive government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe competitive markets are generally better at
regulating than the government,'' he said. ``I am not in favor of
as radical a market culture as the United States. But I do see the
need for less regulation, more competition and for greater
self-responsibility in health and social needs.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how the battle will play out. In response to
the manifesto signed by the 40 self-described young turks, another
group of 40 Greens, who also claim to represent the younger
generation, issued a declaration from the left. Its title, a
reference to the vaguely pro-business ``center'' espoused by
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, was ``Get Out of the New Middle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
