u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-HNS &LR;      07-06 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
IN ISRAEL, BARAK TAKES OATH OF OFFICE AND MAKES PLEA FOR MIDEAST
PEACE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DEBORAH HORAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak used his swearing-in
speech Tuesday to put peacemaking at the top of the nation's
agenda, inviting Arab leaders to help forge a ``a peace of the
brave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is more important in my view than that supreme mission
_ putting an end to the 100-year conflict in the Middle East,''
Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on all the region's leaders to stretch out their hands
to meet our outstretched hands and forge a peace of the brave,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said his new government was determined to advance
negotiations with Syria ``as quickly as possible'' on the basis of
United Nations land-for-peace resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he planned to hold talks with Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat, Jordan's King Abdullah and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and meet President Clinton in Washington in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The overtures confirmed expectations that Barak's government_ a
hodgepodge of peaceniks, Russian immigrants, ultra-Orthodox and
pro-settlers _ would give priority to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   That process has been shaken badly by three years of hard-line
policies pursued by the outgoing prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, whom Barak defeated in elections May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning 56 percent of the vote _ considered a landslide in
Israel's fractious political arena _ Barak has repeatedly promised
to kick start negotiations with the Palestinians, to renew moribund
peace talks with the Syrians and to ``bring (Israeli) boys home''
from a strip in southern Lebanon Israel has occupied since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In a pointed overture to Syrian President Hafez Assad &UR; ,  &LR; Barak
called on the Arab leader to put war behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tough and bitter enemies on the battlefield,'' Barak
said. ``The time has come to build an open and brave peace that
will ensure the future and security of our peoples, our children
and our grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad, on a visit to Moscow, issued a joint communique with
Russian President Boris Yeltsin praising Barak's leadership as an
opportunity ``for constructive efforts toward a comprehensive and
just peace in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Palestinians, Barak vowed to come to an ``arrangement for
coexistence, freedom, prosperity and good neighborliness'' and
assured Palestinians Israel's desire for peace with them was on par
with its desire for peace with other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reaching a permanent agreement with the Palestinians and
achieving peace with Syria and Lebanon are equally vital and urgent
in my eyes,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   The words were seen as an attempt to soothe Palestinian fears
that they will be sidelined while Israel pursues peace with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The swearing-in ceremony, which took place at the Knesset,
Israel's parliament, Tuesday afternoon, signaled the official end
of the Netanyahu government and the beginning of a Barak government
that will include 17 ministers. A new Knesset speaker, Avraham
Burg, was elected by a vote of 110 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously sidelined in Barak's new government were two
fellow Labor Party members most closely associated with previous
peace deals reached with the Palestinians _ Shimon Peres and Yossi
Beilin.
</P>
<P>
   Peres, a former prime minister and advocate of peace deals with
the Palestinians, was appointed minister for regional development,
a new post seemingly created to give the veteran Laborite something
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin, a leading Israeli dove, was made justice minister, a
post far removed from the high-powered bargaining tables of the
peace negotiations. Both men had been natural candidates for the
foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Barak appointed David Levy, a member of his One Israel
alliance, as foreign minister, a choice most analysts said amounted
to putting a yes-man into the spot most likely to determine the
kind of peace Israel ultimately makes with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments and the style in which they were made were in
keeping with Barak's reputation as a gruff military man, analysts
here said.
</P>
<P>
   One commentator, Nahum Barnea of the daily Yediot Ahronot, wrote
that Barak wants to lead ``with a commando knife between his
teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Peres said later that he would stick to his new job only if he
could use the post to advance peace. ``I'll do everything to
promote the peace process,'' he said. ``That's my path and will.''
</P>
<P>
   Beilin, behind nearly every peace initiative with the
Palestinians since the first agreement in 1993, said he would
approach his new post ``with a feeling of holy awe'' and
``determination to fortify the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's government, made up of 75 members of Israel's 120-member
Knesset, is the widest in recent Israeli history. Despite the fact
that it is made up of parties with different, and even competing,
agendas, its breadth means that no one party can bring the
government down by quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Such a comfortable majority will give Barak strength to make
tough decisions in peacemaking, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But it may also make negotiations much more slow-going: Barak
must find a consensus within his own coalition before he can make a
deal with his Arab interlocutors. Finding that internal consensus
may require adopting some hard negotiating lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can expect less domestic opposition to whatever the
government agrees on,'' said Efraim Inbar, director of the BESA
Center for Strategic Studies, Bar-Ilan University. ``But they could
have to agree on less in order to get a consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Barak has kept the details of his approach to
peacemaking largely to himself.
</P>
<P>
   But he has set tough terms for a final peace deal with the
Palestinians, including insistence that Israel retain sovereignty
over all of Jerusalem and in large swaths of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech Tuesday, he professed sympathy for
Palestinians, but kept vague his recipe for peace with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know not only the suffering of my nation, but I recognize
the suffering of the Palestinian people,'' Barak said. ``It is my
desire and intention to put an end to violence and suffering and to
work with the elected Palestinian leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Syria, Barak has pledged to negotiate but stopped
short of stating how much territory on the Golan Heights he is
willing to trade for peace.
</P>
<P>
   And he has pledged to quit Lebanon without saying how.
</P>
<P>
   The BESA Center's Inbar said he expects Barak to be much less
willing to give up territory than many of his fellow Laborites, a
stand which Inbar says reflects the opinions of Israelis at the
political center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barak wants to make very minimal concessions,
particularly in the first stage,'' said Inbar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bulldozers cleared land Monday for a planned Jewish
settlement in the Jerusalem Arab neighborhood of Ras el-Amud. Since
his election, Barak has kept quiet about the project, funded by
Miami millionaire Irving Moskovitz.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Haim Ramon, the incoming minister in charge of
Jerusalem and a leading Israeli dove, suggested the new prime
minister would cancel the controversial building of high rise
apartments for Jews there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to build in Ras al Amud,'' Ramon told Israel
Radio. ``It's a mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
