<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-06 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: MITCHELL'S WARNING
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell, the former U.S. senator who was chairman of the
talks that produced the April 1998 peace accord, told graduating
students at Queens University in Belfast that it would be ``an
immense tragedy'' if the agreement failed because of a dispute on
guerrilla disarmament. Protestant politicians are resisting plans
to start the new government on July 15 unless the IRA begins
turning in weapons first.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: PARIS SHRINKING
</P>
<P>
   A census carried out in March showed 58,416,500 people living in
France, up from 56,615,000 in 1990, and another 1,665,500 in French
overseas territories, the National Statistics and Economic Studies
Institute said. Paris, with 2,115,757 within the city limits and
nearly 11 million in the metropolitan area, shrunk by 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE, MAURITANIA: MILITARY FREEZE
</P>
<P>
   French and Mauritanian authorities said military training
programs between the two countries had been suspended after
Mauritania protested a French decision to arrest a Mauritanian army
captain on human rights charges. Capt. Ely Ould Dah has been
accused of abusing detainees in Mauritania in 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TALKS AT UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   After 11 weeks of a strike by students at the National
Autonomous University of Mexico, the strikers and the
administration have started talks to end the shutdown, although the
two sides remain broadly divided. The administration, which already
conceded the students' chief demand for the university to remain
free of charge, insisted that the strike be lifted immediately. The
students do not want to start substantive talks until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: STRIKE OVER VEHICLE TAX
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of truckers blocked highways and cut back on
deliveries around much of the country to protest a new vehicle tax
intended to raise $700 million to give public school teachers a
$100 monthly raise. The cargo truck union says it will continue the
work action indefinitely until the government backs off the 1.5
percent tax on automobiles, trucks, boats, planes and motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: A RIGHTS PULLOUT
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori introduced a bill in Congress to
withdraw Peru from the jurisdiction of a human rights court
administered by the Organization of American States. The court has
condemned Peru's prosecution of accused rebels in military courts
administered by judges. The bill was quickly approved by a
committee and is expected to win the backing of the full Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: KASHMIR `UNDERSTANDING'
</P>
<P>
   The army chief, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, said the military and the
government had a ``complete understanding'' about Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif's promise to seek a withdrawal of Pakistani-backed
forces from the Indian side of Kashmir. He said the Islamic
militants would be asked to leave their bunkers, and, ``It is to be
seen what will be their reply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
