<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GHANA-POLITICS-ART-NY     07-06 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHANA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A REAL TEST OF DEMOCRACY, GHANA'S PRESIDENT MUST BECOME A
FORMER PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACCRA, Ghana _ ``Messiah,'' declared the sign on a street corner
here, above hand-painted portraits of Jesus Christ, Nelson Mandela,
Bob Marley, President Clinton (beloved here for making Ghana his
first stop on his visit to Africa last year) and this country's
longtime leader, Jerry J. Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
   If Rawlings' portrait can be found on this street corner, as
well as on other corners of this capital where street artists sell
their works, it is evidence of the enduring appeal of the man who
since 1981 has guided Ghana out of collapse and through two
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   That a framed photograph of the president cannot be found in
every small store in the country _ a common practice in many
African nations where presidents have acquired their position
through decidedly undemocratic means _ is perhaps further
indication of Rawlings' genuine popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' said Ben Smith, the artist who painted the ``Messiah''
portraits, ``he's been too long on the seat. From the head of state
down, everyone has to respect the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghana's Constitution limits the president to two terms, and
calls by even Rawlings' most fervent supporters to respect the law
suggest that a democratic culture is taking root. Many African and
Western officials see Ghana as a success story, a country that has
liberalized politically even as many of its neighbors have
stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Next year in Ghana, if all goes according to plan, something
will occur here that is rare on this continent: the president will
step down and elections will produce a successor. But many
opposition politicians and even members of Rawlings' party are
complaining that the president and his inner circle are maneuvering
to insure that he remains the dominant force in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials and foreign donors, who made Ghana a model for
free-market innovations in Africa, are nervously watching whether
their investments will pay off with a smooth transition. They will
also closely watch the election-year spending by the government,
whose largesse in the last two elections derailed Ghana's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it is a country and a government that have generally
been moving in positive ways, both in terms of the economy and
democratization,'' said an American official here. ``But we
continue to see democracy as an evolutionary process, and one
generally fair and free election doesn't make a democracy. So
that's why the 2000 elections will say a lot about democratization
in Ghana.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rawlings, a former flight lieutenant, seized power in 1981,
Ghana was suffering from economic collapse and millions of people
had left the country in search of work. But under the guidance of
institutions like the World Bank, the economy became one of the
most stable in the region. The country became the United States'
largest trading partner in sub-Saharan Africa, after South Africa
and Nigeria. Roads, electricity and drinking water reached millions
more of the 18.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Political liberalization followed. After he was elected
president in 1992, in balloting that the opposition described as
unfair, Rawlings was re-elected in 1996 in a vote that was
considered fair by his opponents and by international observers. In
the last three years, a parliament of several parties and a
vigorous press have emerged.
</P>
<P>
   But with the end of the Rawlings era in sight, his party, the
National Democratic Congress, has sent signals that have led people
to question whether the president is really ready to let go of
power.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, party members have floated ideas that appeared
calculated to test the public's willingness to accept a direct or
indirect continuation of a Rawlings rule. Amending the Constitution
to permit Rawlings' tenure to be extended was suggested, followed
by the idea that his wife, Nana Konadu Agyeman Rawlings, a powerful
political figure, would be the party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   After Rawlings eventually expressed support for his vice
president, John Evans Atta Mills, as his successor, many of the
president's critics perceived the move as a way of retaining
unofficial control. That belief deepened in December when his party
formed a consultative committee and made Rawlings ``lifelong''
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The party has played down these developments, saying, for
instance, that the committee chairmanship is strictly honorary.
Huudu Yahaya, general secretary of the National Democratic
Congress, said the president's opponents had seized on these issues
to portray the party as increasingly authoritarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he would need now is for his legacy to be
sustained,'' Yahaya said. ``Rawlings has become an international
statesman. He's made a lot of pledges outside. He would not want
his pledges to go down, because other heads of states in other
countries have asked us how this can be sustained.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president's critics are not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   After Rawlings announced his support for his vice president, a
group inside his party calling itself the Reform Movement
criticized the inner circle, saying it was autocratic and corrupt.
The group announced early this year that it was breaking away from
the National Democratic Congress, and a few weeks ago took the
legal steps to become a full-fledged party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since last year, there has been enough information suggesting
that the ruling clique is not really considering a full democratic
handover,'' said Kyeretwie Opoku, general secretary of the Reform
Movement.
</P>
<P>
   But more significant than internal party wrangling is a growing
democratic culture expressed through ordinary people or the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the idea of extending incumbency through a Constitutional
amendment was floated,'' said E. Gyimah-Boadi, a professor of
political science at the University of Ghana, ``it was shot down by
the independent media, radio talk-shows and phone-ins. That to me
gave hope that there was a political opening and, while we cannot
take it for granted that progress will continue, that it was
genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gyimah-Boadi is also executive director of the Center for
Democracy and Development, a year-old nonprofit organization that
receives funds from the Ford Foundation and is an example of the
growing presence of civil watchdog groups.
</P>
<P>
   In measuring democracy's deepening roots in Ghana, people like
Gyimah-Boadi point to the Parliament. After the disputed 1992
presidential election, opposition parties boycotted the Parliament,
which became a one-party forum for the next four years. But since
1996, members of several parties have served in the legislature,
free to criticize the executive branch and summon ministers for
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature, though, remained relatively weak. Kwadwo
Baah-Wiredu, a legislator of the New Patriotic Front, the main
opposition party, said members were not given the resources to work
effectively. He has no staff and no office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my office,'' Baah-Wiredu said, opening the trunk of
his Peugeot, which contained folders, a cellular phone and a Palm
Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Although all members can introduce bills, not one has ever done
so. Instead, the attorney general's office has introduced all
legislation since 1996. So acquiring a role in policy-making would
be the next step for Parliament, Baah-Wiredu said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his criticisms, Baah-Wiredu added, ``We are moving
forward, there is no doubt about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
