<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     07-06 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BAD SWING AT THE FANS BY GONZALEZ
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to throw a tantrum, make it a big one. Better to
throw your snit at, say, 495,817 people, the population of
Cleveland according to the latest census estimate, than to fling a
pique at one.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez got a real good mad-on at the influx of fans who
voted Ken Griffey Jr., Manny Ramirez and Kenny Lofton onto the
American League's starting outfield for the All-Star Game, while
Gonzalez, the league's reigning most valuable player _ an honor he
has won two of the last three years _ finished fifth in the
national popularity contest, behind even David Justice. Ramirez,
Lofton and Justice happen to be the regular outfielders for the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, maybe the high dudgeon Gonzalez found himself in might
have been directed at the 1,075,894 citizens of Dallas, or those of
the whole state of Texas, pop. 19,759,614. ``I respect the fans,''
Gonzalez said Sunday, ``but if they don't vote me, then I don't
want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez would surely have been picked as a reserve on the team
by the AL manager this year, Joe Torre of the Yankees, who now says
he won't select him.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to make a sap head of yourself, as Gonzalez did,
then at least do it in style. Preferred would be the statement made
by immortal Garry Templeton when he wasn't voted in as the starting
shortstop on the National League team a number of years ago. ``If I
ain't startin','' he said, ``then I ain't departin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few players in the history of the game have taken such an
attitude, but none of them have been named Ruth, Williams,
DiMaggio, Musial, Feller, Mays, Mantle, Robinson (Jackie or Frank),
Rose, Koufax, Ryan, nor Maddux, McGwire or Sosa. The list is long.
</P>
<P>
   The AL starting teams for the game to be played on Tuesday at
Fenway Park in Boston were announced on Monday, but the final
results for many positions, including the one that Gonzalez plays,
were fairly well determined, unless, of course, he called in some
Chicago aldermen at the last minute to monitor the ballot boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't happen. Actually, times change. Instead of tinkering with
a voting machine, Gonzalez might have e-mailed Bill Gates for
support, for in a crush of last-minute votes via the Internet,
Nomar Garciaparra of the Red Sox nipped the Yankees' Derek Jeter to
make the American League's opening lineup at shortstop. Jeter will
presumably not veto the voters and crawl under his couch and not
come out for the game. Perhaps he agrees with Torre, his manager,
and the AL stars' manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' Torre said about Gonzalez's pout, and he went
on to give his opinion on players being a part of the All-Star
Game, saying, ``I think it is an honor, and if not honored, they
should be obligated.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he was told by the league office that Gonzalez had
asked not to be chosen, so that he would not have to refuse. ``He
deserved to be there,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is 29 years old, old enough to understand that the
All-Star Game is a showcase for his sport. It is a chance for the
fans to see all of the best players at one time on one field.
Baseball is still making its way back from the odor left from the
1994 strike. It has come a long way, but there remains a sense of
fragility about its fan base even yet. The All-Star Game helps
perfume the air a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez understands this not at all. He doesn't understand that
his $7.25 million salary is dependent on the good will, interest
and, it follows, All-Star Game voting of the fans. Gonzalez took
the exuberance of Indians fans for their local love boats as a
personal insult.
</P>
<P>
   Where, as my mother has asked in a comparable goofball attitude,
are his brains?
</P>
<P>
   If anybody should be angry, it's Hank Greenberg. Perhaps the
greatest injustice perpetrated on a potential All-Star player was
done to Greenberg, the Tigers' first baseman, in 1935. He had 103
runs batted in at the All-Star break. Not only wasn't he chosen to
be a starter, he also wasn't chosen to be on the team, period. It's
true that Lou Gehrig and Jimmie Foxx, chosen ahead of Greenberg at
first base, were having pretty good years, as well. But in those
days, the managers of the two teams picked all the players. The
manager of the AL team that year was Mickey Cochrane. Of all
things, Cochrane was the Tigers' manager.
</P>
<P>
   While Gonzalez may indeed merit a place in the starting
outfield, it would surely not be ahead of Griffey or Ramirez. Maybe
Lofton, but Lofton has been terrific. So possibly the Cleveland
fans in their hometown delirium got it right, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   What should make Gonzalez even madder is that, with the panoply
of stars in the game, he will hardly be missed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
