A0971 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NL-STARS07-COX     07-06 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NL-STARS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' All-Star run at an end
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One Braves run of this decade has ended. For the first
time since 1990, the Braves won't have a starter in the July 13
All-Star Game at Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In four of the past eight years, the Braves have had the
starting pitcher for the National League, but with Greg Maddux and
Tom Glavine plagued by slow starts and John Smoltz on the disabled
list with a sore elbow, that honor will go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves are hoping Brian Jordan, Kevin Millwood and
possibly Chipper Jones will find their way onto Bruce Bochy's squad
as backups, no position players were picked by baseball fans, whose
votes determine the staring lineups.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona second baseman Jay Bell overtook Craig Biggio in vote
totals on Tuesday and joined Diamondbacks third baseman Matt
Williams in the starting lineup, making the second-year team the
only NL squad with two players in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza of the New York Mets will be at catcher, Mark
McGwire of St. Louis at first and Barry Larkin of Cincinnati at
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Sammy Sosa, Colorado's Larry Walker and San Diego's
Tony Gwynn were elected to start in the outfield. Gwynn is on the
disabled list with a calf injury, but has been taking batting
practice and might be activated in time to play.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of fan support in Braves' balloting is puzzling,
because Atlanta has the best record and is among the league leaders
in attendance in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it shouldn't be a surprise. Javy Lopez, Chipper Jones
and Walt Weiss finished in the top three at their positions in the
voting, even though Jones hasn't produced the runs he has in recent
years, and Weiss missed 29 games with a quadriceps injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's a reverse compliment,'' said Tom Glavine, who
started the 1991 and '92 All-Star games. ``That speaks highly of
what we've been able to accomplish. It says we can do it without
one guy. ... I don't think anybody's stats are going to jump out at
you. Brian has got a bunch of RBIs. Chipper has had a solid year
but not what people probably expect out of Chipper. But we're
winning games. Production is being spread out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for feeling snubbed by voters?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a big deal,'' Glavine said. ``It's a
popularity contest for starters ... and that hurts a lot of guys
who have to be picked who deserve to be there and won't be. But
it's the fans' game. They ought to see who they want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, one of the few bright spots in the Chicago Cubs' dismal
season, was the NL's leading vote-getter with 2,315,204, finishing
third overall in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   In the American League, Seattle outfielder Ken Griffey Jr.
(2,918,055) led all players for the fourth straight year and fifth
time overall and was followed by Cleveland second baseman Roberto
Alomar (2,793,891).
</P>
<P>
   Before this week, none of the votes cast on the Internet had
been included in the weekly totals. Fans were allowed to vote up to
22 times on the Internet _ the average number of home games for
each team during the balloting. Sosa gained nearly 1 million votes
in the final week of counting.
</P>
<P>
   AL starters were announced Monday. In addition to Griffey and
Alomar, the lineup includes Cleveland's Jim Thome at first, and
Manny Ramirez and Kenny Lofton in the outfield. They will be joined
by Texas catcher Ivan Rodriguez, Boston shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra, Baltimore third baseman Cal Ripken Jr. and Tampa Bay
designated hitter Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and reserves for both leagues will be picked today.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
