<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-CAMP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minicamp to test Falcon no-shows
 &HT;    By Michael Carvel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons will have their first official
team meeting today since the Super Bowl. But they don't know
whether the back who helped the team run away with the NFC
championship will be in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson is considered a possible
no-show for the three-day minicamp, which is mandatory for all
rookies and veterans on the Falcons' roster.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has missed all of the team's voluntary workouts in the
offseason while trying to negotiate a contract extension with the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect everybody to be here (today),'' coach Dan Reeves said
Tuesday evening. ``Minicamp is mandatory, just like training camp.
Anybody not here will be fined, unless they were previously
excused.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his reaction to unexcused absences, Reeves replied
sternly, ``I worry about that when it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is not the only player who has team officials
concerned. Right guard Gene Williams, like Anderson, has said that
his absence from passing camp last month can be attributed to his
unhappiness about the lack of progress on a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have 79 players listed on the roster for minicamp.
Atlanta has agreed to contract terms with seven of nine draft
choices, including first-rounder Patrick Kerney, a defensive end
from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Johndale Carty, a fourth-rounder, and wide receiver
Eugene Baker, who was taken in the fifth round, are expected to
sign in the next two days. Both rookies are expected to report to
Suwanee today.
</P>
<P>
   The loosely structured minicamp will consist of daily practices
just over an hour in length and will resemble the workouts at
passing camp. The team also will begin preparation for training
camp, which starts July 28 at Furman University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minicamp is a chance for us to condition the guys that
have not participated in a high percentage of our offseason
workouts,'' Reeves said. ``We'll also be able to get the guys more
familiar with the system and prepared for later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
