<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's Final Four to be held at Georgia Dome
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With another national sporting event secured, the
Atlanta Sports Council is ready to take on the world. On Tuesday,
the NCAA announced that the 2003 Women's Final Four will be at the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our major initiative right now is to be known as the sports
capital of the world,'' said Gary Stokan, president of the Atlanta
Sports Council. ``A lot of people laugh, but if you look at it from
a business case-study standpoint, as I have, no other city can beat
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Division I women's basketball committee gave Atlanta
the nod over Charlotte, N.C., Detroit and Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, the host school, teamed with the sports council,
the Atlanta Visitors and Convention Bureau, Philips Arena and the
Georgia Dome in luring the April 4-6 event, which is projected to
have a $25 million economic impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia Tech is thrilled and pleased with the announcement,''
said Kathy Noble, Tech's senior associate athletics director.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Dome, which will use either a 24,000- or 36,000-seat
configuration, will play host to the men's Final Four in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot about Atlanta as a great sports city,'' Georgia
Dome general manager Khalil Johnson said. ``Fortunately, we didn't
have to re-invent the wheel in our presentation. We've been in a
lot of these situations in the past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta hosted the 1993 Women's Final Four, in which Sheryl
Swoopes scored a record 47 points in leading Texas Tech to the
title at the Omni.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision extends an impressive run of sporting events
in Atlanta. The city hosted the Super Bowl in 1994, and it returns
in January. Also next year, Atlanta gets the baseball All-Star Game
at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Atlanta hosted the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The men's Final Four returns in 2007, and the SEC (2000) and ACC
(2001) basketball tournaments are at the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the annual SEC Football Championship, the Heritage Bowl
and Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl, two NASCAR events, an Indy car race and
PGA, Seniors and LPGA tournaments, and Stokan's contention has some
merit. ``Put all those things together _ and hopefully get another
World Series _ and we can say things no other city can say,''
Stokan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
