<SLUG> BC-TV-KIDS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIDE POOL AS TALENT POOL (IT HAD TO HAPPEN) 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When children pick up the remote control to watch cartoons, they
find shows about the likes of CatDog, a two-headed mutant (or
``bicranial quadriped,'' as it prefers); Arthur, an aardvark who
wears glasses; a large blue bear who seems to run an animal
commune, and whatever the Teletubbies are. Children's television
hits in recent years have starred giant turtles with martial-arts
skills and a purple dinosaur who appears to be on a sugar high.
Even the classic cartoon shows are about smart-aleck rabbits,
sadistic lisping canaries and laughing woodpeckers. So maybe a
series about a talking sea sponge isn't so odd.
</P>
<P>
   ``SpongeBob Squarepants,'' which has its official premiere on
Saturday at 10 a.m., is not just a new show; it's the first
original Saturday morning series from Nickelodeon, the cable
channel that has owned Saturday morning for the last few years.
Until now, the channel's schedule at that time has consisted
largely of reruns of its weeknight shows like ``Hey, Arnold'' and
``Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob, who looks pretty much like one of those rectangular yellow
kitchen sponges in the four-pack at Gristede's, lives in the
undersea city Bikini Bottom. His house is a two-story pineapple.
His best friend is Patrick Starfish, a surfer-dude type whose
hobbies, according to his official biography, ``include sleeping
and lying dormant.'' Bob's neighbor and co-worker is the unlikable
Squidward Tentacles, who plays the clarinet. Bob's girlfriend, of
sorts, is Sandy Cheeks, a squirrel who wears a bikini top and a
skirted swimsuit bottom. She lives in a glass-enclosed air bubble.
(A sponge may love a squirrel, but where would they make a home?)
</P>
<P>
   A sponge may seem like a particularly passive creature to build
a series around, but that gave the show's creator, Stephen
Hillenburg, a blank canvas on which to create an ``innocent, naive,
excited about life'' character who has ``a kid's energy and
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In the preview episode (first shown in May), Bob gets his dream
job: working as a fry cook at the Krusty Krab. He's a wiz with a
spatula and saves the day when the restaurant is overtaken by a mob
of burger-hungry anchovies on a bus tour. He also meets Sandy (who
greets him with ``Hold on there, little square dude''), visits her
for tea and cookies, and tries to pretend he's not dying. ``Air is
not good, Patrick,'' he gasps to his friend, who has also arrived
at Sandy's water-free dome. ``Air is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Future episodes include the following adventures: Bob cheats on
his boat-driving exam. Bob tries to deliver a pizza in the desert.
Bob's pet snail, Gary, gets sick. Wild disco-loving jellyfish take
over Bob's house. Plankton takes control of Bob's brain.
</P>
<P>
   Hillenburg, 38, is a filmmaker who once worked as a marine
science educator at the Orange County Marine Institute in Dana
Point, Calif. There he found that children were particularly crazy
about tide pool creatures, which include sponges, starfish,
octopuses, crabs and sea cucumbers. So doing the series is a fusion
of his two favorite subjects (animation and sea life), exactly the
sort of thing guidance counselors are always recommending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have teachers in high school say, `You should just
draw fish,''' he recalls. Now he does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
