<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICKLAUS-HIP07-COX     07-06 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICKLAUS-HIP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus to sit out Senior Open
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jack Nicklaus withdrew this week from this week's U.S.
Senior Open in Des Moines, Iowa, preferring to give his sore left
hip more time to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus also had to withdraw during the third round of the
Senior Players Championship 10 days ago, marking just the third
time in his 38-year pro career he was unable to finish a tournament
because of injury. Nicklaus, who underwent hip-replacement surgery
Jan. 27, considered playing this week but decided Monday he's
better off taking the conservative route.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hip is starting to feel good. But I think it would be wise
on my part to wait a week or so to test it again,'' Nicklaus said.
``I'm very eager to play golf, but I just don't think I should
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus' decision means he won't finish any of the four majors
on the Senior PGA Tour this year after playing in 35 of the 36
majors since he joined the tour in 1990. He missed the Tradition
and the PGA Seniors' Championship this spring because of the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus admitted he pushed his body too hard to return in time
to play at his Memorial Tournament and the U.S. Open. He says
there's nothing physically wrong with his ceramic hip, but in
addition to the pain, he still feels pain on his sciatic nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Nicklaus played in Johnny Miller's
Champions Challenge last week. Nicklaus also played in two course
openings last week. He shot a four-under 68 Friday at Roaring Fork
Club in Basalt, Colo., the first time he broke 70 since surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has twice won the U.S. Senior Open (1991 and 1993).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
