<SLUG> BC-IHA-FORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET INSURANCE SALES DEVELOPER RECEIVES FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insurance Holdings of America Inc. has a Ford in its future.
</P>
<P>
   IHA, a 3-year-old developer and franchiser of Internet
technology for retail insurance sales, said Tuesday it has arranged
a $67 million, fourth round of financing from four investors,
including Ford Motor Credit Co.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Ford Credit, the finance arm of the Ford Motor Co.,
will get to use IHA's technology, marketing plan, and other
services to support in-showroom marketing of auto and other
insurance products to buyers of Ford cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   While spokesmen for Ford Credit and IHA refused to disclose
Ford's share of the round, sources familiar with the deal put the
amount at around $35 million to $40 million, making the automotive
giant IHA's largest single investor to date.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors in the round were identified as Pacific Life
Insurance Co., Prospector Partners GSA Inc., Dowling &AMP; Partners
Asset Management, and funds managed by Eastbourne Capital
Management. The new round brings total investment in IHA since 1996
to more than $108 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brian K. McCarthy, IHA's 36-year-old founder, chairman, and
chief executive, said much of the fresh cash is earmarked for
upgrading hardware and software so the company can proceed with
installing on-line insurance sales kiosks at 450 Sam's Club
membership discount stores operated by Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said that program, announced 18 months ago, is well
behind schedule because of technological difficulties, including
problems with data storage hardware from Microsoft Corp. He said
that equipment is being replaced with Oracle Corp. units.
</P>
<P>
   IHA's technology lets franchised independent agents, working
inside Sam's Club stores, obtain insurance coverage information
from several underwriters and generate comparative price quotes,
often while the customer waits.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Credit, which already offers its own insurance products
through dealers, said it sees the IHA system as a way to offer
customers a broader choice. ``The way consumers shop is changing,''
Jim Moritz, Ford Credit's director of insurance, said. ``Customers
want choices.'' The company said it is also considering direct
insurance sales via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While apparently ahead of the pack among Detroit auto makers in
forming a partnership with an outside insurance underwriter, Ford
is not the first. Nancy Carini, an analyst with Conning &AMP; Co. in
Hartford, Conn. said Liberty Mutual began mass marketing auto
policies directly to Volvo owners in April 1998, and The Chubb
Group and BMW Financial Services signed a letter of intent last
April to offer BMW owners personalized insurance packages.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Credit, indeed, test marketed a direct insurance sales
program last year in Florida with American International Group, but
IHA was not involved in that test.
</P>
<P>
   Carini described the Ford-IHA alliance as ``just good,
old-fashioned affinity marketing, except with the technology
platform.'' In many ways, she said, this relationship and the
IHA-Sam's Club partnership resembles the in-store insurance
marketing done between 1940 and 1970 by Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. and
its subsidiary, Allstate Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Credit and the other new IHA investors were recruited by
Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., McCarthy said. Stuart Robbins, IHA's chief
financial officer, said the New York investment banking house was
hired last spring when it became clear more money would be needed
to deal with unexpected technological difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said that along with its problems in data storage, IHA
underestimated the amount of work required to install network
connections to Sam's Club stores and to train personnel. ``The
rollout has been slower than anticipated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said IHA revenues from premiums on policies last year
were almost negligible, with only three states _ New Hampshire,
Michigan and Illinois _ connected to the network between August and
November.
</P>
<P>
   During the first five months of 1999, he said, revenues reached
$12 million, with Arizona, New York, and Georgia already added this
year and Ohio and Pennsylvania about to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins and McCarthy said IHA meanwhile has temporarily
suspended expansion of a separate program that sells group life and
casualty insurance through corporate employee benefit programs,
using franchised local agents to close these sales.
</P>
<P>
   With competition now building, Robbins said, IHA is focused on
building brand identification, in anticipation of an initial public
offering. ``We think we have really solidified ourselves as a
leader by bringing in a partner like Ford,'' he said. ``We are
trying to get this company on a track that will bring long-term
value.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, IHA has about 220 employees in Beverly and 45
at an actuarial center in Longmeadow; 130 more work at a
telemarketing call center in upstate New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
