<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-PLUMERIA-HN     07-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-PLUMERIA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDENING: PLUMERIA BLOOMS TAKE THEIR TIME
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By KATHY HUBER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why won't my plumeria bloom? &QL; 
_ H.H., Houston &QR; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   A:  &LR; A couple of other gardeners have recently asked this
question. Plumerias must reach a certain maturity and produce a
blooming hormone in their tips before flowering. This may take a
year or two if you purchase a rooted cutting. It may take up to
five years for a plumeria to bloom if you start with seed.
</P>
<P>
   The Plumeria Society of America recommends sun, Superbloom and
patience.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn much more about plumerias at the Plumeria Society
of America's meeting at 7:30 p.m. July 13 at the Houston Garden
Center in Hermann Park. The program is free.
</P>
<P>
   The society's plant show and sale will be 9:30 a.m.-3 p.m. July
17 at the Bay Area Community Center, 5002 NASA Road 1 (across the
street from the lake) in Clear Lake Park.
</P>
<P>
   Another free program, ``Growing Plumerias,'' is scheduled for 11
a.m. July 24 at Gateway Ace Hardware &AMP; Garden Center, 6860
Telephone Road, 713-643-0623; and a free Plumeria Workshop and
Garden Tour will be 9 a.m.- noon July 31 at Mercer Arboretum and
Botanic Gardens, 22306 Aldine-Westfield Road, 281-443-8731. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  Someone at our church said he saw a blue oleander. I've
never heard of one. Have you?
</P>
<P>
   What is the best time to plant plumeria seeds? What is the best
way to propagate a bottle brush plant?
</P>
<P>
   And, there is a place called Ty Ty Plantation, perhaps in
Georgia. They sell mail-order plants. If you know the address, I
would appreciate your giving it to me. &QL; 
_ C.S.M., Cleveland &QR; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   A:  &LR; Blue oleander sounds vaguely familiar, but I can't remember
exactly a plant that goes by this common name. Usually oleanders
are designated as pink, cerise, red, salmon, white and yellow.
However, these plants have been subdivided as follows: white into
white and cream; pink into pink and lilac; red into red, carmine
and purple; and yellow into salmon, apricot, flesh, copper and
orange.
</P>
<P>
   I think your friend must be referring to something other than a
true oleander (Nerium oleander), but a plant that resembles an
oleander. For example, the blue ginger, Dichorisandra thyrsiflora,
is not a true ginger but certainly could pass for one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a reader can enlighten us.
</P>
<P>
   Some plumerias rarely develop seed pods, while others produce an
abundance. Among the latter, some create many sterile seeds while
others produce more viable seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Allow plumeria seed pods, or follicles, to ripen on the tree.
This occurs at various times during the year, and it takes eight to
nine months for a pod to ripen. Sometimes, a stem is not strong
enough to hold a heavy seed pod on the tree and it breaks off
before reaching maturity. Should this happen, just let it ripen in
a warm, dry place.
</P>
<P>
   When a pod splits, remove the numerous seeds. Each will be
covered with a tough, brown sheath with a paperlike wing at one
end. Lightly squeeze the seed to test for viability, and keep those
that are solid and plump. Cut a couple of these open, and if this
reveals a creamy-white flesh, chances are good that the seeds will
germinate.
</P>
<P>
   Sow in a well-draining, multipocket tray filled with a
pre-moistened premium potting soil. A warm soil is important
because a cold, damp soil promotes rot.
</P>
<P>
   Sow seed with the wing sticking out of the soil. Press to make
good soil contact around the seed, but avoid pressing the seed
deeper into the soil. Spray to keep the medium moist until
germination, but avoid overwatering to discourage fungal diseases.
You may see germination in three to 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   As the seedling grows, it will cast off the sheath. However,
weak seedlings may need your help _ moisten and remove the sheath.
</P>
<P>
   When the seedlings have put on their true leaves, replant in
4-inch pots. Water thoroughly as seedlings put on good growth, but
allow soil to dry until it feels barely moist before watering
again.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible you may see a bloom in three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   The bottlebrush (Callistemon spp.), a favorite with
hummingbirds, generally blooms off and on from spring to fall. It
is not reliably hardy, especially north of Houston, so it is a good
idea to grow it on the south side of the house. Provide winter
protection with a heavy mulch.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners prune bottlebrush immediately after it blooms,
and that's fine if done by early September. But pruning late in the
year can be risky since pruning can trigger new growth that will be
more susceptible to cold. Prune winter-damaged wood early the
following spring, after threat of frost. Leaving cold-damaged wood
in place will help protect any live wood farther down the branches.
</P>
<P>
   Bottlebrush likes full sun and an organically enriched soil that
has excellent drainage.
</P>
<P>
   You can propagate with semi-ripe cuttings in summer or by sowing
seed in fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Ty Nursery is in Ty Ty, Ga. It has a good selection of bulbs
and plants and specializes in hellebores, plants that have been
gaining a lot of attention in the past few years. I intend to test
various ones here, but have yet to do so. I'm afraid many may not
like our heat and humidity, but perhaps there is at least one
species or cultivar that would hold up.
</P>
<P>
   You may send $2 for a catalog to Ty Ty Nursery at P.O. Box 130,
Ty Ty, Ga. 31795.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
