<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-TELEVISION-ART     07-06 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TELEVISION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL ECONOMY TRANSFORMS EUROPEAN TV INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Europe's television industry is suddenly in the grip of
an American-style consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the forces of the global economy and the power of the
Internet, European media companies are forging cross-border links,
and American giants like Microsoft Corp. are buying into the
action. The resulting corporate alliances are providing a gateway
for advertisers to reach wider mass audiences and an opportunity
for Europe to challenge America's supremacy in television
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The European television market was first opened up in the 1980s,
as state broadcasting monopolies crumbled and commercial channels
sprang up. Now, the long-expected shakeout of an industry made up
of dozens of struggling private and commercial channels has begun
in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, in fact, seems to be charging into a future very much
like America's present, in which the TV industry is dominated by a
handful of huge conglomerates. ``It's a long road, and it will
require a tremendous amount of money, but it will happen,'' said
Marc Andre Feffer, deputy chairman and chief executive officer at
Canal Plus in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The activity so far this year has been intense.
</P>
<P>
   A company in the Netherlands called United Pan-Europe
Communications NV has been gobbling up cable companies across
Europe and in June took a stake in SBS Broadcasting of Luxembourg,
another innovator, to form a strategic alliance. In March, SBS
acquired Central European Media Enterprises, a chain of TV and
radio stations set up in Central Europe after the fall of communism
by Ronald Lauder. United Pan-Europe recently acquired Poland's
leading provider of cable and satellite service and the fourth- and
fifth-largest cable companies in France, lifting the number of its
subscribers to 7.7 million in 10 European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mediaset SA, the Italian television company
controlled by Silvio Berlusconi, an entrepreneur-turned-politician,
and Kirch Group of Germany announced a joint venture in March to
market pay-per-view programming in four countries and handle
Kirch's international film distribution and Mediaset's advertising
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in June, the French conglomerate Vivendi SA tightened its
hold on Canal Plus, the French pay-for-view company, by taking over
the French film production and distribution company, Pathe, that
held a stake in Canal Plus. That gave rise to speculation that
Canal Plus might revive discussions about cooperating with News
Corp. of Rupert Murdoch, the Australian-born media mogul. Murdoch,
who is pursuing the kind of television breakthrough in Europe that
he has achieved in the United States with his Fox networks,
acquired a stake in an Italian pay-for-view channel, Stream SpA,
and a major chunk of German soccer rights through a small German
affiliate, TeleMuenchen, last month.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, at a news conference in London last week, ruled out a
merger between News Corp.'s B Sky B and Canal Plus but kept the
door open for looser alliances in areas like film production and
rights to sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   What's causing this frenzy of reorganization? Mainly, the global
economy, which is forcing Europe's relatively small players to join
forces to cover the costs of switching to digital and pay-for-view
TV and of marketing integrated bundles of television, telephone and
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several axes are evolving,'' said Nick Bertolotti, who follows
the television business at J.P. Morgan in London. Describing the
industry's state as ``very unstable,'' he added, ``Anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   American companies are a big part of the equation. Pan-Europe
Communications is controlled by the Denver-based investor group
Unitedglobalcom, for example. And, imitating the American drive
into ``bundled'' telephone and Internet services, it has already
provided 118,000 of its cable customers with phone service and more
than 40,000 with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft recently acquired a 7.8 percent stake in United
Pan-Europe Communications as part of its effort to extend its reach
into the European telecommunications revolution. ``The rate of
growth is moving very, very quickly,'' said Henrietta Hirst, a
spokeswoman for United Pan-Europe in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has also taken stakes in leading cable companies in
Britain and Portugal, while the American television veteran Harry
Evans Sloan has invested in SBS. American groups like
Unitedglobalcom, which was known until recently as United
International Holdings Inc., and Internet service providers like
America Online Inc. are searching out European opportunities, as
are providers of television programming, like Walt Disney Co., that
see the promise of larger markets for their products.
</P>
<P>
   If much of this sounds like an echo of what is happening in the
United States, it is also boosting the local flavor of European
television. European productions are hardly about to outstrip
American programs as Europe's fare of choice, but the Europeans
have reconquered prime time with home-grown quiz shows and soap
operas. Last year, there were no American series and only two
American feature films among the 10 most popular programs in
Britain, France, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, off-prime time is still saturated with American
products. Cable and pay per view now enable TV audiences to see hit
films like ``Titanic'' within months of their release, and channels
across Europe are showing reruns of ``Little House on the
Prairie,'' ``Hogan's Heroes,'' ``Cheers,'' ``Golden Girls'' and
``Baywatch,'' dubbed into the local languages, as they have for
years.
</P>
<P>
   But the sheer proliferation of new channels and technologies
means more broadcast time for everybody. As a result, European
production of both high-quality programs and knockoffs of American
schlock, like a French version of Baywatch called ``St.-Tropez,''
is making big inroads into American territory.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Europe remains a checkerboard of small markets divided by
culture and language, industry consolidation means that
broadcasters have bigger, more efficient organizations at their
disposal as they offer national programming. Thus, ``the market is
becoming more European,'' said Fedele Confalonieri, president of
Mediaset. He said Mediaset's vision ``is for many local
broadcasters, as there are in the United States, united in large
units, like CBS or ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how this works, consider Mediaset's alliance
with Kirch. Under it, the Germans focus on what they do best _
program production and trading of rights _ while Mediaset brings in
expertise in advertising sales and program distribution.
(Mediaset's parent company, Fininvest SpA, holds a stake in the
European affiliate of the Blockbuster video chain.)
</P>
<P>
   One of last year's most popular programs was ``The Count of
Monte Cristo,'' a $20 million, three-part miniseries produced
jointly by Mediaset, Kirch and the leading commercial broadcaster
in France, TF 1. And as Europe unifies, more and more companies are
broadcasting the same commercial spots across the Continent,
enabling Mediaset to sell air time on a multinational basis. ``The
spots for McDonald's, Sony and Disney are the same in London, Paris
and Milan,'' Confalonieri said.
</P>
<P>
   European regulators are casting a wary eye on the deal-making,
especially on agreements that concentrate a lot of power in a
single entity. In April, for example, Britain blocked a plan by
Murdoch to acquire the leading British soccer team, Manchester
United, for $1 billion. And earlier, Italy limited the television
soccer rights that any one broadcaster could control, thwarting a
bid by Murdoch for most Italian professional soccer rights.
</P>
<P>
   Although those attempts failed, they demonstrated Murdoch's
faith in the power of sporting events to draw big television
audiences. Indeed, News Corp. has succeeded in acquiring broadcast
rights to four of Italy's top soccer teams. And one of the
attractions of Kirch as a partner for Mediaset was Kirch's $1.7
billion purchase earlier this year of the rights to broadcast the
soccer World Cup in 2002 and 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, TV wants to drive ad revenues, which
come from ratings,'' said Jose Violante, managing director of NBA
Europe SA, the marketing arm of the National Basketball Association
in Paris. ``And how do you get those ads? Sporting events.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the United States, pay-per-view TV companies whose cables
reach into millions of households are drawing considerable
investment in Europe, not least from American companies.
Microsoft's decision to gather stakes in European cable television
operators is based on the expectation they will require cash and
technology to offer customers high-speed access to the Internet. In
Italy, the Mediaset parent, Fininvest, has a deal with Excite Inc.,
America's second-largest Internet portal, while Bertelsmann in
Germany is working similarly with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Georges Nahon, the head of Microsoft's Paris-based European
Internet and telecommunications activities, said Microsoft focused
on cable TV because of regulatory restrictions on the use of phone
lines for Internet service. But the cable companies generally need
both cash and technology, Nahon said, explaining Microsoft's policy
of taking equity shares. Microsoft continues to search for cable
partners, he said, and not necessarily as potential investment
targets, but also as customers for software and services. ``We are
looking at companies that are very connected to high-speed data
carriage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the television companies, while entrepreneurial, are
not necessarily all moving at the speed of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Confalonieri of Mediaset, while acknowledging that Internet
access is part of the company's plans, said the immediate aims of
the deal with Kirch were production, distribution and advertising
sales. ``The rest,'' he said, ``is wishful thinking where tomorrow
is a little blurred.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
