<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TOWER COMPANY GROWS THROUGH MERGER, PURCHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- American Tower Corp. completed two transactions
Tuesday _ a $73 million acquisition and a merger with CommSite
International of Virginia _ bringing the total number of towers the
company operates to more than 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston company also recently merged with UNIsite Inc. in a
cash transaction worth about $205 million and gained nearly 400
towers in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   American Tower, which pending the transactions will be one of
the largest broadcast and wireless tower company in the nation,
agreed Tuesday to pay $73 million in cash to purchase 21 broadcast
and cellular towers in the San Francisco area from Watson
Communications Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   These transactions ``represent continuation of our strategy to
focus a significant amount of our resources on the acquisition of
young, newly constructed towers and contracts to construct
additional new towers,'' said Steve Dodge, chief executive officer
of American Tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that transactions of this nature provide the
foundation for profitable long-term growth and other investor
returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley A. Williams, an analyst with Legg Mason Wood Walker who
follows wireless communication companies, said these deals follow
American Tower's pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Tower has a history of doing a lot of acquisitions of
smaller tower companies,'' Williams said. ``This is certainly along
that line. The objective is to continue to expand by buying smaller
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The company purchased all of Watson Communications' assets,
including 11 wireless towers, 10 broadcast towers, and a teleport
that will enable Internet access across the Pacific region.
American Tower already owns an Internet teleports in Washington
D.C., Dallas, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   From its $38.8 million deal with CommSite, American Tower will
acquire towers in Maryland, Virginia, Louisiana, Mississippi,
Texas, Wisconsin, and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also includes built-to-suit towers in Tennessee,
Mississippi, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Michigan, and Louisiana that
American Tower said it hopes will expand the company's presence in
the Midwest and Southeast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
