<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0994 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HOMEPAGES-BOS &LR;      07-06 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOMEPAGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES JOIN IN EFFORT TO CREATE `TV HOMEPAGES' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MarkeTVision Direct Inc. of Boston and a California company have
teamed up to offer TV viewers a way to create their own
``television homepages,'' a service that would supply them with
customized news headlines and sports scores _ and also give them a
chance to buy merchandise tied to the TV shows they watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could buy a Judge Judy gavel,'' said president Andrew
Miller of MarkeTVision, ``or some other kind of collectible.''
</P>
<P>
   MarkeTVision's partner is Steeplechase Media Inc., a California
outfit that looks to make the content of shows such as Judge Judy
interactive. The joint venture, announced Tuesday and scheduled for
a fall debut, is called television.com and aims to be at the
convergence of TV and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to Miller, the day is not far off when many TV viewers
could, by a click of the remote, have a window appear in a corner
of the TV screen on which merchandise tied to the show would be for
sale. A few more clicks, and a purchase could be made, much as
e-commerce consumers buy goods at retail Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   There would also be TV homepages, which could be customized by
viewers to receive the sports scores of a favorite team or weather
reports for an upcoming vacation destination.
</P>
<P>
   Not many viewers can take advantage of interactive TV just yet.
But more will soon have digital cable boxes or special software for
their PCs that could make interactive TV a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that the majority of people want to interact
with the television most of the time,'' said Larry Namer, chairman
of Steeplechase, which owns 75 percent of television.com. ``But we
do believe that all viewers at some point want customized
information at their fingertips that they can access without
leaving the programs they are watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Steeplechase and MarkeTVision said they're making an initial $4
million investment in television.com. After Steeplechase's 75
percent, MarkeTVision owns 15 percent of the new company and
investors own the remaining 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As with any Web idea, it's hard to say whether television.com
will be a smash, a bust, or something in between.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the cost of interactive TV was a big hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   But with the cost to consumers coming down, the challenge is to
make interactive TV easy to use and motivate viewers to make
purchases, said Josh Bernoff, principal analyst for TV research at
Forrester Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this something you can do with a remote in one hand and a
beer in the other?'' Bernoff said.
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is yes, he said, the key questions then are ``do
people really want to look at the Web on TV?'' and can you ``get
people up off their butts to buy things?''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Miller of MarkeTVision fits in. He's gotten folks
to get up off their butts to buy things before, most notably by
devising one of the first infomercials to air on public television
stations.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, public TV infomercials would seem like a
nonstarter. Most people associate infomercials with relentless
pitchmen flogging appliances that process beef jerky _ not at all
the kind of thing that crops up on ``Masterpiece Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, however, produces infomercials that are so low-key that
many viewers mistake them for regular cable TV fare.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a stock broker by trade, Miller was managing money
for violin virtuoso Itzhak Perlman when the two realized that an
infomercial might be one of Perlman's best investments.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1996, and Perlman was compiling a special CD of his
favorite selections. To market the CD, Miller taped interviews of
Perlman and mixed them with concert footage.
</P>
<P>
   For public TV, this infomercial turned out to be ideal for
fund-raising drives. During pledge week, viewers got a welcome
break from celebrities making pleas in front of phone banks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, viewers were treated to the infomercial, which public
TV stations paid fees to Perlman and Miller to air. Viewers who
donated a specified amount received the Perlman CD.
</P>
<P>
   That infomercial was so successful that Miller worked on
variations of it for other TV stations and other entertainers,
including the Grateful Dead and the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a rock band, the Dead is also a $100
million-a-year business that relied on the band's constant touring
to drive album and merchandise sales. When band leader Jerry Garcia
died, the band was hit with a marketing and cash-flow crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Enter MarkeTVision, which produced a Dead infomercial fashioned
on the Perlman format, creating a show that promoted CDs of Dead
concerts that weren't yet available in stores but that viewers
could buy by calling a toll-free phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Now Miller aims to use the skills he perfected working with
Perlman and the Grateful Dead to make commercials, and possibly Web
site infomercials, that will drive viewers to television.com and
persuade them to buy the merchandise it features.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
