<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-1STLD-WR     07-06 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK SWORN IN AS ISRAELI PREMIER, PLEDGES UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to CORRECT to Tuesday, sted Wednesday, in lede and
throughout; in last graf, Wednesday is cq.) 
 (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Seven long weeks of political negotiations after he
was elected, Ehud Barak took office as prime minister of Israel on
Tuesday and pledged that the pursuit of a ``true, lasting peace'
would be his foremost concern.
</P>
<P>
   In a passionate inaugural speech, Barak, 57, addressed not only
the Israelis glued to their radios and televisions but also the
many Palestinians and Syrians who watched, waiting for messages.
Despite a chorus of criticism for the composition of his Cabinet
and a wariness about him in the region, Barak sounded a
conciliatory note.
</P>
<P>
   He reached out to all his domestic constituencies _ from
high-tech workers to blue-collar unionists to soldiers' mothers
``who don't sleep at night'' _ as well as to each of Israel's
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Departing from the confrontational tone of his predecessor,
Benjamin Netanyahu, Barak, the One Israel/Labor Party leader, told
the Palestinians that he recognized their ``suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of the pain and death on both sides of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, and suggested that each stop focusing
on the ``account settling of historical wrongs.''
</P>
<P>
   While Netanyahu always emphasized the dangers surrounding
Israel, Barak described his country as ``strong and confident.''
And he urged Israel's neighbors to meet him at the diplomatic table
with an equal determination to ride the ups and downs of difficult
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on all regional leaders to take our outstretched hands
and build a peace of the brave,'' Barak said, embracing the phrase
that Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, often uses.
</P>
<P>
   With a clear intent to allay the concerns of Palestinians that
negotiations with Syria would take precedence, Barak said he would
move forward on both peace tracks at once.
</P>
<P>
   But, underscoring his keen interest in reopening talks with
Syria, which controls much of Lebanon, Barak repeated his campaign
promise to withdraw Israeli troops from southern Lebanon within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza Tuesday night, Barak's words were received by
Palestinians as a welcome break from the perceived hostility of
Netanyahu _ who officially quit the parliament on Tuesday, shaking
hands and walking out with his back to pursuing television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Palestinian leaders, who are wary of Barak, expressed
cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak's speech is an important and positive signal,'' said
Ahmed Qurei, known as Abu Ala, the speaker of the Palestinian
legislature. ``We hope his words will soon be followed by deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is expected to meet next week with Arafat before traveling
to Washington in mid-July for his first official meeting with
President Clinton. Barak is also expected to see President Hosni
Mubarak of Egypt and King Abdullah of Jordan this month.
</P>
<P>
   Using vivid language in his address, Barak, a highly decorated
former general, described himself as a ``warrior'' who ``for tens
of years wore no other clothes but the olive uniform.'' Citing
verses from the poet A. Hillel, he called himself one of the ``gray
soldiers whose hands are blackened from war and whose nostrils are
filled with death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tongue is dry from the march,'' he quoted, ``And we cry
love into the insides of your souls.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of political negotiating behind closed doors, Barak
re-emerged into the public eye Tuesday afternoon when he presented
his Cabinet to the parliament. Hours later, in a ceremony in the
Israeli president's house, Barak was sworn in as the leader of a
large majority coalition, controlling nearly two-thirds of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``no accident,'' he said in his inaugural speech, that he
had taken almost all the 45 days allowed by law to form a
government now made up of seven very different political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forced by the lessons of Jewish history and the deep
divide within our people to form a government that will be able to
function during the most difficult times with the wide acceptance
of the majority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the lectern, as he spoke of inclusiveness, he faced down
catcalls from Israeli Arab members of parliament who feel unjustly
excluded from his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you going to be the prime minister of everyone?'' one
shouted. ``Where are the Arab ministers?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, from another direction, Barak was rebuked by Ariel
Sharon, the temporary leader of the opposition Likud Party, for not
saying ``one word'' that would characterize the importance of the
state as a ``Zionist Jewish'' enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, the former foreign minister, also criticized Barak for
intransigence during the unsuccessful coalition negotiations with
the Likud, and said that the ``unique'' personal relationship
between them had been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon said that he had requested and been denied the power to
monitor the future peace negotiations _ which, he said, in a
reference to Barak, should not be controlled by only ``one person
no matter how talented he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinging news media criticism Tuesday labeled Barak as a leader
with autocratic tendencies _ calling him everything from
``Caligulan'' to a near ``Ehud Bonaparte.''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism began after Barak unveiled his Cabinet. He was
accused by many of making weak or inappropriate appointments. And
many suggested that he was doing his best to consolidate his hold
on power so that he could tackle his ambitious political agenda
without interference.
</P>
<P>
   In a country with a parliament, it is unusual for the prime
minister to act in a semi-presidential manner, but Barak, who was
elected in a separate ballot from his party, says that he has
received a personal mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak promised fast economic growth, social justice, leaving
Lebanon, completion of the peace accords, national reconciliation
and security,'' Nahum Barnea, a senior political columnist, wrote
in Yedioth Ahronoth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging from the composition of the government, it seems that
he expects to carry out all of these tasks alone, with a commando
knife between his teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new prime minister stared in the face his first political
failure Tuesday, when Avraham Burg, an ambitious Labor Party
official and sometime critic of Barak, was sworn in as speaker of
the parliament. Barak had backed a political novice for the post,
only to have his own party choose Burg instead.
</P>
<P>
   When Burg took his chair late Tuesday afternoon, he shook hands
with the prime minister. ``I have no hate in my heart toward the
prime minister,'' he had said earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, after presenting his Cabinet of 18 ministers,
Barak said he would move immediately to alter the basic law of
Israel. In order to accommodate the seven parties in his coalition
and to take on tasks that are ``humongous, maybe even historic,''
he said he would propose to expand the Cabinet to 24 ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And only one woman?'' Tamar Gozansky, a member of parliament
from the Communist Party called out.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although he pledged to include at least three women in his
Cabinet, he has appointed only one, Dalia Itzik of Labor, who will
be Environment Minister, and no female deputy ministers. He has
been roundly criticized for this.
</P>
<P>
   Against the background noise of these charges, Barak nonetheless
portrayed himself as the leader of all sectors of Israeli society,
a proponent of equal rights, and a healer.
</P>
<P>
   He more or less apologized that Israel has ``not always been
wise enough to invest equally in all of its people.'' This echoed a
legendary apology that Barak had earlier made to the Israeli Jews
of Middle Eastern descent, on behalf of the Labor Party, whose
original treatment of them is now largely considered to have been
discriminatory. He said he empathized with poor people who are
``full of broken promises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will change the national priorities,'' he said, promising
to create 300,000 new jobs over the next four years and to invest
heavily in education.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Barak addressed a personal remark to President
Hafez Assad of Syria,
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been harsh and bitter enemies on the battlefield,'' he
said. ``Now it is time to form an open and brave peace that will
insure the future and security of our peoples, our children and our
grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak also talked about working with Arafat to build a ``true
partnership in this land in which two peoples will live.''
</P>
<P>
   In a challenge to his intentions, bulldozers cleared land
earlier in the day for a Jewish quarter in an Arab neighborhood of
East Jerusalem. The Palestinians have urged Barak to stop the
expansion of settlements on land whose fate will be negotiated, and
the guidelines of Barak's government promises to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Haim Ramon, who was sworn in as a minister Tuesday, will oversee
Jerusalem. He said that the project, Ras al-Amud, should be
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will move into the prime minister's office on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
