<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP-FATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA OFFICIALS TO SEEK OTHER DUTY FOR KIDNAP FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Reacting to bitter criticism over Stephen Fagan's
court-ordered service at a veterans hospital, Florida correction
officials will propose at a hearing this month in Massachusetts
that the convicted kidnapper be assigned instead to do social work
with the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The site chosen by Florida probation officials is Cafe Joshua, a
West Palm Beach facility that provides a wide range of services to
hundreds of people attempting to begin the transition from the
streets to the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is tentatively scheduled for July 20 before Judge
Peter M. Lauriat in Middlesex Superior Court, said Coria Holland,
spokeswoman for the Massachusetts probation department.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, who was convicted in May of kidnapping his two daughters
from Massachusetts in 1979, began doing 2,000 hours of community
service at the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in Riviera Beach,
Fla. The assignment outraged former Florida Governor Claude Kirk, a
World War II and Korean War veteran, who said that a felon's
presence at the hospital was inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk said Tuesday that he has no objection to Cafe Joshua. ``I
think that's a better place,'' said Kirk, a West Palm Beach
resident who served as governor from 1967-1971. ``Veterans, in my
mind, are people we're supposed to honor, and they don't need to be
exposed to this. I don't care where he is, just so it's real public
service and also doesn't put veterans in a less than honorable
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Porter, director of interstate compacts for the Florida
correction department, described the request to change Fagan's
community service as routine. He also said that Kirk was not alone
in criticizing the assignment to the VA hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan's attorney, Richard Egbert, said Tuesday that he had not
been informed of the hearing date and was unaware of the choice of
Cafe Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   Tricia Sweeting, social services director at Cafe Joshua, said
the facility is ``disguised as a restaurant'' with an eating area
in one part of the building and working offices in another section.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person is homeless, not only is there hunger in their
stomach, but there's also a hunger of the soul and the spirit,''
Sweeting said. Cafe Joshua strives to give its clients ``spiritual
support, empowerment and encouragement, and to treat them with
dignity and respect,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The facility retains a five-star chef from Switzerland to
prepare three-course meals for its clients, who are referred from
other agencies. Often, they have left the street recently and are
staying in transitional housing.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe Joshua provides drug and alcohol counseling, emergency
vision and dental care, legal services, mental health therapy, even
makeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting said she did not know what kind of work Fagan would do
at Cafe Joshua if the new assignment is approved.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan and his fourth wife have put their oceanfront Palm Beach
mansion up for sale. He has staunchly defended his decision to flee
to Florida with his daughters, then 5 and 2 years old, and assume a
new identity. Fagan has justified his decision by describing the
girls' mother, Barbara Kurth, as alcoholic and neglectful at the
time of their abduction.
</P>
<P>
   The daughters did not know their mother was alive until Fagan
was arrested in April 1998. He had told them she died in a car
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan's home was the site of a Father's Day protest by a group
called Voice for the Children, some of whose members allege that
their spouses abducted their children.
</P>
</TEXT>
