A1005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEHOUSE-EVE-BOS &LR;      07-06 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-EVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PLANS GALA TO WELCOME MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To usher in the new millennium, the White House is
planning to host a star-studded New Year's Eve gala on the Mall
that could rival New York City's Times Square bash, where thousands
traditionally gather to watch the ball drop and count down the
seconds until the stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Millennium Council, created last year by the
president and headed by Hillary Rodham Clinton, is planning the
three-day event that starts on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities will include a short film by director Steven
Spielberg and outdoor concerts headed by Quincy Jones and producer
George Stevens Jr. of the Kennedy Center. Spielberg's 20-minute
film will highlight historic moments of the 20th century and will
feature an original score by former Boston Pops director and
Hollywood composer John Williams, who did music for films such as
``Star Wars'' and ``Schindler's List.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make this a truly American event,'' Ann Lewis,
counselor to the president, said Tuesday. ``We want people to
realize what a milestone the millennium is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said she expects the New Year's celebration to attract
even bigger crowds than the Fourth of July celebration, which draws
hundreds of thousands of people each year.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials insist the public festivities have nothing
to do with Mrs. Clinton trying to one-up the celebration in the Big
Apple, where her expected chief opponent for a Senate seat, Rudy
Giuliani, is mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always said she would balance her time being a first lady
and a candidate,'' Lewis said. ``This would fall under the role of
first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   And Toby Graff, a spokeswoman for Mrs. Clinton, said: ``Plans
for the formation of the Millennium Council began before the buzz
about Mrs. Clinton's potential run for the New York Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration will stretch across the Mall, from the Capitol
to the Lincoln Memorial, and along parts of Pennsylvania Avenue
leading to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Around 10 p.m. on New Year's Eve, participants will parade down
Constitution Avenue to the Lincoln Memorial. President Clinton is
scheduled to speak, and at the stroke of midnight, ``something
magical'' should light up the sky, according to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The official theme for the millennium celebration is ``Honor the
past, imagine the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at trying to make the New Year's weekend really
special,'' Lewis said. ``We definitely want to mark the turn of the
century with something very festive and patriotic.''
</P>
<P>
   The cultural events on the Mall the following two days are being
coordinated with the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   According to Anne Donovan, the Millennium Council's deputy
director, the Smithsonian envisions bridging a generation gap by
setting up ``teach-ins'' along the Mall, where leaders in
disciplines such as law, sports, medicine, and music teach the next
generation about their respective fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will act as role models for the future generation of
American leaders,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   While the celebration is intended to be ``rowdy and fun,''
Donovan said the activities will stay ``family focused.'' Because
the National Park Service oversees the grounds where most of the
events will take place, alcohol will be banned from the
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Large corporate donors are expected to cover the $10 million
cost of the celebration. Lewis said donors will be recognized in
some formal way during the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who may be busy campaigning for a Senate seat in
New York by that time, plans to mark the turn of the century in
Washington instead of in the state she intends to adopt as her
home, according to Lewis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
