<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strike reported over, but Teamsters picket
 &HT;    By Shannon Shelton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Overnite Transportation Co. announced the end of a
Teamsters strike at its suburban Atlanta service center Tuesday,
but picketing continued at the trucking company's other terminals
here.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company issued a news release announcing the end of
the strike, Teamsters national spokesman David Cameron said he
hadn't received any information about the action being over.
</P>
<P>
   Dockworkers and truck drivers at the Marietta center in
Kennesaw, the north Atlanta center in Lawrenceville and the Atlanta
center on Moreland Avenue began the walkout Monday night. Union
members also picketed at Overnite facilities in Memphis,
Indianapolis and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron said the strike was in response to complaints Overnite
harassed or illegally discharged union workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just false,'' said Ira Rosenfeld, Overnite's director
of corporate communications in Richmond, Va. ``We categorically
deny anybody's been discharged for union activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnite and the union disputed the effects of the strike on the
trucking company's operations Tuesday. Rosenfeld said the strike
has not hindered operations and that 75 volunteer drivers from
centers within 90 minutes of metro Atlanta made sure all deliveries
were completed. He also questioned Teamsters figures on the number
of workers on strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people out there aren't Overnite personnel,''
Rosenfeld said, claiming the Teamsters brought in a striker from
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron said Overnite wasn't being truthful about its operations
continuing as normal. ``They say there are no disruptions, but at
the same time, they are bringing in people from other locations.
They can't have it both ways,'' Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   The trucking firm is negotiating with the international
Teamsters organization, but no negotiations are taking place with
Local 728, the Atlanta-area branch involved in the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
