<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-DUTCH-$ADV11-NY     07-06 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-DUTCH-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A CELEBRATION OF DUTCH FREEDOM, HE FREES HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By ALAN RIDING    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ Jiri Kylian makes his appearance
dressed all in black and riding a bicycle, which seems fitting for
a Czech choreographer who is also artistic director of the
Netherlands Dans Theater. This being a country none too respectful
of hierarchies, however, his arrival at the Lucent Danstheater, his
company's headquarters here, goes almost unnoticed. For all his
international fame, Kylian does not play the star in his own house.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, 90 minutes later, as he presides over a
rehearsal of a dozen young dancers, his authority is absolute.
Sitting on a metal chair beside the console that controls the
music, he speaks softly in English (the lingua franca of the
multinational ballet corps) and makes light of mistakes he spots.
Tall, slim, youthful looking, with only streaks of gray in his
goatee hinting that he is now 52, his very presence seems enough to
bring out the best in his dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for many critics, it is through his quiet leadership as
much as his emotionally charged choreography that he has turned the
Netherlands Dans Theater _ the NDT _ into one of Europe's most
admired dance companies. In September, Kylian steps down after 24
years as artistic director, but he is not abandoning ship.
Dispensing with administrative duties that have begun to weigh on
him, he will stay on as chief choreographer and artistic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   He will not be underemployed. On his watch, two new ensembles
were added: the original 32-member corps founded in 1959 became
NDT1; a 14-member group, NDT2, was created in 1979 for dancers
between the ages of 17 and 22; and since 1989, NDT3 has enabled
five ``seniors'' to keep dancing, as he puts it, ``between 40 and
death.'' They often tour separately, but for Lincoln Center
Festival '99, the entire company will be performing at the New York
State Theater this week: NDT1 will present the United States
premiere of ``One of a Kind'' on July 13 and July 14; and all three
ensembles will participate in an eclectic program July 16 through
July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Kylian has picked his New York showpieces carefully. He
describes ``One of a Kind,'' only his third full-evening work
(after ``L'Histoire du Soldat'' and ``Kaguyahime''), as his gift to
the company because it includes all NDT1 members, dancing as
individuals rather than as a group. Commissioned to celebrate the
150th anniversary of the Dutch Constitution, it is also a homage to
his adoptive country since individual freedom is the unifying theme
of its three sections. Adding an unusual visual dimension, the set
has been designed by an architect, Atsushi Kitagawara of Japan, who
created mysterious abstract shapes through random computerized
programs.
</P>
<P>
   With the second program, the choreographer said, ``the idea is
to show all three ensembles at their best.'' Two of Kylian's works,
``Bella Figura'' and ``Wings of Wax,'' will be performed by NDT1
and a third, ``A Way a Lone,'' by NDT3, while four young dancers
from NDT2 will present ``Skew Whiff,'' by Paul Lightfoot, who is
still a member of the main NDT1 ensemble. These are also American
premieres. Finally, the evening will close with an excerpt from
Kylian's 1995 epic work, ``Arcimboldo,'' which he describes as ``a
cheerful polonnaise'' in which all his dancers as well as students
from the Juilliard School will fill the stage.
</P>
<P>
   So, Kylian was asked, what should people unfamiliar with his
work expect to see?
</P>
<P>
   He looked suddenly uneasy _ choreographers generally dislike
having to define their work. Having abandoned narrative for
abstraction, all too often they prefer audiences to make what they
will of what they see. So, in that respect, Kylian seems no
different. What distinguishes him from some of his contemporaries,
however, is that he aims unabashedly for the heart over the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every piece should give you something to take home with you,''
he said. ``If you don't come away thinking, `I feel a little richer
today because I have seen something special that has to do with
me,' then there is no justification for its existence. But if 30
different people see my work, there will be 30 different responses
to it. My work is very ambiguous. I acknowledge that, but I can't
do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work more realistically before,'' he went on. ``My
themes were such that you could detect them. But lately, some of
the things I choose are quite realistic, but I filter them, I
abstract them. This `One of a Kind,' it started with the Dutch
Constitution. Very nice, but you can't make ballets on the Dutch
Constitution, so you read as much as you can, and then you filter
and filter and filter, and then you come up with an absolutely
basic thing which is the freedom of the human being, freedom of
expression, sexual liberty, freedom of speech. And you make an
abstract version of the kind of freedom you can have within a
certain time and a certain space.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the creator, then, finds it easier to explain his
objectives than to describe the result. ``It's a dance you cannot
define,'' offered Brigitte Lefevre, director of dance at the Paris
Opera Ballet, where ``One of a Kind'' was performed by NDT1 last
December. ``It's a dance with today's dancers, today's concerns,
plus a certain concern for intemporality. It's not a reactionary
dance, it is not reacting against Classicism or Modernism and it
can't be called post-Modernist. It is the product of the experience
and culture of a man called Jiri Kylian who meets a designer and a
musician. It is simple and wise.''
</P>
<P>
   After recently watching Kylian work with eight Paris Opera
Ballet dancers on a new work, ``Deux Mensonges,'' presented at the
Palais Garnier in May, she was more than ever convinced that his
personality held the key to his choreography.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told our dancers, `Since everything we're doing is
absolutely pointless, it must be admirable,' which reveals his
duality,'' said Ms. Lefevre, who has commissioned Kylian to create
another work for her ballet corps in March 2001. ``He makes the
body think, but at the same time it is not an intellectual dance.
It is a dance inscribed in the universe of today, but it is not
avant-garde. It is above all a reflection on life. It is his
personal philosophy of life, his humanity, that shape his
choreography.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, though, it was his talent as a dancer that set him on
his way. Having studied dance at Prague National Theater's ballet
school and later at the Prague Conservatory, at the age of 20 he
won a one-year scholarship to the Royal Ballet School in London.
While dancing there, he was offered a contract to join John
Cranko's Stuttgart Ballet, a contract that enabled him to escape
Prague after the 1968 Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia. In
Stuttgart, he tried his hand at choreography. Then, in 1975, having
created two works for the NDT, he was named its artistic director.
Three years later, he made his name at the Spoleto Festival USA in
Charleston, S.C., with ``Sinfonietta,'' performed to music by
Janacek.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since then. His choreography has become more
abstract and varied and, while his point of departure can still be
a painting or a sculpture or some tiny autobiographical incident,
more than ever his work is inspired by music. And, although trained
as a classical dancer, he now feels less and less constrained by
questions of technique.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
