<HEADLINE>
SELLOFF LEAVES STOCKS SLIGHTLY LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An afternoon selloff pulled stock prices down from
early gains and left the main market averages slightly lower at the
close Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the session, the Dow Jones industrial average, the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and the NASDAQ composite index
were all trading at new highs despite an unfriendly bond market,
where long-term interest rates again moved above 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and traders said that optimism about coming
earnings reports outweighed concerns about interest rates. And
after five days of strong gains, it was not surprising to see some
investors taking some profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have run so far so fast we have to digest'' the gains, said
Bill Allyn, head of listed trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``But I
wouldn't place too much importance in the price moves today because
trading is so thin and the breadth is so lousy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was at 11,135.12,
down 4.12 points, or four-hundredths of a percent. Early in the
day, the blue-chip index was up almost 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader averages, the S&AMP;P 500 fell 3.10 points, or
two-tenths of a percent, to 1,388.12. NASDAQ fell 4.24, or
two-tenths of a percent, to 2,736.78. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies managed to eke out a gain, rising 0.04 points, to
456.55.
</P>
<P>
   With many investors and traders still on vacation, trading on
the first day after the Fourth of July holiday was fairly subdued.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 723 million shares changed
hands. Volume on the NASDAQ stock market was 1.14 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Bullish comments by Ralph Acampora, director of technical
research at Prudential Securities, and Thomas Galvin, chief
investment officer at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities,
helped to push prices higher early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   John Manley, equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, said the
optimism was justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news is pretty good, but as much as I hate to say it, we
can't go up every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, over the course of the next few weeks and months, he
said, the ``earnings numbers should be very good and interest rates
should not be a problem. I think the market has an upward bias
through the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar Tractor and Merck were the biggest drags on the Dow.
Caterpillar fell 2 5/8, to 59 9/16. And Merck lost 1 5/16, to 73
7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Gold stocks were punished after the price of bullion fell to a
20-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Newmont Mining fell 1 11/16, to 17 15/16. And Battle Mountain
Gold dropped 3/16, to 2 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   But oil stocks did better after crude oil prices rose near $20 a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, a Dow component, rose 2 1/16, to 98 5/16. Royal Dutch
Shell, which is part of the S&AMP;P 500, gained 1 13/16, to 61 15/16.
And BP Amoco closed at 112 15/16, up 1 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, which is expected to report its second-quarter results
Wednesday, fell 3, to 175. But America Online jumped 5 11/16, to
120 15/16. And Amazon.com gained 2 13/16, to 126 7/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
