<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR ORPHANS MAY BE HEADED TO BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Four Kosovar Albanian orphans, who witnessed the
murder of their father by three masked Serbs, hope to find a new
home in Massachusetts because of the efforts of Kitty Dukakis, to
bring them here.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Tirana, Albania, Tuesday Dukakis,
the wife of former governor Michael S. Dukakis, said she may be
returning with the children, two boys and two girls, ranging in age
from 15 to 19, this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   She was acting, she said, on behalf of a Concord family, who
wants to give the youngsters a home, and a Concord church who is
assisting them. She did not identify the family.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice tinged with emotion, one of the children, Kreshnik
Zejnullahu, 16, described by phone what had happened to the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 14, my mother died from cancer,'' she said. ``Last
November, when I was in the garden of our home in Pec about 8 at
night, three masked Serbs arrived and grabbed me. They didn't say
anything except to tell me to call for my mother. I told them she
was dead. But, they didn't believe me and started yelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father, who was a doctor, came to the door and, when he
tried to close it, they fired through the door and killed him in
front of all of us. Then, they ran away.''
</P>
<P>
   The children buried their father, and, then, in March, they left
Kosovo by car, arriving in Montenegro, about 45 kilometers away, at
midnight. There, they stayed for about one month and made their way
to Tirana where they have been living with nine other people in a
bedroom in the house of an Albanian man who has opened his home to
the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking forward to coming to America,'' Kreshnik said,
speaking for his sisters, Amella, 19, and Aida, 18, and brother,
Sokol, 15. ``Our only fear now is that it may not really happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Dukakis, who has been involved with the resettlement of
refugees and victims of war for more than 20 years, says she is
going to make sure it does happen. She has enlisted the aid of the
United Nations and official sources on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is cleared so far,'' she said. ``The children's
relatives have consented and their health has been approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis, 62, went to Albania last week on behalf of Relief
International, a California-based refugee organization, where she
had agreed to speak to the women in the camps the organization has
been operating about health and resettlement issues. When the
Concord family learned she was going, they asked her to intercede
on the children's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   While there, she crossed the border into Kosovo, to the town of
Prizrin, something she had promised her husband back in Boston she
would not do because of the presence of landmines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful small city with many burnt houses and
farms,'' she said by phone from Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis said she was impressed by the work of Relief
International, whose executive director, Farshad Raftegar, is,
himself, an Iranian refugee. ``It is a small non-governmental
agency, a small entity without a bureaucracy, that has programs in
six countries. As soon as the Kosovo war broke out, Mr. Rafetgar
had physicians from San Francisco and Los Angeles at the scene,''
Dukakis said.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Dukakis has a long history working with refugees and
victims of war.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, she received a degree in social work from Boston
University and for the last three years she has been working as a
constituent advocate at the International Institute of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, she assisted survivors of the Holocaust and the
Armenian genocide in their efforts to ensure these horrible events
are not forgotten. In 1979, former President Jimmy Carter appointed
her to the Holocaust Council, on which she still serves.
</P>
<P>
   She began working with victims of the Cambodian war in the early
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   Her most dramatic rescue came in 1985 when she went to a
Cambodian refugee camp on the border of Thailand and found the
brother and only surviving family member of a young Cambodian woman
refugee who had been resettled in Lynnfield.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Dukakis was denied entrance to the camp by its
commandant but, when she fell to her knees and begged his approval,
he relented and let her in. She brought Hout Pich back to the
United States and a reunion with his sister Sarom Taing.
</P>
<P>
   Pich is now a physician's assistant working with the Khmer
community in Lowell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
