<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-MERGER-BOS &LR;      07-06 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET-BANKBOS MERGER FACES ACTIVIST ONSLAUGHT AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fiery attacks and impassioned defenses might seem the
stuff of courtroom dramas and public demonstrations. But the
usually staid walls of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston will echo
Wednesday with rhetoric more typical of a trial or a street
protest.
</P>
<P>
   Community activists and politicians, worried about the impact of
New England's largest bank merger on poor neighborhoods, will
square off against executives from Fleet and BankBoston, who will
defend the merits of their historic deal.
</P>
<P>
   Public hearings, held by regional branches of the nation's
central bank, have become an industry rite of passage for large
banks seeking to merge.
</P>
<P>
   As consolidation sweeps through the financial services industry
and spawns ever larger giants, regulators who must approve the
combinations want to ensure that the new behemoths will continue to
lend to areas where they do business. While regulators are more
concerned with antitrust implications than community issues, they
are happy to encourage face-offs between banks and the groups as a
way of reminding banks of their obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every big bank deal of substance has a Fed hearing, some
variation of this zoo-like process,'' said analyst Nancy Bush, who
covers regional banks for Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ``This one is going to
be especially bloody, with the community groups going really wild,
because the banks' market share numbers are going to be so big.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston are merging into the nation's
eighth-largest bank, with more than $160 billion in assets. While
New England has seen plenty of mergers this decade, the $16 billion
combination is pathbreaking in that it will leave a major banking
market with a single, dominant competitor.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, which has one of the most highly regarded community
lending programs in the nation, has said it will imprint its urban
investment philosophy onto Fleet, even though Fleet is technically
acquiring its smaller rival. Fleet, which is traditionally viewed
as a more hard-nosed lender, has attracted criticism for its
affordable mortgage programs and for allegedly cutting lending
after it buys other banks.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the new giant has promised it will not cut spending to
poorer neighborhoods and borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs that the proceedings may turn into a circus
reminiscent of the raucous hearing that accompanied the merger of
CoreStates Financial, a Philadelphia bank, with Charlotte,
N.C.-based First Union last year. At that hearing, community
activists raised a storm of protest over the deal's implications
for low-income housing.
</P>
<P>
   At its trademark aluminum skyscraper in Boston, the Fed plans to
allow 160 people to make five-minute presentations throughout the
day on why the Fleet-BankBoston merger should or should not go
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a prominent New York religious figure and
community activist; US Representative Barney Frank of Newton; and
other leading figures will raise questions about the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting is an opportunity for those with concerns about
the merger to voice them cordially,'' said a Fed spokesman, Thomas
Lavalle.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Marks, a feisty Boston housing activist and a national
poster boy for protesters against bank mergers, promised fire.
``Things could become a mini-riot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks dislike the public hearing process, which they say
encourages activists to blackmail them into spending ever larger
sums on low-income programs and affordable mortgages. Community
groups seize upon hearings as a means for leveraging as much money
as possible out of banks. In the middle are Fed regulators and
Justice Department officials, who are responsible for listening to
complaints about the merger before approving it later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Reinvestment Act, a 1977 federal law, allows
regulators to torpedo mergers involving banks with poor records in
lending to the areas they serve. While regulators almost never
block big mergers, they can put pressure on banks to increase
community spending.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's patrician and relaxed chief executive, Chad
Gifford, who will speak on the merits of his merger with Fleet,
said Tuesday that he ``was about as unnervous for this hearing as
I've ever been.'' Gifford said the new company would lend as much
as each bank individually, minus the amounts the two companies will
shed after divesting branches and deposits to meet antitrust
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the hearing, Gifford's counterpart at Fleet,
Terrence Murray, was less sanguine. Using a hunting metaphor,
Murray, a fiery-tempered Irishman and factory worker's son, said,
``We're in season.'' He added later: ``The key is to be sure that
you don't take anything they say personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who will head the new bank until he retires in 2001, is
dogged by criticism of Fleet's past lending records _ a legacy he
resents. He plans to tell protesters that 35 percent of Fleet's
mortgages nationwide go to lower- to moderate-income borrowers _
above the industry average of 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because the strong economy engenders questions
about what might happen if the boom ends, but community lending is
such a hot topic that not even BankBoston's past strong record is
enough to quell protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston, once bitter rivals, see great irony in all
the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, whose inner-city bank network is among the best
regarded in the banking industry, is the force behind the combined
company's proposal to commit $14.6 billion over five years to
low-income projects, affordable housing programs, small businesses,
and disadvantaged consumers. The proposal, which has been
cautiously welcomed by some community groups, spans eight states,
mostly in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks plan to detail how their multibillion-dollar package
will be spent. About 40 percent of the total package, or more than
$5.8 billion, is earmarked for programs and borrowers in
Massachusetts, Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   The next largest chunk, from $2.9 billion to $4.4 billion, will
go to programs in New York, where Fleet has a major presence.
Around 10 percent to 20 percent of the total package, or $1.5
billion to $2.9 billion, will each go to Connecticut and New
Jersey. Rhode Island will get five percent to 10 percent of the
sum, while New Hampshire, Maine, and Florida will get anywhere from
5 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By merging, Murray and Gifford argue, New England has a better
chance at retaining strong banks that know the community. Had a
financial institution outside the region acquired either bank, the
two men have argued, lending to area small businesses would almost
certainly have dropped. ``The irony as we approach the Fed meeting
was that this deal was a home run for New England,'' Gifford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
