r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OILPRICES-TEX     07-06 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OILPRICES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY OIL PRICE BRIEFLY TOPS $20 A BARREL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A key oil price topped $20 a barrel on
Tuesday for the first time since November 1997, and experts see it
as a signal for energy rigs to get back to work in Texas and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Cross Timbers Oil Co. of Fort Worth is ready to do just that.
The company had trimmed its spending plans to $60 million this
year, from $90 million two years ago. But with the rise in prices,
the company reversed course, and now plans to spend $70 million to
$90 million this year for exploration and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is looking better for oil and gas prices,'' says
Louis Baldwin, a senior vice president for Cross Timbers.
</P>
<P>
   World economic forces are behind the rise in oil prices. The
oil-producing nations have limited their output, and they signalled
yesterday that they intend to adhere to promised production cuts.
At the same, Asian economies are recovering from a slump,
increasing global demand.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, futures contracts for the August delivery of crude
oil crossed $20 a barrel for the first time in 19 months. They
later settled back, closing at $19.78 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The posted price, paid at the wellhead, has cleared $16 for West
Texas Intermediate crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   That is a balm to an industry that has suffered for 18 months
from consolidation, layoffs and other turmoil, as prices fell 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Baker Hughes Rig Count, which measures the number of rigs
drilling for oil, was up last week by 17 nationally, to 580, and by
13 in Texas, to 208. The Texas rig count stood at 200 in the first
week of the year, then plunged to a low of 171 for the week of
April 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more activity in the fields now that people have seen
prices stabilize and some evidence of discipline on the part of
producers,'' said analyst Ken Miller of Purvin &AMP; Gertz, a Houston
energy consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil-producing
nation and the linchpin of OPEC, said on Tuesday that his nation
would stay with production cuts agreed to earlier this year.
Bloomberg News reported that Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates
also said they also would hold the line on production.
</P>
<P>
   Obeid bin Sief al-Nasseri, the UAE oil minister, cautioned
fellow OPEC members not to exploit recent increases in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the good news for producers has not been all bad
news for gasoline consumers. While crude prices are almost double
their lows recorded late last year and early 1999, the price of gas
at the pumps has risen only 20 percent nationally, according to a
Lundberg Survey at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are now waiting to see if the recent oil price spike
was bolstered by the increased demand for gasoline from July 4
travelers. Miller of Purvin &AMP; Gertz thinks it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting prices to drop back a bit, now to the $16.50
to $17 per barrel range,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be one reason the energy producers have not seen their
stocks rise as fast as the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, three Fort Worth companies watched their stock prices
decline yesterday. Union Pacific Resources Group fell 25 cents a
share, to $15.5625, Cross Timbers dropped 12.5 cents to $14.25 and
Range Resources was off 12.5 cents, to $6.3125. Quicksilver
Resources was unchanged at $7.25.
</P>
<P>
   Miller cautions that the supply overhang of oil in U.S.
refineries and pipelines is still almost as high as the record 340
million barrels reported last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest inventory reports show about 330 million barrels
available onshore in the U.S.,'' Miller said. ``So demand will have
to stay very high in order to sustain these prices.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a decline of a couple of dollars a barrel probably
would be acceptable to producers who were looking at $10 prices six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Energy producers in Texas and elsewhere did the logical thing in
the face of such prices: they slashed budgets for exploration and
development. In turn, jobs were lost and equipment sat idle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We capped our capital spending at $500 million for this
year,'' said Dan Sullivan of Union Pacific Resources Group of Fort
Worth. ``Even with that, we really didn't spend much during the
first half of the year because of the price situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan says that while UPR doesn't plan to increase its
capital spending budget for the rest of this year, it will spend
more aggressively within the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said that Cross Timbers will split its extra capital
expenditures on oil and gas wells. Earlier, it had planned to
concentrate almost exclusively on natural gas production.
</P>
<P>
   Like many energy producers, Cross Timbers has focused itself
heavily on natural gas in recent years. Natural gas prices have
stayed consistently above the profit level of $2 per thousand cubic
feet _ they closed at $2.16 on Tuesday _ and gas prices aren't
subject to the whims and politics of international oil markets.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it seems as though the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries has gotten a handle on production and prices.
OPEC let the throttle out in November 1997, and the resulting lack
of discipline among members showered the world with overproduction,
resulting in lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   After several false starts last year and early 1999, OPEC
finally was able to impose some production controls. A survey of
producers by Bloomberg News showed that in June, OPEC producers
made 94 percent of the promised cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC has a goal to reduce production by 7 percent this year, or
about 5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, OPEC at least hasn't added to the oversupply of oil
stocks in the U.S.,'' says Miller. ``But for prices to rise even
higher, that oversupply will have to be reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
