r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-06 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF TODAY IS SHOT, GO FOR TOMORROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Last in their division at the season's midpoint,
10{ games out of first place and no closer to a wild-card playoff
spot, the Los Angeles Dodgers must consider a dramatic solution to
their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up on 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up on the dream of trading for a savior, and instead
seeing the wisdom of trading veterans for prospects to begin
shoring up the team's future.
</P>
<P>
   We raise this possibility now, with weeks to go before the July
31 non-waiver trading deadline and the Aug. 31
playoff-roster-setting deadline, because it might take Dodgers fans
that long to get used to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   It might take Dodgers MANAGEMENT that long to get used to the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's the wise course in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Chase Carey and Peter Chernin, club president Bob Graziano
and general manager Kevin Malone don't seem like men who admit
defeat easily. How embarrassing would it be to acknowledge that
their $84 million team is a bust?
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson isn't close to waiting till next year,
either. ``There's a lot of season (remaining) to put things in
order,'' Johnson said over the weekend, when the Dodgers had lost
six games in a row to sink to the bottom of the National League
West.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have the players packed it in, hard as that might be to
believe, looking at the results. ``I wish I could say we've been
lackadaisical, that we weren't giving a good effort, but I can't,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   So giving up on the season would be painful and unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   It has never been the Dodgers' way.
</P>
<P>
   Most years, when pennant contenders line up to fleece the
noncontenders by dealing unknown youngsters for key veterans, the
Dodgers are among the contenders, if they play that
trading-deadline game at all.
</P>
<P>
   Even this year, the Dodgers don't fit the profile of a
veteran-dumping team, usually a small-market franchise trying to
get !ital!something in exchange for a potential free agent it
couldn't afford to re-sign anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But barring an on-field turnaround (and soon) the Dodgers front
office will face a pivotal decision this month.
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to think about the next century?
</P>
<P>
   If they live for the moment and go after veterans (a shortstop,
a starting pitcher, a middle reliever), they merely continue the
pattern of the past season-and-a-half, during which they've
acquired 14 major-leaguers through trades or free agency, their
desperation only digging them deeper into the quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   But if they go after prospects, they begin a vital and urgent
task, restocking their minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   Once the foundation of a dynasty, the Dodgers' farm system is
barren, the result of lamentable drafts, a tendency to rush
youngsters to the big leagues, and trades like the ones last summer
that sent top prospects Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes to Cincinnati
(for Jeff Shaw) and Peter Bergeron and Ted Lilly to Montreal (along
with Wilton Guerrero and a minor-leaguer) for Mark Grudzielanek,
Carlos Perez and a minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, Triple-A Albuquerque's RBI leader was Wes
Chamberlain, a 33-year-old journeyman outfielder; the home run
leader was Brent Cookson, an outfielder who looked overmatched in
an emergency call-up to Los Angeles last month, and no pitcher had
more than six wins.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the list of All-Stars who were once the unknown parts of
deadline trades for veteran ``pennant insurance'': Jeff Bagwell,
Sammy Sosa, Curt Schilling, Jay Buhner, John Smoltz and Moises
Alou, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Even if finding hidden gems such as those is a rarity, trading
for prospects might look genius-like in a couple of years if it
merely pays off in depth and maneuverability the Dodgers lack now.
</P>
<P>
   One reason they haven't dealt severely with Chan Ho Park's
clueless pitching by sending him to the minor leagues is that
there's nobody worth bringing up to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   First, Malone must decide if it's too soon to give up on this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Is the team underachieving, as the conventional wisdom holds,
and likely to click in the second half? Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitchers are disappointing. But the failures of the
hitters are just as important. In the 26 games in which Dodgers
pitchers have been unspectacular but solid and allowed 3, 4 or 5
runs, the hitters have produced wins for them only 13 times (.500).
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's hard to say the everyday players are doing worse than
expected. Eric Karros, Raul Mondesi, Gary Sheffield and Adrian
Beltre are off to good starts. That's half the lineup. Todd Hundley
(coming off elbow surgery) and Devon White (36 years old) were
question marks to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if Malone decides to concentrate on the future, he has
to decide who he's willing to trade.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's contract might be too big to unload. Trading
21-year-old Beltre would defeat the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But if Boston wants Karros at first base, Cincinnati wants
Mondesi in right field, Texas wants Darren Dreifort on the mound or
Arizona wants Shaw in the bullpen enough to give up young talent,
why should any of them be untouchable?
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers don't make the best of a bad situation now, they
might still be facing this unpleasant decision in July 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
