<HEADER>
A1054 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BARRAQUE-$ADV11     07-06 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BARRAQUE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIANO SONATA CREATED FROM FIRE AND ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(pr) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the dust slowly settles over the second half of the 20th
century, the music of Jean Barraque comes ever more clearly into
view as one of the time's great monuments. Last year his complete
output, of just six big works and an electronic essay, was released
in a set of recordings made by the leading ensemble Klangforum
Wien. Now come two further versions of his Opus 1, the Piano Sonata
of 1950-52, in performances by Pi-Hsien Chen (Telos TLS 006; CD)
and Herbert Henck (ECM 1621; CD).
</P>
<P>
   Barraque's Sonata is an astonishing and challenging achievement
in so many ways. It was written by a man who, in his early 20s,
knew with complete conviction that what was required of him was a
masterwork on the Beethoven level. The work took the highly
fragmented language of immediate postwar Serialism and created from
it a single movement lasting around 40 minutes. It also found,
within a new musical language that was being generally admired (or
despised) as abstract, resources for expressing colossal effort,
heady exhilaration, frustration and, finally, a despair that is
bleak but also life-supporting in being so trustworthy and real.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the piece, in fast or moderate tempos,
oscillates between rampaging passages and others that are still,
fixed around a few notes that go on being repeated in what is
almost a maddening depiction of futility. It is a contrast of fire
_ suggested by how shapes burst into life and re-form within a
supple rhythmic continuity _ and ice. And there can be fire and ice
at the same time, as when beautiful singing melodies, often in a
high register, are combined with cold sequences of notes, or when
the music becomes so violent as to be at once angry and chilling.
</P>
<P>
   These conflicts are not so much resolved as transcended in the
second half, which is slow and much thinner in texture, often
pursuing a single line interrupted by silences, but with occasional
reminiscences of what went before. In some respects, the music
seems to have lifted into the air. In others, it has sunk into an
abyss of hopelessness _ but of hopelessness on the grandest and
most magnificent scale.
</P>
<P>
   The size and technical difficulty of the work deterred
performers for many years. So did Barraque's inconsistency in
matters of rhythmic notation _ a carelessness that may have spoken
for his sense that what mattered was to heave this immense work
onto paper, not to attend scrupulously to its details. Music, for
him, was to be created, not constructed: summoned into being.
Professional etiquette was, at best, an irrelevance.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Loriod made a recording in 1958, but there was no public
performance until 1967, when Elisabeth Klein played the work in
Copenhagen, not knowing that she was giving the world premiere. By
that time the music had been published, in an edition that was
apparently faithful to the problem-filled manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Other pianists performed the Sonata during Barraque's lifetime _
notably Claude Helffer and Roger Woodward, both of whom recorded it
in his presence but neither of whom was able, it would seem, to
persuade him to give definitive answers to questions raised by the
printed music. Only now, 16 years after his death, is a new edition
on the way, prepared by the leading Barraque scholar Heribert
Henrich.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pianists drawn to the piece have had to work out
their own solutions, and Henck, in the note he wrote to accompany
his recording, indicates just what a task this was for him: ``When
I had finished examining the text, an operation that I have to
admit would not satisfy any academic criteria, I had filled 125
handwritten pages with corrections and rhythmic notations.''
</P>
<P>
   He had also, to judge from his recording, filled his mind with
the music. He plays the work with a wonderful fluency, and though
the expressive content is often intense, insistent, even brutal,
the chords, counterpoint and melodies sound right. Often there is a
hint of the composer's beloved Debussy, especially of ``Feux
d'Artifice'' and ``L'Isle Joyeuse.'' It is as if the opals of
Debussy's music had been smashed: the effect is beautiful and
worrying at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chen's recording is also remarkable. She takes a more
sparky, crystalline view of the music than does Henck, especially
in the first part of the work. In a way, this brings it near the
music of Barraque's principal French contemporary, Pierre Boulez,
whose Third Sonata and early ``Notations'' Ms. Chen also includes.
But both she and Henck reveal the Barraque work as having an
imposing continuity and a wide reach far beyond what Boulez was
attempting at that time, or indeed later.
</P>
<P>
   This feeling for the big substance of the piece is missing in
the recording by Stefan Litwin provided in the CPO set, and
Litwin's performance is also dangerously slow. Barraque indicated
tempos only in relative terms, but suggested that the work should
play for about 40 minutes. Litwin extends it to over 54 minutes;
Ms. Chen and Henck are both much more convincing at durations a
little over 45.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chen is a little slower than Henck in the fast music and a
little faster than he is in the finale. Henck's compelling tendency
to push to the extremes adds to the force of his recording. The
Barraque Sonata, like those of Beethoven, is susceptible to very
different interpretations, and Henck's and Ms. Chen's offer
alternative aspects of it. But Henck's recording provides the place
to start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
