<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-REPAYMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-TERM CAPITAL RETURNS $1.3 BILLION TO INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management, the hedge fund whose near failure
last fall rocked world financial markets, returned approximately
$1.3 billion of capital to its investors Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium of 14 financial institutions that injected $3.625
billion into Long-Term Capital in September will receive $1
billion, or 27.5 percent, of their money back under the terms of
the repayment. The other $300 million will be returned to original
outside investors.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the consortium, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said in a statement, ``This is tangible evidence of the
significant risk reduction program that has been achieved'' at the
fund. The statement also noted that after the return of capital,
the portfolio remains ``more than adequately capitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   After Russia defaulted on its debt payments in August, world
bond markets froze and investors fled any instrument that carried
risk. This decimated Long-Term Capital's holdings, causing losses
of about 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the roughly 10 months since the fund's rescue, Long-Term
Capital's much-diminished portfolio has risen in value by 14.1
percent. Year-to-date, the fund is up 4.1 percent. Its portfolio is
valued at approximately $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A Long-Term Capital spokesman said Tuesday's payment means that
all of the hedge fund's outside investors have now had their
interests fully redeemed by the fund. Partners of Long-Term Capital
and the consortium of banks including Citigroup, Morgan Stanley and
Merrill Lynch remain as investors in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Original investors in the Long-Term Capital Fund have endured a
roller-coaster ride since the fund, which is based in Greenwich,
Conn., started in March 1994. One dollar invested at the fund's
outset had grown to be worth $2.78 by the end of 1997. The fund's
management returned money to investors claiming that the
opportunities in world markets were increasingly limited. Then
disaster struck last year. Over the life of the fund, investors
have earned an annual return of around 18 percent, well below the
returns of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index during the period.
</P>
<P>
   The return of capital announced Tuesday gets John Meriwether,
Long-Term Capital's founder, one step closer to being able to raise
money for a new hedge fund. Under the terms of the bailout,
Meriwether cannot start a new fund until he has returned 90 percent
of the consortium's original investment, or $3.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Generating a gain in its portfolio this year puts Long-Term
Capital's returns ahead of some of the biggest, most well-known
hedge funds that have stumbled in 1999. Tiger Management, a hedge
fund with $13 billion managed by Julian Robertson, was down 7.36
percent as of early June. And Quantum Fund, the flagship fund
overseen by George Soros, had lost 14.8 percent at that time.
</P>
<P>
   After years of big returns, these huge hedge funds that make
so-called directional investments, betting on where the price of a
currency, equity or bond will be sometime in the future, have had a
tough time recently. Part of the problem is that the size of their
portfolios makes it difficult to maneuver in any but the deepest
and most liquid markets. But they have also been simply unlucky in
their bets.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller, more specialized funds are doing much better. Still,
hedge funds on average have not been stellar performers. According
to Tremont Advisers, a company in Rye, N.Y., that tracks more than
1,000 hedge funds, the average return during the first quarter of
1999 was a gain of 2.47 percent. A spokesman at the firm, which
only tracks quarterly performance, said second-quarter numbers were
not yet available.
</P>
<P>
   If Long-Term Capital pays the consortium the remainder of the
money it put into the fund last fall, hedge funds' reputations as
investment vehicles may begin to be restored. Hunt Taylor, senior
vice president of Tremont Advisers, said his firm's analysis shows
that using hedge funds as a part of a balanced portfolio does
increase that portfolio's returns and reduce its risk of losses. An
index of pension funds created by the firm showed annual returns of
13.1 percent from January 1990 through the first quarter of this
year. Taylor said that based on hedge fund returns, if a pension
fund had allocated 20 percent of its portfolio to hedge fund
investments, that annual return since 1990 would have risen to 13.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And while the pension fund index's biggest loss from peak to
trough during the period was 9.41 percent, according to Taylor,
with 20 percent of assets in hedge funds, the losses would have
fallen to 7.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we looked at hedge funds,'' Taylor said, ``we found in
almost every category some level of advantage. Either in terms of
their information or their market access or their trading costs.
When you look at the whole body of trading advantages, it amounts
to an inherent return in the discipline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
