<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINTING AUSTRALIAN FALTERS; KIRSIPUU HOLDS ON TO LEAD IN TOUR DE
FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAVAL, France _ Jay Sweet is a 23-year-old Australian in his
first Tour de France who insisted beforehand that he was not
intimidated by most of the greatest sprinters in bicycle racing,
although in his heart he must have known that he was going to a
sword fight armed with a penknife. Then, he crashed twice and badly
sprained his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweet is a sprinter and a good one. Despite his
inexperience, the overall weakness of his Big Mat-Auber team and
now his injury, he has the sprinter's qualities of courage and
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I crashed the first time yesterday, the pain in my ankle
was so, so severe that I thought it was broken,'' he said this
morning. ``When the doctor said it wasn't broken, just sprained, I
said to myself I'll push on to the finish, I'm not going to let
that stop me. Then I went down a second time and I thought it's
definitely not my day.''
</P>
<P>
   In the starting area of the third stage in Nantes, he
brightened. ``But today,'' he continued, his voice underlining the
time element, ``is another day, another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, but not for Sweet, who finished far back as Tom Steels,
a Belgian with the Mapei team, won his second consecutive sprint.
Steels easily finished ahead of Erik Zabel, a German with Telekom,
and Stuart O'Grady, an Australian with Credit Agricole. This was
the 15th time this year that Zabel has finished second in a sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was timed in 4 hours 29 minutes 27 seconds for the
194.5-kilometer (121-mile) spin over moderately rolling terrain
into the likable city of Laval. That was an average speed of 43
kilometers per hour (27 miles per hour), including a high of 67 kph
(41 mph) in the sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In cool sunshine, the stage passed grazing cattle in Brittany's
dairy region and was watched by enormous crowds from start to
finish. So far, this 86th Tour seems to have kept its hold on the
French public despite the drug scandal that nearly scuttled the
last one.
</P>
<P>
   Jaan Kirsipuu, an Estonian with Casino, continued in the yellow
jersey of the overall leader, with time bonuses putting Steels into
second place 17 seconds behind and O'Grady into third 20 seconds
behind. Lance Armstrong, the American leader of U.S. Postal Service
team, was tied with O'Grady, 20 seconds behind Kirsipuu.
</P>
<P>
   An unbroken line of 162 of the remaining 177 riders finished in
the same time as the winner. Forty seconds behind that pack was
Sweet, gamely riding on. The stage Wednesday is also ideal for
sprinters and will offer, as he says, another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking earlier about such champions as Steels, Zabel and Mario
Cipollini, Sweet said: ``Last year, in the Tour Med, I came within
half a wheel of beating Cipo and I came from a long way back, too.
Since then I haven't raced him, so I've been waiting to have
another go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cipollini, who was 10th Tuesday and has been blanked so far in
this Tour, won four daily stages in the recent Giro d'Italia, or
two more than Sweet has won this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian's bravado is typical of sprinters, even when they
do not have the strong teams that the others have _ teams to catch
a breakaway and set the stage for a mass sprint or provide a
leadout, letting the sprinter ride in a slipstream and save some of
his energy for the final dash.
</P>
<P>
   Teams, do it, moreover, to perhaps impede a rival trying to ride
in their leader's slipstream. ``There's a lot of elbowing and
pushing and shoving but there's not much head-butting now,'' Sweet
said. ``Jersey grabbing, that's happened to me once or twice, but
it's a rare thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said slowly. ``Cipollini's got such a strong team,
Zabel's got a strong team, Steels' got a really strong team.'' He
left unsaid that his team, Big Mat-Auber, is a French
second-division team with a small budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I need is perfect positioning in the last kilometer,''
Sweet said. ``If I get a look at the finish line, I'll give it my
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect positioning, however, is not easy to get without some
help. ``Definitely not, not when 50 guys all want the same wheel''
to follow, he acknowledged. ``If I'm lucky enough to hold the wheel
of Cipo and Saeco is giving him a leadout, that's the perfect
opportunity to maybe go for a stage win, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to not having a leadout man, Sweet is also
handicapped by the presence of a second sprinter, Christophe
Capelle, on Big Mat-Auber. ``Obviously, Capelle and I will try to
get organized, but it's difficult,'' Sweet said. ``He's going for
the win and I'm going for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has advantages, too. If he's on the left side of the road
and I'm on the right and it's blocked on the left, maybe I can get
through on the right. Or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Sweet added, ``we might end up on the same side
of the road and both get blocked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
