<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 11,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP (Undated) _ This season belongs to the
kiddie-pop brigades. Applause is passe; the reaction most eagerly
sought by pop culture right now, from music to television to
movies, is a high-pitched squeal from a mob of young girls. When
it's directed at males, that squeal signifies romantic fantasy
while it tests out some newly active hormonal responses. Directed
at females, it's a squeal of sisterly solidarity and fashion
approval. And for the last few years, its volume has been steadily
rising until it threatens to drown out anything with more mature
audiences in mind. Kiddie-pop has always been available to those
who wanted it, but in the late 1990s, it's turning into the only
game in town. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FRANCE (Undated) _ In France, comedy is what we call `une
maladie du regard,' an outlook dooming you to see what is
ridiculous in life,'' said the writer-director Francis Veber. In
Veber's case, comedy has proved to be a malady worth having. In
France, he is like a one-man comedy industry: among the classic
hits that he has created are ``La Cage Aux Folles,'' ``Les
Comperes,'' and ``The Tall Blond Man With One Black Shoe.'' Veber's
most recent movie, ``The Dinner Game,'' (``Le Diner de Cons'')
which opens July 9, has the clash of wills and split-second timing
that are his trademarks. By Laura Winters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-NY-BALLET (New York) _ Since it ain't over till it's over,
it may be premature to declare the New York City Ballet's 50th
anniversary year at an end. The celebration continues through July
24 at the company's summer home, the Saratoga Performing Arts
Center in upstate New York. Nonetheless, the sum went beyond the
parts in the recent City Ballet season at the New York State
Theater. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-FISCHER-DIESKAU (Undated) _ All superlatives for the
artistic impact and record-setting extensiveness of Dietrich
Fischer-Dieskau's singing career have long since been exhausted. It
is to the credit of Bruno Monsaingeon, the director of a
documentary film on the singer just released by Atlantic Records,
that he makes the stale fresh. By Will Crutchfield.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BARRAQUE (Undated) _ As the dust slowly settles over the
second half of the 20th century, the music of Jean Barraque comes
ever more clearly into view as one of the time's great monuments.
By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCULPTURE-ITALY (Pistoia) _ Sculpture gardens bloom in many a
cultured field today. Museums consider them prestigious adjuncts,
cities invest in them as tourist attractions, philanthropists see
them as proof that art is long, life short and bronze a kind of
immortality. In Italy today, the past takes precedence, and
Italians show almost no interest in gardens planted with the work
of living artists. One rare exception is the home of Giuliano Gori,
an industrialist who has created a lovely and uncommon blend of
19th-century Romantic garden and art of the last 20 years at the
Fattoria di Celle, his villa and farm near Pistoia, in Tuscany. By
Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-KIDS (Undated) _ ``SpongeBob Squarepants,'' which has its
official premiere on Saturday, July 17, is not just a new show;
it's the first original Saturday morning series from Nickelodeon,
the cable channel that has owned Saturday morning for the last few
years. By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTIFACTS-HUGUENOTS (New York) _ When looking at good English
silver from the 17th and 18th centuries, one should remember that
it was meant to be seen by the flicker of candlelight. In such
light, silver shimmers with the fluidity of water. Seen under
lighting that suggests candlelight, the 112 pieces of silver in
``The Huguenot Legacy: English Silver 1680-1760,'' an exhibition at
the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum in Manhattan, is like a
glittering ocean with more than a few lobsters, dolphins and water
monsters surfacing in the decor of the objects. By Paula Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
