<HEADLINE>
BLOCK TO U.N. NOMINEE IS APPARENTLY SENATE LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Ky., Miss., Ohio)   (rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Majority Leader Trent Lott, whose office
has refused to identify the two senators secretly blocking a final
confirmation vote on Richard Holbrooke as chief diplomat to the
United Nations, turns out to be one of the two, government
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lott placed a secret ``hold'' on the long-stalled nomination of
Holbrooke in an effort to pressure the White House to name a
conservative Ohio law school professor to the Federal Election
Commission, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have opposed the selection of the Ohio
professor, Bradley Smith, because his writings suggest that he
opposes most campaign finance regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The other lawmaker secretly blocking the nomination is Sen.
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., a government official said, but this could
not be confirmed elsewhere. McConnell has championed Smith's
appointment to the Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The hold means that _ for reasons that have nothing to do with
Holbrooke's qualifications and may have a lot to do with the
partisan debate over campaign finance laws _ a final Senate vote on
the nomination could be delayed several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Relations Committee approved the nomination of
Holbrooke, the former American ambassador to Germany and architect
of the 1995 peace agreement that ended the war in Bosnia, on a
unanimous voice vote last week.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's nomination was announced in June of last year, but
the nomination papers were not forwarded to the Senate for eight
months because of a federal ethics investigation of Holbrooke that
ended without criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   A third Republican senator, Charles E. Grassley of Iowa, has
blocked a vote on Holbrooke's nomination for different reasons,
involving the unrelated case of a State Department whistleblower.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Grassley, who has long called for an end to
the Senate tradition of allowing secret holds on nominations, has
acknowledged his role in preventing a vote on Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, whose office manages the holds, has not acknowledged his
role, and his spokesman said that the senator had no comment on the
issue Tuesday. Spokesmen for McConnell did not return repeated
calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Holbrooke's nomination last week, Lott, a
Mississippi Republican, said that Holbrooke ``has some problems
right now and we'll have to see how that works out.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator did not detail the problems, nor did he give any
hint that he was one of the lawmakers holding up the nomination.
His spokesman refused last week to identify the senators blocking
the vote beyond Grassley or to explain the reasons for the holds.
</P>
<P>
   The secret move to block the nomination has been described by
Democrats as a violation of the spirit of a recent agreement
between Democratic and Republican leaders intended to curtail the
Senate's arcane practice of secret ``holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate rules designed to encourage consensus, any lawmaker
can delay a final vote on a nomination or legislation indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   But under the agreement last February designed to end some of
the secrecy, Democrats and Republicans decided that senators
seeking a hold had to identify themselves to both the Senate
majority leader _ Lott _ and the chairman of the committee with
jurisdiction over the nomination or legislation _ in this case,
Jesse Helms, chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, neither Lott nor Helms was talking, so the
identity of the two lawmakers remained secret. A spokesman for
Helms did not return calls Tuesday. The White House had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's nomination appears now to be tied to the makeup of
the Federal Election Commission, which regulates campaign finance
laws. Under its rules, the six-member commission is made up of
three Democrats and three Republicans, who are appointed by the
president and confirmed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican leadership wants to fill a Republican
vacancy with Smith of Capital University Law School in Columbus,
whose writings have questioned the constitutionality of federal
campaign finance laws. The White House has resisted the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley has said that his hold on Holbrooke's nomination will
remain in effect until the State Department reaches an
accommodation with Linda Shenwick, a budget specialist in the U.S.
mission to the United Nations. Ms. Shenwick has charged that she is
being forced from her job because she provided damaging information
about the United Nations to members of Congress and to reporters.
The State Department has denied her claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
