<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRITISH TELECOM ORDERED TO OPEN NETWORK TO RIVALS
</P>
<P>
   Already under pressure from rival telephone and cable operators,
British Telecommunications, which controls about 85 percent of the
``local loop'' copper network used by home subscribers and small
businesses, was ordered by regulators to upgrade its network and
open it to competitors by July 2001. The directive reflects the
rapidly intensifying competition in Europe to offer high-speed
Internet access and other broadband services. But it also
highlights the difficult situation facing the former state
monopoly: competition is likely to accelerate the growth of the
high-speed market, but it could also reduce British
Telecommunications' slice of it.
</P>
<P>
   BILL COULD CREATE NEW TYPE OF BANK
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what a Congressional conference committee does,
legislation that would overhaul the nation's financial system could
include a provision for wholesale banks, which would take only
large deposits and do everything else a commercial bank does.
</P>
<P>
   OIL PRICES APPROACH $20 A BARREL
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil rose to a 19-month high, near $20 a barrel, on signs
that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would adhere
to its promised production cuts in the months ahead. King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil-producing nation and OPEC's
most influential member, said that his country would stick with its
cuts. Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates also said the output
reductions should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   LATE SELLOFF PUSHES STOCKS LOWER
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon selloff pulled stock prices down from early gains.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 4.12 points, to 11,135.12.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.10 points, or
two-tenths of a percent, to 1,388.12, and the Nasdaq composite
index fell 4.24 points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 2,736.78.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell, sending yields to their highest level in a
week. The yield on the 30-year issue rose to 6.03 percent from 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. SUES BOEING OVER BIAS INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual legal tussle between the government and its
second-largest military contractor, the Department of Labor filed
three lawsuits against Boeing, contending that the company was
blocking its investigation of charges of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH CASTS LIGHT ON FRANKEL'S LIFE
</P>
<P>
   The death of a woman two years ago at the Greenwich, Conn., home
of Martin Frankel provides an unusual insight into the life of
Frankel, who is suspected of defrauding insurance companies in
several states of hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN BUSINESSMEN AID CHARITY
</P>
<P>
   Although Russian businessmen are often vilified as exploiters
and tax cheats, many are making significant contributions to
nonprofit causes. The largest donation made by a Russian company or
individual since 1917 came from Vladimir Potanin, who runs a
financial-industrial group called Interros. He gave $1.4 million to
support the reconstruction of the Rostral Columns, one of St.
Petersburg's historic landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   BATHROOM HUMOR WORKS FOR FILM AD
</P>
<P>
   The advertising campaign for the film ``Big Daddy,'' which shows
two actors poised as if urinating, represents what may be the first
time that a major Hollywood studio has sold a mainstream movie on
the basis of a bodily function. But the ads have received almost
universal acceptance by the media and few complaints.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN OFFICIAL TO HEAD COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to political pressure to reduce the role of foreign
investors, the board of Russia's largest shipping company, Far
Eastern Shipping, elected Aleksandr Lugovets, Russia's deputy
transportation minister, as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   PURCHASING INDEX SHOWS GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management reported that
its index of nonmanufacturing business rose last month, suggesting
the economy will continue to expand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
