<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT     07-06 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY TAKES ANOTHER BIG STEP TOWARD SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton filed Tuesday with the Federal Election
Commission to form a committee to run for U.S. Senate in New York
next year, taking a formal step toward becoming the only wife of a
sitting president in American history to actively seek elective
office.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of a so-called exploratory committee allows Mrs.
Clinton to raise money for travel, advertising, polling and other
expenses in her effort to succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a
Democrat, who is retiring next year after 24 years in office.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mrs. Clinton, who has never lived in New York
state, is to begin a four-day ``listening tour'' through central
New York, starting at Moynihan's farm in Delaware County and
continuing through Oneonta, Cooperstown, Utica, Rome, Syracuse and
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is not expected to face a challenge in next
year's Democratic primary. She is widely expected to face New York
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, who formed his own
exploratory committee in April.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, has
indicated that he also plans to run for the Senate despite
Giuliani's far-wider name recognition and already formidable
advantage in campaign fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has taken to mocking the Mrs. Clinton repeatedly in
recent weeks for seeking public office in a state where she has
never resided. To that end, Giuliani has planned a campaign trip
later this month to Arkansas, where Mrs. Clinton used to live.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in response to a question about Mrs. Clinton's
impending visit to New York, Giuliani said that he was far more
knowledgeable about New York state than his reputation as the
consummate urbanite might suggest. ``I have a great deal of
knowledge of the state of New York, far more than you actually
think I do because you know you think of me as being the mayor of
New York City,'' Giuliani told reporters at his daily news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who often takes great glee in his image as a
Flatbush-born, maniac Yankee fan wholly devoted to the hometown he
modestly refers to as the Capital of Everything, instead stressed
his ties to places like Saratoga, Lake George, Utica and Elmira.
``I have always spent a great deal of time upstate. I know Saratoga
really well. I have been to Lake George. I worked in Syracuse and I
worked in Utica and I have worked in Albany and I have worked in
Binghamton and I have worked in other parts of the state,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani apparently spent the time upstate when he worked as a
law clerk to a judge after graduating from New York University Law
School in 1968. The mayor's press secretary, Sunny Mindel, did not
respond to requests Tuesday for specific details about his upstate
work experience.
</P>
<P>
   Those details are likely to become an issue as the campaign
develops and suburban and upstate voters begin to consider whether
Giuliani, as the mayor of New York City, is any more familiar with
their local needs and concerns than Mrs. Clinton is in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani believes he is. ``Every time I have gone up there, I
have gotten the sense that they like me,'' he said of upstate
voters Tuesday. `` I think they like what I did with New York
City.''
</P>
<P>
   But in yet another example of the difficulty that both
candidates will have in navigating unfamiliar terrain, Giuliani
also said he spent Monday relaxing with his son in Monroe County. A
spokeswoman, Jennifer Chait, later said he had actually been in
Monroe, N.Y., which is in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Tuesday morning, Mrs. Clinton remained at the
White House while Lynn Utrecht, an expert in elections law who is
serving as general counsel to Mrs. Clinton's committee, brought the
single-page filing form to the Federal Election Commission's
downtown offices.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Utrecht was accompanied by Howard Wolfson, the committee's
press secretary, who addressed a crowd of about 10 television crews
that had gathered in the suffocating heat outside the commission's
offices just across the street from the headquarters of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, Wolfson said, ``Over the next months, Mrs.
Clinton will travel throughout the state meeting with New Yorkers
in small groups and listening to them discuss the issues that
concern them the most.'' He added, ``Thank you and see you in New
York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
