<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UAW-HEALTHCARE-NYT &LR;      07-06 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAW-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST OF PRESCRIPTION DRUGS TOPS HEALTH ISSUES IN UAW TALKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Tenn.)   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The soaring cost of prescription drugs for aging auto
workers and retirees is the top health care issue in national labor
talks pitting the United Automobile Workers union against General
Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler AG, auto executives said.
</P>
<P>
   While many industries face rising costs for pharmaceutical
benefits, the auto makers said they had particularly acute
problems. Benefits consultants, who compare costs in various
industries, agree.
</P>
<P>
   Including the cost of covering retirees and their spouses,
Ford's expense is now approaching $2,800 annually for each active
hourly worker. That is roughly six times the typical cost in large
companies, which commonly include retiree costs in such
calculations but seldom have as many retirees, compared to active
workers, as the three auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   The auto makers' costs for prescription benefits are also rising
10 percent to 18 percent a year, the companies said. This is
squeezing profits because new automobile prices have stayed
virtually flat.
</P>
<P>
   The union opposes broad changes in its members' health plan when
current labor contracts with the auto makers expire on Sept. 14. On
the other hand, the union has worked with the auto makers on some
minor modifications, such as suggesting that workers choose less
expensive generic versions of drugs when they are available.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW contended that since some new medicines address ailments
previously requiring hospital treatment, the auto makers should use
the savings to cover pharmaceuticals. Workers should not be asked
to pay more for medicines that save money for employers, the union
said in a recent, book-length resolution outlining its bargaining
goals, adding, ``Such shell games must be resisted.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the labor talks is likely to influence companies
and workers in many other industries, because of the auto
industry's sheer size. The final settlement here could affect the
debate in Congress over President Clinton's proposal last week to
add prescription drug benefits to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the Medicare debate is likely to focus on whether
the costs of a federal prescription benefit program can be
controlled. The labor negotiations here will revolve around the
same issue and are expected to be concluded first.
</P>
<P>
   GM is the nation's largest corporate provider of pharmaceutical
benefits, covering 1.5 million employees and retirees along with
their spouses and dependents. This includes salaried employees,
whose benefits are kept similar to those negotiated for unionized
workers. Ford covers 650,000 Americans and DaimlerChrysler another
400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The three auto makers' benefits costs are particularly high
partly because their work forces are relatively old _ the average
age ranges from 43 at DaimlerChrysler to 48 at GM After hiring few
workers over the last quarter of a century, the three unionized
auto makers also have as many retirees as active workers.
</P>
<P>
   Their pharmaceutical plans are generous, with no monthly fees
and few restrictions on the number of prescriptions, although plan
participants must make a small co-payment, typically $2 to $5, each
time a prescription is filled. While Clinton's plan would initially
limit Medicare's annual payments per person to $1,000, rising to
$2,500 by 2008, there is no such limit on annual payments in the
health plans for current and retired auto workers and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers and the union have not taken a position on the plan
but are likely to support it. The president's proposal calls for
subsidies to companies already offering prescription benefits to
retirees, so as to dissuade businesses from abandoning their plans
and shifting their retirees' pharmaceutical costs on to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Costs have soared for new, so-called life-style drugs, notably
Viagra, an impotence medicine, auto executives said. One reason,
they said, is that the Food and Drug Administration weakened its
restrictions on the advertising of pharmaceuticals in 1997,
allowing drug companies to bolster demand for their products.
``Many individuals as patients are going to their physicians and
demanding drugs that they've seen on television,'' said Preston M.
Crabill, GM's director of health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former union officials share auto executives'
criticisms of pharmaceutical companies' advertising, saying that it
drives up costs. They say that overall costs for the benefits
should be controlled, but not in ways that penalize the health or
pocketbooks of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll always find a sympathetic ear from us, because that's
$2,800 a year you can't spend on wages, pensions and so forth,''
said Douglas Fraser, a former president of the UAW.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign auto makers with operations in the United States were
also complaining about rapidly climbing pharmaceutical costs. While
only their joint ventures with Detroit auto makers are unionized,
the foreign auto makers have chosen to offer the same benefits
packages nationwide to discourage broader unionization. The cost of
these benefits is rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be the nature of the medical business right now,
everybody's looking at skyrocketing drug costs,'' said Thomas P.
Groom, the director of human resources at the Nissan Motor
Manufacturing Corp. USA in Smyrna, Tenn. But the foreign auto
makers have few retirees so far, and their work forces are still
fairly young, so their costs per active worker are much lower.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has begun steering employees toward generic drugs by
setting lower co-payments for them and higher co-payments for
costlier medicines still under patent. DaimlerChrysler made the
same change for its nonunion, salaried workers at the start of this
year, and found that it helped control costs in the first quarter
of 1999, said Nancy Rae, the company's vice president for
compensation and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has long resisted such changes. Union officials maintain
that financial considerations should not discourage workers from
seeking the best possible medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives declined to discuss specific negotiating
positions on how to control costs.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and union officials differ on how much blame for
rising costs should be given to new medicines like Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Executives cite the introduction of Viagra last year to
illustrate the problem of rising costs. Union officials said that
while heavy advertising for Viagra may have increased demand,
emphasizing an impotence medicine trivializes the overall problem.
</P>
<P>
   At GM, Viagra accounted for $10 million of the $676 million in
prescription benefit costs last year, but the cost has leveled off
this year, the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
