<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-ART-NYT &LR;      07-06 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PROVINCIAL TOWN, A CHORUS OF `NO' TO MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
(ART ADV: A graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UZICE, Yugoslavia _ About half an hour before the rally against
President Slobodan Milosevic was to begin Wednesday night, the town
square was mostly empty, but the police were there, scowling.
</P>
<P>
   Then, within the minutes it took worried opposition politicians
organizing the protest to walk two blocks from their headquarters
to the central square, more than 10,000 citizens materialized, many
of them parents with small children in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The police, who had declared the rally illegal, used force to
prevent a sound system from being erected, but the crowd peacefully
overwhelmed them and speakers were set up. For more than an hour
the crowd shouted that Milosevic must give up power _ and soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are a lot of us, they will not use force,'' Zoran
Djindjic, the opposition leader who returned from self-imposed
exile two days ago, told the crowd. He fled during the Kosovo war
after he said that paramilitary thugs loyal to Milosevic had
threatened to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be brave. It will be a hot summer, hotter than any summer that
has come before,'' he said, adding that in the next three months he
expects daily demonstrations in cities across Serbia. He also said
he expects the Serbian Orthodox Church, which last month demanded
that Milosevic resign, to join the opposition in calling for a
nationwide general strike.
</P>
<P>
   No speaker said anything to criticize NATO, which during the
Kosovo war, flattened the post office here and destroyed the local
telephone exchange. Nearly all of Uzice, an industrial town of
62,000 people about 120 miles southwest of Belgrade, is still
without phone service. As the crowd gazed Wednesday night at the
rally's speakers, they could see beyond them to the ruins of the
post office. But it was never mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bombed us because our wrong politics are not in accord
with the rest of the world,'' said Ljubise Maksimovic, 46, a
railroad foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's rally went silent shortly after it began when
the police unplugged a power cord that ran into a private apartment
facing the town square. The sound system came back on when rally
organizers fired up a gasoline-powered generator.
</P>
<P>
   From the elevated edge of the town square, opposition speakers
shifted back and forth Wednesday night between denouncing Milosevic
for ``shaming'' Serbia and mocking members of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, a philosopher and key opposition leader who helped
lead street rallies two years ago that brought tens of thousands of
people in the streets of Belgrade daily for nearly three months,
said, ``In the last 10 years, four times we went into war with
tanks and four times Serbs came back from war on tractors,''
referring to lost wars in Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and, this year,
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst ruler in the history of the world.'' Mr.
Djindjic said. ``We will not allow them to provoke a new war _ a
civil war in this country. The maximum that we demand and the
minimum that we will accept, is this: He must go away before new
elections are held.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing the possibility of any negotiations with the
Milosevic regime, an approach advocated by the largest single
Serbian opposition party, Djindjic said, ``It is too late for
negotiations. We don't have time for a transitional government. The
end of this regime is necessary for the survival of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers focused on Marko Milosevic, 25, the president's
son and a well-connected entrepreneur whom American intelligence
officials have said is a major cigarette smuggler in Serbia. This
weekend he opened a private sports theme park called Bambipark,
which he and other investors built during the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is spending $380,000 dollars on Bambipark while we have
columns of Serbian refugees coming back from Kosovo,'' said
Miroslav Martovic, deputy mayor of Uzice, as the crowd whistled and
booed.
</P>
<P>
   Uzice, a city ruled by an opposition coalition since 1996, was
once a prosperous manufacturing town, with copper, aluminum and
car-parts factories.
</P>
<P>
   Before Yugoslavia began to fall apart in 1991, this city was the
country's second largest earner of foreign currency, exporting
goods worth about $100 million a year, according to the mayor,
Milan Nikitovic. Those hard currency earnings, the mayor said, have
slipped to zero this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we export only fog,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Protests boiled over again Wednesday in Leskovac, a town in
Milosevic's traditional base of southern Serbia. About two thousand
protesters clashed with police day in the town, not far from the
border with Kosovo. They were demanding the release of a local
television technician who had been arrested and sentenced to 30
days in jail on Monday for an unusual protest.
</P>
<P>
   The TV employee, Ivan Novkovic, started the ball rolling in
Leskovac on Friday when a large TV audience was watching a
basketball game between Yugoslavia and Germany in the European
championship tournament.
</P>
<P>
   During half-time, Novkovic, who works for TV Leskovac, switched
off regular programming and broadcast a videotape starring himself.
In it, he denounced a local political boss who belongs to the
hard-line Yugoslav Left Party headed by Milosevic's wife, Mirjana
Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   That programming change, which left Novkovic unemployed and
which made him into a national celebrity, ignited the unplanned
demonstration Monday in Leskovac, which mushroomed from a march
against an unpopular local politician into a rowd of 20,000 people.
Local press accounts described the protest as the largest
demonstration calling for the resignation of Milosevic since the
end of the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   That crowd, according to local news reports, included many
disgruntled Yugoslav army reservists who fought in Kosovo and who
joined the crowd in shouting, ``Go Away Slobo'' and ``Leskovac is
No Longer Red.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Uzice the adventures of Novkovic in southern Serbia were
seized upon as a sign that popular discontent with Milosevic may
run much deeper than anyone had dared hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man called them on TV and 20,000 people went to the
central square without a single political leader _ that's the real
stuff,'' said Slobodan Vuksanovic, a leader of the Alliance for
Change, the umbrella group that called the rally here and is
organizing a string of demonstrations in small and medium-sized
towns in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a signal that shows what we all know and what we
sometimes forget,'' said Vuksanovic. ``People are sick of
politicians. They desperately need an alternative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
