u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-GUARDS07-COX     07-06 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-GUARDS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas prisoner escape plays up guard shortage
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas' highest-security prison was short 31
guards when a Dallas murderer escaped last week, and officials said
Tuesday that they are investigating whether the job vacancies could
have been a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they were not, prison officials said the staffing
shortage at the Estelle High-Security Unit near Huntsville
highlights a growing problem throughout the Texas prison system _
too few guards.
</P>
<P>
   At that unit, officials said only 167 of the 198 guard jobs on
three shifts were filled when Clifford Dwayne Jones escaped June 27
by scaling two tall fences and leaping over a third. He was
captured 49 hours later, treed in muddy swamps less than three
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be looking at whether the manpower shortage at
that unit was a factor,'' said A.M. ``Mack'' Stringfellow, a member
of the prison's system's nine-member governing board who is heading
an official investigation of the escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost positive we were above the minimum staffing level
on the day it happened, but the vacancy rates are definitely a
concern there and at almost every other prison in Texas right
now,'' Stringfellow said. ``We are understaffed throughout the
entire system.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoed board Chairman Allan Polunsky: ``Any time you operate at
less than 100 percent you risk problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the shortage of prison guards has increased during
the past year _ a problem that officials attribute to Texas'
booming economy, low pay and less-than-desirable working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great job if you like low pay, bad working conditions,
a foul-smelling work space _ and if you like dangerous criminals
cursing at you all day,'' one Huntsville area guard said after the
escape last week, when he called the Austin American-Statesman to
complain about the chronic staffing shortage. ``It's no wonder the
system is having trouble filling jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Texas' prison agency had 1,068 job openings for
guards _ 5 percent of the number authorized. Currently, 23,755
guards staff posts at the 112 prisons and state-run lockups. Texas'
prison system houses 145,000 convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pay for prison guards is just over $17,724 a year,
$25,524 after 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a victim of a good economy,'' said Gary Johnson, prisons
director for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice. ``People are
simply leaving for other jobs that pay more, and even though we're
putting four- to five-hundred new officers a month in training, we
just can't keep up with the attrition rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some large prisons are running up to 80 guards short, Johnson
said, while others are fully staffed. Hardest hit are prisons in
the Palestine and Huntsville areas, and in Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Heightening officials' concern over the vacancies is that the
first of four new prisons just like the Estelle High-Security Unit
are scheduled to open between October and April 2000, adding 792
guard jobs to a hiring list that Johnson and Polunsky say already
is too big.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the record vacancy rate, Johnson and Janie
Cockrell, the prison system's security director, said Tuesday that
all ``primary positions'' _ the guards in convict cellblocks and
dorms, in hallways, in guard towers and manning security doors _
are being manned. Secondary guard jobs _ such as outside work
details _ are going begging at some prisons, they said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Estelle High-Security Unit, Johnson said, ``the escort
officers, the rec yard officers, the outside perimeter officer _
all those posts were manned just like they should have been. Even
if we had full staffing there, I don't think it would have made a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's something we're going to be looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell said officials have been able to maintain proper
security by paying overtime and juggling vacations. ``This is
really more of a management problem than it is a security
problem,'' Cockrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, to reduce an attrition rate among guards that reached
18 percent last year and is expected to hit 20 percent this year,
officials have launched a vigorous campaign to find new recruits.
In addition to newspaper and radio ads, career days at community
colleges and recruiting trips to military bases, they offer rewards
for employees who recruit new guards.
</P>
<P>
   Posters have even been tacked up at some prisons urging guards
not to resign _ a tactic Johnson said was started after officials
noticed that 30 former guards a day were reapplying with the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salary and stresses of the job are the two biggest
detractors to these jobs,'' said Larry Todd, a prison system
spokesman. ``Just like the ballet is not for everyone, being a
correctional officer is not for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
