<HEADER>
A1096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEAMSTERS-APPOINT-ART     07-06 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-APPOINT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFA CHOOSES FORMER U.S. PROSECUTOR FOR TEAMSTER'S CLEAN-UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mich., Belgium)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James P. Hoffa, the new president of the teamsters' union, plans
to hire a respected former federal prosecutor to set up an in-house
anti-corruption program for the 1.4-million-member union _ the
first step in an effort to persuade the federal government to end
its decade-long oversight of the teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Teamster officials said Tuesday that Hoffa had selected Edwin H.
Stier _ who oversaw the cleanup of what was often called the
nation's most corrupt union local _ because of his track record in
working with unions to rid them of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Several teamster officials and labor experts said Hoffa's choice
of a well-known crime fighter showed that he was making a serious
first step toward attacking corruption in a union that was long
viewed as the nation's most mob-dominated. In this way, the labor
experts said, Hoffa appeared to be taking a more sincere
anti-corruption stance than did his father, James P. Hoffa, a
former teamsters president who was widely linked to racketeers and
went to prison after being convicted for fraud and jury tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Szymanski, general counsel of the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, said Stier's responsibilities would
include educating the union's members about ethical standards and
training them to investigate allegations of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the union can have true reform unless we show we
can handle our problems in a responsible fashion,'' said Szymanski.
``We have to do that ourselves. It can't be imposed from the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Teamster officials announced Stier's appointment three weeks
after Hoffa wrote the Justice Department to ask it to begin a
dialogue that the union hopes will lead to shrinking and perhaps
ending government oversight of the union. In 1989, the teamsters
agreed to far-reaching government supervision, which included a
court-appointed investigations officer and election monitor, to
settle a federal racketeering lawsuit that charged the union with
being controlled by the mob.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Hoffa wrote, ``The union will assume full
responsibility for proceeding with the reforms which the government
has initiated, obviating the necessity for continued government
supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   Szymanski said Hoffa had chosen Stier because the union
president respected Stier's work in rooting out corruption from
Teamsters Local 560, a New Jersey-based local notorious for being
dominated by mobsters. For decades, the 4,400-member local was
controlled by Anthony (Tony Pro) Provenzano, a Mafia boss who was
convicted of murder and who law-enforcement officials say had a
hand in the 1975 disappearance of Hoffa's father.
</P>
<P>
   Stier, who once headed New Jersey's Division of Criminal
Justice, said he was taking the job because he was convinced that
Hoffa was serious about attacking corruption _ although one
prominent union faction, Teamsters for a Democratic Union, has
insisted Hoffa has links to criminal elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that I've seen and heard,'' Stier said, ``suggests
to me that he is completely serious about dealing effectively with
corruption and dealing with it in an even-handed way that doesn't
just go after his political enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   As trustee of Local 560 for 12 years, Stier had more than a
dozen officials removed or expelled for misconduct including having
ties to organized crime. He often braved threats against him, he
helped restore the welfare and pension fund to financial health,
and he worked closely with the FBI to uncover corruption in the
local.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Judge Harold A. Ackerman of the U.S. District Court
in Newark lifted the trusteeship, confident that Stier had rid
Local 560 of criminal elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Local 560 experiment was about transforming the
culture of a union from tolerance of racketeering to one of
rejection of racketeering,'' Stier said in a telephone interview
while vacationing in Brussels. ``I think a lot of the strategies
that I used over the last 12 years in helping the local transform
itself will be useful for the whole international union.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in New York who is the Justice
Department official in charge of monitoring the teamsters, declined
to comment on the appointment of Stier or about Hoffa's call to end
federal supervision.
</P>
<P>
   In the past she has said she looked forward to working wth Hoffa
to insure progress in cleaning up the union. She has also said the
fight against corruption in the teamsters is not complete,
considering that over the past few years more than 200 teamster
officials or members have been removed or pressured to resign after
facing corruption charges from a court-appointed review board.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor experts applauded Hoffa's appointment of Stier.
``I don't think he could have picked a better person for the job,''
said Linda Kaboolian, an associate professor of labor relations at
Harvard's Kennedy School of government. ``Compared with other
trusteeships, he stands out head and shoulders above everyone else
for the way he conducted the trusteeship and the results he got.''
</P>
<P>
   But some labor relations experts questioned whether Hoffa might
be appointing Stier less to clean up the union than to impress the
government that Hoffa was putting in place his own anti-corruption
program. Richard Hurd, a Cornell University professor of labor
relations, asked whether Hoffa might someday fire Stier, the way
President Richard Nixon once fired the special prosecutor Archibald
Cox, if Stier's anticorruption mechanism targets Hoffa or his close
allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naming Stier is the kind of thing you'd expect a reformer to
do, not the kind of thing you'd expect someone who had questionable
intentions,'' Hurd said. ``I'm reluctant to say this is proof that
Hoffa is serious, but it's certainly a positive sign. The truth
will be in how it plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   Stier said that he expected his title to be special counsel and
that he would quit if he grew convinced that Hoffa was not serious
about fighting corruption or was undercutting him. He said he could
not give details of his plans because he still has to work many
things out with the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective,'' Stier said, ``is when there is an allegation
against anybody at whatever level _ and that includes the executive
board _ then that allegation will be thoroughly and impartially
investigated and if it's found to be true, the members of the union
and the people in power, even if it's an ally of theirs, will view
that as a betrayal and not just a guy doing what comes natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Stier, 59, once worked as director of the criminal division for
the U.S. attorney in Newark and for five years was head of the
organized crime division in the office of the New Jersey attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Brandt, a spokesman for Rep. Pete Hoekstra, a Michigan
Republican who heads the Oversight Subcommittee of the House
Education and the Workforce Committee which has held many hearings
on teamsters scandals, said, ``As long as Stier is given the
freedom that he needs to do his job then this is a very positive
step forward for the teamsters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
