<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-HNS &LR;      07-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESSES CALL FOR INVESTMENT IN POOR COMMUNITIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. _ Normally, the only presidential attention
drawn by a new Walgreens would come from the local head of the
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But in this distressed Mississippi River city, President Clinton
on Tuesday toured a month-old drugstore that is the largest retail
store to be built here in 40 years, calling it proof that private
investment can rally not only businesses but entire communities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his delegation of corporate chiefs and Cabinet
members traveled up the Mississippi Valley, from the impoverished
flatlands of the Mississippi Delta to this struggling town as they
continued their tour of hard-pressed regions left out of the
nation's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Americans benefit when all Americans work,'' Clinton told
1,000 people gathered outside the Walgreens.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the president's emphasis on private-sector
investment, the Bank of America announced it was creating a $500
million Catalyst Fund to invest in projects in economically
depressed areas around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Bessant, president of community development for Bank of
America, said the fund would be just what its name implies, ``a
catalyst for our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America also helped finance the construction of the
Walgreens here.
</P>
<P>
   And, Walgreens' President David Bernauer announced that the drug
chain would build 400 more stores nationwide, many of them in
impoverished areas, and add 10,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walgreens is very committed to serving Americans in every type
of neighborhood,'' Bernauer said.
</P>
<P>
   This small city of 38,000 located across the Mississippi River
from St. Louis, Mo., was once a thriving shipping community
dominated by stockyards and meat-packing companies. But as the jobs
disappeared so did the people. Its population declined 45 percent
in 25 years. The jobless rate, at 9.6 percent, is twice the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a lure to potential businesses, Clinton also touted a
new Department of Housing and Urban Development report that claims
people living in inner cities have about $8.7 billion in potential
purchasing power and that this spending potential far outstrips
retail sales in their areas.
</P>
<P>
   The survey compared the estimated purchasing power with the
amount of retail sales in a city. The gap exists, the HUD report
said, because some poorer communities are dramatically underserved
by retail stores and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that nationwide, residents in poor, inner-city
neighborhoods earn 25 percent more money than they spend in their
neighborhoods. In Los Angeles the gap is 35 percent, and in East
St. Louis it is 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As he has throughout the trip, Clinton promoted his New Markets
Initiative, a mixture of tax incentives for corporate investment
and government assistance, to encourage the economic revival of
areas long burdened by poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing that we encourage people to invest
in Africa, Latin America and the Caribbean, but they ought to have
the same incentives to invest in the Mississippi Delta and
Appalachia and the Native American reservations and the inner
cities,'' Clinton said to cheers at an earlier stop in Clarksdale,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   In Clarksdale, Clinton toured a section of the small downtown
where shops, restaurants and a movie theater have been shuttered
for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-six years ago, on Friday and Saturday, this place was
crawling with people _ it was shoulder-to-shoulder,'' said Mayor
Richard Webster. But as agriculture and other industries became
more mechanized, laborers lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to bring back a different type of labor _ bring
back tourism,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   But there also were signs of success. Clinton toured the
Waterfield Cabinet plant that was reopened after being in
bankruptcy. He also heard from several area business owners who
struggled to get the investments they needed to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in America has a selfish interest now in developing
the Delta. Why? Because most economists believe that if we're going
to keep our economic recovery going without inflation, the only way
we can possibly do it is to find more customers for our products
and then add more workers at home,'' Clinton told several hundred
people sweltering in the cabinet-making plant, which lacks air
conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   While in Clarksdale, the president announced $46.5 million in
community development grants, including $15 million for the
Mississippi Delta, where, he said, poverty and unemployment rates
far exceed national averages.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America's Bessant and Richard Huber, chairman of Aetna,
have spent the week traveling with Clinton to Kentucky, Mississippi
and Illinois, and both support the New Markets Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're ever going to get a few of these areas jump-started
it has to be now,'' Huber said, praising Clinton's initiative for
``having some rationale'' behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have all the incentives in the world and if there
isn't economic reality to draw investors, it isn't going to
happen,'' Huber said. But he said the historically poor regions
provide an untapped market for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's real money to be made in these markets,'' Bessant
said. But she said those regions also are a hard sell to investors,
which is why government incentive programs are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of incentives really attract private sector
investments that otherwise might not be interested,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will continue the tour today with a visit to the Pine
Ridge Indian Reservation in South Dakota and a visit to a
Mexican-food factory in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The president was to end his trip Thursday in Los Angeles but
now may stay in California through Saturday to watch the United
States squad play in the women's World Cup soccer match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TOUR-BOS &LR;      07-06 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES RETAIL DEVELOPMENT IN POVERTY AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. _ Midway through his four-day anti-poverty
tour across America, President Clinton came to this small,
struggling city of 38,000 people along the Mississippi River
Tuesday to hail the opening of a Walgreens drug store, an event
that usually does not prompt a presidential visit.
</P>
<P>
   But the store is the largest retail establishment built here
since the 1950s, and to Clinton it is a shining example of the
profit-making opportunities in low- and moderate-income inner-city
neighborhoods for businesses willing to locate there.
</P>
<P>
   Standing atop a makeshift stage on the parking lot of the
glittering new store, Clinton said, ``We see in this community both
poverty and great promise.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're all going to have to work hard at this.
Nobody's got all the answers. There is no magic wand. But we know
one thing: people make these investments one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came armed with a new federal study by the Department of
Housing and Urban Development that shows such communities are
``under-retailed,'' meaning sales fall significantly short of the
residents' retail purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   The HUD report, titled ``New Markets: The Untapped Retail Buying
Power in America's Inner Cities,'' said the retail purchasing power
of low- and moderate-income neighborhoods was estimated at $331
billion last year, or one-third of the $1.1 trillion total for the
central cities that include those neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Among 48 inner-city areas where HUD found a retail gap and where
20 percent or more of the population lives in poverty, the total
shortfall last year was $8.7 billion, which equals the purchasing
power minus sales.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Optional graf grim) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of those areas, six were in Massachusetts _ Gloucester, Lowell,
New Bedford, Waltham, Westfield and Yarmouth. The study showed
Westfield with the biggest gap between the purchasing power of its
residents and retail sales, 22.7 percent, while Gloucester had the
least at 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(End optional trim) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the huge buying power among inner-city residents, the
study said they often must make purchases in such places as
suburban malls because there are too few retail stores in their
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In this city where the unemployment rate last year was 9.6
percent, more than twice the national average, and the poverty rate
is 44.3 percent, even a Walgreens store that employs about two
dozen people is considered good news.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest stop on Clinton's six-state tour of poverty
areas to promote greater public and private investment in urban and
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with a small band of corporate CEOs and members of
Congress and his Cabinet, Clinton is touting these areas as a way
to keep the economy strong through job creation and lowering of
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``America needs to wake up and recognize that the best new
market for American products and for new American investment is
right here in the US of A,'' he told a group of entrepreneurs from
the Mississippi Delta in a roundtable discussion earlier Tuesday in
Clarksdale.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies apparently are listening. Tuesday, the Bank of
America announced it will commit $500 million of equity to support
community development in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   And Greyhound Bus Co. and Federal Express ann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
