<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HEAT-ART-NYT &LR;      07-06 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEAT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 KNOWN DEAD AS 2ND DAY OF RECORD HEAT AFFLICTS NEW YORK REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.J., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As New York City sagged Tuesday under a second day of
record high temperatures, city officials said that as many as three
people had died from heat-related illnesses, and the region
continued to struggle with maddening power failures that trapped
people in stifling elevators, cut air-conditioning to thousands of
homes and buildings, and knocked out some subway service as safety
signals suddenly flicked off.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulance crews responded Tuesday to more than 130 calls from
people complaining of cramps and exhaustion from the heat, and
emergency officials said the heat may have contributed to several
heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the first confirmed heat-related death, an autopsy Tuesday
revealed that Julia Johnson, 79, of Manhattan, had died of
hyperthermia on Monday, said Ellen Borakove, spokeswoman for the
city's chief medical examiner. Mrs. Johnson was found unconscious
at home by a health care worker.
</P>
<P>
   Her body temperature was 108.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said two other people may have died from
the heat. They were described as a 40-year-old man whose Brooklyn
home had a temperature in excess of 108, and a 27-year-old man who
died at Interfaith Hospital in Brooklyn. Names were not released.
</P>
<P>
   Summer school was canceled in Washington, the lights were dimmed
in much of the Massachusetts Statehouse and block captains checked
on the elderly in Philadelphia's row houses. But relief was in
sight, the National Weather Service promised, with lower
temperatures forecast for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said, ``This is one of the more difficult days the city
has ever had in regard to heat.'' He canceled a political
fund-raising trip to Nantucket to deal with the heat emergency.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said that while they expected the death toll to
climb, they were confident it would come nowhere near the hundreds
of deaths the city of Chicago experienced during a brutal heat wave
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``That number might grow a bit, but certainly it will not
approach what happened in the Midwest,'' said Jerome Hauer,
director of the Mayor's Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave _ combined with record demands for electricity _
put enormous pressure on the region's power system. Transformers
overheated and burst into flames. Power lines melted through from
the heat and high usage. In the dense humidity, bolts of
electricity arced across power lines, causing short circuits.
</P>
<P>
   Utility companies first issued urgent appeals for customers to
conserve energy. Later, to ease the strain on power lines and
transformers and because of ``insufficient'' power reserves, the
companies reduced their voltage output by 5 percent. Even so, power
failures were reported throughout New York City, Long Island,
Westchester County, and New Jersey and Connecticut. At least 55,000
people were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene McGrath, chairman of Con Edison, blamed power failures on
equipment breakdowns, not on the power cutback. ``Those problems
come about from the cables overheating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani scolded Con Edison officials for not giving city
officials more explicit warnings about the extent of the power
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Con Ed is its own entity unto itself and sometimes they notify
us late and sometimes they notify us only when the problem has
already started,'' the mayor said. ``I think it's a cause of great
frustration, for me and my administration and every other mayor
that's ever had this job. They call you about 10 minutes before
there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Weather Service, the temperature in
Central Park reached 101 degrees at 3:11 p.m. Tuesday, breaking the
old record of 98 degrees set in 1986. Temperatures were expected to
moderate this week as a cool front moved through the region Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   As New York City activated its emergency operations center
Tuesday, Giuliani appealed for residents to avoid strenuous
activity and stay indoors near fans and air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember hotter days than the last several and
particularly hotter nights,'' he said at a City Hall press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like everyone to be very, very careful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
