has stirred controversy among the immigrant Vietnamese community.
The paintings are, top, ``Young Woman Forging Steel'' by D. Nguyen
and ``Mother's Heart'' by Do Son. Vietnamese immigrants have been
protesting the exhibit of contemporary Vietnamese art since it
opened inside this Spanish-style museum on June 25. (Edward
Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SANTA ANA, Calif. -- July 6, 1999 --
CALIF-VIETNAM-EXHIBIT, 7-06 -- Vietnamese immigrant Hao Nguyen
carries a former South Vietnamese flag during a protest against an
exhibit showing works of art from Vietnam outside Bowers Museum of
Cultural Art. Vietnamese immigrants have been protesting an
exhibition of contemporary Vietnamese art since it opened inside
this Spanish-style museum on June 25. The origin of the artwork,
compounded by the fact that some of the paintings depict communist
symbols, has angered the immigrants, for whom the memories of the
Vietnam War have yet to fade. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
