<P>
   (NYT9) ARLINGTON, Mass. -- July 6, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-BOS, 7-06
-- Marie Warren works out with weights in the kitchen of her home.
``I hated the idea of being sick, so I really buckled down,'' she
says of her training regimen. Never before has so much evidence
supported the value of physical activity so non-strenuous that you
don't need to shower afterward, and which can be done in
bite-sized, 10-minute segments. The important thing is to make sure
it adds up to 30 minutes a day. (John Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. -- July 6, 1999 --
HAIRCUT-CHAIN-BOS, 7-06 -- Joanna Meiseles, founder, creator and
owner of the Snip-its haircutting chain for children, at her brand
new location in Chestnut Hill. ``We want to be the tooth fairy of
kids' haircuts,'' she explains. ``We want to make haircuts an
adventure.'' (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- July 6, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 7-06 -- A
British firefighter exits a burning house in a neighborhood
inhabited by mostly gypsies late Monday night. NATO authorities
suspect the fires were lit by ethnic Albanians in retaliation for
allegedly collaborating with Serbs. Many homes belonging to gypsies
and Serbs, in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo province, as well as
the countryside, have been looted and burned since ethnic Albanians
returned last month after Yugoslav forces withdrew from the region.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- July 6, 1999 -- DILBERITO-EATING-WELL, 7-06 --
Dilberitos, vegetarian burritos will be showing up in stores in the
next few weeks, have been sprayed with 23 vitamins and minerals,
the same ones listed on the back of bottles of vitamins. Each
Dilberito carries the government's entire Recommended Daily
Allowance. That makes it a vitamin pill wrapped in a tortilla.
(Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 6, 1999 -- BUSINESS-LUNCH-3, 7-06 --
``Years ago you could serve the French classics, but you can't sell
them anymore. Now it's salads, grilled fish, grilled meats, less
starch, more protein and healthier than ever,'' says Eberhard
Muller, the chef and owner of Lutece. Here a customer eats one of
the salads available for lunchtime crowds. (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 6, 1999 -- BUSINESS-LUNCH-2, 7-06 --
Lunch crowds at Gotham Bar and Grill in lower Manhattan. As lunch
has comes under the increasing pressures of time, budgets and
health concerns, many restaurants have realized that they could
either adapt or deal with empty tables. At the Gotham, the $19.99
lunch accounts for about half of the restaurant's lunch business.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 6, 1999 -- BUSINESS-LUNCH-1, 7-06 --
Patrons being served lunch at Le Bernardin in Manhattan. As lunch
