<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      07-06 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TELEPHONE COMPANY ORDERED TO UPGRADE AND OPEN UP TO
COMPETITION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: France, Japan)    By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Already under pressure from rival telephone and cable
operators, British Telecommunications PLC was ordered by regulators
Tuesday to upgrade its huge local network and to open it to
competitors by July 2001. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The British telephone giant, which is known as BT, controls
about 85 percent of the ``local loop'' copper network used by home
subscribers and small businesses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's directive from the Office of Telecommunications, a
government watchdog, reflected the rapidly intensifying competition
in Britain and other parts of Europe to bring high-speed Internet
access and other so-called broadband services to homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   But it also highlighted the difficult situation facing the
former state monopoly: competition is likely to accelerate the
growth of the high-speed market, but it could also reduce British
Telecom's slice of it. Still, the company's shares rose 42 pence,
or 3.8 percent, in London trading to 1,151 pence ($18.04). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cable operators like Telewest Communications PLC and NTL Inc.
already offer telephone services along with cable television, while
rivals including MCI Worldcom of the United States and Energis PLC
are pressing for access to British Telecom's local networks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Edmonds, the head of Oftel, as the Office of
Telecommunications is known, said in a statement that ``with
concentrated work by the industry and successful trials concluded
by the end of 2000, I am confident competing operators can have
direct access to BT's network by July 1, 2001.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, competitors ``should have the ability to roll
out their own technology,'' adding that ``they should not have to
wait for BT to make decisions that determine the timetable for the
rolling-out of new services.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications, Britain's second-largest telephone
company after Vodafone Airtouch PLC, gave a lukewarm response to
the idea of permitting its competitors access to its networks for
their technology.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BT has argued that it should use its own technology and then
bill its rivals for access. Oftel's directive favored rivals that
seek to install their own technology once local networks have been
upgraded to permit much higher speeds for telephone, data and other
services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, British Telecommunications said it had placed a
``multimillion-pound order'' for equipment from Alcatel SA of
France and Fujitsu Ltd. of Japan, enabling it to enhance 400 of its
2,800 exchanges _ catering to some six million households and
businesses _ using what is called asymmetric digital
subscriber-line technology. The technology creates digital channels
for Internet access and multimedia services at much higher speed
than are now available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications said the use of its rivals'
technology ``raises significant technical and security issues which
will need to be evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement drew a sharp response from Michael Butler, MCI
Worldcom's managing director in Britain. ``If implementing
competition proves `too difficult,' we might as well all go home,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
