<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-ELECTRICITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A.C. AT A PREMIUM, POWER UTILITIES SET DEMAND RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (With NY-HEAT) 
 (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Electric companies from here to Maine were
stretched so thin Tuesday by demand from millions of air
conditioners that they breathed a sigh of relief when the weather
broke, even though the break was in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news; they'll have a little more to send us,'' said
William J. Balet, executive director of the New York Power Pool, a
consortium of the state's power generators and users that imports
and exports power to and from utilities outside the state based on
supply, demand and price. The pool also helps coordinate power
production within the state.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities in the eastern United States set new records for
demand Tuesday. Most of those utilities were able to squeak through
on available supplies that they produced or imported, although
electric companies in New York state and a broad area to the south
cut voltage, and some neighborhoods in New York City, Long Island,
central New Jersey and elsewhere lost all power, mostly because the
distribution lines and transformers overheated.
</P>
<P>
   In all, hundreds of thousands of people lost power for at least
part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The peaks in demand for electricity are getting ever higher,
experts say, because all new commercial buildings and most new
houses have air conditioning, and air conditioning is being added
to older houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People left their air conditioners on for four consecutive
days, day and night,'' said Ron Morano, a spokesman for General
Public Utilities, in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Many utilities called on customers to shut off nonessential
appliances; the New England Power Pool avoided voltage cuts but
asked the governors of each of the six states in the region to
appeal to the public for conservation.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Potomac Electric Power Co., known as Pepco,
warned on its Web site that people should curtail consumption to
prevent a ``complete failure of the electric power grid.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pepco, like other utilities, made do with voltage
reductions. Such reductions make electric motors run a bit slower
and make the picture shrink slightly on computer and television
screens, but generally do not hurt computers or other energy-using
appliances. The same cannot be said in cases where power is cut
completely, when computers can crash and data can be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The three major power pools in the northeast all set new demand
records Tuesday: the New York Power Pool, the New England Power
Pool and the Pennsylvania-Jersey-Maryland Interconnection, which
covers most of Pennsylvania and all of New Jersey, Maryland,
Delaware and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   To meet demand, utility officials imported power from Ontario,
Quebec and the Canadian Maritimes, among other sources.
</P>
<P>
   All reported having much less generating capacity in reserve
than they are accustomed to. That left them vulnerable to ``load
shedding'' (their preferred term for blackouts) if they lost a
single big generating station or transmission line.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All said that in areas where power was deregulated, electricity
was trading at a price 10 to 20 times higher than normal, near
$1,000 a megawatt-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Such extreme prices are so far a wholesale phenomenon, but some
energy economists think that they should make their way into
pricing for factories and other big customers, to encourage them to
close up and send employees home on the hottest days, moderating
the demand peaks and reducing the number of plants built to supply
power only a few days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Already, many utilities offer big customers an ``interruptible''
rate, giving them lower prices for most of the year, in exchange
for being allowed to cut them off on days like Tuesday. And
Tuesday, they all got shut down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
