<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA07-COX     07-06 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta worst for bumping
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines has achieved the dubious distinction
of leading the industry in bumping passengers off flights.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's rate of involuntary passenger bumpings soared in the
first three months of the year, leaving the carrier at the bottom
of the industry for its management of overbooked flights. The
Atlanta-based airline reported 8,144 involuntary bumpings in
January-March, almost as many as the other nine major airlines
combined. Delta reported 13,449 involuntary bumpings for all of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's rate of involuntary bumpings was 3.33 per 10,000
passengers in the first quarter, worst in the industry, according
to government figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary bumpings occur when airlines overbook flights to
ward against no-shows, then can't get enough passengers to
volunteer to be bumped to a later flight. Volunteers usually get
credit toward a future trip.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny fraction of air travelers are involuntarily bumped, but a
longtime consumer advocate says aggressive overbooking contributes
to broader problems that have made airline service a subject of
congressional debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things that causes not huge delays but
annoying delays and tension while things are worked out,'' said Ed
Perkins, former editor of Consumer Reports Travel Letter.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers held off flights against their wishes are eligible
for as much as $400 in compensation under U.S. Transportation
Department rules.
</P>
<P>
   Voluntary service guidelines recently adopted by the airline
industry include a general pledge of ``fairness and consistency''
in handling bumped passengers, but no specific measures.
</P>
<P>
   The government tracks bumping as part of its periodic Air Travel
Consumer Report, which lists comparative passenger service
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has recently improved its standing in other categories:
on-time performance, lost baggage and formal consumer complaints to
the Transportation Department. It's ranked among the leaders in all
three categories over the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   But a high rate of involuntary bumping has become a nagging
problem for the carrier, which handles 80 percent of the passenger
traffic at Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Delta executives have promised fixes for more than a year, but
new computer programs to help manage overbooking were delayed and
won't be in use until later this year, spokesman Bill Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot sickout at American Airlines last winter may have
contributed to the spike as Delta tried to accommodate last-minute
passengers stranded by its rival, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to use excuses,'' Berry said. ``The hard fact
is we're by no means satisfied, and we have a high-level team
working on changes.'' The team reports directly to Chief Executive
Leo Mullin, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said overbooking to prevent against financial losses
caused by no-shows ``is a real balancing act for airlines.'' But an
airline with an unusually high rate of involuntary bumpings ``can
instantly solve it by backing off on the numbers they overbook.
It's totally within their control,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of airline bumpings are voluntary. Delta
reported 54,835 voluntary bumpings in the first quarter, second to
American with 70,213.
</P>
<P>
   American, however, reported only 848 involuntary bumpings, about
one-tenth Delta's number.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said the disparity suggests American either offers
better incentives or does most of its overbooking on routes
dominated by leisure fliers, who are more willing than business
fliers to volunteer to be bumped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
