u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-06 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-GUILTY PLEA IN SLAYING A SURPRISE TO FAMILY AND LAWYER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Israel)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A plea of not guilty by a Maryland man facing a
murder charge in Israel has produced anger and frustration in
Montgomery County, Md., where the crime was committed two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   After assuring the Israeli Supreme Court that he would plead
guilty if he were not extradited to the United States, the
defendant, Samuel Sheinbein, unexpectedly entered a not-guilty plea
on Monday in a lower court in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein, 18, and a friend, Aaron Needle, are accused of
strangling a classmate, Alfredo Enrique Tello Jr., then burning and
mutilating his body to cover up the crime. Needle hanged himself in
a jail cell 15 months ago, just before his trial was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid prosecution in the United States, where he faced life
in prison without chance of parole, Sheinbein fled to Israel, where
he had never lived, claiming citizenship by virtue of his father's
birth there in 1944. In fighting extradition, his lawyer told the
Israeli Supreme Court in February that Sheinbein would admit to the
killing if he could stand trial in Israel, where a conviction would
bring a lesser penalty and the possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas Gansler, the Montgomery County state's attorney, who
has been working with the Israeli authorities on the case, said in
an interview Tuesday that the change in plea caught him by surprise
and could result in a chance for Sheinbein to win acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Sheinbein's plan to fight the charges would
put enormous pressure on Israeli prosecutors to mount a convincing
case before the three-judge panel that will preside over the trial,
scheduled to begin in October. With virtually all the evidence and
witnesses in Maryland, he said, Israeli prosecutors have only
passing familiarity with details of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has manipulated the judicial system of Israel to his
advantage,'' Gansler said of the defendant, predicting that, if
convicted, Sheinbein would be sentenced to no more than 20 years in
prison, a term that could be reduced to as few as 11 years if the
defendant pleaded a form of insanity defense known in Israel as
diminished responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens,'' Gansler added, ``it pales in comparison to
the crime as a torturous murder.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Supreme Court ruling, the Israeli Parliament repealed
the extradition law, lifting a ban and allowing Israeli citizens
who are not residents to face prosecution abroad for crimes
committed abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The not-guilty plea also caught the victim's mother off-guard.
Eric Dawes, a banker from Silver Spring, Md., who is engaged to
marry Tello's mother, Eliette Ramos, said she was ``bummed out,
exhausted and frustrated'' by Sheinbein's latest judicial
maneuverings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her son was brutally murdered, and she has no way for
closure,'' Dawes said. ``It has been one charade after another. She
feels no sense of justice. She is more than frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said his chief concern now was helping the Israeli
prosecutor, Hadassah Naor, build her case, given the limitations of
distance, money and language.
</P>
<P>
   Had the trial been held in Maryland, Gansler said, he was
prepared to call as many as 80 witnesses who would have weaved
together evidence showing that Sheinbein had engaged in what
Maryland prosecutors say was a ``thrill kill,'' by strangling Tello
in a car after picking him up from his job at a shopping center on
Sept. 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said prosecutors had also collected forensic and genetic
evidence, as well as handwriting samples, to show premeditation.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's lawyer, David Libai, a former Israeli justice
minister, told the Tel Aviv court that his client would only admit
to picking up Tello and that the victim's body was moved, cut up
and burned. He said Sheinbein would not admit to any part of the
killing, a suggestion that Needle played the leading role in the
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   But Gansler said he had evidence that Sheinbein confessed the
murder to his father and his brother. In Israel, however, parents
and siblings of a defendant, like spouses, are not required to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   He also doubted whether there was enough time before the
scheduled start of the trial for Israeli prosecutors to organize a
complete case. He said that Ms. Naor spoke ``little English'' and
that all the documents her office had shared with the authorities
in Montgomery County were written in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler also expressed concern about the Israelis' promise to
pay costs of litigation, which will undoubtedly include
transportation and hotel expenses for witnesses. He predicted the
cost could reach as much as $500,000. But an unsatisfied request by
his office for $14,000 to cover costs incurred over the year
following Sheinbein's flight to Israel has left him wondering about
their commitment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what's going to happen next?'' Gansler said. ``This
is going to be a logistical nightmare. We could try the case here
tomorrow. They say they have a trial date of Oct. 10 and it will
take about a week. I think that's highly unrealistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
