<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     07-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOTECH LEERY OF CLINTON'S MEDICARE DRUG PROPOSAL  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;        c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
On its surface, President Clinton's proposal to add a drug benefit
to Medicare would seem to give the biotech sector a boost, making
more money available for new remedies.
<P>
   But industry lobbyists are leery of the plan's nuances, and even
more fearful of what might happen as Congress has its say on a
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed last week that Medicare pay half of a senior's
prescription drug bill _ up to a limit. The annual cap would start
at $2,000 in 2002 and rise to $5,000 in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech lobbyists want Clinton to take an entirely different
approach. Let seniors pay for the first $1,000 or $2,000 in
prescriptions. Once their spending exceeds this deductible, let
Medicare kick in to pay the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the seniors spending $10,000 to $20,000 a year on
medications who have the most dire need,'' said Walter Moore,
Genentech's lobbyist in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the biotech industry is motivated partly by
self-interest. Biotech-created drugs tend to cost thousands of
dollars a year, so the industry would rather have catastrophic care
coverage than a payment cap with no deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is one case in which industry's position may coincide
with the needs of the sickest and poorest Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton's proposal is enacted, thousands of seniors
would exceed the Medicare drug cap and find themselves right where
they are today: unable to pay for their medications and without
government help. So why would Clinton opt for such a ``cap out''?
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the financial and political realities, said Carl
Feldbaum, president of the industry trade group called BIO.
</P>
<P>
   To finance his drug plan without bankrupting Medicare, Clinton
had to propose that seniors pay a monthly premium starting at $24
in 2002 and rising to $44 in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Because it would be tough to persuade seniors to pay for a
benefit with a high deductible, political expediency demanded that
the president offer to pay 50 cents on the first dollar in drug
costs _ even if that meant imposing a $1,000 to $2,500 cap on this
government help.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly looking to appeal to the broadest electorate
possible, by giving everyone at least a little benefit,'' Feldbaum
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep. Pete Stark, D-Hayward, have
authored a Medicare drug benefit bill far more generous than
Clinton's proposal. Under this plan, once seniors satisfied a $200
deductible, Medicare would cover 80 percent of their drug expenses.
Once their drug costs exceeded $3,000, Medicare would pay the
entire bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kennedy and Stark haven't yet put a price on their
proposal, BIO lobbyist Chuck Ludlam called it ``vastly too
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry likes one aspect of the plan. ``We'd like the
catastrophic part of the Kennedy-Stark bill grafted onto the
Clinton proposal,'' Feldbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   FEAR AND LOATHING? On the subject of Medicare and drugs, another
bill floating around Washington, D.C., has industry quivering in
its lab coat.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine, has authored legislation that would
force drugmakers to offer steep discounts on all prescriptions sold
to Medicare beneficiaries. The discounts, amounting to roughly 24
percent of the drug's wholesale price, would pertain regardless of
whether the government, a private insurer or the patient paid the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has imposed similar price controls on
drugs sold through the Medicaid program since 1990, said Moore, the
Genentech lobbyist. Medicaid patients buy 10 to 15 percent of the
nation's drugs. Medicare patients buy another 30 to 40 percent.
Private insurers buy the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Industry is adamant that the price controls on Medicaid not be
extended to Medicare's larger client population. They argue that
price controls on Medicare drugs will make it harder to recoup the
high cost of developing new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must oppose (price controls) to the death,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's bill has six Bay Area co-sponsors, all Democrats. They
are: Stark, Rep. Nancy Pelosi of San Francisco, Rep. Barbara Lee of
Oakland, Rep. George Miller of Martinez, Rep. Lynn Woolsey of
Petaluma and Rep. Tom Lantos of Hillsborough.
</P>
<P>
   Industry lobbyists worry that Allen's price-control language
might get inserted into one of the Medicare drug benefit bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of bashing drug companies is quite delicious in
Washington, D.C.,'' said Moore, adding that ``some Democrats have
identified Medicare drug benefits as a wedge issue'' to get seniors
out to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Others scoff at the notion that drug benefits and price controls
are issues cooked up for election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members have been hearing consistently of the enormous
difficulty seniors are having keeping up with the cost of
medications,'' said an aide to Stark. She added that although
industry argues that price controls would squelch the flow of R&AMP;D
money into research, ``we haven't seen any evidence of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
