<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGSTEP-E-BUSINESS-SF     07-06 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGSTEP-E-BUSINESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIGSTEP A BIG BOOST TO SMALL BUSINESSES  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Internet startup Bigstep.com will unveil a full menu of services
Wednesday to help small businesses get into e-business quickly,
easily without hiring a professional or spending a dime.
<P>
   The design-it-yourself services, available at www.bigstep.com,
let little companies build and host Web sites, communicate with
customers and visitors, set up online product catalogs, promote the
sites, take and fulfill orders, and analyze site traffic and
trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigstep.com allows small businesses and entrepreneurs to do
what they do best _ create a unique business and provide
personalized customer service, instead of forcing them to be tech
wizards,'' said Andrew Beebe, co-founder and CEO of the year-old
San Francisco company. ``Our goal is to make Bigstep.com a place
where e-business is everybody's business.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly will please Internet users who are used to getting
a lot of free stuff online.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will small-business owners pay nothing for the service
and step-by-step instruction, Bigstep will not run advertisements
on customer Web sites. Beebe said businesses do not like it when
their customers leave their Web sites for someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bigstep will not charge any fee to connect small
businesses to outside e-commerce services, such as to register a
Web address or establish a merchant account with a bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are giving away the store,'' said Beebe, who talks
differently from most CEOs and also wears a ponytail. ``We look at
e-business as a right, not a privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   How, then, does Bigstep expect to make money for its 45
employees and its venture capital backers, including U.S. Venture
Partners and Mayfield Fund, which invested $10 million last month?.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe said Bigstep plans to get revenue eventually by selling
``value-added'' services such as customer-lead lists and online
auctions. It also will accept sponsorships on its own Web site from
companies such as Visa and UPS that have relevant products and
services for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe was student body president at Dartmouth College and a
White House intern before getting into the Internet world. After
stints at NetObjects and Tele-TV and as a Web designer, he started
the predecessor of Bigstep. Called the Springfield Project, it was
named for TV character Homer Simpson's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Bigstep and its investors hope the company will be as popular as
the cartoon icon. The market is huge. Bigstep estimates that less
than 10 percent of the more than 7 million U.S. small businesses
have e-business sites. But within three years, it is expected that
more than 3.3 million small businesses will be creating online
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Bigstep is in a competitive market. IBM, Intel, Hewlett-Packard,
Microsoft and many other high-tech players all have products and
services aimed at the small business sector.
</P>
<P>
   But Bigstep's free services and broad array of do-it-yourself
tools make it stand out.
</P>
<P>
   One Bigstep fan and adviser is Terri Lonier, author of several
popular books on small business and founder of the Working Solo
consulting firm. ``When I learned about the company in March, I
thought it was too good to be true,'' she said. ``Small businesses
want freedom, flexibility, fun and control and Big Step provides
all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some big companies also support Bigstep. The company said 14
organizations, including First USA, Sun Microsystems and Service
Corps of Retired Executives, have signed up to develop and
distribute its service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
