<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-OWENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS THIS REPUBLICAN GOVERNOR FROM TEXAS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He's a Republican governor from Texas, a self-described
``compassionate conservative,'' and on Tuesday he could be found on
an airport tarmac urging Colorado voters to get behind a certain
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush? Nope. It was Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, a Fort
Worth native who, unlike Bush, was actually born in Texas. (Bush
was born in Connecticut.)
</P>
<P>
   Tapped to drum up support and money here for the Bush
presidential campaign, Owens helped round up a group of Hispanic
leaders to endorse Bush. Some of them crossed party lines to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Democrats up here,'' Bush said. ``We
welcome them. My vision for America includes everyone.'' About 14
percent of Colorado's 4 million people are of Hispanic origin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was greeted at Centennial Airport by about 350
placard-waving supporters, who sang ``Happy Birthday'' as the Texas
governor took the stage. Bush turned 53 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   After the airport rally, Bush went to a fundraiser at the Hyatt
Regency in downtown Denver. Hosts included Peter Coors, CEO of
Coors Brewing Co., and both of Colorado's GOP senators, Ben
Nighthorse Campbell and Wayne Allard.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who graduated from a Fort Worth high school, moved to
Colorado 22 years ago. Last year, he became the state's first
Republican governor since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is backing Bush for president because the two share a
similar philosophy, including the ``compassionate conservatism''
they both proudly promote.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush popularized the phrase, Owens said he has been a
practitioner of compassionate conservatism for years. He cited, for
example, his efforts to reach out to minorities and members of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of his cabinet are Democrats, including Larry
Trujillo, director of General Support Services. Trujillo, a former
Democratic state senator, joined other Hispanic Democrats in
announcing their support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said reaching across the partisan divide has not been
difficult, since he once worked in Washington for former U.S. Rep.
Jim Wright, a liberal Democrat from Fort Worth who later became
House speaker. The two have been close friends ever since.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990706.0330 </DOCNO>
