<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-COLUMN-SFCRON &LR;      07-06 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-COLUMN-SFCRON </SLUG>
  
 FERRETING OUT Y2K WOES THIS YEAR  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: I have a small business and haven't the foggiest idea about
whether my computer is Y2K compliant or whether it will crash at
the end of the year. What can I do to find out?
<P>
   A: You are not alone. According to the U.S. Commerce Department,
40 percent of U.S. small businesses are still not prepared for
computer problems that could be triggered by the year 2000. Even
more alarming, a third of small businesses plan to do nothing at
all to address this complicated issue.
</P>
<P>
   But with 177 days to go before Y2K, help is available.
</P>
<P>
   The department has a Y2K Self-Help Tool/CD-ROM, available in 11
languages. Its goal is to help small and medium-size business
managers around the world identify and rate their various
functions, from accounting to telecommunications to utilities, that
might be susceptible to Y2K problems. The easy-to-use program also
contains helpful online links, checklists and contingency plan
templates.
</P>
<P>
   You can get it by calling the National Institute for Standards
and Technology's Y2K Help Center for Small Business at (800)
925-7557. The software also can be downloaded via the Commerce
Department's Y2K Web site (www.doc.gov/y2k).
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Small Business Year 2000 Readiness Act signed
into law in April, the U.S. Small Business Administration provides
a loan guaranty program for fixing Y2K problems that allows up to a
one-year moratorium on principal payments. Check www.sba.gov/y2k
for further details.
</P>
<P>
   There also are private companies that specialize in helping
small businesses over Y2K hurdles. One of these is Oasys Network
Solutions Inc. in Concord, which offers consulting services and a
$49.95 online compliance service at www.fixyear2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   Oasys manager Rod Bacon offers these 10 Y2K tips for small
businesses:
</P>
<P>
   -- Get Informed: Y2K exposure can exist  &LR; exists  &LR; in your
computer's hardware and software, other office hardware and your
business relationships. Check out helpful Web sites like
www.sba.gov/y2k or www.year2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- Check The BIOS. The only piece of hardware to be concerned
with in your computer is a chip called the BIOS, the basic
input-output system that controls the PC. Test your computer's BIOS
with a free testing tool from www.rightime.com or www.ntsl.com. (Do
not test by simply rolling your computer clock forward.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Correct BIOS problems. If after completing this test, you
find that your BIOS is not Y2K ready, you will need to acquire and
apply any available patches. See www.mitre.org for a good list of
BIOS patches.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make a list of key software installed on your computer
(including the operating system and business applications). You
will need the following information: manufacturer, application name
and version number.
</P>
<P>
   -- Check the software. Go to the software manufacturer's Web
site to determine compliance, and download any patch you need for
the application. These patches are usually free.
</P>
<P>
   -- Follow the directions and apply patches or upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   -- Document everything you do to make your business Y2K
compliant. This will be useful in case of any future legal battles.
</P>
<P>
   -- Control your environment by tracking all new hardware and
software brought into your business.
</P>
<P>
   -- Check back. Keep compliant by returning to the manufacturers'
Web site in November and applying any new patches.
</P>
<P>
   -- Verify, in writing, that all of your vendors and suppliers
are following a similar Y2K compliance program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
