<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, JULY 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-AIRPORT-AIR-TRAFFIC-NYT (moved on Friday, July 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 2,
about air traffic problems in the Northeast misstated the location
of Green Airport in Rhode Island. It is in Warwick, not Providence.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TOTAL-ELF-NYT (moved on Monday, July 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 5,
about a $43 billion takeover offer from Total Fina of France
misspelled the name of the company Total is seeking to acquire. It
is Elf Aquitaine, not Acquitaine.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DERTOUZOS-FUTURE-NYT (moved on Monday, July 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 5,
about a interview with Dr. Michael L. Dertouzos, a computer
scientist who is concerned about the social impact of computers,
misstated the site of the creation of the World Wide Web. Tim
Berners-Lee invented the Web and wrote the first software for it in
1990 and 1991 while working at the CERN physics laboratory outside
Geneva. He joined the Laboratory for Computing Science at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June
30, about Pokemon Pinball for the Game Boy referred incorrectly to
a feature. The first cartridge to include a built-in mechanism that
causes the Game Boy to vibrate is Top Gear Pocket, not Pokemon
Pinball.
</P>
</TEXT>
