<HEADER>
A1127 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZCAMPUS-DEVELOPER-S     07-06 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZCAMPUS-DEVELOPER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEVELOPER CREATES CORPORATE HOMES FOR TECH TENANTS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Rich Robbins is not your Donald Trump-style real
estate mogul. The transplanted New Yorker doesn't have his name on
his company or bask in publicity.
<P>
   Over the past 22 years, Robbins has built four corporate
campuses along the I-80 corridor in the East Bay. He also has a
dream list of bio- and high-tech tenants occupying more than 3
million square feet of space in more than two dozen buildings.
</P>
<P>
   His East Bay empire includes the Point Richmond Tech center,
longtime home to Steve Jobs' Pixar Animation Studios; Aquatic Park
Business Center in Berkeley, Calif., which is dominated by such
biotech heavyweights as Bayer Pharmaceutical, Roche Diagnostics and
Xoma; Chiron's headquarters campus in Emeryville, Calif.; and the
nearby EmeryStation-Heritage Square project.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the tenants moving into the new EmeryStation project this
summer are NorthPoint Communications and Ask Jeeves, which both
recently launched wildly successful initial stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   While many developers build corporate campuses for a single
client, like Levi Strauss in San Francisco or Oracle at Redwood
Shores, Calif., Robbins' niche is providing homes for multiple
clients.
</P>
<P>
   His Wareham Development firm, based in San Rafael, Calif., near
where Robbins lives, specializes in turning old factories and
abandoned warehouses into mixed-use developments. Not only do these
multiclient complexes often generate more rental income than
projects leased to a single tenant, they create interesting
communities that become a magnet for additional development. In
addition, they are more financially stable because the departure of
one business does not cloud the future of the entire campus.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins prides himself on preserving much of the original
character of the buildings he buys while adding airy skylights and
other architectural touches, gardens and patios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are competing more than ever before to attract and
keep the best employees,'' said Robbins. ``They realize the
workplace can be part of their package of benefits. Workers who
have their pick of the job market prefer offices with the right
amenities _ windows that open to let in fresh air, gardens and
atriums, workout rooms with showers, and terraces and balconies
throughout the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, 50, grew up in Jamaica Plains, N.Y., the son of an
entrepreneur who manufactured everything from decorative
refrigerator magnets to wooden spoons at factories in Hong Kong and
Brooklyn. During college _ Bucknell as an undergrad, Wharton for an
MBA _ he made money on the side renovating brownstones, and then
went to work for a very successful real estate and insurance
executive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Robbins decided to strike out on his own and moved to
California. His first project was buying a paper recycling plant
near the Albany shoreline for $1.6 million and turning it into a
mixed-use development. Consolidated Fibers was paying 15 cents a
square foot (per month) for the space, but Robbins figured he could
make twice that by chopping it into smaller chunks and renting it
out to auto painters, brass bed-makers, sculptors and others.
</P>
<P>
   He approached his father about making an investment. But Robbins
recalls that after looking at the property, his dad told him,
``It's such a good idea you don't need to borrow from me.'' Robbins
values this lesson in ``tough love.'' He said it helped him to
develop relationships with bankers and be innovative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, he legally converted the first industrial building in
the Bay Area into artists' lofts and studio residences. The
live-work space at the Hollis Street Complex in Emeryville
originally was built in the 1920s by General Cableand, and for many
years, it churned out submarine engines. Now, it is home to more
than two dozen artists and a host of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great work environment,'' said Alan Rhodes, an 18-year
tenant who owns Pacific Flame Glass Works, which designs
sophisticated scientific glassware. ``There's a Tibetan prayer flag
flying on the building, and Rich is interested in the community and
has kept rents down to help artists.''
</P>
<P>
   At his Aquatic Park Center in Berkeley, Robbins similarly turned
the the former Art Deco headquarters of Durkee Famous Foods into a
consortium of artist live/work studio galleries. Durkee's former
spice warehouse was renovated as a theater and cultural center.
Bayer Pharmaceutical occupies a gutted 40-year-old industrial plant
at the same complex, and at the other end of the campus, Roche
Diagnostics is housed in a former Langendorf bakery.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, Robbins has focused primarily on
serving the burgeoning Berkeley biotech businesses, starting with
Cetus and Chiron and attracting university researchers with an
entrepreneurial streak. More recently he has turned to Internet
up-and-comers.
</P>
<P>
   A new Wareham tenant is NorthPoint Communications, the San
Francisco Internet access service company that is growing so fast
it needs a new headquarters in San Francisco and an additional
100,000 square feet in the new five-story EmeryStation complex.
</P>
<P>
   The company looked at a dozen other sites in the East Bay before
settling on Robbins' latest development just an exit and on-ramp
away from the Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked the location and links to the Amtrak station (which
Robbins also built) and the Emery-Go-Round shuttle to BART,'' said
NorthPoint real estate manager Bryce Mason. ``We also like the
campus-style setting, the wide open floor plans and Rich's
personable style and reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-story, brick-clad $75 million complex features a large
glassed-in atrium ``winter garden'' and patios that are accessible
to more than half of the office space.
</P>
<P>
   The building is already fully leased. In addition to NorthPoint,
tenants include Ask Jeeves, the natural-language online search
service; the Gallo Center, a research group affiliated with the
University of California at San Francisco that is researching
alcoholism and is financed by the Gallo wine family; and the
nonprofit Save-the-Redwood League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new work culture wants more unconventional spaces and
amenities like access to balconies,'' said Jeff Heller of San
Francisco's Heller-Manus Architects, who designed EmeryStation.
``Rich believes in this and buildings that fit the character of the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, ticked off by what he calls ``the
mow-and-blow'' gardeners, Robbins started the ``Gardening Angels''
group with the help of his wife. Now a half-dozen gardeners are on
the payroll planting wild flowers beside the sidewalks and tending
the gardens at Wareham's various developments.
</P>
<P>
   To cement long-term relationships, Robbins also likes to keep
10,000 to 20,000 square feet of what he calls ``surge space''
available to accommodate the short-term needs of new and future
tenants. For example, he recently bought out the California State
Automobile Association's lease on a building in Berkeley to make
way for NorthPoint Communications until its space in the new
EmeryStation is ready for occupancy next month.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins also has been willing to work out other deals with
tenants. For example, he took stock from Chiron, Sybase, Xoma and
other companies instead of cash for some tenant improvements. A
number of these trades proved very lucrative, but that was not the
only motive, Robbins said. ``Sometimes it was necessary to make a
deal happen, and it also created a stronger bond with management.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins declines to discuss his personal finances or those of
his private company. Until recently, he leveraged Wareham's growth
with his own funds and loans. Six months ago, he sold half interest
in the EmeryStation project and eight other properties to a unit of
Prudential Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many developers, Robbins professes no interest in
forming a public real estate investment trust where he would be
obliged to worry about quarter-to-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in my makeup to buy and sell,'' he said. ``I get
committed to the land and involved in the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
