<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      07-06 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS FLY INTO KOSOVO AFTER IMPASSE IS RESOLVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLATINA, Yugoslavia _ Russian airborne troops flew into Kosovo
Tuesday, starting the deployment of the main Russian peacekeeping
contingent, a day after NATO and Russia worked out the last
wrinkles to their participation.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of about 200 Russians was greeted with general
relief on the ground. It signaled the opening of Slatina airport,
just west of the capital, Pristina, for military flights, and for
the first U.N. relief flight Tuesday, which arrived with vital
communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the thorny political issues have been resolved, some
eight more relief planes are expected to arrive in coming days,
U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For the several hundred Russian paratroopers already based at
the airport, the flights will provide welcome reinforcements of men
and equipment and enable the Russians to start deploying properly
as a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have seen how difficult it is for our Russian contingent
to fly here, but I think these problems are behind us,'' said Gen.
Anatoly Volchkov, chief of the airport, as the second Russian plane
touched down in mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had been ready to fly in for several days but were
prevented from doing so after neighboring countries denied them
flight paths, at NATO's request. Two days of talks in Moscow ending
on Monday cleared up remaining issues, but the delay seems to have
irritated the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was frustration here,'' said a British liaison officer
to the Russian general. ``They were all ready. They have the most
difficult logistics to get here of all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Valery Yevtukhovich, who will command the Russian
forces in Kosovo, arrived with the first of three planes of Russian
troops and equipment that flew in Tuesday. He replaces Col. Gen.
Viktor Zavarzin, who led the Russians into Kosovo in the early
hours of June 12, stealing the show from NATO forces and taking
control of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Jackson, the commander of NATO forces in
Kosovo, greeted Yevtukhovich and joined him at lunch in a tent by
the tarmac. The Russian brought along ``a very good bottle of vodka
which was shared by General Jackson and General Zavarzin,'' the
British liaison officer said.
</P>
<P>
   Zavarzin returned home Tuesday, and Volchkov, who met with
reporters later, said he expected no difficulties with the chain of
command worked out for the Russian force. ``For all safety and
security of aircraft in the airfield, it would not be possible
without coordination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement with NATO, the Russians have reserved the right
to refuse to carry out orders. But Volchkov said he did not expect
to receive orders from his commanders that would go against the
NATO commanders' wishes. ``I only receive such an order from the
command after there have been consultations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude may end the one-upmanship that has troubled the
NATO force's first weeks in Kosovo, after the Russians seized
control of the airport. The Russian presence and the subsequent
political wrangling delayed use of the airport for both military
and aid flights for weeks. It also delayed the deployment of the
full Russian peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The running of the airport now seems to be worked out. The
Russian and British troops have agreed on a detailed
military-technical protocol outlining their respective areas of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians will make it their main base and will have 750
officers at the airport, part of a total contingent of 3,600. They
will be in charge of security and transport on the airfield.
British forces, which number 250 at the airport so far, will be in
charge of air traffic control, and they have supplied radar
equipment and fire services.
</P>
<P>
   Together they have patched up the bomb-scarred runway and
prepared the airport to handle civilian flights. Commercial flights
are not expected for several months.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have been hampered by the dispute since they rely
almost entirely on direct flights for their supplies and
reinforcements. The British have helped them out with water,
providing 20,000 liters of bottled drinking water to keep them
going. In the meantime, the Russians are sorting out local
contracts for supplies of food and meat.
</P>
<P>
   They now have a logistics base at Kosovo Polje, a predominantly
Serbian settlement between the airport and the city, and can be
seen buying local produce from Serbs on the street. During the next
weeks they will start to deploy their forces out into the regions,
basing hundreds of troops in each of the French, German and
American sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Greeted by the Serbian community as fellow Slavs, the Russians
are viewed with suspicion by Albanians. Volchkov said they did not
expect to encounter antagonism from the Kosovo Liberation Army, but
were ready for all contingencies. ``They fully understand why we
are here and what task we are fulfilling,'' he said. ``It is quite
normal for them to be suspicious, especially after what happened
here. It will need time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
