<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-EXCURSION-LADN-(S     07-06 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-EXCURSION-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOICE SHOTS IN TEMECULA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMECULA, Calif. _ The biggest problem about a golf getaway to
this southern Riverside County wine country might be choosing which
course to play. Given the combination of beauty, price and
facilities, the area is hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   With SCGA Members club, Redhawk, Temeku Hills and the 27-hole
Temecula Creek Inn all within six miles of each other, the golfing
choices are multiple and optimum. In the summer, none of these
courses costs more than $55 (cart included) to play during the
week. All can be played for much less with super-twilight rates
(after 4 p.m.), which are worth trying just for the spectacular
sunsets in this mountain-highlighted region.
</P>
<P>
   The best test in terms of difficulty is Redhawk, but
single-digit handicappers only need try this beast from the back
tees.
</P>
<P>
   At its full length of 7,180 yards, par-72 Redhawk plays to a
course rating of 75.7. The slope rating, used to assess the
relative difficulty of all golf courses, is 149 at 9-year-old
Redhawk. By comparison, Industry Hills and TPC Stadium Course in La
Quinta, courses legendary for their difficulty, have respective
back-tee-slope ratings of 142 and 143.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unique and a challenge,'' Redhawk head pro J.B. Sneve
said of the Ron Fream-designed layout that can test golfers with
rolling terrain, five water holes, elevation changes and 18 tiered,
undulated greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got some sensational views from elevated tees and there
are a lot of holes that can be visually intimidating,'' Sneve said,
``but it's a course for all ability levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty, he said, depends on what tees you choose and how
aggressively you play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more aggressive you are, the more apt you are to make
mistakes that can get you into trouble,'' Sneve said. ``If you play
a little more conservatively, you have a chance of doing better.
Keep the ball in the fairways and on the right tier on the greens
and you can score. Shortside yourself and you'll have to find some
magic in those wands.''
</P>
<P>
   __ SCGA Members Club, designed by Robert Trent Jones Sr.,
features the large scale that has defined his architectural style.
Everything seems bigger than normal at Members Club, from gaping
bunkers to huge, undulating greens to wide, sweeping fairways.
</P>
<P>
   Even the wind is big, especially in the afternoons, and it is
the single biggest barrier to low scores. In keeping with that
theme, Members Club offers SCGA members a sizable discount _
charging $40 on weekdays and $55 on weekends, cart included.
</P>
<P>
   __ Temecula Creek Inn gives golfers a choice of three par-72
courses from a mixture of three nine-hole layouts. The Creek/Oaks
combination (both courses designed by Dick Rossen) has been the
most popular mix. The newer Stonehouse side, designed by Ted
Robinson, is most scenic. Temecula Creek also offers lodging, with
all-you-can-play packages available.
</P>
<P>
   __ Temeku Hills, another Ted Robinson-designed course,
challenges visitors with elevated, snaking greens that are the
course's primary defense against par. Hitting approach shots below
the flagstick is the key to success here. But that can seem
difficult for golfers who approach with a club longer than the
distance would indicate because of those elevated greens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
