<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA AND U.N. WORKING ON KASHMIR FLIGHT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations and India are struggling to
resolve a dispute over an airport that India closed to
international civilian traffic as fighting erupted in May in
Kashmir, U.N. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, the dispute involves the United Nations' use of the
airport in the Indian city of Srinagar, south of the line that
divides hostile Indian and Pakistani forces in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute also reflects the far broader tensions between
the United Nations and India, which has refused since 1972 to
recognize U.N. involvement in the fate of the disputed Himalayan
territory.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the United Nations had used the airport to transport
personnel, equipment and supplies for a small observer mission that
has been stationed on the dividing line since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   But about the time the fighting erupted in May, India told the
United Nations that its chartered plane from Pakistan could no
longer land at the airport, because Srinagar did not have
installations to control customs and immigration. All planes from
foreign countries would have to land first at New Dehli, which has
such an ability.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations stopped using the airport, one official said,
arguing that routing its plane through New Dehli would cost the
extra time and money.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have been conducted since then, and it now appears
that the United Nations is ready to yield to the demand that its
flights land first at New Dehli.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to regain the use of the airport soon,'' said Joachim
Hutter, director of the Asian and Middle East department of
peacekeeping operations for the United Nations. ``It's one of
several issues that we've been trying to sort out.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has little choice, a senior official said,
adding: ``We cannot challenge India's sovereignty in its right to
control its air space. But it will be more expensive for us to
operate now. There's no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said he could not yet say how much more the mission
on the Line of Control would cost because of India's decision.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Indian mission to the United Nations in New
York said only that the matter was ``under consideration'' by his
government.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the timing of the decision, he said only it was
intolerable for India to have ``people wandering around the country
without stamps in their passports'' and to have equipment moving
through it that had not been cleared through customs.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat played down the notion that the decision reflected
India's uneasiness with the U.N. stance on the Kashmir conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But other diplomats said the dispute reflected India's
unhappiness with the U.N. role on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Like Indonesia's incorporation of East Timor in the mid-1970s,
India's claim to what it regards as its part of Kashmir has never
been recognized internationally.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Security Council passed resolutions in 1948 and
1949 that called for a plebiscite among Kashmiris to decide the
future of their territory. India has consistently refused to heed
the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, India has also refused to recognize the observers,
stating that the U.N. mandate was no longer valid, because New
Dehli and Lahore signed an agreement that year to settle the fate
of the disputed territory bilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, India maintained, the mandate of the mission had
lapsed, a position that Pakistan rejected.
</P>
<P>
   A succession of secretaries-general has maintained that only the
Security Council can end the mission, an action the council has
chosen not to do.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the dispute over the mandate, the 47-member
mission, the second oldest U.N. peace-keeping mission, is stationed
on the Pakistani side of the line that divides the forces in
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, now headed by Col. Fleming Johansen of Denmark, has
had little to observe, because the peacekeepers are far from the
region where Pakistani-backed Islamic militants and Indian forces
have been fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout its history, the mission has had nine fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of May, Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged India and
Pakistan to continue discussing their differences and stop
resorting to violence.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan could do little more than express his concern about
the conflict near Kargil, the scene of recent heavy fighting.
</P>
<P>
   After India and Pakistan tested nuclear weapons last year, India
refused to see a U.N. emissary sent to the region to encourage both
sides to stop such tests and abide by treaties that ban them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
