<SLUG> BC-BOEING-LAWSUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ACCUSES BOEING OF BLOCKING RACE-DISCRIMINATION INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Ariz.)  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusual legal clash between the government and its
second-largest defense contractor, the Department of Labor filed
three lawsuits against Boeing Co. Tuesday, accusing Boeing of
blocking an investigation of charges of racial discrimination at
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The suits accuse Boeing of refusing to provide access to records
after an African-American employee complained of widespread
discrimination last December. The suits also accuse Boeing of
refusing to cooperate in a review of the company's compliance with
federal nondiscrimination requirements at operations in Wichita,
Kan., and Mesa, Ariz., as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denying us that access cannot _ and will not _ be tolerated,''
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing said that requests by the department's Office of
Federal Contract Compliance Programs were out of line. ``To the
extent that Boeing has withheld data from the agency,'' said Peter
Conte, a Boeing spokesman, ``it has done so based on its good-faith
belief that the request is either unreasonable or exceeds the scope
of the OFCCP's authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Conte said the company hoped to resolve the issue informally,
but he added that Boeing ``is prepared to defend its positions
vigorously and believes that it will ultimately prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is the world's largest aerospace company and the
country's single largest exporter but only its second-largest
military contractor after Lockheed Martin Corp. During the 1998
fiscal year, Boeing was awarded $11 billion in government
contracts, according to the Labor Department. As a federal
contractor, the company is prohibited from discriminating against
its employees on the bases of race, sex, religion, color, national
origin, disability or veteran status.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation by the Labor Department, which was begun
earlier this year, came at the same time Boeing was facing a
private class-action lawsuit charging racial discrimination against
10,000 African-American employees. The lawsuit accused the company
of, among other things, discriminatory hiring practices, failing to
promote qualified minority workers and tolerating a hostile work
environment.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Boeing chairman Philip Condit, flanked by the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, announced a $15 million settlement of the suit in
which Boeing did not acknowledge any wrongdoing. But the deal has
since been challenged by some Boeing workers and has not yet been
approved by the federal judge sitting in the federal class-action
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two cases are technically separate, they are
connected, according to two people involved in the current dispute,
because much of the information the government is seeking is
related to the charges in the private lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Conte said that the government requests were unreasonable
because they were ``so broad that it would take hundreds if not
thousands of hours and hundreds of people to actually gather and
compile the information. Or the requests are so narrow in scope
that the data they are seeking does not exist in the form they are
seeking it.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the the Labor Department, which conducts 4,000
to 5,000 compliance reviews a year and rarely sues a company in
such a case, believe they were on firm legal ground and have asked
for an administrative law judge to hear the case on an expedited
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a condition of their contract, they agree that they will
engage in certain affirmative actions,'' said a Labor Department
official. ``They also agree to maintain certain records and make
them available. We think that we have a clear legal issue that
entitles us to these records.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
