<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VIETNAM-EXHIBIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT OF VIETNAMESE ART ROUSES IMMIGRANT ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. _ The Vietnamese immigrants gathered outside
the Bowers Museum of Cultural Art here believe that the Communists
they crossed an ocean to escape are haunting them again, this time
with paint and canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants have been protesting against an exhibition of
contemporary Vietnamese art since it opened at the museum on June
25. They are angered by the origin of the art and that some of the
paintings depict communist symbols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that painters try to convey a feeling,'' said Ky
Ngo, 47, who fled Vietnam in 1975 and who stood across the street
from the museum with a few dozen other protesters on a recent
afternoon. ``But here they want to convey communist thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   In one painting, a woman standing next to a forge is wearing a
military uniform, its lapels decorated with the red flag of
Vietnam. In another painting, a mother prays at an altar of
photographs, some of which show communist soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the paintings in the exhibition, which features
nearly 100 works since the 1920s, do not have any political
imagery. Many are scenes from Vietnamese life like fishing boats
and rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   That makes no difference to the immigrants, who believe that the
entire exhibition, which runs through Sept. 30, should be closed.
They say that artists in Vietnam do not have the freedom to paint
what they want and that the show is propaganda for the Vietnamese
government.
</P>
<P>
   The show, called ``A Winding River,'' was organized by the
Meridian International Center, a nonprofit cultural institution in
Washington. Nancy Matthews, vice president for arts at the Meridian
Center, said the exhibition's curators, who traveled to Vietnam to
select much of the art, had total freedom in visiting galleries
there and were not required to receive permission from the
Vietnamese government to take the works out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Nghi Phan, a Vietnamese immigrant who fled Saigon a day
before the Viet Cong took control of the city in 1975, sees the
show as ``just the start of the infiltration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Communists are very malicious; they go little by little like a
drop of oil,'' Phan said.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants say their protest is part of their larger agenda
to end all interaction between the United States and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition has appeared in seven American cities. The only
other significant protest was at the Artcenter in Plano, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Baker, curator for Asian art at the Bowers Museum, which
is operated by the City of Santa Ana, said she had expected some
criticism of the exhibition and had invited prominent members of
the Vietnamese community to view slides of the show before it
opened.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the immigrants liked the show, Ms. Baker said,
others were critical.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession, museum officials agreed to remove the painting
of the woman at the forge, which was a particular concern to the
immigrants, but reversed their decision after some members of the
public and other museums complained that they were submitting to
censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baker agreed with the protesters that artists in Vietnam do
not have total freedom but said visitors could take that into
account and decide for themselves whether the art was communist
propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protesters are very concerned about freedom,'' Ms. Baker
said. ``But if they are protesting the right of museums to show
this work, then they are denying the museums their First Amendment
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baker said the debate had doubled museum attendance to about
200 viewers a day. The exhibition has been the focus of dozens of
local news reports by English and the Vietnamese news
organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
