<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VULGARITY-AD-COLUMN-N     07-06 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VULGARITY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: THE GROSS-OUT GENRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When historians of advertising and popular culture look back at
the emblematic campaigns of 1999, the images they will scrutinize
will most likely include an adorable girl who sells soft drinks
with the dubbed voices of celebrities, a dog that seemingly talks
to peddle tacos, a veritable galaxy of aliens pitching products
tied to a science-fiction film _ and two actors posed as if
micturating.
</P>
<P>
   That last image, promoting the film ``Big Daddy,'' starring the
comedian Adam Sandler, represents what may be the first time that a
major Hollywood studio has sold a mainstream movie on the basis of
a bodily function. Print and poster advertisements for ``Big
Daddy,'' created in-house at Columbia Pictures, depict a scene from
the movie in which Sandler, portraying a slacker who plays father
to a boy, teaches the child how to cope with a sudden need to
urinate by using a restaurant wall as a lavatory. The scene is also
included in some of the television commercials and trailers for the
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Daddy'' is one of the hit films of the summer, taking in
an estimated $90.1 million at the box office since opening on June
25. The opening-weekend take of $41.5 million was the most ever for
a Sandler film so far.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a special ad created to run during the Fourth of
July weekend, when ``Big Daddy'' finished second in ticket sales
behind only ``Wild Wild West.'' The original image was revamped to
pose Sandler and the boy facing an elaborate display of fireworks
exploding behind the Manhattan skyline _ and the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing a multimillion-dollar campaign for a movie on a call of
nature may well be a sign of the times, reflecting a general
coarsening of commercial speech as well as popular entertainment.
After all, ``Big Daddy'' is competing against films in the
so-called gross-out genre whose very titles titillate: ``South
Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who
Shagged Me'' and ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a striking visual that would represent the
movie's irreverence and `break us out' in a very competitive time
period,'' said Senn Moses, senior vice president for worldwide
marketing at Columbia in Burbank, Calif., owned by Sony Corp. of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a naughty movie,'' he added. ``We're a funny
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   No less indicative perhaps is the almost universal acceptance of
the campaign by the media and owners of outdoor advertising spaces
and the almost complete absence of negative reaction to the ads,
apart from scattered complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new high in low that an image like this raises no one's
eyebrows,'' said Richard Kirshenbaum, co-chairman at Kirshenbaum
Bond &AMP; Partners in New York. ``I personally found the image
distasteful.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, The New York Times has received just 10 complaints
protesting a decision to run the ad.
</P>
<P>
   While ``we take all complaints seriously,'' said Lisa
Carparelli, a spokeswoman for The Times, ``given the millions of
readers exposed to our advertisements, 10 is a relatively small
number of complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Daily News in New York, owned by Mortimer Zuckerman, Les
Goodstein, executive vice president and associate publisher, said:
``We of course reviewed the ad and decided to take it. We have
gotten not one complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   There have also been no complaints to speak of at The Washington
Post, owned by Washington Post Co., or The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, owned by Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do take a look at ads and try to think through what issues
there may be,'' said Debbie Reetz, assistant national ad manager at
the Atlanta newspaper. ``We kind of thought we possibly might hear
something, but there haven't been any comments that I've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Why has there been so muted a response to what at one time may
have been so provocative an image?
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture is totally debased,'' said Barbara Lippert, a
critic for the trade publication Adweek in New York. ``There is
tolerance because this is accepted now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not responding because it could be worse,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Donny Deutsch, chairman and chief executive at Deutsch Inc. in
New York, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't even do a double take anymore because you're
desensitized,'' Deutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are `overmedia-ed,''' he added, ``and living in a world
where almost nothing is sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirshenbaum attributed the calm to a perception that the ad fits
the product being marketed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at Adam Sandler as a brand,'' Kirshenbaum
declared. ``He is known for such fraternity-style humor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad is not out of character, so it's not controversial,''
he added. ``People do not look at it as they would if it were
Harrison Ford.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Senn at Columbia said that ``the way we approached''
creating the campaign was to consider ``what would most represent
the movie and the Adam Sandler brand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find a visual with that irreverent and
unpredictable appeal Adam has,'' he added, ``and to convey his
comic take on fatherhood. And we wanted to find something everyone
could relate to, either the younger or the older audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Dick, vice president for worldwide advertising at Columbia,
echoed his colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never considered the ad in bad taste,'' Dick said, adding
that the image ``seemed to encapsulate the character Adam played, a
guy not equipped to be a father but trying to do his best.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly magazine, in an article that graded poster
ads for summer movies, condemned the image as ``revolting'' _ but
quickly added that it works because ``you pretty much know the
plot, the cast and the tone of `Big Daddy' in one quick glance.''
That earned the ad a grade of B+.
</P>
<P>
   The ad has proved so popular that it was spoofed to promote a
rival release. A newspaper ad that was part of the campaign for the
``Austin Powers'' movie replaced Sandler and the boy with two
characters from that film, Dr. Evil and his smaller doppelganger,
Mini-Me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely a parody ad,'' said Steve Elzer, senior vice
president for corporate communications at New Line Cinema in Los
Angeles, the unit of Time Warner Inc. that released and marketed
the Powers comedy. ``It's keeping with the spirit of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   New Line, too, received no complaints about its ad, Elzer said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few rejections for the ``Big Daddy'' ad came from the
Metropolitan Transit Authority in New York City, which vetoed the
image ``because of what it depicted,'' said Tom Kelly, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes against everything we're trying to do with the
system,'' he added. ``You don't want to have anyone urinating
against a wall or a door.''
</P>
<P>
   Which might be the next summer movie ad to walk the fine line
between acceptance and outcry? It could be the campaign for
``American Pie,'' a coming-of-age comedy opening this Friday that
seeks to be the ``Porky's'' for the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the ad's double entendres about ``your first piece of
pie.'' Wait until moviegoers find out the significance of the flute
displayed in the ad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
