<SLUG> BC-BBN-ALL-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA AN ALL-STAR STARTER AS ORDONEZ HOPES FOR BID  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Considering that he had been either elected or selected to the
All-Star Game in each of his first six seasons in the majors, Mike
Piazza was pretty much a shoo-in in the balloting for starting
catcher this year. The National League confirmed it Tuesday when it
announced the starters for next Tuesday's All-Star Game in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets will have at least one representative in Fenway
Park. But will Piazza have company?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm not going alone,'' Piazza said after he was elected
by fans as the NL's starting catcher for the sixth consecutive
season. ``It's no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The National League reserves will be announced Wednesday, and
from the Mets, Edgardo Alfonzo, Robin Ventura, Rey Ordonez, the
injured John Franco and his replacement as closer, Armando Benitez,
all merit consideration for San Diego manager Bruce Bochy's roster,
as might Roger Cedeno, who leads the major leagues in stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Piazza seemed to be pushing extra hard for Alfonzo, who
was seventh in the league in hits and was batting .299 with 12
homers and 53 RBI going into last night's game with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they give me the opportunity to go, then do you think I'm
going to say no?'' said Alfonzo, who otherwise will spend the
three-day break helping his wife take care of their newborn son
while trying to convince his 3-year-old son that the new addition
to the family is not a new toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fonzie, for a second baseman, has some tremendous numbers,''
said Piazza, who has some pretty good numbers himself: a .306
average, 16 homers and 47 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza received 1,645,304 votes, third-most overall, and he
easily out-polled the runner-up at catcher, Pittsburgh's Jason
Kendall, who received 511,587 votes, but a fractured ankle ended
his season on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa, who leads the league with 32
homers, led all NL players in the balloting with 2,315,204 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was voted to the National League's starting outfield along
with Colorado's Larry Walker and San Diego's Tony Gwynn. However,
Gwynn, who is on the disabled list with a strained left cal,
announced Tuesday that he will not play. Barry Bonds of the Giants
finished fourth in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   The other winners at their positions were St. Louis' Mark
McGwire at first base with 1,669,066 votes, second most in the
league; Arizona's Jay Bell at second base and Matt Williams at
third, and Cincinnati's Barry Larkin at short.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin edged Ordonez by a margin of 58,345 votes _ 858,203 to
799,858. But Larkin was pulling away from Ordonez by the end of the
voting period.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mets General Manager Steve Phillips and Manager Bobby
Valentine were pushing for Ordonez's selection, which would be his
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's played like an All-Star,'' Valentine said of his
shortstop, even though the two have sometimes had a tacky
relationship this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go,'' said Ordonez, who was hitting .296 _ 54 points
better than his career average before this season _ going into last
night. ``Everyone wants to go to the All-Star Game. But if I don't,
I'll go to Miami for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, not everyone wants to go if they are not voted in; see
Texas' Juan Gonzalez. But Piazza, who has never missed the game,
feels pretty much like Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get tired of going,'' Piazza said. ``As long as I'm
elected or selected, I'm going to go. I even have a routine, now.''
</P>
<P>
   That routine will not include the home run derby, although
Piazza will serve for the second consecutive year as an ESPN
commentator on the exhibition. ``I've done it before,'' Piazza said
of the home run hitting contest, ``and I didn't do too well. ``It's
nice for me to take that off and just watch it and let the McGwires
and Sosas do it. And with the weather and the position I play, I'd
rather go up and watch it in the air-conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is looking forward to getting to hit at Fenway Park. His
only previous visit there was last June _ and Pedro Martinez of the
Red Sox, who will likely start the game on Tuesday for the American
League, hit Piazza with a pitch in his first at-bat. Piazza missed
the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to hit in a game there and not get hit,''
Piazza said. ``It will probably be against the same guy, too.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
