u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      07-06 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JULIE MASON
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ When Texas Gov. George W. Bush touched down in Colorado
on Tuesday, his birthday party was a bipartisan one _ he turned 53
and collected endorsements from 26 of the state's Hispanic leaders,
more than half of whom are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the front-runner for the 2000 Republican presidential
nomination, also stayed long enough to continue his voracious
fund-raising, appearing at a $1,000-a-person downtown event on the
first leg of a three-day campaign swing through three Western
states.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Republican Gov. Bill Owens said he was not surprised
that his Texas counterpart was attracting support from outside the
party. At an airport rally early in the day, Owens appeared with
Bush and Hispanic elected officials, business leaders and
educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a campaign bring together the excitement and
unity this campaign has brought together,'' Owens said. ``Not just
in this state, but in the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, many of the Hispanic leaders endorsing Bush said
they did so based on his record in Texas, and also his promises to
Colorado and the nation. Hispanics make up Colorado's largest
minority, accounting for about 13 percent of the state's
population.
</P>
<P>
   Many noted Bush's accomplishments in education as a key factor
in deciding their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are faced today with a great opportunity,'' said Larry
Trujillo, a Democrat acting as spokesman for the group. ``I know
Governor Bush is going to help us solve our problems in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father, former President George Bush, lost Colorado to
President Clinton in 1992, but Republican nominee Bob Dole carried
the state in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, looking tanned and relaxed, made a few remarks in Spanish
and offered some snippets from a speech he would give later in the
day to prosperous downtown contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a uniter, not a divider,'' Bush said. ``I understand
polls, they're important. But there is only one election that
matters, and I am going to work Colorado as hard as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was traveling without his wife, Laura, was greeted at
a private airport by about 200 mostly Anglo supporters who carried
signs that read, ``Viva Bush!''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he was particularly pleased that 14 of the 26
Hispanics who endorsed him are Democrats. He said there is room on
his stage for many, because ``my vision for America includes
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a few Democrats standing up here,'' Bush said.
``And they are showing a lot of intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his likely general election opponent, Vice President Al
Gore, intend to compete for Hispanic voters, who may be a key group
in many states. Bush's appeal to non-Cuban Hispanics, a traditional
Democratic constituency, is one of his greatest assets entering the
Republican nominating contest.
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek poll of 505 Hispanic adults released Tuesday shows
Bush and Gore currently tied for the Hispanic vote, with each
attracting about about 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a fund-raiser attended by several hundred supporters,
Bush offered a general outline of his priorities for himself and
the nation, including civil justice reform, strengthening the
military, improving free trade and emphasizing ``responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my most important responsibility is when I put my hand
on the Bible, I will not only swear to uphold the laws of our
country, I will swear to uphold the dignity of the office of the
president of the United States of America,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also made solemn reference to the recent tragedy at
Columbine High School, which is in a Denver suburb, promising
``tough love'' policies to instruct young people about the
consequences of their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can pass laws to give schools and principals more authority
to discipline children and protect the peace of classrooms,'' Bush
said. ``We must encourage states to reform their juvenile justice
laws. We must say to our children, `We love you, but discipline and
love go hand and hand, and there will be consequences for bad
behavior.'''
</P>
<P>
   Toughening juvenile justice laws was a centerpiece of Bush's
first term in office.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting his own success in Texas, Bush promised to allow
states more authority and flexibility to fashion their own
solutions to education. He said Americans should make a solemn
commitment that every child will be educated.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also told the crowd of business leaders, lawyers, elected
officials that the nation's prosperity should be inclusive and
available to all. To that end, Bush suggested reducing the
regulations that ``strangle enterprise'' and creating an
environment where businesses and families can flourish.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of his remarks, Bush was presented a cake and he
remarked of his 53rd birthday, ``I used to think it was old. Now I
know it's young.'' Overhead, speakers blared Lyle Lovett's song,
That's Right, You're Not From Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
