<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWDEN HAS BUILT REDS INTO SURPRISE CONTENDER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ga., Calif., Wash., Texas, Ariz., N.J.)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Mets can accept the reality of their inability to
overtake Atlanta for the National League East championship, they
can then focus on a second-half pursuit of the wild-card spot for
the playoffs. But in assessing their chances for that position,
they have to face the emergence of two new, unexpected guests at
the wild-card party.
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, the Arizona Diamondbacks were given, at
best, a remote chance to contend for a playoff spot. Their
expensive stockpiling of starting pitchers during the winter
created that chance. They have unleashed an unexpectedly potent
offense on the league, however, and appear to have become a
legitimate contender for something (as opposed to the illegitimacy
of the Los Angeles Dodgers, but that's another tale).
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, the Cincinnati Reds were, at best, an
intriguing team. Some off-season moves they made _ the acquisition
of starting pitcher Denny Neagle and slugger Greg Vaughn, for
example _ gained them some attention, but many weren't sure what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them at the beginning of the season as one of the
mystery teams because of the moves they made,'' said Gerry
Hunsicker, general manager of the Houston Astros, the team that had
been viewed as the best in the NL Central. ``A team with the
ability to surprise but with enough questions that you couldn't say
they were going to be one of the top teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Mets can't be sure if the Reds or the Astros
will contend with them for wild-card honors, but they both can't
win the division title. The same idea applies to the Diamondbacks
and the San Francisco Giants in the West, or any other team that
becomes a second-half bloomer.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one team to watch as the second half progresses,
it's the Reds. They have just gone through possibly the most
arduous stretch of the schedule that any team will face this year,
and they responded magnificently.
</P>
<P>
   Playing two division leaders, the Astros and the Diamondbacks,
the Reds won 12 of 14 games and leaped from six games behind to one
game ahead in first place. In the course of that sizzling span,
they became the first team in history to win 10 consecutive games
against first-place teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they're playing about as good as any team could
play,'' Hunsicker said Tuesday by telephone from Phoenix. ``They're
getting great offense up and down the lineup, they're getting great
pitching and they're not beating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They surprised me with the consistency they've shown. The
first month of the season, they looked like they were just another
team. Now they look like a legitimate contender. They're going to
be a team to be reckoned with the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are the $31 million production of Jim Bowden, who is
perhaps the most creative general manager in the business. Saddled
with the shrunken payroll of a low-revenue team, he has pieced
together a team that has produced unexpected developments all over
the field.
</P>
<P>
   The infield epitomizes the talent the Reds have exhibited:
</P>
<P>
   _ First baseman Sean Casey, who entered last night's game
hitting .371, has been first or second in the league in batting
much of the season. He also leads the league's first basemen in
fielding average and is among the league leaders in a host of other
offensive categories, including slugging and on-base percentages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Second baseman Pokey Reese has made only one error, none in 58
games since April 27, and is hitting .305, not bad for a third-year
major leaguer who had a .241 average in six minor league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shortstop Barry Larkin has been his old reliable self but
outdid himself in June, leading the league with a .430 batting
average.
</P>
<P>
   _ Third baseman Aaron Boone was hitting .218 when he was sent to
the minors May 12. Since returning two weeks later, he has hit
.310.
</P>
<P>
   Surprises abound on the pitching staff as well, although they
work both ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me in spring training,'' Bowden said, ``that
Neagle wouldn't win a game and Brett Tomko would have three wins
and we'd have the second-best record in the league, I wouldn't have
believed you.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, whose acquisition opened second base for Reese because
Bret Boone was sent to Atlanta in the trade, has been on the
disabled list (for the second time) since May 24 with a weak left
shoulder. He has made only six starts, losing three and winning
none.
</P>
<P>
   Tomko is a third-year major leaguer who spent the first half of
May in the minors taking a refresher course. Bowden had counted on
15 victories from him this season after 11 and 13 the previous two
years. Tomko took a 3-4 record into his start in St. Louis Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the surprise line, Ron Villone stands very
tall. ``He was drafted No. 1 by Seattle and he's been traded for
Andy Benes, Greg Vaughn and Marquis Grissom,'' Bowden said.
``That's four teams that saw potential. I guess it took the fifth
team for him to reach the potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving credit to manager Jack McKeon and his pitching coach, Don
Gullett, Bowden was talking about a 29-year-old left-hander from
Bergenfield, N.J., who had relieved in the majors 162 times and had
never started a game before June 8. He has made six starts, and in
three of them he allowed only one hit each _ in five innings
against the Mets, seven against Houston and eight against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The last two games were part of the Reds' recent remarkable run.
``What we've shown,'' Bowden said, ``is we have a baseball team
that can play with the big boys in our league. Obviously our young
players have matured and come together quicker than anticipated.
The young kids have been phenomenal, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   So has the Reds' relief corps. Led by Scott Williamson with 10
saves, a 7-2 record and a 1.45 earned run average, the bullpen crew
has been the best in the league, achieving the most victories and
the lowest ERA and opponents' batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our teams that won in 1995 and 1990 had good bullpens and good
defense,'' Bowden said. ``That's what this team has in common with
those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden expects the team to suffer a letdown at some point. ``I
think all teams go through a cycle where they have a good run and
then a bad run,'' he said, ``but I think this team has proven since
opening day that we can play with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Because their starting pitching has been the Reds' weakest
ingredient, Bowden is scouring the other 29 teams for possible
acquisitions, an exercise being undertaken by just about every
other contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all of our scouts out in the field,'' he said.
``We've targeted 32 pitchers. Not all are available, but we're
doing our homework.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bowden does his homework, he more often than not gets an
A. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
