<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-AID-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AID PLAN IN PARTISAN GRINDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For lawmakers who want to strengthen the military
or save Medicare, there are plenty of opportunities to write
legislation to make their case. After all, the federal government
controls the purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   But because more than 90 percent of the money spent on public
education comes from state and local governments, members of
Congress have few ways to show they care about it. And that is why
the law intended to improve the education of children from poor and
minority families, up for renewal in Congress this year, has become
an object of sharp partisan debate over how the money should be
spent, with no resolution in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines are sketched in these comments from two
veterans, one from a Democratic administration, one Republican:
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Smith, President Clinton's acting deputy secretary of
education: ``In this nation's brand of federalism, there is more
disparity at the local level, less at the state level and even less
at the federal level. The allocation of resources is fairer at the
federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Chester Finn, an assistant secretary of education in the Reagan
administration and now a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute:
``We've had 34 years of a Washington-knows-best education policy,
and it hasn't worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Title I provides federal money, now $8 billion a year, to
schools in poor and minority neighborhoods for things like teacher
training, after-school tutoring and classroom aides, with the
Education Department overseeing how the money is spent. When it was
first approved in 1965, in the rush of domestic legislation that
President Lyndon Johnson called his Great Society program, there
was little question that the spending of the federal money ought to
be directed by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But critics like Finn, most of them conservative, say that the
law has not worked and that the spending ought to be directed from
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, an undersecretary of education in the Reagan
administration who is now seeking the Republican nomination for
president, said, ``As a conservative, I already had my biases, but
it became clearer to me that it was better when decisions on
education are made on the local or state level.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 22, Republican leaders in Congress introduced a bill
that would embody that philosophy by allowing the states to use
federal money for education programs of their choice, pledging in
return to meet specific performance goals.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the House Committee on
Education and the Work Force, said: ``For more than three decades,
the federal government has been sending money to the states through
scores of Washington-based programs. But all the studies,
evaluations and reports show little or no academic results from
these programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration insists that there has to be a
national program, run from Washington, to insure that the spending
is highly focused and increases the chances of helping poor
children.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dale Kildee of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the
Education Committee, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governors like to spread the money around rather than target
it,'' Kildee said. ``They would like the money to be left on a
stump and let them come and pick it up and spend it where they
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a program loses its identity, it loses its advocacy, and
then it loses its dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisanship over Title I goes back a long way.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why the law had not achieved its goals after 34
years, Smith blamed the Republican administrations of the 1980s,
which he said sought to cut the law back and otherwise neglected
it.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, the Reagan education official, ridiculed the work of the
Education Department, saying, ``I spent 90 percent of every day
saying no to dopey ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone sees the debate in these terms. One
conservative who does not agree with the concept of block grants _
the federal government sending money to the states to administer a
program _ is Michael Greve, the author of ``Real Federalism: Why It
Matters, Why It Could Happen'' (American Enterprise Institute,
1999) and the director of the Center for Individual Rights, a
conservative public-interest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governors, mostly Republicans, say, `Give us the money and
we'll decide how to spend it,''' Greve said. ``That is an
irresponsible position.'' If states and school districts continue
accepting the federal money, he predicted, ``regulations grow and
money gets scarcer: a bigger stick and a smaller carrot.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor George Farkas, director of the Center for Education
and Social Policy at the University of Texas at Dallas, said, when
asked to choose between Federal and state control, ``I have a third
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spent $118 billion since 1966 when Johnson did all
this,'' Farkas said, and the gap in achievement between children
from poor and better-off families has not been narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a portion of the money to go into an account that the
parent controls, from which money could be spent for things like
tutoring,'' the professor said.
</P>
<P>
   Two studies have found that Title I programs ``weren't narrowing
the gap,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department counters by saying that scores last
year for reading were up in all three grade levels tested _ 4, 8
and 12 _ for the first time since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Educator Diane Ravitch, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, said of Smith: ``He's overstating the academic gains.
There was a dip, then it rose slightly. You can't say the federal
program did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The education law, which expires this year, is renewed in
five-year segments and will remain effective even if Congress does
not get around to acting on it soon, a practice that is not
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have a bipartisan reauthorization by mid-2000,''
Smith said. ``We won't have it this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
