<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-WOOFIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WOOFIE' BANKS, AN IDEA WHOSE TIME MAY HAVE GONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They go by the name ``woofie,'' although, in truth, they do not
have much ``woof'' to them. The term woofie refers to a type of
wholesale bank that was to have been created in the financial
overhaul measure that recently passed both houses of Congress. In
reality, however, the measure has dragged on so long that an idea
that seemed sparkling many years ago has little backing or meaning
today.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when the idea of eliminating Glass-Steagall
restrictions separating commercial from investment banking was
first floated, a basic bill was written. After various forms and
incarnations, it is now heading toward the finish line in Congress.
In that bill was a provision to create a new financial charter that
became known as a woofie.
</P>
<P>
   So, what is a woofie? It is a nickname for a wholesale financial
entity, a bank that would take only large deposits _ the minimum
would be $100,000 _ and, then, function essentially as a commercial
bank. It would not get federal deposit insurance, but would be part
of the Federal Reserve system and have access to the Federal
Reserve's discount window, should it need to borrow money for
liquidity needs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the House version of the measure provides for
woofies, but the Senate version does not, and it is unclear whether
woofies will be restored or jettisoned as congressional conferees
reconcile the differences between the two versions later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woofies are these bizarre little things,'' said Andrew
Parmentier, assistant communications director of the House Banking
Committee. ``Well, actually, they are not so little. They would be
a full-service financial institution for wealthy individuals and
corporations. They could do anything a commercial bank could do _
like make loans. But instead of managing $100 million from a
million people, the bank would be doing it for 10 people.''
</P>
<P>
   A woofie is basically a commercial bank that does not engage in
retail activities _ making car or mortgage loans _ and does not
take retail deposits. Instead, it would do all the corporate
activities of big banks, like making big loans to big corporations,
but would not have to pay insurance premiums to the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. since the insurance covers only deposits under
$100,000. As a result, woofies would not be subject to oversight by
FDIC examiners.
</P>
<P>
   But while escaping FDIC oversight, woofies would still be
subject to the same capital and soundness requirements of all
commercial banks and would be regulated by the Federal Reserve,
state banking regulators or the office of the comptroller of the
currency, depending on how the woofie was chartered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not sure anyone is interested in woofies anymore,''
said Ed Yingling, chief lobbyist for the American Bankers
Association. That is because the financial overhaul bill has
dragged on so long that financial institutions that once pressed
for woofies either no longer need them or no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people who were interested in woofies have been
merged out of existence,'' added Yingling. ``So a lot of the oomph
has gone out of woofies.''
</P>
<P>
   As some lobbyists explain it, woofies were originally proposed
as a way to get securities firms, which felt that banks were
encroaching on their turf but that were prohibited from doing
banklike activities, to endorse the concept of ending
Glass-Steagall restrictions and allowing banks to begin to
underwrite securities. The idea was that this would allow
securities firms to begin to take on more banking activities, while
avoiding the difficulties of a retail banking operation, with
tellers, branches and consumer concerns. A woofie would enable a
securities firm to get into commercial banking _ but only with
their familiar big-ticket customers and big-ticket numbers.
</P>
<P>
   So, a woofie working group including Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co.,
Bankers Trust, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, J.P. Morgan Securities,
Salomon Brothers and several other firms was formed to start the
woofie bandwagon rolling. Since then, several of these firms have
merged and lost interest in woofies; those that have not, have
little interest in woofies anymore.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, woofies have gotten ensnared in issues related to
the Community Reinvestment Act, which is intended to get more bank
credit extended to low-income areas. Originally, woofies would have
come under the provisions of that act, something that most Wall
Street firms accepted readily. But, this year, Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, who heads the Senate Banking Committee, has objected
strongly to extending the act's provisions to woofies, and his
opposition is one reason that woofies are no longer in the Senate
version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Securities firms had no intentions of wanting to become a
retail bank,'' said Karen Thomas, director of regulatory affairs
for the Independent Community Bankers of America. ``But they liked
having the bank charter as an adjunct to their securities
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
