<SLUG> BC-MA-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI SET TO NAME TOCCO HIGHER ED CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Governor Paul Cellucci plans to appoint Stephen P.
Tocco, former head of the port authority and a well-connected
political strategist, as chairman of the state's board of higher
education, administration sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is expected to make the announcement in the next
several days, but well-placed sources said that he had decided last
week to appoint Tocco, his close political adviser, to the powerful
education post.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the planned appointment stunned those in education
circles Tuesday night. In choosing Tocco, the governor is opting
for someone with strong political and adminstrative skills, but no
background in education, and a history of making headlines and
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Cellucci is convinced Tocco, 52, can provide the
leadership the governor wants to advance the administration's
higher education agenda. Tocco has a reputation for taking on tough
assignments, butting heads with opponents, and battling special
interests, most notably the state's labor establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good leader,'' said one top administration source
familiar with the governor's thinking. ``We need leadership and he
can drive the agenda for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though unpaid, the chairman's post is among the most prominent
in the administration, with responsibility for the state's public
colleges and university system.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci had been struggling to choose a successor to James F.
Carlin, who chaired the board for 3 1/2 years. The governor sought
to appoint Charles D. Baker Jr., his former secretary of
administration and finance, to the job.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker pulled himself out of the running when he took over as
president and CEO of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, the beleaguered
health maintenance organization.
</P>
<P>
   Tocco, who served in the Weld/Cellucci adminstration as
secretary of economic affairs and earlier as a senior aide to
former governor William F. Weld, now heads a public strategy and
lobbying unit at one of Boston's major law firms, Mintz Levin Cohn
Ferris Glovsky &AMP; Popeo.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci first brought Tocco into state government in 1991, and
promoted his advancement in the Weld/Cellucci admininistration.
Their relationship dates back to Cellucci's days as a legislator,
when Tocco headed the state's building contractors association.
</P>
<P>
   But as head of Associated Builders &AMP; Contractors, Tocco deeply
alienated the state's labor unions by pushing to roll back certain
wage laws.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci brought Tocco into the Weld/Cellucci inner circle in
the 1990 campaign, but immediately his divisive style _ and what
some call an outsized ego _ created friction. Weld and Cellucci
handed him major assignments after they took office, and Tocco's
personality again generated strong resentment, this time among
other top administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Weld, who had taken control of the Massachusetts Port
Authority board, engineered Tocco's appointment as the agency's
executive director. There, Tocco launched the $1 billion-plus
renovation of Logan Airport and concentrated on developing the
seaport.
</P>
<P>
   But he also tried to quarterback the development of megaplex for
South Boston, at times crossing swords with former Senate president
William M. Bulger, who is now president of the University of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said Tocco was too close to Patriots owner Robert Kraft,
and that he was trying to strong-arm the South Boston community
into swallowing a new football stadium on Massport land.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Tocco, Cellucci is turning to someone with political
skills but with no significant education experience. While Carlin,
too, had a business background, he had served on the University of
Massachusetts board of trustees for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Spencer, a current board of higher education member and
the entrepreneur behind the Pizzeria Uno empire, reportedly was
interested in assuming the chairmanship. But some said Spencer
would not command the same headlines and high profile needed to
succeed in the job.
</P>
<P>
   The new chairman inherits a 29-campus system _ with 175,000
students on five UMass campuses as well as state and community
colleges _ largely in good health.
</P>
<P>
   Applications are breaking records at UMass, and the quality of
students is higher than ever. The board has cut tuition for four
straight years, while the average price of public universities and
colleges nationwide has continued to rise about 4 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts board has also won nationwide acclaim for
eliminating remedial education at state universities and state
colleges, referring unprepared students to community colleges
instead.
</P>
<P>
   But not insignificantly, Tocco also faces a union alienated by
Carlin, whose reputation as a change agent was largely due to his
willingness to battle head to head with the state's professors. An
extension on the state college professors' contract expired at the
end of last month, and the past year of negotiations has been
largely hostile and unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin and the state's higher education chancellor, Stanley Z.
Koplik, have called repeatedly for reducing the number of tenured
professors in the state's schools, which have a higher rate of
tenured faculty than universities and colleges nationwide. Carlin
also suggested increased teaching loads.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, in turn, accused Carlin of doing nothing but
constantly attacking them. They derided him as an ``insurance
salesman,'' referring to the insurance company that is part of his
multimillion dollar network of successful businesses. In firing
back at him, the unions often said Carlin had no experience in
education, and insisted that just as they wouldn't tell him how to
make his money, he shouldn't tell them how to run their campuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
