<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHENICIE'S JOB IN LIMBO AT CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The status of CSUN assistant football coach Rob
Phenicie is unknown and not even head coach Ron Ponciano knows if
Phenicie will be on his staff this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, reports surfaced that Phenicie, the Matadors'
offensive coordinator, would leave the program and that Ponciano's
status at the school was in jeopardy. The program has been under
investigation for alleged rules violations.
</P>
<P>
   Phenicie, on the recommendation of his lawyer, said Tuesday he
would not comment. A school spokesmen said Phenicie was still with
the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Phenicie) will continue to be on the university's payroll and
at this moment, he is on vacation,'' said the CSUN Public
Information Office's John Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano, meanwhile, will fight for his reputation Friday when
he meets with investigators for just the second time since the
probe began more than a month ago. On May 19th, the school's
athletic program received an anonymous letter alleging infractions,
initiating an investigation by a campus board of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not anxious to talk to them, I am  &UR; !ital! &LR; excited to talk
to them,'' Ponciano said. ``I am going to go in there and fight
because I know who I am and the type of principles I have. After
they've heard all the voices, some of those that were tied to or
linked to the whole anonymous (letter), I think it's about time
that I've finally got a chance to be listened to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said he has not received a clear answer from the school
regarding Phenicie's status, adding the month-long investigation
has hurt the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person I talk to (about Phenicie), I get a different
answer,'' Ponciano said. ``Depending on who you talk to, I've
either lost (my) best coach, and (or) some kids want to leave (the
program).
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's a hit that not many programs can recover
from. But if there is one program (that can), it is Northridge,
because these kids are used to dealing with adversity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
