</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S SUICIDE ADDS BIZARRE LIGHT ON INSURANCE FRAUD INQUIRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Miss . )   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, a young woman named Frances Burge was found dead
in Greenwich, Conn., hanging by a rope from the deck of a luxurious
house.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the death, ruled a suicide, was a personal
tragedy, the sad end to a troubled life.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, Miss Burge's death, and the year leading up to
it, provide an unusual insight into the life of a shadowy
businessman now being sought by federal authorities. They say the
businessman, Martin R. Frankel, defrauded insurance companies in
several states of hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich police, and parents and friends of several women he
employed, also say Frankel's personal life was as complicated and
unusual as his financial dealings, involving many women and
sadomasochistic sex behind the walls of his Greenwich mansion.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Miss Burge was at the bottom of the Greenwich
pyramid. She went to work for Frankel as a gal Friday, hoping to
fulfill her dreams of money and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter was young, she made some foolish mistakes,'' her
mother, Gabriella Burge, said in an interview. ``She attracted the
wrong men. She wanted to be wanted. It makes me very sad for the
lonely girl. She was looking to better herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Her experiences working for Frankel, as told by her mother,
friends and police records, offer one of the first pictures of a
life style that blended the trappings of Wall Street with the
sprawling excesses of a well-heeled commune.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Burge, 22 when she died, answered an ad in The Village
Voice placed by Frankel in summer 1996. By September she was
working at his mansion, running errands for a household of female
friends and co-workers. She told friends she was learning the stock
business.
</P>
<P>
   She does not appear to have played any role in what federal
authorities say were Frankel's intricate financial schemes. Nor,
she told her mother, was she involved in the sadomasochistic sexual
practices that the police say Frankel favored in his Greenwich
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not psychologically prepared inside for this
situation, for this life situation,'' said Vera Mirnova, Frankel's
Russian housekeeper. ``She was a very nice girl, but she got into
something she was not prepared for.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Burge, from the blue-collar village of Shirley, N.Y.,
was born in 1974 to a Jewish mother and a Mormon father and was
baptized a Mormon at 4.
</P>
<P>
   According to her mother and police records, Miss Burge's
teen-age years on Long Island were marked by a suicide attempt,
hospitalization for depression, a pregnancy (she gave up her baby
for adoption) and a period of living in a homeless shelter with her
mother after her parents separated.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Miss Burge had received a high school equivalency
diploma and was working at a Blockbuster video store in Shirley.
She was living with her father in town when she saw an ad in The
Village Voice and replied.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, a black limousine sent by Frankel appeared at her
house in Shirley and took her to Greenwich for what she told her
mother was a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Miss Burge described what happened. Her mother
said that Frankel served her dinner at a long table and then asked
her to disrobe. She complied, her mother said, but she did not get
the job.
</P>
<P>
   During the investigation into the suicide, Frankel gave the
Greenwich police a different account. ``During that evening,
Frances had taken her clothes off and wanted to have sex,'' he told
police, ``but I did not want to.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Frankel decided to hire Frances Burge after
all. She told her mother she was working as an office assistant for
a millionaire independent investor.
</P>
<P>
   She moved into one of Frankel's mansions. Mrs. Mirnova said as
many as 100 people worked in a nearby mansion, including cooks,
assistants and computer workers. A phone directory for the house
from 1997 lists the numbers and beepers for 42 people.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel had 80 computers and a fiber optic line installed at the
mansion, according to court papers. But it is not clear what
business transactions, if any, he conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Burge, Frances Burge's father, told the police during
the investigation that his daughter complained of not being paid
regularly. She was occasionally given traveler's checks or cash, he
said, and had to keep receipts for everything she purchased.
</P>
<P>
   One woman who said she was hired as an office consultant said
that she saw only benign eccentricity. ``They were all kooky, and
the reason they hired me was to organize,'' she said. ``There was
no toilet paper, but there were 40 cans of tuna fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Life in Greenwich changed Miss Burge. She returned to Shirley
for visits, and her former co-workers at Blockbuster recall that
the overweight woman who never tucked in her shirt was wearing
makeup now, her hair in a French braid, a slimmer physique visible
in a new exercise suit. She drove a Champagne-colored sedan and
carried a pager and a cell phone. She boasted of shuttling to a
Manhattan apartment, shopping without limits and deciding what
investments Frankel should make.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Mrs. Burge visited her daughter, and while Miss Burge
refused to take her inside the mansion, saying it was forbidden,
they drove by. As the months wore on, Mrs. Burge said that her
daughter said she had tried to learn more about sadomasochism,
visiting a Manhattan club, the Vault, with Frankel's girlfriends.
``She said, `Marty promised to teach me,' Mrs. Burge recalled.
``And I kept saying, `What is there to learn?'''
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, on Mother's Day, Miss Burge returned home for a
final visit. She told her mother she felt empty and depressed. She
also referred to knowing that Frankel was doing ``something
wrong,'' Mrs. Burge recalled.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 8, one of Frankel's office workers stepped outside the
mansion and found Ms.Burge hanging by a noose from a beam of the
elevated deck.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenwich police report notes the presence of
sadomasochistic paraphernalia, including ropes, a riding crop and
videotapes. The police interviewed Frankel, his employees, Miss
Burge's psychiatrist and her parents. They did not speak to any of
Frankel's neighbors, one of whom later relayed to federal
authorities that he had heard female screams the day Miss Burge
died. It was not clear whether that information was given to
Greenwich police.
</P>
<P>
   The police defended their two-month investigation, saying they
had found out enough to rule the death a suicide. Police officials
said their inquiry confirmed Ms. Burge had a history of depression
and was on anti-depressant medication. A toxicology and autopsy
report led them to rule the cause of death as asphyxiation by
hanging.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Miss Burge's death, her parents sifted through
her belongings in her room. They found a completed application to
Mercy College in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., her mother said. The bible she
had kept since childhood was missing.
</P>
<P>
   While his staff prepared a buffet meal for Miss Burge's parents,
Frankel remained elusive. Mrs. Burge said she asked Karen Timmins,
identified in Greenwich police reports as Frankel's office manager,
if she could meet her daughter's boss. According to Mrs. Burge, Ms.
Timmins said: ``Well, Marty is very busy. The market crashed the
night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women who lived and worked at the house attended the
funeral in Shirley. Frankel did not show up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
