<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good day for Lopez's knee
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Javy Lopez breathed a small sigh of relief Tuesday,
feeling a little better about his sprained right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to make it back,'' said Lopez, who was
diagnosed with a slight ligament tear in a recent MRI exam.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez had expressed fears Monday that the injury, suffered in
Arizona on June 20 sliding into second base, might sideline him the
rest of the season. After running on it Tuesday, including some
hard sprints, cutting and quick stops, he was more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed because I thought it would hurt,'' said Lopez,
who said he felt some pain but it was minimal. ``The question is
tomorrow, to see how it feels once it quiets down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez plans to test it more today by squatting to catch for the
first time. He did some hitting for the first time Monday. He said
having his knee on his back leg injured doesn't limit him hitting
as much as it would if it were his front leg.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez expects to be out at least until after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more beneficial to me because I'd like to go out there
and play, not 100 percent healthy, but close to it,'' Lopez said.
``I don't want to go out now and the next day hurt myself again.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Star waiting
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan and Kevin Millwood are eagerly awaiting word of
today's All-Star reserve announcements, but they're trying not to
get their hopes up. The Braves' two best All-Star candidates got a
little boost upon learning that National League manager Bruce Bochy
called Braves manager Bobby Cox Monday and talked to him about
Jordan and Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   Working in Millwood's favor are his top-10 rankings in the
National League in wins (tied for fifth with 10) and ERA (sixth
with 3.30).
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be disappointed a little (if I don't make it),''
Millwood said. ``I feel like I've got a good chance to be there.
But it's not my decision. ... I'm trying not to think about it too
much, get my hopes up. If it happens, great. If it doesn't, I don't
want to be bummed out over the All-Star break.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan finished eighth in the outfield voting with 390,795 but
is tied for fifth in the National League in RBIs with 68. Jordan
was snubbed last year by National League manager Jim Leyland
despite leading the league in hitting at the time with a .339
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even worried about it,'' said Jordan, who's ready to
cancel plans for a family trip to Disney World in exchange for a
trip to Boston. ``Whatever happens, happens. Last year I was
anxious and disappointed. No sense in getting anxious this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon to undergo MRI exam
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Randall Simon is scheduled to have an MRI exam on
his left knee today as a precautionary measure. He injured it
sliding home in the Astrodome three weeks ago and has been playing
on it since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hurts,'' Simon said. ``Every day when I wake up, it's
stiff. But I come in here, get in the whirlpool and loosen it up
and it feels better. I'll go check it out. The doctor has told me
even if something's wrong, I can still go through the season, then
after the season get (surgery).''
</P>
<P>
   Chen will start Friday
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chen arrived in Atlanta on Tuesday after getting word at 1
a.m. he'd again be replacing John Smoltz, who's back on the
disabled list with an inflamed right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Chen last pitched for AAA Richmond on Sunday, which works out
well if he's to fill in for Smoltz in his turn in the rotation
Friday, which Cox indicated he planned to do.
</P>
<P>
   Chen got a no-decision in each of two May starts for Atlanta,
allowing six runs in 12 innings. He had one poor start in Richmond
after being sent back but won three starts after that. His focus
has been on keeping his pitches down and being more consistent with
his offspeed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going to be nervous,'' Chen said of his seventh
major league start. ``But it's not going to be like the first time
I came up (last September).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
