The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Wednesday, July
7, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOEING-RACE (Seattle) _ The U.S. Labor Department said it sued
The Boeing Co. on Tuesday, alleging the aerospace giant had denied
access to documents linked to a race discrimination complaint. As a
federal contractor, Boeing is prohibited from racial, sexual and
other forms of discrimination against employees. It is the
second-largest U.S. defense contractor, receiving $11 billion in
government contracts in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``f''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   BUS-AFTERMATH (Seattle) _ At 3 p.m. the day after Thanksgiving
1998, a gunman put a bullet in the driver of a Metro bus, sending
the bus off the Aurora Bridge and triggering a chain of events that
would test the limits of Seattle's emergency medical services. The
lessons learned in the 1 hour and 17 minutes it took to respond to
the scene, secure, treat and transport all injured passengers have
already changed some of the Seattle Fire Department's procedures.
In the emergency response community around the nation, there has
been steady interest in how the bus incident was handled and what
could be learned from it.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   UNITY (Seattle) _ Coverage of a town hall meeting on ``Color and
Credibility: With Too Few Minorities, Can a Community Believe the
Media?''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting takes place on the eve of Unity '99, a convention of
the four minority journalists groups, being held this week in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-DONATION (Seattle) _ Thanks to big eleventh-hour gifts
from the state's new technology millionaires, and 5,000 mostly
small donations, the drive to preserve 25,000 acres of wild
state-owned forest at the northeast corner of the Cascade Range has
reached $13.1 million. While it appears to have saved the Loomis
Forest from logging, the campaign hasn't made it entirely out of
the woods yet. The state must complete one final appraisal of the
remote forest before the state Board of Natural Resources can
approve the buyup of logging rights to the remote land.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON (Seattle) _ The Alaska Seafood Marketing Institute says
consumers are confused about whether it is all right for them to
eat salmon because they fear threatening and endangering the fish.
Alaska salmon is different, they say, and they have launched a
$250,000 ad campaign to carry their message to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   By Arthur C. Gorlick. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WITCH (Undated) _ Interview with the two young creators of
``Blair Witch Project,'' a low, low budget horror film that is
truly scary and is generating big buzz prior to its July 16
opening.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
