<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY WANTS NO REPEATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Seattle outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. is hoping
there will be no repeat of what happened during his appearance at
last year's All-Star Game in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who received more votes than anyone this season
(2,918,055), was named an American League starting outfielder
Monday. He will be making his 10th All-Star appearance next week in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Griffey originally elected not to participate in the
home run-hitting contest. He later decided to take part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Gonzalez and Sammy Sosa didn't participate last year and
they didn't get hammered like I did in the newspapers and they
didn't get booed by the fans,'' Griffey said prior to Tuesday's
game against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of friends told me what happened after I left
(Denver). The fan reaction came from one of Colorado's owners, who
called a couple of radio stations and told the fans to boo me.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey did not say on Tuesday whether he intended to
participate in this year's contest.
</P>
<P>
   __ Trade winds: Angels pitcher Chuck Finley will be making one
of the more important starts of his career Friday in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, in the thick of trade rumors, has given up 21 earned
runs in his last 112/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss to explain why,'' Finley said. ``The last three
starts, I have been brutal. I mean absolutely terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins already has prepped Finley for his start
in hitter-friendly Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get to Colorado on Friday, I told him he needs to get
ahead in the count,'' Collins said. ``As a manager, there are
things that are out of my control (such as trade talk). We want to
get Chuck back on track. We need him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Salmon swings: Outfielder Tim Salmon, out of the lineup since
May 3 with a sprained left wrist, took swings off a batting tee
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did take some dry swings, but there is no timetable,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Also: Seattle rookie Gil Meche was the 23rd Mariners pitcher
to take the mound this season, tops in the big leagues. The club
record is 25. Seattle has used 11 rookies as well. . . . The Angels
optioned left-handed pitcher Mike Holtz to Triple-A Edmonton
following Monday's loss. That opened the slot for Mike Fyhrie, who
made his debut Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
