<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-EAST-COAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST COAST MOBILIZES IN A BLOCK-BY-BLOCK RESISTANCE TO THE STIFLING
HEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-HEAT, HEAT-ELECTRICITY) 
 (nk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They canceled summer school here in the nation's
capital, dimmed the lights in much of the Massachusetts Statehouse
and sent block captains out to check on the elderly in
Philadelphia's row houses.
</P>
<P>
   Relief was in sight, the National Weather Service promised, but
much of the nation _ especially the mid-Atlantic region _ was still
staggering Tuesday under the unforgiving weight of a heat wave that
broke records, sent power use soaring and kept almost everybody
racing from one air-conditioned environment to another.
</P>
<P>
   Some, of course, didn't have that option, like William Gauthier,
a 27-year-old labor foreman on Boston's massive highway
construction project known as the Big Dig. He described working in
this heat as ``terrible,'' ``horrible'' and ``the most
uncomfortable feeling in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Livezey, senior research meteorologist at the Weather
Service's climate prediction center, said late Tuesday that ``it's
clear that tomorrow will not be as bad as today and conditions will
continue to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was scant solace in the here and now of a brutal
Tuesday. Jeff Moran, a spokesman for the Philadelphia Department of
Public Health, reported that there had been three heat-related
deaths there so far, all of them among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But officials there, and in Washington, said that they had
learned from the large number of heat-related deaths in the past
and were much better prepared for this heat wave. In Philadelphia,
people could call a special telephone number for advice on coping
with the heat _ and when warranted, be provided with checkups by a
nurse in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's capital, Sam Jordan, director of the office of
emergency management, said officials were working with
organizations for the homeless to watch for dehydration among
people living on the streets. Officials also distributed fans to
residents of public housing projects without air-conditioning, and
set up cooling centers around the city where people could get water
and ice.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, including tourists, persevered despite the heat. At
Independence Hall in Philadelphia, 2,900 tourists trooped through
Tuesday, carrying their water bottles. But the Washington Monument
was deserted in late afternoon, with only two or three scattered
families wandering up the hill to its base. And, in an equally
telling indication of the effects of the heat, only three softball
games were underway in the area nearby.
</P>
<P>
   New England had already set a record of power use by early
afternoon, and the lights were turned out in the halls of the
Massachusetts Statehouse to show support for conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Blanchard, 55, who works as a security officer at a
Boston courthouse, declared: ``If I had to compare it to hell,
Boston would be hotter. The devil doesn't stand a chance in Boston
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostas Havalavatos, 55, said he had gotten used to the heat
after managing eateries in Faneuil Hall for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is 100 degrees outside, it's 103 or 104 in the
kitchens,'' he said. ``I've seen guys work here for a week and then
quit because of the heat, but it's just part of the job, and I say
if they don't like the heat, they can just get out of the
kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Ligon, a visitor to Boston from Edmond, Okla., said,
``It's not real hot to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Weather Service said information was still
coming in about records broken Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chartuk, a spokesman for the National Weather Service,
said Tuesday's highs included 99 in Atlantic City and 102 at
Baltimore-Washington International Airport. He noted that over the
past 20 years, an average of 380 people die a year because of heat.
But he added that many cities have, in fact, instituted
comprehensive plans in recent years that have managed to stem those
losses.
</P>
<P>
   One of the neighborhood organizers in such a program in
Philadelphia, Shelly Thomas, sent her daughter, Latasha, over to
check on an elderly woman across the street. She found the woman
fearful of plugging in her air-conditioner, afraid it would cause a
blowout. Latasha persuaded her that it would not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
