<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: GOODWILL GAMES HEADED FOR BOSNIA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The war in Bosnia from 1992 to 1995 destroyed nearly all the
athletic sites of the 1984 Winter Olympics in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   The wooden seats from the Zetra arena were used for coffins. The
bobsled run turned into trenches. The mountain site for Nordic
skiing was transformed into a Serbian artillery position. The
Olympic stadium became a graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   But Sarajevo, which plans to bid for the 2010 Winter Olympics,
is trying to jump-start its resurrection by persuading Turner
Sports to take the Winter Goodwill Games to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of reconciliation in Bosnia needs a spur,
something to show the people that we are capable of pulling
together,'' said Muhamed Sacirbey, the ambassador to the United
Nations from Bosnia-Herzegovina. ``There have been three great
world events in Sarajevo: the assassination of Archduke Ferdinand,
the 1984 Olympics and the siege of Sarajevo. We prefer to be
remembered for what the Olympics stand for: pluralism, tolerance
and good will.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey first discussed the Goodwill Games several months ago
with Harvey Schiller, the president of Turner Sports. Mostly they
discussed TNT's televising a figure skating event at the rebuilt
Zetra, but the show was canceled because of NATO's bombing in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' said Schiller, who visited with Bosnian
government and Olympic officials in Sarajevo last week. ``But we've
expressed our concerns with their ability to get it done. They've
got rebuilding to do. The challenge lies with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey admitted that his intense push for the 2001 Winter
Goodwill Games will depend in part on the ability of Bosnia to
attract public and private investors to build hotels and finance
the continued reconstruction of the athletic sites. A deal with
Turner, he said, may persuade private lenders and sponsors to make
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``With private partners, they hear Bosnia, you think war, and
why do you want to be there,'' he said. The athletic sites are in
various states of repair, he said. The Zetra is ready. Some skiing
has been restored. The speed-skating track is being rebuilt. Work
is about to start on the ski-jumping facility. The bobsled and luge
runs will not be resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller is uncertain if Turner will commit to Sarajevo.
Turner's first Winter Goodwill Games will take place in Lake
Placid, N.Y., next year; to run two in consecutive years may not be
plausible. Yet Schiller will consider it. A report on Sarajevo is
due in September.
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey does not think a delay until 2002 is feasible because
of the Winter Olympics that year in Salt Lake City. And 2003 seems
too far away. ``You want to maximize the benefits of this by doing
it as soon as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller said, ``They'll need a lot of economic wherewithal to
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey would not rule out 2003. Bosnia is in no position to
force anything. ``We're looking to work as partners,'' he said.
``We've had a good dialogue. No one wants to play hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   The allure of Sarajevo to Turner Sports, which staged the
Goodwill Games in Moscow (1986) and St. Petersburg, Russia (1994),
would be to reclaim the original peaceful intent behind the event.
Ted Turner launched the games in 1986 after the United States
boycotted the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow and the Soviet Union
boycotted the 1984 Summer Games in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the games came to New York City, their purpose
was redefined to raising money for the Boys and Girls Clubs of
America and Unicef International.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon Bidding
</P>
<P>
   With Wimbledon over, so are NBC's and HBO's contracts to
broadcast the tennis tournament. NBC wants to continue, but HBO
does not. ABC appears to be NBC's main rival, with ESPN, Fox Sports
Net and the USA Network looking to replace HBO.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is unlikely to bring in one of its cable units, MSNBC or
CNBC, and would have to live with ESPN, Fox Sports Net or USA
selling commercial time for the same event. (HBO carries no
advertising.) NBC could team with Turner Sports, with which it is
planning a football league, but it is not considered a strong
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is not likely to be in the fray because the All England Club
would not be thrilled to have its Wimbledon jewel on the same
network that carries the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good time for Wimbledon negotiations. The past weekend's
ratings soared, because of the strong American showing and the
placement of both singles finals Sunday. The overnight Nielsen
rating on Sunday leaped 40 percent to a 5.6. For the semifinals on
Saturday, the rating jumped 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Tiger-Duval Shortfall?
</P>
<P>
   ABC might not show all 18 holes of the Aug. 2 Tiger Woods-David
Duval prime-time (8 to 11 p.m., Eastern) match-play golf
exhibition. The PGA Tour is insisting that the event begin at 7:30
p.m. Eastern (4:30 p.m. at the Sherwood Country Club in Los
Angeles) to guarantee enough time to complete a round. ABC would
join it in progress. ``The history of match play shows it takes
between 3 hours and 20 minutes and 3:40,'' said Henry Hughes, the
chief of operations for the PGA Tour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
