</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WEBSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEVERIDGE WEBSTER, A PIANIST   AND A LONGTIME TEACHER, DIES AT 91  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Pa., Texas, Mass., Germany, France)   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beveridge Webster, a pianist and teacher who was best known for
his elegant performances of the French repertory and his commanding
accounts of contemporary American scores, died on June 30 at
Kendal-at-Hanover, a retirement community in Hanover, N.H. He was
91.
</P>
<P>
   Webster was a particularly authoritative interpreter of the
music of Ravel, whom he had met in the 1920s when he was a student
in Paris. Webster gave the first performance of Ravel's ``Tzigane''
in Paris in 1924. In 1975, he celebrated the Ravel centenary by
performing all of the composer's solo works at the Juilliard School
and by touring with the Ravel Piano Concerto.
</P>
<P>
   Debussy was also among his specialties. Webster's three-concert
series at Town Hall in 1968, to commemorate the 50th anniversary of
Debussy's death, was the first complete survey of Debussy's piano
works in New York. Reviewing the first concert in The New York
Times, Harold C. Schonberg wrote admiringly of the variety of color
Webster brought to the works, his clarity of line in the ``Suite
Bergamasque'' and his virtuosic accounts of ``L'Isle Joyeuse'' and
``Feux d'Artifice.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave premieres or made first recordings of many contemporary
works, including pieces by Louise Talma, Roger Sessions, Roy
Harris, Aaron Copland and Elliott Carter. He also championed works
by Schoenberg, Berg, Bartok and Stravinsky. He taught for five
decades, at the New England Conservatory from 1940 to 1946 and at
the Juilliard School from 1946 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Webster was born on May 13, 1908, in Pittsburgh. His first
teacher was his father, who was also named Beveridge Webster and
who founded and directed the Pittsburgh Conservatory. In 1921, at
14, he began five years of study in Europe, principally with Isidor
Philipp and Nadia Boulanger at the Paris Conservatory. He was the
first American to win the school's first prize in piano. He studied
with Artur Schnabel in Berlin and toured Europe as a soloist in the
late 20s and early 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Webster's American debut was a performance of the MacDowell
Second Concerto with the New York Philharmonic in November 1934,
followed by a recital at Carnegie Hall. By the end of the '30s, he
had performed with many major American orchestras. He had a
reputation as a sensitive chamber music performer, collaborating
with the Juilliard, Kolisch, Fine Arts and Concord Quartets.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, Webster shared the recital stage with his
son, the clarinetist Michael Webster.
</P>
<P>
   Webster is survived by his wife, Frances Brown Webster, his son,
of Houston, a daughter, Wendy Webster Ardizzone of Worcester,
Mass., and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
