<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins halt Glavine's win streak
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tom Glavine was on the brink of some delayed
gratification Tuesday night, reaching out for his first winning
record of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He had climbed there from a humble 0-3 beginning, a long first
two months of the season and four consecutive wins in his last four
starts. But waiting for him were the Florida Marlins, the ragtag
1999 version of a team that hasn't lost to Glavine since September
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins got to Glavine for a 5-2 win with a lineup featuring
four rookies and ranked 14th in the National League in batting
average (.260) and runs scored (360). The Braves have lost to the
NL East last-place Marlins only twice this season in six meetings,
both times with Glavine pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of pitcher Alex Fernandez, whom the Braves faced for the
first time since the 1997 NLCS after he missed all of last season
with shoulder problems, and former teammate Danny Bautista, whom
the Braves cut at the end of spring training, the Marlins were
looking awfully unfamiliar.
</P>
<P>
   But those two did the most damage. Bautista gave the Marlins
their first lead with a home run in the second inning and drove in
two runs, while Fernandez held the Braves to two runs on three hits
over the first eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins raked Glavine for a career-high 15 hits, and the
five runs were the most allowed by Glavine since a disastrous
nine-run outing in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins refused to swing at Glavine's borderline pitches and
found holes all over the infield on the pitches crossing the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine surrendered eight hits to the first 13 batters he faced,
seven of them singles. He allowed four in a row in the third inning
before allowing two runs on a bases-loaded walk to Preston Wilson
and a Bautista sacrifice fly. Another run an inning later and
Glavine had allowed four runs through the first four innings, the
most he'd allowed in a start since June 4 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Glavine kept it close, holding Florida to one run on six
hits in the fifth, sixth and seventh innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
