<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-DREAM-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBILITY OF DREAMWORKS MOVE HAS SAN FERNANDO VALLEY'S ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The San Fernando Valley has developed a case of
DreamWorks fever following the studio's recent decision to ditch
its ill-fated expansion into the marshes north of Los Angeles
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have started to get a lot of calls about sites,''
DreamWorks spokesman Andy Spahn said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks SKG, founded in 1994 by entertainment moguls Steven
Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen, has been vague
about expansion plans since the company killed a $250 &UR;  &LR; million
studio project at Playa Vista last week. ``We're not focused on
making an immediate decision about expansion,'' Spahn said.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt that DreamWorks will receive plenty of
proposals, although the winning offer will have to be sweet due to
the premium for snagging Spielberg, one of the world's most
successful filmmakers. The city of Los Angeles, for example,
offered more than $70 &UR;  &LR; million in incentives but that was not
enough to overcome what DreamWorks said were difficulties in
financing construction at the Playa Vista site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are still going to be very interested in
DreamWorks,'' said Kevin Skislock, an entertainment analyst at
Laguna Research Partners.
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, DreamWorks will bulk up slightly at its
three major locations _ headquarters and film-TV operations on the
Universal Studios lot, a year-old animation campus in Glendale and
music operations in Beverly Hills _ by closing smaller offices. For
the longer term, the San Fernando Valley is far and away the most
likely site if DreamWorks decides to consolidate at a single site.
</P>
<P>
   ``All signs for DreamWorks are pointing to the San Fernando
Valley,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist at the Los Angeles
County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks has three options in the San Fernando Valley:
</P>
<P>
   _ It could expand its 14-acre campus at Glendale, nine miles
north of downtown L.A., which has enough adjacent land for
development of another 150,000 square feet of office space, and
then develop more property in the surrounding area if it can be
obtained. Spahn called this ``an attractive option.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian-style animation campus was built with the help of
the Glendale Redevelopment Agency and Glendale City Manager James
Starbird wrote to DreamWorks last week that the city is ready to
help with further development. But finding property nearby may be
difficult partly because The Walt Disney Co. owns some of the
adjacent land, according to Assistant Redevelopment Director
Darrill Quashnik.
</P>
<P>
   _ It could expand the Universal Studios operation, where
Spielberg has been housed for the past two decades, as part of
Universal's ambitious overall expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Universal, owned by Seagram Co., had no comment on the prospect
of an expanded DreamWorks on its lot. But its expansion plan _
which would add 3.25 million square feet for entertainment, film
production, offices and hotels _ has not yet gone through the first
round of approvals and has drawn opposition from nearby homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank City Manager Robert ``Bud'' Ovrom, who wooed DreamWorks
actively before giving up last year in the face of the Playa Vista
deal, said making DreamWorks the key component of Universal's
expansion could soften the opposition. ``Universal could be better
off with DreamWorks there instead of a resort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cody Cluff, president of the Entertainment Industry Development
Corp., noted that Universal will likely make strong efforts to keep
at least part of DreamWorks on its property. ``Universal gets a big
benefit from having Spielberg on the lot,'' he said. ``It creates a
lot of good will among a very successful group of people in the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' decision on Playa Vista also resurrected rumors,
published again in Tuesday's edition of The Hollywood Reporter,
that Seagram and DreamWorks would discuss a merger. Spahn denied
the report, calling it ``absolutely untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   _ It could become the principal tenant at the North Hollywood
Studio Project, where developer J. Allen Radford has been cleared
by the Los Angeles Community Redevlopment Agency to build a $750
million project with 10 sound stages, two 20-story towers and a
business campus. Radford and the CRA are negotiating an agreement
on a development plan and construction could start as early as
2001.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Radford repeated his position that North Hollywood
would be a ``viable'' option for DreamWorks and added he has not
yet contacted studio executives since they bailed out of Playa
Vista. ``I think a period of time needs to pass first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Joel Wachs, whose district includes North
Hollywood, said DreamWorks has been silent on whether the Radford
project would be attractive but added he will push hard to convince
DreamWorks that such a move makes sense. He also said he would
support the same sort of incentives the city arranged for Playa
Vista.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd bend over backwards to get DreamWorks here,'' Wachs said.
``The motion-picture industry is one of the engines that drive our
economy and provide a lot of well-paying jobs. It also would fit
very well with that area's overall redevelopment project.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Margolis, director of communications for Mayor Richard
Riordan's office of economic development, said it was too early to
say whether Riordan would support similar incentives at the Radford
project. But he noted that executives from DreamWorks and other
studios have looked over the site and added, ``It will be the only
state-of-the-art studio in that part of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Several observors cautioned that the idea of a new DreamWorks
studio in the Valley may slip away, much like the dream of a
state-of-the-art facility at Playa Vista; in other words,
DreamWorks may stand pat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could live very, very happily just as they are in the
Valley,'' said Kyser, noting that both Miramax and
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer both operate without a studio lot. ``Hollywood
is moving toward becoming a virtual industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluff also noted Hollywood's economics may no longer lend
themselves to building a new physical studio plant. ``Traditional
studios like Warner Bros. work only because the land was purchased
many years ago so the carrying costs are a lot lower,'' he said.
``For now, there are enough good sound stages available locally
that DreamWorks doesn't have to go into that business.''
</P>
<P>
   Skislock believes DreamWorks will take a measured approach to
expansion, citing the studio's slow-but-steady strategy in film and
TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``DreamWorks could have done a 20-film slate, so resisting that
temptation shows to me that they're great businessmen,'' he said.
``I give them great credit for hanging in as long as they did with
Playa Vista. I think they're committed to doing it right and they
don't feel as if they have to build a monument to themselves as
soon as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
