<BODY>
 ARIZONA VISIT PART OF CLINTON PUSH TO POLISH LEGACY  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 and MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's visit to Phoenix Wednes day is
tied to the legacy he hopes to leave when his term is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is personal, but there are political elements: reaching
out to the Hispanic community and trying to promote the model of a
``New Democrat'' who believes in a differ ent sort of government,
compassion ate but more scaled-down, than his party predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to arrive at Sky Harbor International
Airport at 4 p.m. His motorcade will take him to the office of
Chicanos Por La Causa, then the factory of La Canasta Mexican Food
Products, and on to an undisclosed location before he leaves for
Los Angeles at 9:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trip's message is similar to that of Clinton's
welfare reform of 1996: The federal govern ment needs to provide
limited assist ance to needy businesses and individuals, then get
out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes that such a centrist philosophy will help propel
Vice President Al Gore to the presidency in 2000. The Democratic
Party is intent on keeping Arizona in the fold, since the state
went Demo cratic in the last presidential elec tion for the first
time since Harry Truman ran in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to aides, the four-day trip, taking Clinton from
Appalachia to Watts, has been especially about his desire to try to
make his mark against poverty before he leaves office in January
2001. This is a president who was enamored as a boy with President
Kennedy and his family and their reputation for caring about under
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, the White House staff has been trying to play
down the politics and play up the an ti-poverty theme. Aides have
been emphasizing that the mission of trying to relieve economic
distress crosses party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not places (on the agenda) where there's great
political power,'' economic adviser Gene Sperling said. ``These are
not places where there's an easy politi cal message.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling termed it ``extraordi nary'' that a president would
spend four days, from Monday through Thursday, highlighting some of
the most impoverished areas in the nation while ``in the midst of
one of the strongest economies of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Clinton's focus in Phoenix on Hispanic businesses, the
trip's political benefit takes on a strong ethnic tone, local
observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton today wades into friendly territory: The areas he will
visit have voted strongly Democratic for years, and were Clinton
strongholds in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic Party shouldn't take these voters for
granted, pollster Earl de Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democrats are very concerned about the efforts by
several lead Republican candidates and the Republican Party to go
after the Latino vote,'' said de Berge, who leads the Behavior
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Texas Gov. George W. Bush has been courting Hispan
ics, a key constituency in his home state that helped elect him
governor twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of crossover po tential on this compassionate
con servative thing,'' de Berge said, referring to Bush's political
mantra. ``(He's) actually going to them and asking for their
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Arizona's presidential candidates, U.S. Sen. John McCain,
has always had strong Hispanic support in Arizona, de Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   A HispanicTRACK poll that de Berge conducted this spring found
that nearly four out 10 Hispanic heads of household identify them
selves as politically conservative. About 30 percent labeled them
selves liberal, and the rest classified themselves as moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Even though seven out of 10 Hispanics are registered as Demo
crats, de Berge said his poll find ings indicate that they could be
swayed by a GOP message.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Sproul, executive director of the Arizona Republican
Party, said Hispanic support for key GOP officials in the 1998
state election should have Democrats sweating about whether Arizona
will vote Democratic in next year's presiden tial race.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're certainly worried that they'll lose Arizona this
time,'' Sproul said. ``Common sense would indicate that when you
have a popular governor, and two popular (U.S.) senators and a
popular secre tary of state, a Republican is going to do well
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they're not taking Hispanics for granted. In fact,
Clinton's visit should be a reminder that the Democrats have been
with Hispanics for a long time, said Danny Ortega, a Phoenix lawyer
and Democratic activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's administration and all its success right now
will be shared by Al Gore,'' Ortega said.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Republicans' outreach to Hispanics is good for
the Latino community, Ortega said, it's just ``lip service'' at
this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the party of immigrant bashing,'' he said of the GOP.
``That's what George Bush has to work with. He still has a party to
drag along.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even some of the most ardent political animals in the Val
ley said they don't see a heavy emphasis to the president's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's domestic agenda has always held that small businesses
should benefit from economic suc cess, said Mary Rose Wilcox, the
lone Democrat on the Maricopa County Board of Supervisors. She
called the trip a ``non-partisan visit'' but acknowledged that it
nonetheless could serve to shore up the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even before it began, Clinton's trip was political fodder.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Rep. Jim Talent, R-Mo., said Clinton's effort to
open up investment to the distressed communities was doomed to
failure. Talent said in a briefing paper that the president's
initiative is focused too narrowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offers these communities nothing for savings, home owner
ship and drug and alcohol abuse treatment, integral aspects of
revital ization,'' Talent said in the briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other Democratic presidential candidates before
him, Clinton considered Arizona a Re publican stronghold when he
began his 1996 candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But, after a speech in Phoenix, poll numbers indicated that he
could make a good showing in the state, especially on the issues of
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   And so Clinton ended up return ing to Arizona, and visited the
Grand Canyon before the election.
</P>
<P>
   After capturing the state's eight electoral votes, Clinton
returned to Tucson last February, partly to say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   The date for next year's Arizona Democratic presidential primary
is not yet set, which makes it difficult for Gore and challenger
Bill Brad ley to assess its relative importance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
