<HEADER>
A1314 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CHINA-LADN     07-06 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CHINA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Byk JIM BARRERO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ How's this for serving notice?
</P>
<P>
   A 5-0 victory in the semifinals of your sport's biggest event
against the defending champion of the worldwide tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That's what China did to Norway this past weekend in the
semifinals of the 1999 Women's World Cup. If there were any doubts
about the team's ability to finish its chances and put teams away,
they were erased during 90 dominating minutes at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, anybody 5-0 against Norway, holy cow, it's a
shocker,'' said U.S. veteran midfielder Michelle Akers on her
reaction to China's victory.
</P>
<P>
   That China will face the U.S. in the final Saturday at the Rose
Bowl is less a surprise than how it has increased its level of play
as the three-week tournament has progressed.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, this seems to be a far different Chinese team
than the one eliminated in the quarterfinals of the inaugural
tournament it hosted in 1991. After that loss, China actually shut
down its women's program for two years to regroup. China rebounded
to advance to the semifinals of the '95 World Cup and the gold
medal match of the '96 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. assistant coach Lauren Gregg said the Chinese team
resembles its American counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the area they've most gained, is they have a psychological
dimension,'' Gregg said. ``I think in the past we've had the edge
there. I'm seeing a lot of confidence and a hardness not seen in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   It all starts with forward Sun Wen, a national-team veteran who
has scored seven goals in the '99 Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the areas they've improved is that they are
better at finishing their chances,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   But the formula has numerous components, including midfielder
Liu Ailing, who scored two of the tournament's most beautiful goals
against Norway. Other keys are forward Jin Yan and defender Fan
Yunjie, who jumps into the offensive half with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Akers said China's team concept is beyond reproach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a team in every sense of the word,'' Akers said.
``They play off each other well. They play for each other. They
move and attack and defend as a unit. They have personalities that
can win the game for them and yet their attack or defense, as a
whole, can win the game for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested Akers sounded as though she were describing
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be,'' Akers said. ``Could be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
