<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXECUTE-AZ-AZR &LR;      07-06 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTE-AZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHICAL CHASM OPENS IN CASE OF MENTALLY ILL DEATH ROW INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona officials believe that Claude Maturana is ill, and they
want to make him well.
</P>
<P>
   So they can execute him.
</P>
<P>
   But state doctors are refusing to go along.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, Maturana, a death row inmate diagnosed as severely
mentally ill, sits in a special unit on the grounds of the Arizona
State Hospital _ and at the center of a clash between the demands
of the justice system and the ethics of the medical profession.
</P>
<P>
   One psychiatrist likens the practice to ``fattening the calf
before slaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous ethical dilemma for the treating
psychiatrist,'' said Dr. Steven Pitt, a forensic psychiatrist
formerly on the state hospital staff. ``It's a lose, lose, lose
situation all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturana, a French citizen, was sentenced to die in 1992 for
killing a teenager near Tucson. In January, however, a judge agreed
with two court-appointed doctors that Maturana suffers from
schizophrenia, meaning Maturana has lost touch with reality, and
thus cannot legally be put to death.
</P>
<P>
   State doctors are now supposed to restore him to competency,
then send him back to death row.
</P>
<P>
   By law, that responsibility rests with the state Department of
Health Services. However, DHS doctors say professional ethical
codes forbid them from taking part.
</P>
<P>
   So, Maturana remains on the grounds of the state hospital,
receiving just enough medication to maintain his mental stability
but not enough to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jerry Dennis, the state hospital's chief medical officer, is
charged with treating Maturana.
</P>
<P>
   But for Dennis, ``treatment'' doesn't include preparing a
patient to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the physician, you're there to provide care and
treatment and do no harm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been providing maintenance, not aggressively pursuing
further medication or other treatment approaches that would restore
him to competency,'' Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state health officials are scrambling to find another
doctor, or even a nurse practitioner, who can administer
medications, to try to restore Maturana to competency. None has yet
agreed to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   The search itself is also drawing controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administrator who is putting out these contracts is
basically trying to subvert the medical profession,'' said Dr.
Kenneth Iserson, director of the Arizona Bioethics Program at the
University of Arizona's College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a bedrock thing now. It's not some obscure
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturana, 41, is a former auto mechanic with convictions in
Texas for burglary and aggravated assault. Little else is known
about him for sure, according to his attorney and court records.
</P>
<P>
   He claims to have children, any number from one to 11, and a
military background with the Air Force, French Foreign Legion, the
``Natural Navy,'' and a secret unit called the ``Veterans Force
AIPS.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas records show that Maturana was paroled from prison in
February 1990; five months later in Arizona, he killed a
16-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, Maturana and Stephen Ballard lured
Glenn Estes away from home with the promise that they would party
in the desert. They drove him to a remote location west of Tucson,
where Maturana shot him at least a dozen times. Ballard then slit
the boy's neck with a machete.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard received a life sentence. Maturana was sent to death
row, where he's remained since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Maturana's attorney, Carla Ryan, says her client is so severely
mentally ill that she can't communicate with him or get his
assistance in his case. She filed a motion claiming he isn't
competent to be executed. A landmark 1986 U.S. Supreme Court ruling
prohibits states from executing such inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Pinal County Superior Court Judge Gilberto Figueroa
declared Maturana incompetent, based on written evaluations from
two court-appointed doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling triggered a state law that says such inmates
should be confined to the state hospital until they become
competent to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Because Maturana's case is the first to test the law, Figueroa
encouraged attorneys to seek guidance from the Arizona Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors say that is premature. They first want to hold a
competency hearing before Figueroa and have the chance to call
witnesses such as prison correctional officers to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carry on normal conversations with him, and he seems fine
to them,'' said Jon Anderson, assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few doctors say he has mental problems. Almost anybody can
be diagnosed with a mental problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson said such a person can ``still understand what they
need to understand to be competent to be executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan and at least three doctors contend that Maturana is
seriously mentally ill. In reports to the court, Dennis said
Maturana suffers from chronic paranoid schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   He said Maturana is convinced he is an agent of the ``world
police'' and gets in and out of prison to conduct top secret
investigations for the ``Federal F &AMP; I'' and ``Central TBS.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dennis' report, ``He believes that his (prison)
sentence has already been commuted by `Rule 11, Margaret 3.' He
further states that the `Embassy' and `NATO TOBY' divisions are
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Dr. Michael Bayless, a Phoenix
psychologist, Maturana ``seemed to relate everything to numbers.''
He described himself as a world conductor in ``American 601'' and
said he didn't need medication because he has an ``1107 working FBI
702.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to his illness, Dennis wrote, Maturana doesn't adequately
understand that he has been convicted of murder and sentenced to
death. The doctor recommends that Maturana's sentence be commuted
to life imprisonment without parole.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant Attorney General &UR; Anderson said that would be up to
the state Board of Pardons and Paroles, which could recommend a
commutation to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Maturana's case is in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association has ethical codes that prohibit
doctors from taking part in executions. That includes restoring
inmates to competency and giving lethal injections.
</P>
<P>
   When Maturana was sent to the state hospital in February, Dennis
and others refused to try to restore him to competency, said Jack
Silver, hospital chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   So, the state began looking for another doctor or nurse
practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect them (state hospital doctors) to practice
according to their code of ethics,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not faced with an ethical dilemma. (But) I have the
dilemma of having the responsibility of upholding the state law and
a court order.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitt, the state hospital's former director of forensic
psychiatric services, sharply criticized health officials for
accepting Maturana's case. He said the state hospital should have
``drawn a &UR; line in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Instead) everyone is engaging in passive resistance,'' he
said. ``This idea of treating but not treating is really just an
effort to appease the court order, but it's not addressing the
underlying issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Potts, chief of the forensic services unit for Maricopa
County Superior Court, also criticized state health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should just say, `We're not doing it,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Potts and Pitt advocate a change in Arizona law that would
allow a judge to commute a death sentence to life without parole in
the case of an inmate found not competent to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, such as Missouri and Maryland, have such laws on
the books, said Richard Dieter, executive director of the Death
Penalty Information Center, a Washington, D.C.-based organization
that opposes how the death penalty is applied.
</P>
<P>
   In other states, governors have commuted the sentences of
incompetent inmates. In May, for instance, Virginia's governor
granted clemency to a mentally ill man four hours before his
scheduled execution and commuted his sentence to life without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt noted that there are no easy answers in cases like
Maturana's, which involve not only the inmate and doctors, but the
victim, the victim's family, judges, lawyers, state officials and
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are multiple competing interests,'' he said. ``And that
makes this issue so incredibly complex.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
