<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HILL FOR 2ND TIME IN 3 DAYS, HERSHISER BEATS EXPOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only once in a mostly superb 16-year major league
career had Orel Hershiser ever started a game on two days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1986, at the age of 28, when, according to the Elias
Sports Bureau, Hershiser pitched a complete-game, eight-hit shutout
for the Los Angeles Dodgers on the final day of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Never had Hershiser started on one day's rest, however. But on
Monday, when manager Bobby Valentine of the Mets asked the
right-hander, now 40, if he would do just that Tuesday night at
Shea Stadium, Hershiser said he could pitch whenever the Mets
needed him.
</P>
<P>
   The result was five shutout innings in a 10-0 victory over the
Montreal Expos, a wonderful twist of irony because the final score
was exactly the same as the one in the September game Hershiser
pitched 13 years ago, when he started against the San Diego Padres
on two-days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad way to rebound for a pitcher who had been driven from
the game in the third inning of a start against the Atlanta Braves
on Sunday night. But two nights later, Hershiser not only
rediscovered his sinkerball, he also had the Expos beating the
pitch into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In improving his record to 9-5, Hershiser scattered three
singles as he faced three batters over the minimum of 15 and pulled
within one victory of the 200-plateau for his career.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Mets backed him with three runs in the first
inning on a night when Brian McRae hit a two-run homer and Edgardo
Alfonzo a two-run double to power the offense.
</P>
<P>
   There were, as general manager Steve Phillips pointed out before
the game, a number of reasons the Mets asked Hershiser to take the
mound Tuesday night. It meant they could bump rookie right-hander
Octavio Dotel back a day and allow Hershiser to start on Sunday (on
four-days' rest) against the Yankees in the last game before the
all-star game break.
</P>
<P>
   The move also allowed Masato Yoshii, who has been bothered by a
sore right quadriceps muscle, to rest an additional day before his
next start against Montreal. That could make it possible for Al
Leiter, who beat the Yankees at Yankee Stadium on June 6, to start
the weekend-series opener at Shea Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reasons being offered about why Hershiser had
struggled against the Braves on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had too much adrenaline,'' Mike Piazza, the catcher, said,
reasoning that Sunday's start was against the first-place Braves
after the Mets had dropped the first two games of an important
series. Hershiser was a little too pumped up.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied to win that night, getting Hershiser off the
hook. On Monday, Hershiser was on the spot after Valentine asked
him to start Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A little arm fatigue always helps a sinkerball pitcher, Piazza
argued. ``Maybe he won't overthrow, and the ball won't be flat,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It took Hershiser just 59 pitches to prove Piazza right. And 45
of them (76 percent) were strikes. On Sunday, Hershiser threw 52
pitches before he was lifted with two out in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   If that outing had worried Hershiser, however, there was no way
to tell. After Edgardo Alfonzo's three-run homer had powered the
Mets to a 7-6 victory, Hershiser facetiously told Valentine,
``Without me, Fonzie wouldn't have been the hero. It would have
been a blowout.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday night's game, Hershiser was equally cool, no
matter how hot it was outside. He poked fun as his teammates argued
over a card game. Later, as he looked at films of the Montreal
hitters in their last series against Atlanta, Hershiser said in
mock anger, ``I'm really upset, because the scouting tape is of
Kevin Millwood and John Smoltz. Do I throw like either one?''
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser didn't need to throw hard Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for five innings, he was able to mimic what he had done
in Miami on June 29, when he went 8 1/3 innings in a 5-1 victory
over the Marlins, his best outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos obviously did not watch tapes of that game. Nine of
the 15 outs Hershiser recorded Tuesday night were on grounders.
Four were on strikeouts. One was a soft liner to short. One was a
fly ball to right. With the three singles Hershiser allowed, only
four of the 18 Expos' hitters Hershiser faced hit the ball out of
the infield.
</P>
</TEXT>
